text: rye crystal and malted oats gives it the colour and aroma , challenger and goldings give it the bitterness .  this beer is a great looking o'fest beer .  this is a very refreshing beer . i love a hoppy , complex tasting beer , but sometimes i just want a lighter beer that is n't heavy or dominating the flavor of my food . this beer is light , crisp , and has a great taste . perfect pairing for a good pizza .

smell is not very aparent , maybe a slight maltiness to it . taste is buttery and slightly spicy , behind it are grassy euro malts .  bottled 07/27/10 pours an amber/ice tea color with 3 fingers of fluffy khaki colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : cakeyness , woody & herbal hops , fusel boozeyness once warm t : follows the nose , toffee sweetness up front , plus some boozeyness .  this is something that i was really looking forward to at the southeastern ratebeer gathering . the huge aroma is screaming spruce at me . the malt is dry and clean and really comes across as a dry brown ale than a porter . still , it 's tasty and one of the few dark beers i 've had that had dominant hops that i really think work that way .

no aroma to speak of . taste is excellent , caramel malt with the lightest touch of hops to balance .  a - huge true blonde foam with tons of lace and excellent retention .  i hate to give a beer ( especially a trappist ) a bad review but this beer was not very good at all . i had a few sips and then poured the rest of the 750 down the drain . i may have gotten a bad batch but i found this beer to be quite bitter and sour and not what i would expect from a tripel .

smell is malt , light smoke , hint of citrus & spice .  pours a two finger clingy tan head over a brilliant light copper liquid . head is large bubbled and soapy looking , but holds together well .  medium-bodied rather than thick .

i 'm a big fan of smoked porter and while i liked this , it was n't my favorite . smell was lacking . just not as strong a `` smoke '' smell as some others ( see alaskan smoked porter !  this is the first time i had a foreign hefeweizen and i am very impressed . i love it .  m - a bit on the thin and watery side .

the aroma is the highlight of this beer , distinctly belgian yeast with floral hops and fruit , namely grapefruit and pear . the finish hits you with a bold hop bitterness that lingers for a while then slowly dies off , leaving you with a hint of sweet fruit . a great variation of one of the classic ipas .  a - a great thick orange color . a nice white head with amazing lacing up the entire glass .  mouthfeel was n't bad , but was n't great either .

s-reminds me of a coffee flavored candy of my childhood -- a little too sweet smelling for my taste in a beer t-1st is sweet coffee- finishes with a nice bitterness , good carbonation if drunk with large head -- less so later -- but even after head is gone good for a stout d- would only want one of these per session between richness , coffee flavor and abv .  a - pours a huge puffy white head into a pint glass . the head sticks around forever and leaves some very nice lacing .  mouthfeel - medium..maybe a little on the more watery side , but still creamy-ish .

smell is pretty light and phenolic . - with the red fruit nose .  ruby color with a fantastic head thats lasts the duration of the beer .  a- i had it in a bottle so i ca n't say . also this was the imported munich gold version s- smells like awesome sauce t- the taste is kind bready with some sweet maltige m- not much slides right on down d- goes down the hatch with ease overall i really like this juice !

above average lacing & head retention s : a little bit of grainy cereal & caramel as this warms t : caramel & grainyness up front .  brilliantly clear dark copper hue . covered by a thick , rutted , persistent ivory white head that leaves rough lace .  in the mouth , it 's a touch thin and gritty .

some lacing s- flowerly hops t - crisp hop bite up front , with malt underneath .  poured a gorgeous ruby red , with a cream coloured , fluffy thick head . excellent retention , thick film of foam on the side of the glass , and thick layer of foam atop the beer . one of the best i 've ever seen from a bottle .  high carbonation is the only downfall i can find in this beer .

the alcohol adds a nice touch that goes perfectly with the sweet malts without making it too spicey/hot . incredible smell . t : the bourbon really comes to the forefront here . notes : man ... if only this beer tasted like it smelled ... the smell was such a tease here . like a cheap bourbon ... the smell was too damn good to not have a slightly sweeter beer and halfway through it i was more interested in sniffing a few more times than finishing it .  it is a beautiful looking beverage .  mouthfeel is a little on the light side , but when it comes down to it this is a really amazing beer .

a good plain strong beer smell .  poured from 22oz bomber into mug . a - poured slightly hazy amber orange color with high head that slowly dissipated leaving a lot of lacing around the glass .  m - the mouth feel is lush and oily but a tad too soft by the end .

smell was mainly malt with subtle hops . not the greatest aroma . taste was much better .  another kick ass brew from stone . black liquid , white head .  sampled this beer at founders own tap room . the beer was way too sweet . the malts from the stout style could not overcome the maple and and sweetness from the high gravity . that rarely happens , i almost never orphan a beer . founders has many beers that are excellent , this was not one of them .
nose is burnt malt with some coffee .  dumped in to a footed glass . brilliantly clarity , tawny amber .  m- this beer is very carbonated and somewhat thin , very refreshing .
aromas were light for a beer so dark , gas station coffee and toffee .  i must say that the bottle is very cool looking !  mouthfeel : light to medium .

s - wow . this has got to be one of the best and funkiest noses ever ; it is amazing what the brett has done the the olfactory aspect . not the same type of 'wow ' as the smell elicited , this is more of a shocking letdown . the flavor is nothing like the nose promises . it is not that its bad , but it is definitely massively underwhelming . but it smelled so damn funky and fruity !  appearance : pours a deep black into a shaker pint glass with no light getting through . a hearty one-and-a-half-finger tan head forms on top and does n't really budge and only eventually drops to a splotchy yet full surface covering of foam . honestly , there is n't anything about how this beer looks that is n't perfect .  you could certainly taste the chocolate , but it did n't fill the mouth with the heavy , rich bitter chocolate of some other beers in this same vein . i enjoyed drinking this beer ; it went down easily , but if given the choice , i would take the brooklyn chocolate stout , which is more like comfort food in the fall when it 's getting cold and the leaves are dying . this is supposed to be a beer you can snuggle with next to the fireplace while watching monday night football .

s- a fair whiff of rasberry , very subtle but nothing special . t- a hearty punch of cereal flavors starts out and ends with a nice sweet rasberry burst that lingers pleasently .  beautiful in this glass . truly , a sight to behold . ok - on to the beer ... opaque - dark as night - the darkest night .  m- a little on the watery side , a little carb still hangs around .

the aroma is moderate , all roasted malt and a bit of coffee and chalk . the taste is really nice , stoutish but a bit more complex , presumably from the yeast .  750ml champagne style bomber poured into a tulip thanks to jebus3513 holy thickness . this pours like ink black motor oil . i ca n't get over how dark the color of the head is .  m : pretty low carbonation , which is definitely not a problem for the style . the body 's a little thinner than i 'd prefer , though . a nice , smooth mouthfeel to the beer .

aroma is very faint , but i 'm in a typical college bar so i would be surprised if i could smell anything beyond the stale beer , ashtray and urinal cake . anyhoo , what i could detect was some sweet malt , faint fruity esters , and some flowery noble hops .  this looked exceptionally wonderful .  mouthfeel is a bit lean , and watered down .

2010 bottles on the shelves now are probably not worth buying at $ 9- $ 10/pop unless you have a lot of patience and extra space in your cellar ... i did have the fortune of trying a version of this beer at new beer distributors a few months back in december that was `` randalled '' through coffee beans that had been soaked in bourbon .  i love the style so i 'm excited to give this guy a nice review ( er ... i mean ... my objective review will reflect the beer 's merits ) it is a very stout-looking brew , both in that it looks like a stout and looks stout . tight brown lacing leaves some tight lacing .  mouthfeel : thin to reference the entire continuum of beers , but average for a pilsner .

the smell is on the weak side but i note some sweet malt . further sips only enhance the taste of grain and it makes for a rather dull , imo , lager that has a pretty decent colour for the style .  from notes reviewed on 11/19/10 : bomber poured into a duvel glass , best by 4/17/11 a : golden orange , clear , huge 3 finger foamy white head that looks like pillows of clouds bursting out of the glass . great head retention and lacing .  m - light-medium body a bit chewy but with a ton of carbonation ... a bit distracting and makes the beer lose steam and fizzle in your mouth .

the beer has a sweet bubble gum-like smell with faint malt and spices in the background . the smell is a lot stronger than the taste .  beautiful dark ruby colour , very good thick head .  m - nice carbonation , but it could be much bigger bodied .

s. smells no different than matilda . a little sour , typical quality belgian ale .  pours red amber with a towering off-white head . two and a half fingers of thick foam that is going absolutely nowhere . i could eat this head like it 's ice cream .  appearance : pours a cloudy amber , moderately carbonated with offwhite foam , leaving moderate foamy lacing . smell : hops are floral and sweet , blending well with the strong raspberry undertones . taste : begins tart , with mellow floral hop taste , very light toasty malts which bring forth the hints of raspberry and honeycomb , finishes witha tangy bitterness that allows a slight yet lasting raspberry lingering . drinkability : very delicious small batch by mbc , its well brewed and the subtle notes of the raspberry are not forced , decent abv as well .

i expect the regular ipa aroma , but this one is subdued - seems just as malty as it does hoppy .  on cask at aobf a fluffy tan head rises over oily black , black , black .  f & t : crisp , firm moderate body , more rounded feeling than a lot of macro lagers .

the smell is unfortunately faint , but there are hints of grain and hops .  pours a pitch black color with a dense , solid , foamy head with excellent retention and lacing .  poured a darkish amber red with a smallish head , big hop nose and very hoppy but not overly bitter finish , carbonation was somewhat low on this beer but as big as it is that does not seem to hurt seems more like how a barley wine would be , as the beer warms up it becomes much more mellow and takes on a carmelly complex flavor . all in all i would say a very good 10 % iipa

very slight smell of malt and a light hop aroma . the taste is spicy and slightly peppery with a very pleasant hop bitterness at the finish .  the nitro can widget leads to a beautiful cascading effect , pefectly dark beer , with the fluffy white head . looks fake it looks so good .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . medium-low carbonation .

hats off to my beer brother james for giving me this bottle as part of a birthday present package . the subtelty of the finish is the best part ... no bitter beer face  the appearance , however , is really cool - the dark cloudy auburn colour and the massive head .  entry is nice withy carbonation lightly brushing the sides of the tongue with a mouthfeel a little thinner than i 'm used to with an ipa . midtaste hits the sweet spot with a nice pale malt and grapefruity hops .

very low aroma of light malt and hop . flavor is rich , thick sweet malt with hints of fig and raisin , also some cocoa and caramel .  drank from a 750 ml bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a slightly hazed , bright , orangey-golden yellow with a huge , bubbly , off white , sea foam head that ever-so-slowly dropped to a thick , moussey cap of froth . dense patches of lacing stuck all down the glass .  this is a pretty good belgian , but the spicy character takes away from the drinkability and the mouthfeel .

i found blue moon belgium white to be a very delightful beer with an interesting aftertaste and has a creamy texture . worth a try !  very beautiful to look at . the color is just awesome !  in a snifter a : deep , dark ruby red ; very little head ; s : raspberry , sweet , bottle fermentation t : outstanding flavor ; perhaps not exactly what i expect in a quad ; strong , complex , bold belgian-style ale with prominent streaks of cherry , berry ; toffee and caramel flavors enter too ; this beer aims toward the flavor profile of a port i liked this beer very much , overall ; although it is quad-style , do n't expect it to try to reach the quad prototype ; quaddish is probably a better name , and you 'll enjoy it all the more .

s : bouquet is a tad faint , but suggests that this will be chocolatey porter . t : semi-sweet and super rich , founders porter boasts molasses , chocolate , and caramel .  it pours a leopard skin pattern with a background of black with periodic cherry holes , which is an outstanding feat for a liquid . the head is huge with large frothy bubbles .  milk sugar in a beer ?

very minimal smell - some floral notes , but otherwise not much coming through .  a- i believe to be one of the most beautiful looking beers , a copper orange color that naturally pours with the look of a nitrogen infused beer , yet only produces about a 1.5 finger head .  nice dry finish . a bit too carbonated for my liking .

light caramel smell with a hint of grass .  visible carbonation , this is one fizzy looking beer ! pours with a thick creamy and towering white foamy head . heavy and sparkling lacing . wow , perfect example of the style !  mouthfeel : medium body with a bit of oil that leaves a coat .
aroma : a bit of a tang , along with a small bit of a soapy smell . very nice .  poured a very nice deep copper color with excellent head and lacing .  taste : very little carbonation .

maryland brewed , not sure about the label dating . s -- mild balance of roasted malts and citrus hops . o -- aside from being light in aroma , this is a great example of a robust porter .  the yellow-tinted head was a full three-fingers thick and displayed very good retention as a cap . the lacing was very thick and consistent all the way down my glass .  pours black but with some deep red highlights with a slight off-white head that is gone in a flash leaving nothing behind , milk chocolate is very prevelant in the aroma with a little smokiness and a roasted coffee hint.nice deeply roasted flavor with big doses of cocoa and smoke , alot of flavor melding going on but seemed a little light in the mouthfeel department otheriwise a top notch brew.a easy drinker with alot of flavor needs a little tweaking to be great in my opinion .
well , there pretty much is no smell .  a - awesome head ! ! ! pours into crazy shapes ... brew is cloudy orange/amber color . lots of great lacing .  m : very normal carbonation .

smell : typical skunky smell when first poured , but let it sit for a few minutes and that will subside a little .  absolutely stunning upon pouring .  m : medium-bodied , but i feel like there 's something missing .

a huge light an head great retention and lacing ... the aroma is light and disappointing , not a ton going on . light soapy hops , chocolate , a hint of alcohol .  this brew pours a medium head of fine to large sized mostly lasting bubbles and an opaque black colored body .  the mouthfeel is light to moderate .

was a little surprised by the color of this i thought it was going to be a golden color.poured a light mahogany with a light tan head.aroma browm sugar , malts , dark fruits , sweet . flavor , the flavors did not come close to the aroma , everything was on the weak side , got malts , some hops , sugar . to bad the flavor did not live up to the aroma . it was a easy drinking beer .  the head has pretty amazing retention , lasting even after i have consumed half the beer .  it had a medium to light body .

aroma was decent ... lightly fruity but hardly overpowering .  dark gold/bronze with a full pillowy beige head and very active carbonation .  mouthfeel is a bit dry , but that does n't really take away from it 's drinkability .

nose is musty belgian yeast . very small amount of bitter hops detectable . the nose is much more belgian than ipa .  fierce ubiquitous beeding which really carries a nose of almost sweet banana . dense super concentrated almost batter like foam head which finishes all whippy almost like the top of tin tin 's head . underneath the beer has a deeply golden fog .  crisp , largely watery with low carbonation .

s- hints of coffee and semi-sweet chocolate . the coffee and chocolate hints are noticeable but do show up like the smell would suggest .  bottled nov. 2007 , batch 3 this looks fantastic . very thick , black , with a dark tan fingers of head .  m : a bit too fizzy upon sipping , and i was looking for a bit more 'heft ' .

retention is very good and there is nice soapy lacing down the side of the glass . s - the aroma seems somewhat muted but i can pick up on the rye mixed with your common stout qualities ( chocolate , coffee , molasses ) .  12 oz bottle poured into a nonic 2008 vintage a - the usual ris color with a 2.5cm tan/brown head that would have been larger had the glass been taller . d - the beer itself looked beautiful , but its flavor and aroma were really weak .  m : 3 day old ginger ale type carbonation ... o : not a great beer .

appearance : beautiful crystal clear pale golden beer that pours a very thick & sticky white foam head . smell : soft grain , metallic and floral hop aromas .  gorgeous coppery amber color with a great fluffy head .  this was probably just average on the mouthfeel , imo - whether you consider this a wild ale or bsda .

very little on the aroma front . maybe a bit of grain but very feint .  bottled on 12/15/11 this beer is dark , darkest head i have seen .  i really like it and find that , though the mouthfeel makes it sharp and crisp , it does n't help sustain the nice flavors at work here ... wheat , hay , raspberries ( of course ) . yes , nothing overwhelming .

a : pours an orange color with small head , slight lacing down the glass s : smell is amazing ! ! very citrusy hop scents abound . very slight biscut scent as well t : slight biscuty taste up front with a citrsy bitter bite at the end m : medium bodied oily mouthfeel d : this tastes as fresh an ipa as you could get ... i 'm sure its not ... i live in washington and its brewed in pa ... great beer tastes just like i 'm at the brewery .  appearance : dark copper brown , great clarity , thick tannish creamy head on hard pour , some lacing aroma : upfront banana-like fruitiness , big hit of caramelly malt , some molasses , no hops , touch of alcohol flavor : mellow sweetness initially with a rich melanoidin roundness to the palate , toasty caramel sweet smoothness balances out with just enough hop bitterness in the semi-sweet finish , sumptuously tasty mouthfeel : medium-full bodied but not syrupy , gentle carbonation and a tantalizing alcohol warmth without any burning sensation overall impression : this is a supremely well-crafted beer , one of the hallmarks of the style .  medium carbonation and thin mouthfeel makes this brew very drinkable .
s - subtle nose . citrus and floral notes .  great retention and great lacing .  i gave the mouthfeel a lower score due to the extremely bitter after-taste and the thin-ness of the body .

s - very light amount of spices . not much there .  color : pours very dark brown , almost black . sits midnight with a very small dark brown rim . big , rich , creamy mocha head with great retention smell : over-ripened bananas upon approach . wierd .  m-moderate carbonation , medium-bodied beer , with a noticeable hoppy dryness .

s - not overly aromatic , faint citrus with a little caramel malt and some alcohol is there , but does n't smack you in the face . m - a lighter mouthfeel than expected and very smooth for the style . o - a well-balanced , highly drinkable ipa that does not overwhelm with flavor complexity , but is still quite enjoyable .  this one pours out to a red color in the glass with an almost , exploding-like head . the appearance of this beer was incredible . i mean , come on , its red beer with a slightly red head .  only complaint is it is a little thin but nothing that deters me from wanting more . the rich citrusy hops , leave you wanting another drink to quench your thirst they are so drying , it 's basically a no win situation . mid palate is lacking roundness but otherwise delicious . because of the immense amount of hops it would be hard to drink many of these .

leaves a little spotty lacing the aroma is really , really faint .  this pours from 750ml swing top bottle a pitch black with a 2 finger head of billowy tan foam . certainly a looker in my glass .  the only odd thing i noticed was sort of low carbonation , odd because there was a lot of foam on pouring . but it was n't really stale feeling , it just could have had more mouth presence .

s : very faint hop aroma . a little weak for this style . t : good layered hop flavor throughout the drink .  the spectacular shaker show with bubbles moving up and mostly down like a spectacular chocolate brown cascade during a good minute . it stabilizes almost black with a foamy nitro thin-bubbled beige head .  i found the mouthfeel to be decent , and found it to be very drinkable .

very nice . t : not as good as the aroma here , but still not bad .  pours an almost copper color with about 1 finger of firm foamy head that left a strip of lacing on the glass after each sip . interestingly when i finished the beer the glass was perfectly striped with left over lacing .  smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing . the apple/apricot scent is strong but would be overpowering to the tongue , the muted apple notes balanced well . i would definitely order this again .

the nose is malt sweet , with some hop floral tones .  bottle courtesy of fonefan : poured a dirty beige yellow color ale with a huge foamy head with great retention and perfect lacing .  mouthfeel : dry , grainy texture in a medium-light body with medium carbonation .

smell - smells a bit like an ipa . my first thoughts were that it was very watered down .  a : poured a deep dark brown with a thick creamy head , but that was the highlight of this beer .  presented much carbonation when poured.a thick beige head with spotty traces of sticky lace.a strong malt and coffee aroma.very nutty , molasses , and chocolate smell also.the color looks to be a very dark red to almost black.the smell and appearance are above average for most sam adams beers.the mouthfeel is a bit weak and watery.no carbonation bite to it.a very dry finish with a touch of a hop bitterness that stays in your throat.a drinkable stout and goes down smooth but is average .

appearance - 4.5 poured 3 fingers of thick cream coloured head which lingered before reducing to a still impressive 2 fingers and leaved fantastic lacing while i drank it . smell - 3.0 not particularly alcoholic , the predominant smell being of sweet malt . there is also some berry-like fruitiness and a little banana . a fine belgian .  appearance : huge head that never ends with a soft coco color . nice lace trails while pouring followed by deep dark chocolate color to finish it off .  it 's very easy to drink , crips , and light , but it 's a bit thin in character & feel .

n : alcohol right up front makes itself known , grassy background flavors with some yeast and some banana specs . no detection of hops . t : abundance of fruity sweetness and spices . d : extremely drinkable and i think it would be even moreso with some age on it .  incredible retention and the most sticky lace i have ever seen .  great finish , though a little thin .

nose - chocolate malts with a clean , hoppy aroma . very distinct . taste - roasted malts with deep sweet cola taste .  a thick pour into my tulip glass yielded an opaque black body with a beautiful mocha head that seemed to last through the entire beer . gorgeous .  let down by light and somewhat watery mouthfeel .

s : a dark , roasted smell with some coffee undertones which was quite enticing .  sinister jet black pour with a towering head of stiff mocha froth that lasts and clings beautifully . stiff peaks form a crown that eventually settles into a lasting shroud .  mouthfeel is on the thin side , and a bit to the beer 's determent .

aroma is understated , but it 's all about the flavor .  nice white pink head . a thing of beauty . sm : the slightest twinge of the df funk , but very subdued .  unremarkable mouthfeel , but the drinkability is pretty solid on this one .
the spelt brings a bit more musty earthiness than the average wheat .  huge frothy tan head , 4 '' of foam on top of 1 '' of beer early into a moderately strong pour .  mouthfeel : a touch thin .

s- a big malt presence and a decent barrel presence .  pours a ruby color with a 1 finger fluffy pink head . good amount of carbonation rising . just beautiful to look at .  mouthfeel : i 'm thinking guiness extra stout ( from the bottle ) light . medium body with a decent carbonation . lighter than expected and a bit prickly on the tongue and throat when going down .

this beer poured a reddish amber with a very thick foamy head but suprisingly littel aroma . thi beer put up a great appearance butt eh flavor and aroma somewhat left me feeling let down .  pours a lovely hazy gold with loads and loads of light carbonation bubbles running throughout .  m : mildly carbonated and dry .

it smells like cheap beer , kind of grainy .  a - an inch of creamy white head sits on top of a pale golden-orange beer . the head has some legs and sticks around for awhile . it leaves plenty of sticky lacing as it settles .  i am almost positive this is living under the assumed name of `` doc mason 's ryepa '' at solana beach . aroma is rye , caramel malt , and hops . nice hop bite up front with a smoother rye and caramel back . acidic and alcoholic finish .

smell is hard to discern , but there is definitely a vegetable taste in there but in the best way possible .  pours a surprisingly clear amber , with a fluffy , sticky , voluminous , lace-leaving head of slightly off-white .  m : it was watery with lots of carbonation .

a nice fluffy one finger red brown head coats the top of my beer and leaves a lattice lacing on the glass . s- aroma is weak but i get hints of brown sugar and sweet malts . some caramel and/or toffee rounds it out . t- a nice caramel and toffee type of taste .  a : very dark pour with carbonation bubbles that fall down and end up creating a long lasting dark tan , wet sand , brown head .  the mouthfeel has decent body , ok carbonation .

s-light oaky notes with a bit of sweet malt .  a - bright but murky copper . huge white head that stays a very long time .  carbonation is quite high , body is medium but filled with bubbles , mouthfeel is creamy but slick . very flavorful , but the carbonation ruins the mouthfeel for me .

s : not my favorite beer aroma , its decent though . the alcohol is very present in the nose , which i do n't get in the taste . the maltiness of the beer is very present in the smell which i like .  poured this into my pint glass it has a murky orange color with a freaking huge slightly off white 5inch head . lacing is scattered all over the sides of my glass , man oh man this beer looks fantastic .  m- good carbonation .

the smell was amazing and what i liked most about this beer . every aspect of this beer works together great and it was worth buying .  after drinking my first , and it was a gift , i 've got to tell you that this beer is _seriously overrated_ a- clear straw color , white foamy head , great lacing , nice bubbles , looks fabulous . s - mild t - mostly just a warming of alcohol , everything else is subtle .  mouthfeel is way too light for what i was expecting .

fuggles are used , but although i could taste them , their presence in the aroma was minimal . there was n't much malt content in the smell either , in fact there was very little smell to talk about .  deep amber/copper hue with a beautiful stream of bubbles hurrying to the surface .  as far as mouthfeel , it was rather carbonated and had a bit of a bite going down , especially when it was at its coldest .

it smells of caramel malts , yeast , allspice , cloves , and dark fruits -- perfect smell for a dubbel .  appearance - opting for the slow pour to minimize cloudiness and sediment , i ended up with a beautiful semi-hazy pour into a tall hefe glass . a stiff peak of meringue-like foam crests well above the top of the glass . the beer has a pale light yellow color in the narrow bottom of the glass , but shows off some orange shading in the wider top half of the glass . maximum aesthetics .  22oz in my piraat snifter i thought this was one of the best pumpkin beers that i have ever tasted . it poured golden to copper and had a huge nose of nutmeg and spice . i did not find it terribly sweet but like a pumpkin cookie . it had some notes of gram cracker to . i think it hides the 9 % abv very well not hot at all . i would have another . i think this bee would pair well with a pumpkin mousse pie very nice because of the gram cracker notes .

aroma - malty , some smokiness and coffee aromas . some yeast influence , but brief . not bad , just not inspiring . great .  appearance wise it might be the most beautiful ale . a dark clear ruby color .  a touch too much carbonation for my liking .

appearance - clear golden brown color with very nice 2 finger frothy head smell - wonderful citrus/hops scents .  poured into a duvel tulip ( fitting i think ) a fairly clear golden color with a big fully white head that slowly recedes leaving lace along the way .  full bodied with low carbonation that made it feel a bit flat and dull , mild astringency and a bit of warmth . the texture was pretty good even with the low carbonation .

honey , caramel and dark roast coffee taste . not alot in the nose , slight hint of coffee .  gorgeous , i can hardly wait to drink this beer it looks so good ( i write that after having drank it ) . beautiful light read with perfectly accompanied head .  while not a huge fan of ipa 's i have tried several i 've enjoyed . i ended up regurgitating the three sips back into the glass . the worst beer i have ever tried to drink .

i gave it taste - it smells like port wine - not like any other irs , or any other beer for that matter .  poured a beautiful amber color , crystal clear with 2 finger head thatleft great lacing in its wake .  the mouthfeel is light also and thin .

s - overall , a restrained nose . light amounts of 2-row and some english noble hops .  the color is really fantastic on this one , a deep reddish brown with a fantastic , yet thin , layer of head that does n't quit .  at the downtown chicago rock bottom , they named it rooftop pilsner for its rooftop dining area ( with a fine view of all the much taller yuppie condos surrounding it ) . they had to brew this in a hurry following the may windstorm that blew their rooftop taps open , draining all of their serving tanks ! pretty good for a style which we 've all had bad examples of . fizzy head leaves a golden yellow color underneath . no off-flaveors to speak of . nice citrsy hop aroma which i found to be a little stronger after a scoop of salsa . a decent session beer .

so i 'm coming off a vacation ( cruise ) where all they had was mostly american/mexican balony beer ... i was jonesin ' for something with some taste and body ... ooohhh yes ... .had two bottles of samuel adams scotch ale chillin in the fridge ... .soldiers from a recent mixed pack ! this beer has a great malt flavor . its dark amber color and white head give way to perfect lacing as i drink down this wonderful libation . the drinkability and mouthfeel are excellent ... session ... no question ! could drink this all night long ! ! !  a - beautiful dark amber with tons of head - good 2 inches . retention is pretty good over the course , lacing sudsy but thick and a little web like .  like most light lagers , the only character to the smell and flavor comes from the malt , hops and water . there is a clear attention to the quality of ingredients , and a successful attempt at balance and smoothness . the mountain-filtered water imparts nothing offensive on the palate .

smell is clean and crisp , bit of sweetness . no alcohol in the nose .  it is really a nice looking beverage .  moderate to thin mouthfeel , carbonation is ok . my only problem with this is the mouthfeel was n't as creamy as i was expecting , but overall , a very nice stout .

smell : i 'm not too sold on the spices . i was hoping for a bit more here but its still not too disappointing taste : this is where the beer shines . overall : this is a fantastic beer . i love the fact that it was the first belgian beer commercially produced and if i was able to buy this i 'd hop on this pretty frequently .  black with a tan head , good retention , phenominal lace .  mouthfeel/drinkability- a very thin beer in general , the carbonation breaks early in the mouth , then goes quickly and smoothly down the throat .
a ruby red colour , with a nice smell to it too .  it pours a dark brown , almost black , color with a beautiful chocolate milk colored head .  mouthfeel is smooth , but this is kind of thin .

aroma is delicious , dark fruits , caramel , bread , a mild grassy hoppiness .  d- looks amazing and sure gets you effed up , but i was disappointed with the kaiser after being enlightened by the maharaja .  m - high carbonation , but a little watery .

s : flowery scent , hint of plums t : terrible .  poured into a pioneer stein ( # 42 , 2009 edition ) , formed a 2 1/2 '' frothy tan head over the slightly cloudy caramel hued brew . head falls slowly with an audible sizzle of bubbles bursting , with tons of lasting lace .  m-to me its a little thin to carry around this level of hops .

the aroma is okay with some caramelised malt and slightly metallic hops playing on the nose . not a lot really going on here .  lots of lacing and amazing retention s - a little coffee and smoke , and tons of fruity esters .  i found this beer to be one of the easiest-drinking beers i 've ever had . now , my review is flawed because i do n't believe i have any other saison/farmhouse ales to compare it to - this is my first . but from the description of the style , i expected something a bit more complex in flavor , and this was not complex at all . low abv combined with a mellow flavor equals very easy drinkability . for an every day summer beer , i 'd choose this hands down over the bmc beers ; unfortunately this runs $ 32 a case , so it could be come an expensive habit .

a-clear yellow , no carbonation s-i had a hard time picking out any flavors but some grain flavors are present . t-some lemon flavors , not much bitterness but it is there also has some wheat in it as well . m-also rather light d-rather drinkable , easily sessionable . there are better out there but nothing in the beer seems like it could offend anyone .  it pours a dense ink black with an amazing looking dual tone caramel/tan head .  on the tongue , everything that was on the nose is amplified , bigger , bolder , stronger , more . the body was a bit different than typical , a touch more syrupy and thicker . still nice but not what i 'm really looking for in a wit .

the smell was very minimal , but some malt could be detected .  joyful bubbles ( yes , even the bubbles are happy ) climb up the sides of the glass , a very lively brew for sure .  m : fairly light , slick body with a low amount of spiky carbonation . mediocre .

nose a light musty toasty straw and wheat like , light crisp lager , light sweetness , very light nose .  fantastic presentation . very light and frothy head over orange-yellow .  m : this is where this beer turns a bit down for me . to me this tastes a bit undercarbonated , making the mouthfeel a bit watery for me .

not much scent coming off this , sweet and a little nutty . good craftsmanship that pushes just to the edge of pallate overload .  appearance : jet black with a huge billowy lingering lacing head .  mouthfeel medium mouthfeel with carbonation that is just over the top in my judgment .

smell is not too good . funked and skunked with a little bit of bo in there . tastes better than it smells . lagery with a touch of strawberry .  500ml bottle with batch code 5368. tasted in late april 2009. very dark , brownish amber . lots of thick tan head , which recedes very , very slowly to creamy wisps and a foamy ring . amazing lace for a bock !  the mouthfeel was a little thin , watery which is my only complaint , i expected a bit more of a robust feel to it .

s : lightly grainy malt aromas balanced well with some slightly herbal/spicy hops and a bit of light fruitiness . a bit bland , but not bad at all . t & m : clean grainy , lightly sweet malt flavor is quickly cut by a spicy hop flavor from the saaz hops .  a - deep brown black with 4cm thick cream head that last to end of the glass .  m : a bit dry . average carbonation .

very light sweet malt and floral hops hops are a bit light but nice little flavors . fairly full , carbonation has a bit of bite not bad , i was thinking it would be a bit more but its pretty easy to drink and the low abv is pretty nice .  the foam stopped exactly at the top of my perfect pour glass , nice trick . it 's a pretty ruby red color with moderate carbonation .  this is truly a one-of-a-kind beer . the aroma is purely apricot . the taste has the essence of fruit with a dry ale finish . it has a lot of flavor , but that flavor does not linger , making it possible to drink quite a bit of this beer in a session . if you have not tried this yet , try it . you 'll either love it or hate it .

the smell was not remarkable - average at best .  appearance : this is a gorgeous looking brew , amazing head retention it just about sticks everywhere .  medium carbonation and a slight astringency .

s - mostly sweet hops . it 's not a very overpowering smell .  pours clear dark brown color with a huge 3 finger light tan head with fantastic retention , that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts .  m - medium to light bodied . it 's just thinner than i expected .

sierra nevada esb pale brown with a fluffy slight off-white head . slight herbaceous hops and pale malt balance . extremely refined bitter , clean and crisp overall with a wonderful malt balance . carbonated and defined upfront with a sticky pine hoppiness , feint grass , caramel and pale malt along with a clean aftertaste . just a very well made esb , easy to drink , and tasty . recommended .  pours thick with a nice big head that lasts and lasts .  mouthfeel is pretty average .

i pour this chilled sample into my pint glass and the hop aroma hits me immediately . but back to the appearance first . the aroma is dominated by hops , floral scents first then i pick up hiints of pine and some sour citrus notes too . i get a quick hint of sweetness coming through and then the hops take over .  a - dark as a new moon night and no light penetrates the pint glass full .  the mouth feel is very dense and viscous that is entirely too syrupy . a little too thick to be enjoyed , but if you can separate the mouth feel from the flavor , youre in for a treat .

nice prominent frsh citrusy hop aroma . west coast style apa all the way . a nice apa but a bit light in body ... ( $ 1.89 / 12 oz .  poured this classic from a bottle , dark brown with thick creamy off white head .  mouthfeel is very light , a little watery , with a somewhat crisp feel to it .

this was my first try at a scotch ale and i found that i really liked it . the smell and mouthfeel were nothing special to me as it smelled and felt like a typical malty beer .  very nice lacing . o : the appearance of this beer was outstanding . beautiful !  but overall , mouthfeel was ok. after having a couple bottles of this in the past , felt this was a terrific sixtel to kick off the summer .

smell - very faint bitter malts with some chocolate tones . taste - malty and chocolaty , but the cocoa type .  half dark brown liquid half egg cream like foam . staying power is somewhat exceptional .  carbonation is too high , but it tastes pretty clean and fresh .

light toasty malt is about all i get from the aroma . maybe it 's just a style of beer i do n't appreciate , but i 'm not impressed yet . lightly toasted grains with subtle hop bitterness . fairly clean flavor over all with a bright crisp bitterness . a nice sweetness and subtle fruitiness . what impresses me most is the clean freshness to this beer . it 's a very solid oktoberfest beer with a nice toasted malt profile and slight hop character , but unfortunately i 'm not a huge fan of most lagers .  this beer is a dark golden color and leaves a perfect head when poured into a glass .  m - even , with a slight bitter aftertaste .

really stong , and just a rich nose in general .  pours that customary imperial stout used-motor oil black - totally opaque - while yielding a solid 1 '' mocha-toned head ; surprisingly great retention and lots of lacing . wow , what an appearance - even in a style where it can be tough to stand out .  surprisingly carbonated mouthfeel , with a finish of coffee , slight taste of alcohol and dark chocolate . if there is any drawback to this beer , it is the carbonation .

appearance- dark black with a bit of carbonation and a moderate tan head , smell- slightly roasted malts and slight hop smell not a very overpowering smell at all taste- i really like the taste of this beer , its a mix of slight roasted malts and chocolate and espresso tones mixed with crispness and slight hop bitterness of a lager , its a great combination and each sip is very enjoyable , a unique combo mouthfeel- light crisp and refreshing with good carbonation , just very smooth drinking drinkablitly- i find this drink from the can to be just so incredible in drinkability , its so refreshing and so enjoyable , its something i often now seek out for a unique and refreshing beer , and it has to be stated that it such a value !  poured a beautiful dark amber with a nice head .  the mouthfeel of the beer was a bit on the lighter side , but still acceptable .

s - very faint of the barrel it was aged in . faint rasin and citrus .  a huge cottony off white head with some pretty fantastic lacing leaving a magnificent cling down the glass . quite a sight ! when swirled the foam becomes a frothy cap on top of the beer .  sampled at the paper city brewery on free beer night . i know that this beer was free so i should n't complain about it but there was something wrong with this beer . my guess is this was a bad keg otherwise they brewed it with their dirty gym socks . reflection : i know that this is a harsh review but unless you were there that night and tried it you ca n't understand the horror of this beer .

appearance-amber color with an off white head with an amazing amount of lacing smell- a very weak malt smell taste- an amazing carmel malt taste . very sweet with a hint of bitter .  pours with a dark brown to black body topped by a thick creamy tan head with good lacing .  mouthfeel is average for the size of the beer , and quite drinkable .

aroma is completely covered by the smell of my not so expensive glassware . color is a slow yellow with visible carbonation around the sides that comes out when drinking .  has little carbonation and a small whitish head that dissipates into a milk mustache ... a beautiful auburn color that diffracts the light .  mouthfeel is rather light with less than medium carbonation .

s - i 'm picking up some slight caramel malts and a bit of spiciness . not alot of aroma going on here t - but then it hits you ... big malty taste , nice sweetness with molasses , some coffee and brown sugar . the aroma leaves no hint of whats to come .  the carbonation in this beer is incredible , it looks like the beer is alive .  the mouthfeel is slightly thin and foams up in the mouth a little ; the beer needs some sort of aeration .

solventy alcohol and toffee are all i really pick up in the aroma . it 's odd that i ca n't pick up the coriander in the aroma , because it 's actually quite prominent in jacobites flavour .  a - beautiful completely opaque dark copper , beautiful fluffy white head . its rare to see a ipa this dark .  the woodiness also makes an subtle appearance on the finish mf : very very very high carbonation on this which is sharp on the tongue but seems to work well for the sourness on the palate .

it has a small spice smell with a bit of sweet malts in there not impressed with smell , other than that the taste is quite refreshing the mouthfeel was a little lighter that i had hoped but overall a good winter ale .  with a dark caramel color , large bubbles and good lacing , it was certainly something to look at .  m : the feel is thick and a bit undercarbonated . the carbonation issues detract from the beer slightly though .

smell : you can smell the candylike hoppiness , and this gives you the impression it would taste like the smell , but it does n't . taste : hop on the palet , does not really hit the nose , and lingers in the throat , not very pleasant .  medium amber with a big , tight head that does n't seem to recede at all throughout . tons of lacing . tiny , tiny bubbles rising all the while . man this looks inviting .  similar to points cascade pale ale where the hop just shines right through and you taste the hops in every swig . the abv has to be pretty low cuz it was a little watery tasting . but overall a great refreshing , thirst quenching summer brew . i 'm guessing the batch was limited , cuz i heard horizon hops are in real short supply .

s- a slight malt smell , had trouble smelling much from it though .  this stout is thoroughly unique . it pours exceptionally dark - no light creeps in even around the edges .  mouthfeel- thin body with medium carbonation .

had this on tap a few times today at septemberfest in dublin ... a : nice golden color with a small head ... s : not much aroma aside from some grassy smelling hops ... t : nice full taste , the bitterness is there but the hop flavor is not very pronounced ... m : crisp , very nice .  into a stemmed brooklyn glass , poured a cloudy golden hue , with nearly three fingers of bright white , with fantastic head retention and great lacing .  the pluses : the mouthfeel is ok , it looks very good , fruity appearance with a white head . but the taste is sourish and horrid , and something i could not bring myself to have much of .

the smell was average at best with some sour cherry and bit of malt . overall another good and very unique brew from smuttynose .  a : poured a nice clear amber & selective yellow body with a creamy one fingered head , rises nicely . the lacing on this is outstanding . t : that lasting head gives this a strong creamy hoppy taste .  mouthfeel was kind of thin and light and the blueberries gave it an intense sweetness that would make it hard for me to want much of .

the aroma is very light , small amounts of hops but that 's pretty much it .  not even the same name , but anyway ... appearance : opaque , glorious deep orangey gold with big white head receding to leave heavy lacing .  m - the mouthfeel is average for a porter .

aroma is grainy , fruity and sweet . light hops .  pours a beautiful deep dark mahogony with dark cherry barely peeking out on the edge if held up to a light an awesome thick rock light brown head rushed to the top of the glass .  m : a tad overcarbonated , a bit watery , medium-light body . a bit astringent .

poured from the bottle into a wide mouth pint a-pours dark black nice big head with very good retention and nice sticky lace s-nose is pretty subtle rosted malt , with small alcohol and chocolate notes .  pours a brown/chestnut with 3+ fingers of rocky sand colored head . outstanding head retention & lacing s : bready , roasty , & nuttyness t : bready , roasty malt , & dryness up front .  i 'm so sorry , but i do n't see what everyone else does in this beer . the malt flavor is too aggressive and tastes over-toasted . in this case , both flavors are too aggressive . still , in all departments i find it profoundly below average , except maybe appearance and mouthfeel , which are standard ( gold with a tinge of brown and not too oily , respectively ) . this is just one of those beers i ca n't get into .

there was not much smell other than hints of grain .  as dark as a moonless desert night , the head is quite modest in size , the texture spumescent , light chocolate in color and as it degrades leaves behind a fine coating of lace upon the glass .  carbonation was ok , but with the heavier than expected mouthfeel , i think the hops were lost on the palate more than others textures .

aroma : having a hard time getting a nose on this . maybe because there are too many other smells around me in the kitchen , but i 'm picking up a sweetness and perhaps some corn ? honestly i 'm not detecting much .  the body is deep black and holds a huge ; two fingers thick , mocha head that is so thick and lasting it almost looks like it is brooding .  this is way to watered down for me . mouthfeel and drinkability : finishes somewhat dry . this brew also has a super light body with higher levels of carbonation-okay , these are appropriate for the style .

the aroma is a of light herbal yeasts , with pleasant fruit notes . there is a definite musty , skunky undertone .  pours black and appears to be clear if one could see through it , a big tan/light brown head rests without much thought to receding above this moderately carbonated ale .  mouthfeel is okay , but needs to be either thicker or creamier to work with the taste -- as is , it 's just a tad watery .

a : orange hued , 1/4 '' head s : not a lot going on , primarily hoppy pine aromas . t : very pleasant .  appearance - wow at first it looked like a coffee milk shake , but after it settled it was a pitch black color with a creamy tan head .  mouthfeel is light with low carb , which is nitro 's biggest downfall in my opinion . this is a delicious beer , with the only bummer being the lighter , undercarbonated body .

strong aromas of diacetyl contribute a definitely distinct aroma of butterscotch & butter , though it is not at the rancid butter stage .  poured an opaque dark baker 's chocolate brown with a slow rising tan head that fills the glass and stays up forever yeilding a thick wall of lace , just beautiful . and that 's just after the pour , i hav n't even smelled it yet !  i think this means that the same strain of yeast is used . anyway here 's what i thought . they have chucked a lot more than hops into this . well i 've got a case to get through and i 'm not going to throw it away . if my opinion of this improves , if i acquire the taste , well i 'll let you know !

aroma has sweet candied sugar and caramel malts on top of the belgian yeast backbone . dark fruits come through as it warms .  pours like it 's worth the mad duckets . inky , opaque black with a full brownie colored soapy stout head that absolutely will not die no matter who tries to kill it .  a very strong and thick mix of bannana and cloves , both interlace and dominate in a very very pleasing way . despite the heavy mouhtfeel , it is very light and very drinkable . imo , only downside is the aftertaste , a little messy and thick , but still , a very nice hefe .

exactly what a stout should have . s - light carmel and hops . not as full .  appearance : opaque pitch black with a chocolately head . beautiful .  it 's rare that i ca n't even stomach a beer long enough to get a few sips down . this beer gave me one of those rare moments . the smell was a sour , and the taste was dirty and skunky . i did n't want to waste the pack , so i made a couple of michelada cocktails . they were actully quite tasty.. nothing like worcestershire and tabasco to make something taste better !

s : belgian malt ( fig-like ) , fruity ( some banana ) , but with a clean , almost solventy smell . t : very nice belgian malt flavour .  the color is as promised - not just copper , but the most refined , polished expression of crystalline copper purity you 've ever seen in an ale . the head is feathery and shows graceful retention and lace .  full body with slightly too high carbonation .

i just busted my first bomber of this brew , and i do n't know if this bottle is past its freshness date or not , but this might be the worst beer i 've ever tasted . incredibly sour , with no redeeming flavor quality at all .  bottle , from whole foods in tustin , ca , a : pours a dark maroon red , with a thick rich cap of white foam , great head retention , extensive thick lacing .  mouthfeel - average crispness , moderately thin body , i 'm okay with it .

very caramelly and a little bit cloying . big floral , citrusy hops . firm hop bitterness is just a little lower than i 'd expect from a west coast brewed ipa , but very smooth nonetheless .  poured amber colour with creamy white head which retains well and has good lacing .  this beer drinks very easily ; it is actually pretty light on the mouthfeel , a little creamy smooth , but mostly just light .

i guess i was expecting something like a lemon version of buffalo bills orange cream ale , which i though was a relatively good balance between the beer and fruit flavors . saranac would have been better off calling this a shandy or something other than `` brew '' . anyway for what it 's worth : a - golden yellow , average top..looks like beer s - get some lemon , but still could be beer t & m - really no beer here , not even a decent lemon flavor , overly sweet , cloying . finish is syrupy and well ... just bad d - drainpour this concept works well with ice tea , not so much with lager ...  absolutely stunning pour .  mouthfeel is a little thin ( but then again , what do you want from a wheat beer ) with tangy carbonation .

not much carbonation as is expected with this hand pumped beer . the flavor is rich with cirus , orange , hops , mixed malts i suspect , cream , raisin sead and a sweet yeasty flavor . this is a good ipa and if i could get it everyday in a cask-conditioned state , i would drink it often .  for something that is this old to have this much carbonation . i am fucking impressed . a two finger off white head is standing proud over this dark red body . so good .  a delicious golden red , mild mannered taste and aromatic bloom are all qualities of this beer . widely available in all super markets and at a good price . this beers fits in well with any dinner menu . it is n't as hoppy and bitter as its west coast conterparts but still a very excellent beer . sam adams offers a huge variety of different beers so it is easy to good a feel for how they brew their beer and their taste philosophies .

s : very little aroma , i 'm just not getting much there . a subtle hint of caramel is about all i 'm picking up . t : a bit of caramel . toasted malts .  the color is a deep mohagony with a very thick foamy head and lots of lace .  it tastes like a quadrupel ... .vinous , lots of sticky caramel malts , somewhat flat mouthfeel ( which i 'm never all that fond of ... i wish quads could be more prickly somehow ) ... but again , the addition of the slightly sour cherry keeps this from being a garden-variety quad .

good smell , not strong , lemons , malt .  pours with a very healthy light tan head ... .some molasses , burnt caramel aroma ... dark ruby red ... quite smoky on the first sip , which develops some delicious flavours ! ... alcohol is very well masked ... leaves some great lacing ... some will find it abit thin but i find it very drinkable and way to easy to drink , this sixer will be gone very quick !  the body seems a bit lighter than i would have expected .

a light coffee aroma and not much carbonation . very drinkable and one of my favorites .  2006 vintage batch 2 16.03 % abv poured black as the background of ba into a southern tier imperial glass , tan fluffy fine bubbled head rose quickly and fell jest as fast leaving a nice topping of bubble . not exactly sessionable but it makes you marvel at stouts like black albert with nearly as much alcohol that can hide it as well as they do .  it was very astringent .

the ice axe was enjoyable and easy-going , but was not what i was expecting for a west coast ipa . the aroma was mainly sweet fruity esters typical of a british ale yeast , with a fair amount of malt , but overall rather mild . there was very little hop aroma or taste , certainly not the bright citrus or pine flavors often found in oregon , just a bitter firmness to balance out the finish , nothing in your face .  beautiful looking beer .  to me smelled like wheat/grain , nuts . t : taste just like you would expect , after smelling . d : pretty good beer , surpassed my expectations . could drink this one all night and be satisfied !

s - very light . some malt and hops . t - strong hops , sweet caramel , good alcohol burn in the finish .  bottle courtesy of hopdog : poured a light amber color lager with a super huge foamy head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is highly carbonated and drying , as it should be .

s -- from the bottle i got a malty fruity sweetness , from the glass i got a metallic scent .  bottle : poured a clear deep brown color ale with a nice huge foamy head with good retention and some nice lacing .  not a big wit guy , but it is summer in san diego and i just got done playing some b ball and was thirsty . i always see it at places and not big on most japanese breweries . very refreshing and complex at the same time . over all i am glad i tried it and i am actually going to buy a pack down the street right now .

s : was expecting a little more here . no real discernable hop aroma , perhaps just a faint whiff of malt . the alcohol level in this definitely allows this beer to be sessionable if wanted , but i enjoyed taking my time to savor this great west coast pale ale . my last thoughts on this are , if stone can make a pale ale with this much going on , what on earth must arrogant bastard taste like ?  incredably dark with a massive nesquick colored head , and some burnt bubbles on top .  yes officer i have been drinking tonight as a matter a fact i have a fuck of a lot to drink tonight , i think 12 beers but i ca n't remember . yes i will take a breathalyzer and a blood test . yes my breath does smell like hops . no your machines are n't broken , i forgot to mention the beers i was drinking are 0.5 % alcohol by volume .

sporadic sloches of soapy lacing left behind . citrus hop aroma with hints of pine and citrus fuit balanced out by some sweet caramel malt . very hoppy for the style with a bitter piney hop blast up front which is balanced by a nice caramel malt backbone . i 'm also picking up slight hints of rye .  '' a- dark mahogany/black and opaque . ~3 fingers of creamy , cascading tan head . loads of sticky lacing . beautiful .  medium bodied slick mouthfeel , slightly cloying .

try getting them to drink a belgium ; ) do n't get me wrong i like incredibly hoppy beer , but you know i 've forgotten how nice a well balanced ipa can be . smell was perhaps a little lacking . but a very pleasing beer .  poured a rich 3 finger head , blacker than the blackest black times infinity .  medium to thin in the body . i thought the carbonation seemed a bit to high and lessened my enjoyment of this brew .

s : bright clean rye smell , nothing particularly stands out at first . as it warms i detect a funky belgian-like banana aroma . t : wowza , this tastes like whiskey !  black oily pour with a medium dark brown head .  mouth feel is medium bodeid really dry with a fair amount of carbonation .

s : floral and very very sweet . strong raspberry scent coming though .  appearance is fantastic ... .my whole glass fills with head as i begin to pour . wonderful lacing , beautiful dark brown with amber hue in color smell and taste are of sweet malt , with a bit of alcohol , and in the taste there was some raisin flavoring mouthfeel was good .  m- i found the body to be medium , maybe a tad full bodied for apa , but the carbonation was significantly lacking on this one . i think a bit more rye presence and more carbonation would have moved this beer up quite a bit for me .

corn and a stinging , antiseptic-like aroma were the main components . of course , this got worse as the beer got warmer . and the smell is bad .  what a great looking beer , so dark and the head is big and beautiful and sticks around with some lacing .  mouthfeel : a bit dry on the finish and the aftertaste . little carbonation , and a bit sticky . decent but not special .

the smell of this brew is lightly fruity and a faint touch of citrus that quickly dissolves . more smells reveal a bit of cereal grain to biscuit sweetness or crackers to the aroma . the taste is lightly fruity that blends into a biscuit type of grainy sweetness . while i would probably not seek this one out , it would make for a fine brew to pair with some brats and you could effortless throw a couple of these back if you did n't care about what you were drinking .  pours a dark brown with a nice one inch of tan head after a gentle pour . retention was excellant with plenty of lacing .  this is an epl through and through . do n't be persuaded by the pilsener title . i had it after a holsen which is a real grain bomb . neither beer is that great but this one seemed inferior . and compared to holsten permium that is n't saying much . i you like stella artois or heineken or something like that in a can then go or it , but it is n't too good .

s - the aroma is very burnt , but there is some fruitiness towards the back . little aroma of yeast .  pours a deep purple sort of like a red wine color with a one finger pinkish purple head . the head recedes to skim and leaves gobs of lacing up and down the glass .  m : the only real cavet of the brew is the feel . but it 's generally a bit thin .
the aroma is fairly subdued , with a touch of malt a caramel .  pours dark and thick like motor oil with a thick fluffy dark brown head .  mouthfeel : it was a very light beer .

the smell is very subdued , almost faint . there are some tart cherries , some vinegar sour notes and maybe some soft grape skins way down deep . the taste is much more bold than the smell .  appearance is an inviting cloudy golden yellow with an outstanding pillow head and great lacing .  4.5 m a bit on the thin side .

poured into my westy chalice , which is much easier to find than any of their actual ales ... a : opaque brown , except when held up to a bright light : this gives a warm , deep glowing amber color . s : sweet caramel . dark malts . not bad , just undistinguished .  pours very very black . big two and a half finger head . the light brown head dissipates rather quickly leaving a thin layer on top of a black ocean of goodness .  a beer haiku for you : '' norwegian beer ? yes ! a great ipa option , seek out and find one ! '' my first norwegian [ that 's what she said ] . nice citrus overtones , not too 'hoppish ' , and very drinkable . a rare find , but well worth the money to have another option .

s : the aromas are not bold ( though this one has sat a year ) but what is there is rather nice . nice sweet brown sugar with notes of cinnamon and nutmeg . a light fruit juice aroma that i ca n't quite put my finger on . t : wow , this is one wonderful brew .  the first pour is exceptional - perfect rate of head formation , looks absolutely great in the glass - liquid gold .  t & m : slightly alcoholic bite at first . very fizzy taste of citrus with a somewhat sour lemony wheat taste . d : very fizzy so will fill ( bloat ) you quickly . exemplary of the style .

very long lasting had nose is small . hops present but fairly undefined . a little rich for the style .  a serious black hole of a beer . a dark , burnt 1 finger mocha head forms and sticks around . great lacing as well . the best head i have ever encountered on a beer .  this 'beer ' is weak . this 'beer ' is flavourless . no wait , i can taste some corn syrup , and what 's that ... pickle juice ? honestly , i think i taste hints of pickle juice !

s : dried fruits , bready ... not very strong but nice . sweet ( ish ) .  once again that exemplar color for a porter or a stout , black walnut brown , to ebony with a elephantine , head , and lace so thick you can cut it with a knife , both light chocolate in color .  good , predictable macro carbonation , not too fizzy , and a softly crisp , dry , thin , light bodied mouthfeel , average , to be expected , nothing to really complain about here , again , predictable , you know what you getting before you pop open the can .
the aroma is sweet and full of rotten fruit ( yuck !  huge sheets of lacing and good retention .  m - disappointing , frankly .

a bit of a gusher at first sip s_slightly bready . a bit mild t_huge banana bread flavours up front . d_not sure if this fits into the category but like a lot in the brooklyn brewmasters reserve it is a tasty crossover of styles . this is almost more of a dunkelweizen mixed with a dubbel to me and perhaps too sweet to drink too many of .  a nice looking beer .  had this on top at ye olde boise brewer 's festival 2007 ; enjoyed the beer and enjoyed talking with the brewmaster , who seems to care quite a bit about what he 's doing . this is an extremely pleasant summer fruit beer , and contrary to what has been noted by previous reviewers , i did n't get the sense that the fruit flavor was from any sort of unnatural source . this could have something to do with it being on tap , and therefore theoretically fresher . it did come across very much like other orange tinged wheat beers ; nothing remarkably different , but a very drinkable beer regardless .

s : a clean aroma of orange peel and wheat . the smell is n't super strong .  pours a great looking dark brown color with a nice off white two finger head that gives way to good retention and lacing .  m : a bit light and quite fizzy for the style .

s : not much of one . faint aroma ... malt maybe ? t : corn , grain , maybe some faint hop bitterness . d : with the exception of a total lack of flavor or aroma , no big complaints .  felt sneaky drinking a quintessential american pale in an english pub . clear straw color with a thick and creamy white head . peppery skim retention puts up the most impressive display of lacing that i have ever seen on a pale .  overall quite mouthfilling , cakey , dangerously smooth and rounded . the beer takes a bit of a down turn towards the end as the flavors fizzle a bit and the beer seems to thin out and go a bit watery . mouthfeel , while not ever being truly creamy , comes close with real soft and smooth carbonation .

smells doughy with a bit of teriyaki ? theres also a bit of citrus and pear but i still get a bit of teriyaki , but not in a bad way . much maltier than i expected in flavor with noticable alcohol . im thinking this would go well with a smoked gouda .  1in off-white creamy foamy later with great retention , bubbles rise through the slightly hazy brew turning the head into swiss cheese with chunks of wispy wavy lace on the glass .  feel : the carbonation seems to take over much of the mouthfeel vs the flavor .

releasing southampton 's altbier from captivity put its exquisite reddish copper hue on display . as the head began to dissipate , a nutty , slightly sweet aroma presented itself . traces of grain and yeast also pulled through , leaving behind any significant hop aromas . though perhaps appropriate for the style , the aroma seemed too subtle to appreciate . mellowed from extended conditioning and with a balanced , though slightly sweet flavor profile , this altbier makes for an exceptional session beer .  nice downward bubbles on pour ... dark brown to black with a slight ruby edge , a tan creamy nitro head , and lace like wallpaper .  refreshing ale , i have only recently started drinking ales as a regular drink recently . the sa gold i have is my brothers and id rather rate my ale by , if i grabed another one or not ... i drank 4 bottles last night : ) im guessing this is quite and average ale as fursty ferret tastes remarkbly the same and thats what im going to use as my `` beer to rate by '' or mean `` beer '' id recomend this beer if you saw it available .

quite subdued in the aroma . notes of citric hops , big eathy nose , some mustiness and a softened roasted grain . nothing special going on here , and certainly not when compared to the rest of the beer 's characteristics . finish is try with roasted notes and grain .  appearance- golden honey , beautiful color in the pils glass . no unattractive , excessive bubbling . a nice head formed during the pour and lasted the duration of my drink . there was a significant amount of lacing on the sides of the glass .  low carbonation and medium in the mouth . average feel .

nose is a bit subdued . musty hops - orange rind , oak , floral notes .  pours a nice cloudy golden amber with a big two finger white fluffy head that slowly fades to about one finger and it 's sticking around with a bit of lacing .  m - syrapy with a decent carbonation .
not much aroma that i can pick up , a touch of sweet maltiness though .  a perfect look for an impy .  m : smooth & a little flat ( thanks to the nitro i 'm sure ) .

sweet caramel smelling but with a tiny hint of metal .  a beautiful looking beer . there is a milky-white cloudiness to this beer that is oddly appealing .  it is a harsh raunchy smell , with a fizzy spoiled fruit flavor . they taste is no improvement this is no beer and if you cant count hard ciders malt beverages should be no different .

s - nice mix of bread , malt and roasted coffee , no hops -- just right for the style .  pours a slightly cloudy reddish brown with a gorgeous light tan head with amazing , photographic-quality lacing along the sides of my cab glass .  mouthfeel is smooth . so it gets an average score .

smell is average , mostly roasted malts . a very good tasting beer ... tastes like a stout , but not nearly as heavy .  the head is a nice light tan , and leaves incredible lacing . the body lets through just a bit of ruby light in an otherwise jet body .  nothing special for the style on the palate but still quite good ; frothy but not especially thick . smooth enough and tasty enough to drink in quantity , one of the better weissbiers for sure but not quite the best .

aromas were very thin and a hint of skunkiness , but not bad .  appearance : beautiful copper color , not orange ... nice fluffy off white foam and extreme lace left !  the mouthfeel is a little crisp but does smooth out .

aroma does n't reveal much with faint hints of dry hay , cardamon , ginger and cocoa . flavorful , spicy with juicy hopiness , light malt , spice -- mostly ginger and clove -- and apple .  a : opaque black , showing dark brown at the edges , with over one finger of diminishing beige foam head . heavy lacing remains on the glass .  the mouthfeel is thin with a watery texture , and lively carbonation .

s : sweet malt and faint hops , citrus , earthy . m : light to medium body with nice , lively carbonation . t : sweet barley malt followed by mild , grassy saaz hops .  pours a golden yellow with about a finger and a half of rich , creamy head . the foam is thick and retains very well , and leaves behind some impressive lacing .  the mouthfeel is like nothing i 've tasted before ... kinda an awkward feel . '' not necessarily bad , but just very different and weird feeling .

light aroma . love that . sweet and dark upfront . lovely .  12oz bottle , freshness date 07/09 poured into pint glass : a : amazing . hazy , deep golden color .  deep red-brown color with amazing billowy off-white head : thick and lasting with good lacing s : hoppy and malty balance with yeasty notes and spices t : orange and nutmeg maltiness with a hoppy bitter finish m : a little thin , but this is towards the end of its season by now .

good taste and average smell but nothing real distinctive .  easily the most impressive appearance of any single ipa ive had . perfectly clear deep amber in color . an average pour yields a 1 1/2 head that hangs around for a minute leaving lace on nearly every area it touched .  taste : flavor of the hops becomes present late in the beginning , and remain throughout the middle and finish ; the tangy undertones are forward followed by a sweeter sensation , finishing with a bittersweet lingering .

s : bready kind of sweet malt with some faint bitter hops and even fainter citric notes . t : sweet bready malt , light roasted . d : a german pilsener that 's weak in smell but otherwise a nice example of the style .  appearance- poured a luscious fist of a head into my mug . the head retention was very good . the beer poured a cloudy , deep garnet brown with a lot of lacing .  mildly thin body , but not alarmingly so .

s- i was n't able to get that strong of a smell from this beer . it taste like roasted spices . d- it was a good beer as far as pumpkin beers go .  spezial weisse looks about as good as any hefeweizen con look .  medium mouth feel , with decent drinkablity

nice complex but balanced smell . t : very complex . overall a very good , complex beer .  this brew produces big bright white and rocky head . the body is hazy with a white/gold colored body .  m- not its most impressive trait , actually evokes a macro in its carbonation level and texture .

s : not much to speak of here . faint phenolic character ... fruity notes . t : complexity is evident and enjoyable .  the head is full and thick fading a lingering creme like a great espresso . lacing on the glass is wonderful .  m - moderate to thin body - the backbone appears to be driven by its hefty carbonation .

smell is of yeasty esters with a grainy background . there is a hint of a vinous character in the smell , a characteristic of the yeast i think . taste is smooth but rich and complex dry roasted maltiness with an earthy character and a hint of bittersweet .  this irish stout is pasteurized , pressurized , draught style , in a 1 pint can and pours a beatifully authentic pub draught style creamy head with a pitch black body . the taste of the body of the beer is a bit thin for a stout and felt somewhat metallic on the palate , however , the rich creamy head offsets this upon mixing your mouth . i would say this stout is much better than the overrated guinness but if you want the real stout experience , go for young 's double chocolate , samuel smith 's or north coast .  mouthfeel is smooth but i couldnt drink a ton of this . thinner than other milk stouts or impy stouts but not a bad change of pace .

the smell was fantastic though , sweet and yeasty .  heavenly looks of a brew with a king kong head that lives forever and a gorgeous dark golden hue of hidden treasure proportions.breathtaking aroma of manure , hay , and farm grass .  mouth feel is medium bodied , but i think it could use a bit more carbonation .

s : smells of chocolate and very little else . it 's not very strong but the scent is there without needing to completely submerge the nose . t : it tastes very chocolaty , and roasty .  it pours a beautiful deep gold/orange , crystal clear .  the mouthfeel is a bit less but certainly the best `` light '' beer i have found thus far .

i was underwhelmed on first try of this brew . i find that a heavy , yeasty aroma masks most the fruit and malt notes .  pours a beautiful red/brown with a creamy tan head .  mouthfeel - average to thin body which could be better . subdued carbonation which i kind of prefer for this coffee stout style .

very easy to drink . a lot of flavor but still very smooth . good winter hefeweizen , not too light ! !  a : looks great . black with a 1/2 '' thick dark brown head .  m - the feel is sharp initially with a chalky and sublime salty finish on the palate .

easy light drink , bit much on water , particularly with lower alcohol . a bit of bite -molasses and hoppy . liked : only mildly roasty , only bit of the coffee , and hint of chocolates and nutty . very good stout .  [ /rant ] anyways , this canary-bottled 12ozer pours out a nice glossy black with ruby highlights when inspected closely against a light . it has a beautiful pillow brown head that is signifcantly large when poured , and remains quite nice all the way down . this might just have the best lacing i have ever seen .  m : a little spritzy and thin for my taste .

aroma is muted and not really impressive .  here we go ... this stout arrived at my table just as i remembered . very dark brown ( almost black ) , fine bubbles just churning away in the liquid . the whole inner surface is completely coated with creamy foam ... not resembling lace at all . this may not be the best tasting stout , but is sure is the best looking .  clarity 's good , color 's nice but there 's no lasting head to speak of and i could n't really taste malt or hops . it 's sort of like an odd flavored soda pop . miller is one of the many traditional american 'who cares they all taste the same ' beers . i suspect that it 's a pretty healthy dose of cornstarch .

had a pint of this at the flying saucer in raleigh , nc , served from the tap . s- not much in the nose , a little floral hop , but not much . i 'd just had a dogfish head 90min ipa , so there was a very noticable difference in the big aroma of the 90 to this one . t-surprisingly good considering the lack of nose i was getting .  cockeyed cooper pours a clear garnet color into the glass with a massive , frothy off white head on top .  carbonation is medium to medium-heavy , and mouthfeel is slightly viscous , landing just north of water .

appearance : amber color with a 1/2 '' off-white head ; looks really good smell : little bit of hops ; some kind of weird smell ( maybe some caramel malt ?  love it when a beer looks imposing enough to quell dreams .  my first rye . the smell struck me as among the likes of a strong imperial ipa . yet the taste was a lot less hoppy than ipas , more typical average beer . and yes i 'd say there are some flavors in common with rye-based whiskey .
