nose is full of banana and coriander , though `` full '' may be an overstatement as the aroma is not particularly strong . the way i would put the taste ... peaceful banana . i 'm really enjoying this in mid-september as i 'm transitioning from summer ales to festbiers .  pours a dark , black coffee color with three fingers width of mocha colored head . reduced to a fingers width over consumption . great head retention and the lacing was so thick it just caked the sides of the glass .  m - body is a little thin and watery , but silky smooth from the oats d - this is a really good ris - i have been wanting to try it for a while now .

as i 've read in other reviews this beer it was extreamly carbonated . but by the third or forth gulp it was clear i loved this beer . unfortunately after a week after having this beer i 'm giving my review and i ca n't remember all the flavor notes , but i do remember this ... it had the darker toasted flavors of a stout or porter , but was absolutly refreshing with a very light mouthfeel . some friutyness , but it was subdued . there where plenty of other great brews on tap but i kept coming back for the orchard . some might find the carbonation a turn off but i think it really compliments this beer .  poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' tan head over the slightly cloudy reddish chestnut brew . head holds on with a miser 's grip , leaving incredibly thick layers of sticky froth .  a nice malty finish mouthfeel is a crisp and clean , quite a bit of carbonation , somewhat dry and sticky aftertaste . a bit more body would have made it excellent for it was a bit light a very drinkable beer .

970ml bottle poured into pint glass 25/8/11 a darker shade of maroon with a two finger mocha head that hangs around for a few minuets leaving lace where it existed s faint licorice and molasses pretty basic and i doubt this ice cold serving dose much to bring out the aroma t some prune with faint chocolate and coffee to go with what little i could smell , an improvement over the smell m enters silky and bubbles quickly give it some life , thin but enough carbonation to keep it from feeling flat o by far the best quilmes beer i 've had but that sadly means it 's pretty average perhaps my last pint in south america , i may have time for quite a few more if irene heads towards miami cancelling my flight .  bottle dated 2/9/11 a- dark black with a nice tan head s- coffee smell with some roastiness .  very poor example of an oktoberfest . there seems to be too much of the malt that gives oktoberfests their sweet syrupy quality . this beer is just too sweet and stinks of overly ripened rotten fruit . it has a pickle quality to it as well that i just cant stand . this was a hard beer to finish . undrinkable , and way too sickeningly sweet .

bready and somewhat sweet aroma along with some mild citrus hops . very nice and certainly refreshing .  bottle : poured a bright golden color ale with a large foamy head with excellent retention and some very nice lacing .  matching , but mild , after-taste m-medium creamy carbonation . somewhat watery finish . the carbonation really bothered me with this one also .

please dont be infected ... please dont be infected ... bottled 1/13/2010 ... smell is lovely with some alcohol scents and some great maltiness and chocolate ... but the taste ... dammit !  a- this one pours a beautiful ruby red colored body with a finger of bright white head on top . head lasts a while and leaves behind solid rings of lacing . perfect .  somewhat thin on the mouth , dale 's pale tastes like citrus hops , only a hint of malt . it 's crisp and clean , quite hoppy . a great example of the style , and very refreshing .

s - subtle coffee and cocolate aromas witha slight accent of anise .  this stout pours perfectly with mounds of tan head , which sticks well to the glass .  i hate to rate this beer so low but this is the crowning achievement in the awful stone collaborations . at first interesting and great saison taste , then the herbs kick in . every other sip is horrible . were they trying to brew grass ? 1st they brew a pepper ipa ? then a spice rack saison ? whats next in the grab a random ingredient from the kitchen a brew a beer collaboration . that being said , i will always support stone and its their choice to keep brewing whatever the hell they want .

not something the style is known for , but even less here , as the roast characteristics do n't really come through . just faint crackery malt and a trace of earthy spice . t -- much better than the nose . the malt on this is fantastic . pretty tannic , especially at the beginning , which makes it taste like tea with orange rind it .  hazy gold with an enormous amount of white foam that chunks and laces everywhere that it touches .  tasted in at the brewery on a breezy december day in tustin . aroma minimal . just a little bready . pale gold in color , minimal head . some chill haze . light body with a noticeable grain sweetness . a very easy touch of floral hops . an excellent example of a drinkable light ale .

scent is a bit floral , a bit bitter and ever so slightly nutty .  appearance : pours into my hennepin chalice a crystal clear pale gold color with a huge , loose-bubbled , white head . the becomes very rocky as it drops leaving tons of lacing down the side of the glass . this looks perfect .  the body does seema tad watery , i would expect more fo a `` fullness '' , but overall i feel the beer is a great scottish ale , overpoweringly malty , no hops that i could detect and pretty much no smoky presence which i can appreciate , since i 've had one too many smoky sottish style ales .

aroma was a blast of fresh hops . very fresh and nice . pretty nice balance for such a hop bomb .  creamy off-white head with rising bubbles . fluffy head - lacing is moderate - all lasting several minutes .  very mild flavor and mouthfeel , but very lively and well carbonated .

not much smell there , which is a huge letdown compared to everything else about this beer . faint slightly smoky smell with hints of chocolate . no real pepper smell , but you can actually feel a slight burn in your nose . t - chocolate , roasted malt , slight smoky flavor , and chipotle pepper in the background .  sundance is the best looking amber ale i 've ever seen . true to its name , it looks like a setting sun . the body is a deep , translucent amber with a pillowy , stable head sticky like melted marshmallow .  m : smooth and creamy , though lacking the body found in non-nitro stouts , not bad though , a fuller body than guinness .

aroma is somewhat roasty , but an inadequate prelude to the flavor , which is light and drinkable but also somewhat roasty .  this beer looks great , with a huge rocky and cream like head floating on a clear and golden orange sea of a well carbonated potation .  light-medium bodied , needs to be fuller .

nice hop aroma . nice citrus notes .  appearance - caramel , dark amber , deep and comforting after a long week . small but solid cap of medium cream colored head . impressive sheet lacing on the side .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .

likewise ale drinkers may order a smithwick 's with a guinness head . s - i rate every beers smell as average due to the fact that i can not smell t - smooth and refreshing . i am not a guinness draught fan but i am a smithwicks fan . o - p e r f e c t in every way possible  nice lacing . looks very thick .  m : the body is perhaps a touch watery with a surprisingly low carbonation .

hudy 14-k is a very very good 6.99/12 pack beer . it has a pretty nice head for such a light lager and is very crisp and refreshing . not much of a review needed for this one but overall , this is a very easy to drink beer with good flavor and at 6.99 , it 's a bargain . much better than any busch/pbr/natty beer .  bottled in hilo on the big island , the first thing noticeable about this beer is the crazy foaming head -- super tight and tan , jus ' like da ' wahines out on the sand . i found this brew to be very malt-forward which surprised me considering the aggressive head retention . pouring more volcano into my glass sends up plumes of amber and golden turbulence within the red ale .  m - lot 's of carbonation is there making this really move . unfortunately it 's to the point of almost being painful . medium body . it 's sort of an odd one because of the carbonation .

smells like old foghorn - underattenuated extract homebrew . actually , okish , at this point , as an american bwine but ... but the color and smell are just so wrong .  a : highly carbonated like a true belgian . huge snow white head sits on top of an unfiltered golden hay colored body .  first sip reveals a mild smooth body and fine rolling carbonation . the body gets a little watery on the finish , but it is a mild and the brew goes down very easy and would be an excellent session beer .

pours out a dark orange , w/ a really thick light peach head , takes a bit to fill the mug . kinda gives off a herbal smell , a bit of pear in there too ( at least that 's what it smells like to me ) , though that does n't stay for long .  poured a deep and clear amber color with a huge off white rocky head which remained for the duration . a beautiful beer .  drinkability suffers a bit from a somewhat awkward and viscous mouthfeel .

a very creamy half finger beige head quickly recedes to a nice cap s : pretty subdued , pick up some nice toasted malts along with a bit of coffee and chocolate t : all of the different flavours picked up in the aroma are present in the taste , along with a slight burnt bitterness that blends everything together m : nice and creamy , easy on the carbonation but a tad thin d : a great session beer for the cooler months .  750ml bottle , split with some friends during the bears game appearance : poured into these massive snifters that seemed like they could hold the full 750ml somehow ( probably an exaggeration ) ... dark mahogan body , huge chocolate beige foam head and great retention smell : aroma is a tad flat , faint and distinctly belgian , cocoa powder tones present but not overpowering taste : i kind of knew going in that this wasnt really as chocolatey as it advertised ... .its not really a stout obvious either , at least by my definition ... lots of dark fruit , yeast , light cocoa notes .  mouthfeel i liked the fullness of the body here , but the carbonation was quite annoying . otherwise , this felt good .

s : kind of bitter . not in that good way , but almost skunked bitter . t : has a very bitter taste , but it is good if you are down for that kind of flavor . despite the smell , it is n't skunked , just bitter . m : just like the smell and taste , bitter .  this beer pours a beautiful head .  m-for a beer and a stout this is a very odd mouth feel . it is super creamy and leaves a mess on your tongue .

while the appearance resembles a porter in color , it is actually a lager and tastes as such . hints of cocoa , but not as drinkable or tasty as a porter ... in fact , it would have been hard to distinguish this beer from , say , a decent lager , in a blind taste test ... well , you could taste a hint of roasting , but not much . still , a decent once-in-awhile beer .  pours a nice brown amber , with huge foamy off-white head that has great retention .  mouthfeel is the only real weakness for this beer .

the smell was very light , with a bit of malt and a hint of sweetness .  watching this beer settle is part of it 's mistique - its a lava lamp for beer geeks ... once settled , a perfect 1-finger head of slightly off-white cream meets a pitch black beer . the commercial ( widget bottle , nitro-can ) are pale shadows compared .  the body has a little chalky hard-water feel to it -- like mineraly .

very interesting . m : good mouthfeel . o : very good ipa , up near the top .  liked it last year ; let 's see how this stacks up pours caramel with 2.5 fingers of rocky off-white colored head . stellar head retention & lacing s : subdued hop nose up front .  spices are clearly evident in the flavor ... some cloves and cardamom both come through with a lot of caramel malts , and an unfamiliar flavor , that i am , in my mind , linking with the yeast used . the beer is pretty light for such a dark color . i expected more carbonation , and i was a little bit disappointed at the smoothness .

presentation : 12 oz . smell : i 'm surprised that i do n't get a bit more here , but what i do get is a hint of fruity sweetness , a preview of the hops that are sure to follow in the first drink and just a bit of caramel . taste : wow ... my nose did n't fail me , there is the hop bitterness right up front , but it is complemented later on by the malt character that follows . like a good imperial ipa , these go down easy and hide the higher abv . verdict : a great beer , but a bit young and brash .  cork marking 0205 ... poured a ruby , garnet color with a medium sized pink head and light lacing on the glass .  surprisingly dry finish in the back m - a bit think , could use some more bubbles or hops to round out the malt a bit .

overall really light on the nose .  the head is fluffy first and rocky later , ivory white in color and incredibly long lasting . huge peaks and craters cover the surface . as it eventually fades , chunky sea foam lace coats the glass .  mouthfeel - very average .

the nose is limited , offering just a bit of malt , but it 's clean and welcoming . it 's dextrinous in the mouth with a fine , moderate carbonation ( @ 2.4 volumes co2/ltr ) that leaves it quite smooth .  12 oz bottle poured into traditional pint glass a - pours a cloudy light orange color with a huge , billowing head that becomes very rocky with time . lacing is terrific .  medium bodied but a bit thinner than expected with a prominent roasted coffee presence that lingers over the dark malts and subtle barrel character into a dry finish .

not sure if i should review this beer based on expectations for an ipa or for the flavor alone . the taste starts with some nutty malts and finishes hoppy , with a slightly metallic taste somewhere in between . at 5.5 % abv i 'd consider this a session brew . as a side note : what is the difference between this and your standard run-of-the-mill brown ale ?  this beer went great with the pizzas they were serving and the marlboros we were smoking . it has a dark color and a roasted taste and scent . i liked this beer so much i braved over-the-rhine in the dark by myself so i could fill up my growler .  the carbonation is moderate it is perhaps a bit too high for the style though .

s : right off the bat i am not able to detect much of anything beyond a faint barley sweetness in the nose . as the beer warms the nose becomes sweeter , but i 'm still not smelling much .  nitro tap served at crossroads coffee and icecream on southside richmond , va. a : black with three finger superfine nitro head s : booze !  mouthfeel : medium-thin body .

good head retention , very clear , and light aroma . first sip and you can taste the light maltiness of this brown ale .  a : pale brownish straw . clear with a great white head and stellar lacing .  m - medium to light body .

a-yellow amber in color with white head s-very sour and funky . this style gets me every time t-sour and funky yet very smooth and delicious .  massive head from an aggressive pour , twas quite nice . lacing was awesome .  the mouthfeel is a bit lighter than expected but doesnt detract , and drinkability is excellent for the abv .

smells like caramel malts with a hint of hops .  the appearance is flawless . the contrast of the thick tan head and deep black body is visually appealing .  m : dry , bitter , light/medium bodied , crisp , too much bite from the alcohol .

aroma must be hidden beneath the foam and remains quite mellow despite its rather distinct flavors .  pitch black color . two fingers of thick creamy medium brown head with pretty good retention and a glass absolutely plastered with lacing .  feels thin for such a high abv barrel aged beer but it is easy to drink and the alcohol heat is mild considering .

aroma is surprisingly subdued . little bit of herbal aroma , slight bit of alcohol .  a : a very smooth looking brownish red hue . perfect 2 finger head with nice lacing . and nice tight foam .  m : slightly watery , but forgivable considering its low alcohol content .

the smell was a roasted malt .  pours very dark brown/black with a huge tan head , fades at a slow rate and leaves some good lacing .  the beer 's mouthfeel is smooth , if a bit watery ; this may be the same problem as the vanishing head .

quite unique , but i 'm very impressed . the taste is a lot lighter and less robust compared to the aroma .  beautiful transparent amber body . rocky healthy head .  tightly packed carbonation which makes the body feel more medium , feels just a bit too foamy for my tastes .

s - sweet plums and malt . t - robust hops flavor throughout .  a-pours a beautiful ruby red with a thick , billowy cream colored head . there is some cascading and lacing left on the glass . i ca n't say enough how beautiful this beer looks , its amazing . s-grapefruit stands out the most from the hops .  mid palate is substantially thin .

s - slight malt notes , but otherwise i 'm just sniffing air . this is a solid english pale ale , solid body of hops and malts , nothing to let you down initial taste is a bit bitter with mostly malts ; the finish is slightly hoppy though it appears to be clean it is just the big malt backing to the beer ; the finish is slightly bitter and malty sweet .  a- excellent black color with a large lingering head- tinted grey- and some lacing .  really interesting for a christmas seasonal . a good amount of spice and hops as it poured into a nice dark orange , with a little bit of lacing and head . i did n't really feel the `` festive ale '' as much as some of the other beers i 've had around this time , but it did have some good spices and taste .

brandon 's version pours well , with a clear , macro-lager yellowness to its hue . the aroma is mild , even for the style , with notes of grain husks , cereal , and dried grasses . mineral water & a light sourness in the background . kudos to highland ( and you might want to consider offering this dude brandon a job !  recived this from secret santa 08 , poured into my duvel tulip glass , poured a rich black that at its thinest point as a glass is tiped back has a hint of red to it , a great 3 finger tan head rose to the top and stayed for a few seconds befor becoming a light lacing around the rim .  m - heavy , almost cough-syrup consistency with light carbonation .

no head or lacing ( 2 ) s : hmm , this is ... interesting ? smells of burnt toast , prunes and a bourbony vanilla ( 3 ) t : oh dear , that 's abrasive .  beautiful 3 finger tan to almost brown head rests on top of a black body . this is the christina ricci of porters .  mouthfeel : smooth with a relatively full body .

let us taste it . first , we discover the chocolate at first sip ; then , our palate is greeted by a warm blanket of malt that denotes a rather smooth , yet biscuit-like , mouthfeel . this one , if ordered on draught , must be allowed to sit if you wish to truly experience it - the way it was meant to be .  appearance : a slightly hazy , deep reddish-orange body capped by three fingers of off-white head that fades slowly and leaves brilliant lacing .  the taste ends with a really nice strong bitterness that lingers on the palate for quite awhile . the carbonation seems to be moderate perhaps a little more on the high scale but seems to be average for the style .

great mildly spicy taste though . nothing overwhelming , just a very tasteful winter beer .  retention is pretty impressive and it leaves quite a bit of lacing on the glass . really pretty looking barley wine .  m- near dead flat . it seems to be a bit on the thin side as well . d- despite the feel this beer still drinks deadly smooth .

if this beer has a weak point , its the aroma . i did n't get a lot off of the nose . i did smell the grain along with tiny hints of lemon and hop . overall it was sweet and slightly buttery . great taste , hardly filling , absolutely one of the best lagers i 've had .  pure white head and beautiful opaque yellow body .  the aroma has a touch of stale coffee that then moves to a better defined roasted malt in lager form . the dark malts are great , minus ther adjunt must to it . i ca n't really explain why , but this is one of my , `` right after a hard day of work while you wait for dinner to cook beer . '' easy on the palate and tastes good from the bottle and the glass .

the smell indicates roasted coffee ; not much chipotle to be detected in the nose .  a : crystal clear golden color with a beautifully thick white head that never really quits . one of the best looking brews i 've seen in a while .  has a nice malt smell that i find lacking in the lesser expensive pilsners . taste is malt with just enough hop to bitter finishes crisp and dry but not astringent . on a personal note this is the type of pilsner that i classify in my mental list as `` old world '' as apposed to `` lawn mowing '' . i 'd recommend it .

average head retention & lacing s : bready , grassy , lemony , white pepper & coriander . i wish this tasted it like it smelled t : lemons , orange peel & grassyness up front , then some coriander up front , along some nice wheat tartness . finishes crisp & slightly grassy mf : light bodied with slight carbonation drinks really easy , liked this much better than a previous time when i had this on draft years ago ( served too cold imo ) , nice if simple take on the style  a-pours an orange/copper with a head that is four fingers thick . the head is extremely dense and it dissipates slowly leaving a thick lacing on the sides of the mug . there was lacing down the entire glass .  not very extreme in any one area very balanced m : a little bit thin for a stout .

bottle lists things this beer does not contain : wheat , barley , crustaceans , eggs , fish , peanuts , soy beans , milk , lactose , nuts , celery , mustard , sesame seeds , sulphur dioxide or sulfites . it 's a very dark beer with a reddish-purple tint when held to the light . rather fruity aroma , but with a ... maybe a butterscotch tinge to it .  pours a lovely mahogany -crystal clear and brown-red with a slight fluffy khaki head .  smell : wheat , alcohol , wierd hops , tangy smell , maybe some wine alcohol smell in there too taste : hints of grass , toasted wheat , nice and smooth , mellow , nice malt aftertaste and a bit tangy mouthfeel : a little tart , this one is pretty highly carbonated .

this turned out to be good as it gave me a good chance to take in the aromas . i was hoping for more apricot in the aroma , but that fell a little short . it is very drinkable even at 7 % alcohol .  an amazing looking beer .  the mouthfeel however , is not bad - very light and bubbly .

subtle aroma , but followed with an eye-openingly brilliant taste .  poured a motor oil brownish black with a light brown head of frothy , creamy foam . good head retention and a fair amount of laced sticking .  about 10 seconds after taking a mouthful i had a strawberry aftertaste in my mouth .

smell is lacking and is the worst attribute of this beer .  a- poured into my dogfish head snifter , this beer pours solid black with a big dark brown head that settles slowly and sticks around for the duration of the beer , leaving some blankets of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

aroma was lightly sweet and hoppy .  smutty ipa pours a stunning bright orange , with a nice creamy white cap that hangs around for a minute before coating my glass with lace . absolutely gorgeous .  its a huge beer , but the mouthfeel isnt as thick as i would like or expect . good levels of carbonation , and they did a great job of hiding the alcohol .

smell -- bready and yeasty , with plenty of malt sweetness , a bit of melon , and some grassy hops .  beer pours a gorgeous golden color . clear but not pristine , there 's a subtle haze in there . little bubbles stuck all over the inside of the glass . nice snow white head ... pillowy , tight bubbles .  the beer did suffer a bit on the palette from the high hopping rates , as this did not glide down in a soft manner , and presented a bit of an edgy mouthfeel .

smell : the aroma was somewhat soft and weak , as only a hint of caramel and floral hops were detectable . drinkability : i found this to be extremely flavorful , its a shame the nose was so weak . nice brew .  the beer pours a dark black color with a thick , creamy , cocoa looking head . retention is very good in this beer and there is plenty of sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel was pretty thin for this type of beer , but a good beer overall .

smells of roasted malts and alcohol . i am not a big fan of the style but this brew is pretty good .  this beer pours a slightly cloudy golden yellow color , with a thick , fluffy , white head . the head fades very slowly , leaving a massive lacing .  mouthfeel is thick and flat , with a slight prickle that could come from carbonation or just from the alcohol .

decent , somewhat watery lacing s - nothing too special in the aroma category , maybe a little malt , slight lime citrus t - sweet malt with an excellent wheat finish .  a-extremely dark brown in color , almost black , completely opaque with a huge and thick dark coffee colored head that lingers for well over a minute and leaves a nice lacing on the glass .  only criticism : powerful aggressive carbonation , would it ease if i left it a while - just too fresh ?

great head retention & lacing s : a little caramel t : sweet bready malt , caramel & earthy hops up front .  appearance ; thick , stiff white head , excellent retention and messy spider web-like lacing .  m : higher carbonation than expected , medium-full bodied .

smell is muted . there are some nutty hints and that 's about it .  appearance - total black pour with a finger of smooth , rich , mocha foam .  source/serving : draft smell : coriander , orange flavors , belgian yeastiness , and some brown sugar . overall fairly deep , dark flavors . taste : quite sweet up front with pronounced coriander . the middle does n't really go anywhere , just sustained - or even more - coriander . perhaps there is a ephemeral note of some ripe fruits and alcohol . disappointing . finish is oddly bitter , noticeable alcohol and has a slightly off spiciness .

aroma was light on the hops for a double ipa , more caramel malt aroma . a very nice job .  gorgeous dark brown pour settling inky black in the glass with a mighty thick dark tan foam of mashed up graham cracker-like quality . the lacing is more like shelving as it grabs on to the glass with thickly set curtains of foamy soup .  m/d - a little thin , though probably appropriate for a session beer .

this winter lager looks fantastic . something in the smell puts me off a little .  pours a deep darrk amber/brown with a creamy thick light brown head , very sticky .  no offense ... er..ahem ... gentlemen , however your review of this all time worst pisswater excuse for even a macro beer is to say the least , culpable , at best , dubious , but in truth , how can you live with yourself ? t-non-existent m-ok , not too harsh , but goes flat quickly . good carb up front .

caffrey 's on-tap is less creamy than the nitro can , but seems to be more substantial . a decent session ale that is quite quaffable . ( review taken from notes before coors pulled the plug on the brand in the u.s. ) .  poured a massive light custard yellow head which lasted longest i think i 've ever seen ( almost a merengue ) .  mouthfeel - low carbonation .

s- caramel and malt . there was not a strong alcohol smell . nothing extraordinary . nothing too strong here .  pours blacker than a saharan night during an eclipse . head is a thick , dense , and tan .  very little carbonation in this beer . the mouthfeel seems pretty unexceptional it 's pretty smooth with a medium body .

gimmicky label and a little bit better than an ordinary lager but smooth .  a - pours murky brass , tons of white head , stays for awhile . cling lace looks like it is digging in for the long haul .  light body and mouthfeel .

big oil can , just finished watching crocodile dundee in los angeles , so i had a hankering for this , a : pours a typical , pale yellow , but the head is really nice initially , and has pretty good retention , a nice , soapy white . s : very light , faint , some malt notes . t : light malt notes are backed up by a surprising amount of hops for this style of beer , definitely not an ipa or pilsner , but for an american macro lager , it 's got a bit of a crisp hop bite .  poured black with a nice tan head that didnt last long .  mf : fine . just take it away . thin for a strong ale drinkable ?

the aroma is full of grain and grass notes , about what i expect from a beer that is designed to compete with mexican lagers . i get the same grain and grass notes as in the aroma , as well as some light orange citrus notes .  fantastic lacing & head retention smell : slight fruittyness taste : nice hoppy bittterness & caramel up front .  the scents are the same in the taste though it seems to lose something in the mouthfeel , which is a bit thin .

for a pilsner , i was n't expecting much in taste , but this beer proved me wrong . although i am new at trying to predict what craft beers taste like , this pilsner was a ten compared to mass-produced beers . great looking bottle .  a : this is a great looking imperial stout : black in color with a nice mocha colored foam .  this was highly carbonated which produced a slighlty unpleasant tingling mouthfeel .

smell was awful skunk and corn what a combonation ( no pun intended ) .  looks impressive with sheets of cascading lacing on the glass after every drink .  a little thin in the body for my taste , and a bit low in carbonation .

bomber from the lcbo . absolutely huge fruity ( pear , lychee , peach ) , spicy ( cinnamon ) aroma . floral , sweet flavour with strong hints of cinnamon .  appearance ; thick and creamy beige head , perfect retention throughout the drink . beautiful chunky lacing , dark , brownish amber body .  surprising amount of carbination gets you with the first sip , it foams up in your mouth . but the body is alot less than i was expecting ... not think , just mostly carbination on top of a thin to medium body.. ? the flavors linger on your tongue , mainly at the back sides .

mild aroma . good fine head with lots of lace .  i just love the way this beer looks . the color is a clear bright pumpkin orange , and the head totally overwhelms the glass with thick white billowing foam . thick lacing remains after the clouds recede .  mouthfeel is not very good . the carbonation is almost non-existent and so it 's a bit too slick . still , a nice beer and i 'd have to imagine it would be much better with any semblance of carbonation .

summit maibock is the most drinkable bottled beer that i 've found since quaffing red hook ( nee , ballard bitter ) `` ya sure , ya betchal '' in paul shipman 's tasting room in his converted auto repair ship in ballard wa . unlike the dreadful generic maibock of yore , this brew has a deliciously mild hoppy taste and is so smooth and drinkable you 'll find it hard to keep your cooler stocked with the stuff .  despite being pumped off a cask , the clarity is striking . showing off is a color as deep , varied , and impressive as a well-stained piece of fine , dark mahogany . the head is soft , even , and leads to good lacing , especially for such a low gravity ale .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation . smooth , easy to drink , but gets kind of muddy in the finish like some of the other nognes i 've had , which kind of makes my mouth feel dirty , but good winter beer nonetheless .

there is a distinct smell of fresh grapefruit that is unbelievably pleasing to the nose .  sampled on 4-11-08 batch 8369 bottled on 4-4-08 pours a super thick clear amber-gold , with lots of little bubbles that slowly rise to the surface .  weaker on the mouthfeel than i would expect from a stout , although it aids in the drinkability .

smell-malt and yeast with a lemon undertone . not very inviting at all . taste-wow , really tasty .  pitch brown/black with a giant , never-ending mocha head . plenty of lace left behind . one beautiful beer . certainly the chocolate and coffee element are there , earth and oak make a solid appearance .  mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish .

nice lacing too folks . s - caramel and molasses topping an alcohol and malt base . t - mild dark chocolate under heavy malt and medium coffee with a perfect hop .  a- dark with some amber/brown highlight ; thick , tan head leaves perfect sticky rings down the glass .  smell : piney hops and malts are slightly toasty , tickles the nose readily easily . taste : hop sensation is immediate , blending with the mild toasty-earthy malt taste , progressing to a light , tangy-hop bitterness in the finish , surprisingly balanced . drinkability : darker than a typical ipa , the character of the malts successfully complements the well-hopped taste , very drinkable .

very nice . t : up front it 's a nice oktoberfest with some slightly fruity flavors and just a bit of alcohol warmth , but like many upland beers , there is a strange aftertaste to it that i 'm not too keen on .  hazy apple cider coulourd liquid tumbles from the bottle and stirs up a huge white head which immediately threatens to spill over the lip of the glass . as the head slowly recedes it leaves huge chunks of lace that defy gravity , while a huge circular island takes up residence and refuses to die .  this brings us to mouthfeel and i 'm once again taken back to the question of carbonation . in the mouth there is a degree of weight and intensity , however this is beset on both sides by an intense carbonation that strongly effects the overall weight of the beer . the carbonation issue is really just a thing of personal taste but it needs to be put out there , but , overall ; this is a fantastic beer .

s- faint aromas of malt and wood . you get some wood and whiskey right on the nose , along with the earthy hops and bready malts of the base beer .  this stout pours with a dark brown to black body toped by a medium thick , brown head with lots of lacing .  feels like champagne .

smell : my worst sense and this one seemed slightly astringent with a layer of sweetness a little nuttiness and alcohol . drinkability : the hacker pschorr and this are among the cheapest of german imports , on this level at any rate . paired great with a turkey burger and clausen pickle .  this is a fantastic looking beer .  a - deep clear brown with some dark amber highlights ; one finger tan head settled down to a nice frothy cap ; light lacing that seemed to slide down glass s - rich , dark coffee starts to come through then milk chocolate and caramel t - coffee is present throughout but it is understated and just part of the profile ; some malt and bread toward the end with a mildly sweet chocolate and caramel finish m - very lightly carbonated ; thin bodied ; no bite or drying finish d - while this one left a bit to be desired in the mouthfeel and taste department it is very drinkable overall - thin body and light carbonation make it go down easy with a nice light , coffee/candy bar flavor ; what 's not to like right ?

aromas are lightly sweet and roasty but nothing jumps out at me here .  this is a beautiful looking beer .  i found the mouth feel a little thin , not as think and syrupy , as i would expect , but it 's a minor complaint .
s : very little smell coming out of this one .  great retention leaves a lace storm splattered within my glass .  m : smooth yet just a bit carbonated on the way down ; a little too thin .

an ipa brewed with mango , pineapple , and grapefruit purees added . s : bouquet is somewhat faint , and suggests all of the fruit that are held within . there is also a nice hit of hops mingling with all of the fruit .  pours pitch black with a 2-finger ever-lasting head that leaves beautiful rings of lacing on the glass .  rich deep amber red / clear / mild carbonation / mild head sweet sugar almost like a cake / fruity and roasted sweet and tart / significant bitterness / powdery malt / rich roasted / fruity floral hop impact too / interesting sushi flavor must be spices and proteins or maybe it just smells like horseradish / rich caramel sweetness / finishes tart mildly spicy carbonation / medium body beautiful color . would go nicely with sushi . high enjoyable brew .

the smell is intense . if you like hops , imagine a normal ipa and multiply that by ten . a potent warning to stay away if you ca n't handle it . excess , thy name is hop 15 . this beer is about hops . once again , insanely rich grapefruit , sweet caramel . this tastes like pine smells . mad citrusy with alcohol swimming around .  a : a vibrant goldlen ale with a strong haze . towering snow white head ... frothy and creamy . looks like scoops of whipped cream .  it 's very refreshing to the mouth ( do i say that about all the beers i review ? ) , with small , present carbonation and what i 'm finding to be a lighter body than i expected from a wee heavy . by virtue of this lighter than expected body , however , this is an extremely drinkable beer .

s : sent of pine and flowery hops . no citrus smell at all . the pine smell dominates . t : big pine and floral taste , limited malt flavor , all hop presence .  appearance- wonderful semi-cloudy off orange , slightly golden colored pour . full one inch head on pour which form a ultra creamy milkshake-like head . actually , more like cool whip . leaves behind great trails and patches of lace .  mouthfeel - thick and foamy . better than the other aspects of this beer .

the smell is skunky , and smells like a cheap euro lager .  half the glass is huge , frothy , rocky head . nice !  i poured this guinness into my tumbler at 45 degrees . the beer was very black and bore out a big tan head . the beer smells like a guinness as it should . the taste was big molasses but the brew had a bit of a dry finish . i like the beer and will buy again .

not picking up a huge aroma but i am getting some , faint roasted malt and hint of vanilla and toffee . i 've had this many times before and i 'm glad it 's readily available in case i wanted a darker beer that is n't so brutal with a lower abv and subtleness to it .  really beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is avera- man , this beer is actually giving me a headache .

ridiculously amazing nose of white wine , oak , ripe pear , white pepper , and earthy brett . really special . getting a ton of that chardonnay character in the taste , lots of ripe melon and pear , oak , white grapes , and honey with a touch of brett and more saison flavors of white pepper , yeast , and lemon peel . not quite as epic as the nose , but still very unique and delicious . mouthfeel is crisp , with a medium body , sharp , `` spritzy '' carbonation , and a nicely dry finish . overall an excellent saison , and easily one of the most memorable examples of the style i 've ever had !  pours a cloudy golden amber with tea tones filled with a massive head of white foam that melts very slowly to extremely sticky white lace .  the mouth feel is a little thin , unlike some higher-end ales , but the drinkability is very good .

s : pretty tight on the nose , i am getting white spices , and some tree fruit .  very dark , nearly black , nice brown foamy head , lots of sticky lace .  m : light in body . on nitro , this would be alot creamier ... but it 's still damn good .

rich coffee with just a touch of acridity . there 's a slight fruitiness as well but the aroma is not as good as the flavour .  the beer pours a crystal clear red/amber color and produces a huge 4-finger light tan head , so be careful with the pour .  m : lightly carbonated , but bitter for a porter .

smelled pretty good , got the orange peel and the spicy yeast all up in the nose . the taste lacked a lot of what was good about the smell .  this fine brew has a big fluffy dense head and lacing that sticks to the glass .  the ringwood yeast just tore this up and gave it a slab of butter on top ... m : crisp , but just tastes pretty bad ... d : a pretty bad beer , the ringwood yeast dominates this brew so much that i had to drain pour the rest , too bad .

the ideal looking pilsner . corn and adjuncts dominate the aroma , but they do n't carry quite the same unpleasantness that macro lagers have . the stenching smell of corn syrup becomes overly sweet . this is a damn fine pilsner .  a - forms a very large , slightly off white head that settles down pretty quickly and leaves good lace on the glass . rosy orangeish color and moderately hazy , really an extraordinary color when you take the time to appreciate it .  m : slightly flat , with low to medium low carbonation . mouthfeel is likely the weakest part of the beer .

odors of malt and a touch of cooked corn .  out of a bottle this beer was a chestnut brown color with a huge three finger head . the khaki foam died back slowly , displayed good retention and excellent lacing .  it had a medium body but was kind of rough along the palate as it went down .

the smell is nothing special , but has hints of bread and malt . the taste of this beer is exquisite .  a - one of the thickest heads i have ever seen , looks like lemon meringue pie ... also reminds me of a giant thunderhead with a tornado of carbonated bubbles going from the head to the bottom of the glass that will not quit . very cloudy yellow as the head begins to settle .  3.0 m : something about this beer just does n't sit well on my tongue .
smells like fresh noble hops .  poured this into a duvel glass and was taken aback . a beautiful pillow white head on top of a semi cloudy golden ale .  somewhat thin and watery mouthfeel .

s : smells very good , of cranberries , of course , and ripe apples , a full smell that hits you as soon as you open the bottle . there is a nice cranberry undercurrent of flavour there , but it is too damn sweet to be very appealing , almost like soda pop .  bottled january 2008 appearance : pours into an allagash tulip a deep burgundy brown with ruby red highlights . a 2-finger high light tan head forms on top and takes absolutely forever to drop .  mouthfeel was slightly on the thin side , not quite watery , but close .

s : mild hoppy smell , but overall pretty nonexistent .  massive and dense biege rocky foam cloud that measures about 4 fingers tall and leaves incredible lacing rests on top of this deep dark dirty brown brew .  very smooth , all flavors mesh together nicely medium bodied but thin , which is a turn off for me . i feel like this could have been a very special stout if this would have had a thicker mouthfeel ... not very carbonated at all . the thin body was a low point but the smell and taste of this beer is way too good to let that ruin the beer .

s : really surprising aroma for an ipa .  ap : very thick and smooth light tan head , great retention , beauiful maroon amber , lace t : sweet and bourbon , very woody , strong caramel , syrupy and sweet , honey , spicy wood , strong dates , spicy smooth bourbon is very strong , strong golden raisins , apricot in finish , strong syrupy/fruity sweetness m : full and syrupy , low carbonation , alcohol warmth at end , ends very sweet o : delicate , flavors are in balance well but it is way too sweet , nice bourbon and wood character , perhaps having some darker malt character would help  little thin on the feel as all their brews tend to be but it was not horribly distracting in any way .

so far so good . taste is fairly bland for such a high rated beer .  bottle into a snifter appearance- pour is black with a 2 finger tan head . when held to the light nothing is entering this , just deep dark and beautiful . leaving good sticky lace . appearance wise , this is perfect for an impy stout .  source/serving : draft smell : raisins , dark cherries , dark chocolate , nutmeg , a little licorice and even some honey . taste : semisweet vanilla , slightly oaked chocolate malts , and raisins up front are awesome . plateaus at some roasted malts in the middle that has a punch of sweet , ripe prunes and caramelized wood followed by some pepper and more roasted malts and yeastiness . finish is cocoa , semidry , oaky , and ripe prunes .

nose smells like rubbing alcohol at first , with a punch of hallertaus coming in next .  this beer has the most classic pour in the world . the cascade was fast , beautiful and entrancing . it 's a classic beer but i prefer beamish or murphy 's for a more pleasing dry stout experience .  mouthfeel was n't terrible , with the nice carbonation going on it actually kinda danced on the tongue .

s : a bit weak here , not much of a smell..bitter , a bit of citrus . t : awesome ! i 'm a huge non-chill filtered scotch fan , the more bite on the tongue the better .  reviewed from notes taken on 4/4/2011 appearance : pours jet black with three fingers of thick tan head .  aside from the dry end this is an easy to drink beer with an average mouth .

it 's lightly floral with overtones of honey.. and surprisingly the canned version retains this as well . it really just smells good and it 's one of the few accessible beers you can enjoy poking your nose in and smelling before opening your mouth .  excellent head retention and lacing . surly beers always look amazing !  the taste is of roasted malts , toffee , and to some degree , molasses . the smell is good and the taste is incredible ... but letting this porter get warm isnt such a good idea since it significantly reduces its drinkability . i will definitely pick up another case of this becauce it is probably the best porter i 've ever had . if you like this then definitely give brooklyn black chocolate stout a shot because thats damn good too .

awesome . taste- greeted with the normal citrusd peel , but more emphasis on grapfruit zest and some malts .  a rich back body with one finger dense tan head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , slightly syrupy , and carbonation is low which produces a somewhat still feel .

smell is odd . the smell of cooked vegetables is coming through .  sparkingly clear , reddish caramel brew forms a beautiful , peaking light tan head atop small bubbles with excellent retention and exquisite lacing .  m - full bodied , low carbonation , dry finish . the body was full , but the finish seemed oddly watery .

cereal grains dominate the aroma with a touch of butter . overall , an extremely solid malt liquor , much better than others in the style .  12oz bottle into a goblet a : pours pitch black with almost two fingers of light brown head . carbonation is very thick and seems to stick around forever . beautiful .  m - somewhat thin to medium bodied but with just the right hoppy aftertaste to leave my mouth tingling for another drink .

s - lightly scented - just a bit of yeast spice and light malt notes . the wild yeast notes come through ever so slightly .  a - black as night with about a one inch brown head .  slightly creamy body , though it falls flat at the front of the palate . it could use ( i ca n't believe i 'm saying this ) a bit more carbonation . or more body .

the neglected little brother of negro modelo , modelo especial , is an exceptional crisp clean summer beer .  holy shit , what a beer . great head with amazing retention .  m : fairly light bodied and the only part that 's halfway decent .

nose was rather dull , a light roast , hints of caramel malt , hint of piney hops . i was more than pleasantly surprised by this beer , church key is not usually high on my list of breweries worth trying . roast , espresso , hints of oats perhaps , an odd creaminess that seems in line with an oatmeal stout , mixed with a slightly piny bitterness that leans way to the british hop variety side with a pleasing , long finishing bitterness . like a well hopped english stout . nice caramel sweetness , hint of brown sugar . i really dug it and would gladly order another pint .  a : the beer pours a rich dark color with a huge foamy caramel/parchment colored head .  mouthfeel is pretty sharp and fizzy from the bubbles . average kind of body , but mostly just bubbly .

a : almost clear amber , like watered down apple juice s : distinct raspberry and pomegranate smell that is appealing , it also has almost a diet soda scent .  golden in hue w/ a slight haze , topped by a formidabily thick , creamy , rocky persistant head that leaves lace . it 's reminescent of a belgian strong golden in appearance .  m - a bit thin .

the nose is very light , but hints of banana and light caramel malt .  appearance - copper orange poured into a pilsner glass . a finger of cream-colored head creates a solid film of lace on the glass . mad bubble action keeps a thin blanket on top of the beer .  m : this beer has a slightly creamy consistency that lingers after you swallow , surely due in part to its being unfiltered .

the smell is pretty simple , grainy malts and not too much else .  can courtesy of sammy : poured a deep dark brown color ale with huge dirty white foamy head with great retention and lacing .  it is perhaps a bit on the thin side , but otherwise rather good .

s - rich , malty , honey , and hoppy smell . the hop smell really stands out here .  very nice looking beer .  very clear and bubbly , one finger head that looked like the fizz produced when pouring a pepsi . smells hoppy , lively citrusy orange peel and carbonation galore . the hops mildly dominate the brew , just enough to mask any malty flavor . well worth it . would recommend this brew .
smell : caramel and banana bread . i believe that 's expected in this style .  liquid dark bread .  sweet tasting ... m : a little on the acidic and sour side to me .

distinct dusty , musty ringwood yeast in the nose , with hints of buttery diacetyl , faint roasted , suggestions of chocolate / cocoa , and delicate floral .  oct 19 , 2003 dark , cherry red body with a pink head .  it does feel a little thin in your mouth , but it smells exactly what it 's name says : a cocoa porter . the beer tastes like chocolate milk made with nesquick or ovalteen or anything other chocolate powder brand with a mild , beer after-taste .

i did n't get much from the smell . i had it in a tulip to try and accentuate , inasmuch as possible , whatever aromas i could glean . pleasant , just not all that exciting . mouthfeel reminds me a farmhouse , like ommegang 's hennepin . i should have figured it was something like that , but it hides it completely .  this one pours a nice opaque black in the glass with nice a tan/brown head that has good retention . a perfect picture of a stout .  it had a medium feel in my mouth with ok carbonation .

the smell was faint hops , almost no smell at all .  this is a beatiful beer with a rick cloudy ruby topped off with a thick , dense , off-white head .  mouthfeel is a letdown - it may just be this bottle but the carbonation is too weak . only have one of these 750ml bottles as it 's imported and a special occasion but i 'd be keen to have another one , if only to compare the carbonation .

pours nicely to create a beautiful colored head with good lacing with a slight malty smell out of the glass . nice ! very good subtle mouth feel makes this beer feel , oh so drinkable .  bottle , with santa claus on the label , a : pours a dark , turbid brown , with a huge , voluminous white head , almost like a duvel in size , which leaves generous lacing .  from notes , bottle to pint look brown , red flares from the side thin head smell : wine , fruity , sweet and sugary taste : grape , fruit , malt and sugary with a slight sour . honestly feels like more of a imperial red taste honestly mouth : good but not great , nothing stood out drink : is tasty cant deny that , but i couldnt do a lot of these

s : the dominant smell was a sweet malty aroma , and there was maybe a slight hint of non-floral hops . t : the beer tasted very similar to how it smelled .  a : a gorgeous deeep dark brown .  m : a bit thin . crisp , somewhat dry .

a giant tan head forms and for the first time ever i 'm almost worried about my snifter overflowing . smell : fruity and tart . hay , apples , and cherry . this was awesome and i 'm glad to have a whole growler of it .  dark golden , sorta amber , about a finger of frothy white head . lacing and retention are both great .  m suitably moderate to big but nothing extreme like an ris .

not much aroma . taste is different for a winter warmer and a nice change of pace .  appearance : golden amber that looks great beneath the fluffy off-white head that lasts . decent lacing . my favorite appearance for an apa .  mouthfeel : medium bodied i guess . it was definitely carbonated but it was n't something i wanted to leave in my mouth that long .

a frothy billowing slightly off white head erupts from this brew . what little aroma is present is well balanced between yeast , malt , and hops . no single fragrance takes over . barely any fragrance is detectable .  550 ml bottle , marked sg13b1 , poured into a pint glass apours solid black with a 2 inch dark tan fluffy head that slowly falls down to a pillow top that floats on top , lacing looks like swiss cheese . beautiful .  m - a little watery . carbonation good for the style .

smell : the kolsch odor is not present , in fact not much of an odor at all .  dark brown with red hues , tan colored head with very good retention and lacing .  m - little carbonation . relatively light-bodied on the mouth .

to acidic or stale , it faded as i drank it down , but the initial smell was not pleasing . t - after the smell factor i was worried about the taste , but was pleased with the distinct hop bitterness . not real powerful , but a nice , crisp ipa .  a- cork shot off like champagne , pouring pitch black with an ever-growing tan head that retained well and left excellent retention .  m : mouthfeel is thin and light . thin in an offputting way .

the smell was very modest but there was a hint of malt .  poured into a delirium tremens glass . pale amber color with two fingers of head that refuses to retreat . it sits so perfectly in the glass .  ... big foamy head in to the glass that seems to break its neck to dissipate , but leaves a tiny ring ... is very refreshing and tangy but when it warms it can be a beast , serve cold ! ! .. better than most bmc products and probably somewhat better than miller chill ...

smell - the most noticable aroma is a crisp and bitter hop presence . the malt character is moderate , and definitely in the background . overall this is an average pale ale , in my opinion .  dark red-brown/mohagony body topped by a thick off-white lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  the one area this beer disappoints is in mouthfeel , where it falls into a watery trap .
no freshness date . subtle earthy and sweet aroma with hints of roasted malt .  perfect lacing . i mean perfect lacing .  feels a bit thin , low-medium body and medium carbonation .

s : some chocolate and coffee notes.. not getting a huge scent off this one ... t : sweet chocolate . d : i could do a six pack of this.. a pretty decent imperial stout , for a pretty fair price .  i do n't like ambers , but this one is interesting . the looks are one of the best i have ever seen . lovely light amber colour .  m - sharp carbination starts off this beer , and turns almost tart . it seems young .

plums are right out front on the nose . more than i expected actually but it works very well with the other dark fruity esters typical of the style . pleasantly yeasty while the alcohol is detectible in a brandy-like aroma .  beautiful lava lamp look when the yeast diffuses down through the hazy straw body and fluffy white head .  m - light bodied , thin with a bit of a sticky feel .

the smells is where this beer really shines . lot of sweet , candied hops are on the nose . apricots and a bit of earthiness show up .  dark with some visible light . fluffy big head and nice lace .  well balanced m : a little coppery and bitter .

the aroma was very sweet and of chocolate .  awesome 1 inch head and great retention and some circular lacing smell : vanilla and chocolate taste : upfront carries some roasted smokiness that i was not at all expecting and then the vanilla takes over and covers your whole palate .  for the most part this is quite smooth , although the carbonation is just a tad too harsh to fully appreciate some of the nuanced flavors .

it 's easy to slam this and other mass produced american beers , but remember , we 're not judging the style as a whole . bud is a crisp , refreshing , drinkable beer , although not heavy on flavor . it would never be my first choice ( nor would any other mass-produced lagers ) , but if i 'm at a cookout or pool party and the host offers budweiser , i 'm not going to complain .  this is one of the most attractive brews i have ever seen . a light ruby color with creamy light head that has a finger and a half upon pour and settles to a ring . no lacing , but good legs .  the mouthfeel is just average .

s : plenty of spiciness from the wheat and yeast , but not much else . underwhelming . t : far , far better than the smell : big wheat sharpness , plenty of yeasty spice , and some nice fruit flavors as well ( apricot and lemon ) ; some cinnamon on the finish , and just a bit of booze on the aftertaste.. quite complex and thoroughly enjoyable .  a cloudy golden body with a white head that stands strong and leaves thick cloud like plumes down the side of the glass . i have n't seen a beer look this good in a glass .  smells very nutty with mild chocolate roast . the beer fairly sweet tasting with the nuttiness coming through . cabonation is a bit higher than i would like , but other than that it is a very good brown ale .

s - aroma is very faint but it is mostly citrus ith hints of light malts . t - the taste is a very nice balance of malts and bitter hops . first you taste slightly bitter and very citrusy hops and right after comes faint malts just enough to excellently balance the taste.w m - mouthfeel is also a nice balance of crisp and smoothness .  thick , black beer pours with a beautiful , fluffy head that is the color of light caramel . it shows staying power that would make a porn star proud . a very well distributed lace is left behind .  m - slick and slightly thin .

it does n't give me much smell , but there is at least a hint of sweet fruit .  appearance is exceptional due to the huge creamy , rocky , tan head .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin side , but drinkability is excellent .

it has a nice cereal character that i really like , but the overall impression is just a nice drinkable beer . the beer has a slight tutti-frutti to the nose , but that does n't translate to the taste , where the raw grains take over .  moderate to light brown pour , turns opaque in the glass . huge head that holds well , has a touch of oil and stickiness to it .  little bit of fizziness and a lingering cottonmouth aftertaste i could have done without .

the small is a bit light , and malty . the taste is strong very malty , no other flavors are present , this beer is just for those who want beer and nothing else . overall this is an excelent beer , one of a kind .  decent amount of head for a strong barleywine . very nice looking .  this is miles better than early versions when moo brew was just getting off the ground . nose is very expressive and lifted with intense oranges and tropical fruit . the flavours are much more serious and show genuine pale ale chracter ; firm , bitter hops , some piney notes , but surprsingly the fruit offered on the nose is a bit hard to find . doesnt harm the beer though . well worth its percentile rating .

the aromas seem a bit subdued .  the bottled version pours dark brown , almost black , revealing deep crimson highlights when held to the light . an awesomely creamy tight head the color of chocolate milk shows no signs of stopping even at the bottom of my glass .  im sure this loses ratings for its thin palate , but taste wise this is spot on . more roasted coffee flavors and a touch of smokiness . an imminently sippable brew . nicely done .

nose : cafe au lait aromas , sugar in the raw , some fennel notes , sage , really complex . palate : medium-bodied and really herbal and dry . serious beer and seriously dry for a stout . drinkability suffers due to its heft and spiciness .  a : poured into my pint glass , this brew pours a perfect black , with an even more perfect dark coffee bean colored head . the only stout that is better in appearance is espresso yeti .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery , but more substantial than most light beers .

s - i can smell the pumpkin as soon as i pop this one open . i just do n't think it works all too well with the roasted aroma that 's also present . not a bad smelling beer but not my favorite .  great 1 finger dark brown head . head is much darker than most stouts i see these days with the body pitch black . funny i do n't really detect the espresso .  m : somewhat thin , especially for the style i hoped for something richer .

s : not much of a nose , but some good roast notes . t : great mix of roasted malt bitterness and sugary sweetness here .  thanks to kurtissellen and everetends for throwing this beer into a trade , this beer is about 8 months old a : wow , fantastic , this is what a big stout is supposed to look like inky black with a dark stained mocha wood foamy head that is rich and creamy .  mouthfeel is too thin .

aroma was absolutely perfect . strong vanilla dominates with oak and bourbon intertwined .  great looking beer . looks like carbonated orange juice or maybe a mimosa .  lacks a good bite . it 's dry and nibbles , but i want a good bite in my iipa . not that this is bad , just a bit short . easy drinking , though .

the aroma was citrusy , bready and with mild hops . overall though the aroma was n't too strong though .  on to the beer : it looks just like a duvel . outstanding head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is average , thin and just a bit too carbonated for my taste .

s : not particularly smelly . light notes of hops , caramel malt and faint mint . t : citrus hops dominate .  this beer pours a brilliant cherry amber that picks up some gold towards the edges of my tulip with a semi-thick , sustained film of slightly tan head .  more of the same in the finish , kept triggering my gag reflex medium bodied , slick with moderate carbonation , skewed way to sweet , needs some alcohol burn to mitigate this horrible drinkability .

absolutely beautiful aroma that reminds me of the finer czech pilsners , not that that is surprising . in short , a superb smell . the taste is harshly bitter with almost a hot pepper bite .  a creamy , marshmallowy , eggshell white head foams up about 1 cm and rests effortlessly on the surface . very nice appearance !  decent so far , all the way up to the body , which is askew . slightly too light for the style , and slightly too carbonated ... a couple years should fix one of those .

as i lifted the beer to take my first smell , i quickly realized i was about to taste a diacetyl bomb ... pronounced dyacytle ( butterscotch , butter , etc ) completely covered any other characteristics . all i smelled was diacetyl .  head is huge , retention is amazing and lacing is all over the place .  m - a bit dry and rugged to the palate but still fresh . good enough carbonation .

s : inviting fresh aroma ; metallic and a grainy/wheat smell .  a dark green cover now drapes what was , just a few short hours ago , a crystal blue liquid paradise . freshness date is l 184 h. appearance- much more yellow than amber , this supports an incredibly sustaining four finger crown . lacing is outrageous , draping the inside of the entire glass .  m : medium body that could use more carbonation .

smell : malt sweetness is mild but pleasant . taste : nice malt profile with caramel , bits of chocolate , and a soft bitterness .  a : pours a beautiful golden hued , deep pink color . a slightly off white two finger head . the head dissipates fairly quickly , but retains a nice foam cap for the duration of the glass . moderate lacing .  had my fifth sn pale ale tonight thought id have another for reviewing purposes and same as always it goes down very smooth very clean light hops aroma with a piney finish taste . even though i love this beer i do think its an extremely drinkable all around beer just a bit hyped maybe ?

s - surprisingly subdued but there are definite hints of dark fruits , especially figs . it smells tasty , but not like something extraordinary .  pours a clear amber-orange in color with a dense whipped cream like , pure white head . it does that whole `` reverse cascade '' thing too . impressive pour .  a bit light for style , would have like to see more depth . the carbonation is light but balances well . the body is lacking but still a good beer .

fairly dull aroma of malt . weakest part of this beer .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : beautiful hazy yellow-copper with a towering , rocky two-to-three finger head and sheets of lace s : hallertauer hops smell great -- tangy and spicy .  m : the body is medium and the carbonation is medium as well .

there are times when you say `` aw what the heck '' and i did just that for orange flavored beer . the aroma is oranges - period . could n't smell a hop or the first thought of malt .  it comes out of the tap a beautiful dark opaque brown - very inviting .  mf is a bit lacking , thin , though creamy .

very light body , fairly hoppy , but generally mild . this is a good choice for someone looking for a lighter bodied beer .  pretty clear golden color with a humongous white head . tons of stick here , crazy frothy , and overall just beautiful .  poured into my maudite snifter and produces a caramel color with a finger and a half of off-white foam . light carbonation . banana , pear and floral aromas . a rather tart , spicy taste with some alcohol taste present . while this is highly drinkable , the experience is more enjoyable as it warms .

smell is lightly funky , and a little unforgivably skunky . i 've got a feeling from the aroma that i might have been drinking a mishandled bottle .  appearance- beautiful beer ! gold , leaning almost into a cognac tone , the monstrous three to four finger crown billows and slowly begins to pop away . incredible , massive lacing .  m : on the thin side , and carbonation is on the low side .

curious back story drew me in . split a bottle during an afternoon 's round robin . looked like a perky rose wine or a pink champagne with 7-up advertisement effervescence . initial taste was unanimously honey which mellowed w/each sip . the sake influence almost slipped in unnoticed , but was worth the wait , like an old friend arriving at a party full of strangers .  bomber poured into tulip glass a : wow ! this one is a sight to see . pours with a huge khaki colored head , that reduces slowly and leaves nice full cap on top . tremendous lacing . impressive .  m - average carbonation .

s : clean and crisp . bread with just a touch of hops . t : slightly tart and malty .  pours perfectly for a soft pillowy white head , which is about three fingers thick in a 25cl tulip .  m- medium body , slightly carbonated , has a bit of creaminess to it .

s - clean biscuit and toffee . slight damp earth smell . not a ton of character overall . t - everything an english ale should be .  the appearance of this beer was phenomenal . the golden amber body hosts a wonderful setting to the flurry of little carbonation bubbles that run circles in the glass . the head is fluffy and sticky enough to drownd yourself in .  the only thing that i wish were improved was the body . yes , it 's nice and smooth , but it could be thicker .

then the cleaner aroma of chocolate was more prominant . t- big flavors of roasted malt , coffee , dark cocoa , chocolate covered raisins .  ..poured from a can into my tulip glass ... . appearance : wow , liquid tar pours out of the can and into the glass . this stuff looks like it could stain the glass its in .  the carbonation is better tasted and felt than seen during the initial pour .

raisins , grass , chocolate . d - it 's really not that pleasant to drink .  pours very dark with some beautiful ruby highlights when held up against the light . exceptional to look at .  thin body , decent carbonation .

as far as i 'm concerned beamish is just what a dark beer is supposed to look like . heavily roasted barley gives it at rich , complex , almost meaty flavor . it does n't reach the level of complexity of some of the best dark belgian beers , but i do n't think it 's supposed to . it 's mild enough that it wo n't conflict with any food pairing , and simultaneously robust enough to stand up to anything . i ca n't give it above average for smell because it does n't really have one , but that hardly detracts from the overall experience .  blend 3 bottled 1/18/11 poured into a tulip appearance- pours ruby red , transparent with lots of active carbonation . large fluffy white head , with a touch of pink . great retention and nice lacing .  mouthfeel : has a fair body , but nothing out of the ordinary .

slightly more hoppy than malty but a pretty tame nose altogether . the roasted chocolatey malts make their way forward about halfway through the glass .  appearance- *glugs* a hazy , pale gold color into the glass ... the crisp , soapy head is snow white and persistent at two full fingers thick . even after several minutes standing , the dollop of foam is still fat and stalwart ... the lacing is sticky and wonderful .  mf - medium body , very creamy , light carb .

smell : i could n't really smell much . taste : definitely bitter , but in a good way .  poured into a tulip pours a beautiful clear deep amber with two fingers of thick , creamy head ( almost like foam on a root beer float ) .  the belgian/wheat characteristics are present in the background but also help to make it such a smooth drinking brew m : average mouthfeel with a slight ammount of tongue tingle d : highly drinkable beer with very smooth characteristics but still beautiful tastes overall i absolutly love this beer and it is my mission to spread its wonder to all

the smell is a bit weak and there are fine notes of some malt and dry bitter hops .  purs a nice , dark brown color , with a slight dark red color around the edges . 3 finger head , with really nice lacing throughout .  mouthfeel - refreshing but a little sour-ish on the tongue .

first thing i get is faint herbal hops in the nose . lightly metallic . rich , far more rich that the nose suggested .  pours a very , very dark color , almost pitch black with a nice tight head that clings to the glass perfectly .  a little watery on the feel as the carbonation disappears completely as you work your way down the bottle .

aroma is very light here , just a fruity hop note is all .  looks awesome ! s : smells super roasty with bitter chocolate upfront .  i like the way this beer opens up although it ends up tasting a bit thin for the rest of the drink . m- smooth , sticky , but not thick at all .

a great smelling ipa . smooth , almost fruity flavor , high hop bitterness in the back , some sweetness up front , nice palate connectivity .  pours a golden yellow with a centimeter of foam and a geyser of bubbles nearly turning my glass to a boil and maintaining the head to the last drop . beautiful .  a little , fizzy , cherry hit , followed by with a slightly bitter , tangy , vanilla-y taste . ) after the initial few sips , i start noticing the bourbon influence , and it takes on a slightly woodsy element . it 's warming .

smell was a little weak but there was hints of hops and alchol .  pours with a two-fingered head and leaving a good lace . beautiful , clear amber/ruby color .  i 'm just back from a trip to the bahamas and the place i stayed at offered heineken , kalik and miller lite . i 've had both heineken and miller lite so i thought i 'd try the local brew , kalik . boy was i impressed . i drank quite a bit of this brew while sitting by the pool and each one tasted as good as the last . i sure got a good buzz but even better , no headache ! if you ever get to the bahamas be sure to try kalik .

it had a nice wood scent to it .  bottle courtesy of thebeercellar2 : poured a slightly hazy blonde color ale with a huge foamy white head with great retention .  i quite liked this beer ! though for a wheat the color to me was not quite what i thought it should be . drank it on my front porch with friends , it was a great summer beer . this is beer # 12 of my 2 new beers a week !

s - pine and grass come through first . the aroma is mild . too mild .  a - this looked absolutely beautiful .  m - the pumpkin gives this beer a slick mouthfeel , and it could use a bit more carbonation , too .

opaque light yellow brown with a light orange hue . smell is huge -- fragants of sweet honey , mellow almonds , nutmeg , etc . fairly balanced between other flavors -- some nutmeg , cloves , a touch of cinammon ?  appearance : poured with an amazing white frothy foamy head that stood 1inch over the rim of the glass that dissipated very slowly leaving a beautiful lacing all down my glass . the beer is slightly cloudy yellowish gold .  it 's a little too thin for my taste , but like i said i could easily drink this all night and this is why .

not much aroma , just a slight malty nose .  aesthetically this is a beautiful beer with its deep garnet hue and relentless tan head . plenty of lace clings to the insides of the glass as i take each gulp .  the taste is nice , the coffee does n't seem overbearing or anything , but i 'd prefer more a thicker body and maybe more sweetness . very tasty but more body would be nice for a fit with the flavor .

s : aroma is not forefront to this brew , but it smells like good fermented barley should .  lots of lacing and spectacular lacing . tons of effervescence fed from the etching in the perfect pint . this beer really does have a beautiful color , there really isnt anything like it .  only knock on this beer is mabye a little too much carbonation .

off the bat , i was surprised by the flavor of this brew . a nice ginger kick with nice malt flavor and a decent hop finish . definitely a nice winter brew . i was pleasantly surprised .  this beer pours a cloudy pale orange color . this beer looks a lot like a really good hefe , and i like that .  the color was the only thing remotely impressive about the beer i thought , it was a fine dark reddish color with a medium body , there was almost no head ( maybe a half inch ) . this beer has a very weird taste , almost like bubble gum mixed with some fruit and spices . for me this is typical of magic hat , i only really enjoy the heart of darkness . the after taste was even funkier than the initial flavor , i doubt i 'd drink this again .

the smell is veryy subdued , even as it warms . spicy with caramel and vinous malt . the fact is this is a fantastic quad , exceptionally smooth and very drinkable .  the beer pours a winsome onyx color ; the head is a cap of frothy chocolate and the residual lace a sticky sheet .  the beer is a little above average in drinkability , but the mouthfeel left much to be desired .

smells of molasses and a sort of sweet oak .  it looks absolutely beautiful in the glass , with a ruby brown color that really catches the light nicely .  mouthfeel is a little thicker than i thought it would be , and it 's drinkable if it 's cold enough to mask its most interesting characteristic : this beer tastes like bananas .

smell : mild - alcohol is detectable , but through the smell alone this is not an overpowering element . pleasant , peaty finish , somewhere between a cheap porter and a complex english dark ale .  it just looks fantastic in a glass .  the mouthfeel was slightly thinner than expected .

i 'm not really getting anything special in the nose . some roasty toasty ness .  the head is a very large frothy , foamy monster ! lots of lacing .  the carbonation is really about where an ale should be and there is just a bit of chewiness . to be honest , i would really like to see the darker malts removed and the carbonation reduced a bit but i suppose at that point it might as well be a whiskey .

i wish the malt and chocolate aroma was bigger . t : thats more like it .  pours ruby with a large persistent head leaving loads of lacing . beautiful .  this is a quite a bit thicker than other ris that i have tried which i liked , it doesnt have an overpowering taste like others that i prefer .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . this is amazing ! and canned pineapple ! or pineapple sherbet , with a metalic ( aluminium , i dont know why since it 's a bottle ! or maybe i 'm just used to good ipa 's . it is good , but not definitely not outstanding .  appearance-gorgeous looking beer , pours beautifully into my pilsner glass . solid gold with a huge two finger head , very appetizing .  m & # 8211 ; the feel is , surprisingly , a little under-carbonated .

i have never been a particularly huge fan of the original arrogant bastard ale , as i find its strike on the palate a bit overwhelming . smells similar to the original ab , with less of the hoppy notes associated with the original . i was pleasantly surprised upon tasting it .  pours jet black with a small tan head . one of the nicest looking heads i 've seen .  taste is crisp grain , fizzy carbonation , dry aftertaste . really enjoyably light , but with reasonable malt flavor and thankfully without the taste of corn .

nose : usual belgain nose , thick . the nose is close together , for me , that means the different scents are hard to pick between . i get cofee , tofee , spice .  this stout looks as delicious as it tastes .  feel is light bodied with little carbonation .

cold , it smells a little like weak french roast . warming up , i get coffee creamer & cocoa powder , bark , & surprisingly clean yeast ( where are the belgian phenols ? the alcohol detracts slightly , but overall , a really nice beer .  pours a rich and bright amber colored brew with a tight laced and thick white foam head thats healthy , retains very well and clings to the glass and creates a pleasing lacing effect . its a gorgeous looking beer .  m - thin to medium body , but not watery . the carbonation is at a moderate level . the mouthfeel overall is at the appropriate levels , but nothing jumps out as distinct or mind blowing .

people seems to give guinness alot of flack for being `` not stout enough '' ect ect . at only 136calorires a pint , you can throw back quite a few , compaired to the 300+ with `` stoutier stouts '' .  it 's almost kind of amazing how dark this beer pours .  mouthfeel : a bit loose , i expected it to be a bit thicker . carbonation is spot on though .
