faint , somewhat subdued aroma , of caramel and some cookie dough like sweetness . just a faint hint of some earthy hoppiness . nice clean and crisp flavors .  the pour is impressive ; dark brown , almost black , with a thick light brown head .  this felt very light on the palate , but given it is a pale ale it does what it is supposed too . again the sense of freshness was brought through to the taste .

smell is the weakest point here , mostly smells like metallic yeast .  winter version this beer pours deep orange-amber and is very hazy -- no filtration here . the off-white , creamy head lingers for the duration and also features great lacing .  on the flip side , it 's bitterness is comparatively mild , and the body is lighter than most as well , which leads to very high drinkability .

the first sniff smells like glue -- yes , glue . overall , a very potent brew that i 'm glad i 've tried , but not one that i should probably have too often .  extrememly frothy and creamy . leaves large chunks and patches behind . a nice lightly clouded golden colored pour .  poured on tap . big thanks to sean for this ! pours a deep cloudy golden color with almost no head at all . smell is nice and sweet with a great maple aroma . taste is nice and sweet , maply but sweet enough to even it all out , easy drinking and super excellent , very awesome !

smell is a bit soft , but a yeasty , bready component is sadly the most noticable aspect . delightful roasted malt fills the mouth on the first sip , as an explosion of carbonation tickles the tongue . thankfully , the yeasty component that was so present in the nose is absent , or at least much more subdued , in the taste . i do n't think this quite qualifies as a `` great '' beer , but it 's pretty damn good .  pours a dark brown with some reddish hue.foamy head , vanilla colored milk shake looking lace that lasts the duration of the drink .  taste is malty sweet goodness with a light hop finish . this is a nice session beer very drinkable . it has the malty sweetness i have been craving lately mmm .

the nose is quite fantastic , rich and complex . brown sugar , vanilla , vinegar , oak . very complex . cherry skins , ripe berries and a buttery chardonnay character that reminds me of depuration , this beer is mildly funky . pretty insanely drinkable , this !  dark ruby/burgundy color with a full head that forms interesting shapes .  although moderate in body all around , the mouthfeel is a touch too fluid , and needs additional viscosity . eeriely akin to an aged osa 2002 , albeit with less body .

smells like citrus . reminds me of summer and we 're in the middle of a grey november day , so that 's nice . smooth , well-balanced taste , but perhaps a touch too bubbly .  very nice looking .  mouth is one area where i feel this beer falls to average . way too carbonated and a tad on the thin side for where i prefer an imperial stout .

s : nothing particularly special . if you swirl well you can get a hint of hops . t : an interesting mix of hops and malts . i tried hard to be objective reviewing this ale . i like the maltiness but i also like that bitter citrus finish and this one has them both without being too refined .  this brew pours an almost opaque black color . the head is massive , creamy , and brown .  m - seems thick at first yet fails to stick .

smell is excellent . orange , berries , bitter , big sweet tropical and mango scents and slight pine and slight wheat scents but very full . almost frothy mouthfeel it is so light and creamy but still has a good body but extremely bitter .  this beer pours with a lot more darker golden colored body , than its pilsner sister .  far from a traditional belgian , this beer is a good replacement for cider in the fall , or a refreshing change-up for a summer day . m - nothing special here , especially due to the lack of head .

smell : sweet , but too shy to detect it correctly . taste : smooth and sweet .  a - pours a clear amber with brilliant ruby edges . gorgeous spiderweb lacing .  fairly light body and a slightly watery mouthfeel .

not huge in the nose , but a somewhat sweet malt calls me in and a nutty earthy character sits patiently in the background .  poured into an english pint glass with an oily black colour and large frothy tan rocky mountain head , easily aggrevated from a gentle pour .  the body is a bit lean and draws somewhat thin in the finish .

aroma is actually a little weak , i can smell a bit of the roast and a bit of the pepper .  12 oz bottle poured into pint glass a : hazy orange color little bits of yeasties floating around with lots of creamy off white head.. about 2 fingers worth of head and the foam stick around ... . wonderful lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little weak .

s - it smelled of sweet cranberry with some tart notes . not much else here . d - this is a very nice lambic .  black , looks fantastic .  the carbonaton is a bit high and detracts a bit from the quality of this beer , but overall an excellent , potent stout that is sweet without being too sweet .

there 's not much to say about the nose on this beer ; there 's a bit orange blossom fruitiness . overall , this is a very enjoyable ipa .  the beer is a super dark red or amber . it looks delicious on appearance .  this is one of my favorite beers . had it at a fall rennaisaunce festival locally . hate that it 's seasonal . it was light , and very refreshing on a hot autumn day in the south , and yet warm and comforting on the cool ones .

nothing special about the smell -- maybe i 'm getting sick ? nah , just not a strong nose on this one . tastes really nice . very light on the spices .  a : deep copper color with compact , dense and full head , tiny bubbles , clear s : medium deep roasted , burnt malt nose with etoh presence , some oxidation t : nice beer , some hints of oak aging , good deep roasted/burnt malt with yeasty qualities , reminded me of an amped dubbel , slight amount of sourness in finish ( barrel aging or infection ?  t-coffee up front followed by a grape raisin in the middle and a cocoa powder/unsweetened chocolate finish . m-kind of watery and a bit syrupy , not unpleasant but not great d-alcohol very well hidden , but warming and at 4.50 $ a bomber could be quite dangerous .

nothing to report in the smell department ( it 'smelled liked a beer ' to quote my g/f ) the flavor is also amiss , with no real malt sensations tho some honey style sweetness could be detected . thin bodied , but easy to drink but thoroughly lacking in character overall .  looks delicious . whats amazing is how dark the head is .  m - nice light carbonation and creaminess , but the body is a little light and watered down .

s : weak smell , slightly sweet and malty a : perfect blend of very subtle bitterness with a perfect amount of woody sweetness . d : an excellent amber .  a : oqaque black with a two-finger caramel sticky head that stays with a solid lacing . t : thick milk chocolate melted ice cream , the roast lingering through the end with the hops that are somewhat resinous ( pine needle or rosemary ) and slightly citric .  the carbonation is medium strong ; the few medium sized bubbles are fresh . the liquid is semi-smooth . a lager with lots of off flavours .

what i could get from the aroma was a dry sweetness and something of a crisp mineral scent .  had this out of a bottle poured into a dfh pint glass ... a : copper color with a nice 2 finger white head . the lacing on this one is fantastic ... s : smells of floral hops and sweet malt .  taste : thin malt levels , corn , honey , green grapes , grass , and no bitterness . mouthfeel : lightly crisp to start , dry and smooth at the finish . light in body , thin in flavor . clean aftertaste .

s- light smell of hops , more pine than grapefruit . not much else in the aroma .  8.4 oz bottle poured into a tulip . pours an absolutely beautiful blood red , crisp and clear , with a thick , dense , foamy bright pink head .  i had this on tap at victory brewing a - a very pale golden with good clarity and small snowy head with small bead , little lacing collects s - the smell is yeasty , with subtle sweet malt and mild floral hops m - the feel is thin , but apropos to style w/ light malt texture sweet herbal hop feel and kind of watery finish t - the flavor is crisp , clean and sweet w/ floral hops not really adding any contrast in the way of bitterness .

i was a little displeased with the nose on it i honestly could n't get but a faint citrus and a slight malt undertone . it felt nice on the mouth , well hidden ethanol affect even at 6.8 .  poured into a snifter a : very dark pour which gives a huge head , coffee colored . fantastic sticky lacing all over the place s : roasted malts dominate the nose , but there is some coffee present too .  m : the body is medium with a moderate to high level of carbonation .

extremely dark brown color and approaching black . there is a sweet and smooth malt attack . faint traces of coffee are present in the finish . it is pretty sweet and malty compared to what i normally prefer , but i really enjoyed this .  the beer pours out a hazy reddish orange , and has a magnificent head that stays around for minutes and leaves lacing down the side of the glass.. has a very clean taste .  m : good but nothing outstanding d : i could drink a lot of this .

s- huge , seductive hefe aromas of soft banana , clove and bubblegum soar up out of the glass . t- wonderful , rich sweet banana and clove flavors make up the attack . but unfortunately the mid-palate and finish are thrown off balance by too much hop bitterness . had this `` doppel weizen '' not been over-bittered , it would have been knocking at the door of the weihenstephaner vitus and ayinger weizen-bock , two of the greatest beers of their kind in the world . clearly , the expert hands of bavarian masters were involved in this beer , but was it a hop-centric american who had the input to jack up the ibu ?  the head is truly fantastic , and the lace clings tenaciously to the glass all the way to the bottom .  mouthfeel is strange .

s-smells of banana bread , some dark fruit , and a bit of roasted and chocolate malts .  bottle : poured a cloudy hazy dirty orangey color ale with a super large foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  good flavors , with excellent roasted grains and a huge creaminess ; very little detectable hops , which was fine ; perhaps just a bit too much on the creamy , sugary side . a little rough , going down , but not too bad ; it just would n't be an all-the-time beer because of this .

thin mouth feel and over whelming smell and taste of nutmeg and cinnamon .  this beer pours black as night with a creamy amber foam . nice carbonation .  medium light body with moderate carbonation . somewhat astringent .

flavor was heavy on the lemon-citric side with floral elements as well , though there was surprisingly little aroma . a good quaffer .  mikkeller beer geek breakfast is an opaque black beer with a dark muscovado colored head that gets blotchy and has outstanding retention and lacing .  it was watery and smooth with just a little carbonation and a strong malt aftertaste .

the beer is slightly aromatically challenged , although pleasing notes of malt do slip through restrained piny hop smell .  pitch black with a large 1 '' creamy redish khaki head . looks like black coffee ( with an added head ) .  its actually too carbonated for this type of brew .

s : unremarkable , nothing really there that stood out .  attractive ruby body with delicate carbonation and a velvety tan head .  in terms of style , the mouthfeel was flawless . however , since it is packaged as a winter brew i feel it falls short of the mark . imo , the carbonation is too coarse , or the body a bit too thin , for a `` winter warmer '' .

smell : upfront it has a wine-like tannic with some acidity . i was a little put off by the nose though , does n't seem to match well , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  a very nice looking beer .  it was thin and gave a slight hoppiness that did n't last long in the mouth .

s : lots of sweet citrusy fruits aromas mixed with fresh hops . t : hmmm .  pours a hazy dark yellow with a big fluffy wihite head that retains well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel is a little lacking in my opinion but does not detract from the beer too much .

it 's a subtle scent and quite pleasing .  appearance : the beer poured a nice 3 finger chocolate colored head . also , beer is pitch black with no clarity and no signs of carbonation . the head of beer has not come down yet and will have to say the retention is fantastic and lacing on the glass .  weakest aspect of this beer is the body , which is a bit on the thin side , with light carbonation .

s : light , some roast and sweet oats .  appearance - a few moments after uncapping , a plug of foam starts slowly creeping up the neck in the bottle . the beer has a purplish red cast , but needs a strong backlight to show it .  unfortunately this seems a bit thin but very tastey though . well for a sawbuck per growler it is real nice .

the scent is a little underwhelming . i 'm trying to get something out of this , but it 's being quite abstinent . mmmm .  had about a one-finger head with great retention .  m - medium-bodied , but a bit too hoppy on the finish to be as refreshing as it should be .

smell- the smell was very mute in this pouring ... maybe just this in specific , all i could detect were mild vanilla notes .  pours a dark , hazy amber/brown color .  mouthfeel - prickly and a little thin .

smell is quite strong . i could smell it after the pour from an arm 's length . very bitter and hoppy , slight sweet malt aroma .  really quite impressive . the liquid is cloudy with a yellow-gold color .  m- now this is a little off , the body is a little flabby , and even slightly watery .

the aroma is pleasant - noticeable pumpkin , some spices - clove , cinnamon , and nutmeg ? overall an interesting brew , the aroma is nice , but the flavor is n't .  big three fingers of off-white head , fading to a thick cap with great retention and maybe slightly patchy lacing . looks more like a nice stout than a bsda or black ipa .  m : smooth and creamy mouthfeel , thin body , light carbonation . a bit light on the body that i think affects the flavor , but it 's still very enjoyable .

smells of fudge , tobacco leaf , sweet and vegetal , a little musty , very very nice . definitely smells better than it tastes , looks , and feels .  one of the coolest looking labels that i 've ever seen . it is blacker than charcoal and forms a great mocha colored head .  mouthfeel is oily and slick , and a little fizzy .

low smell , lots of lurking semi-roasted malt and some booze . some fruit , too .  poured from a bottle that was filled in december 2009 , this one glows in the glass with a medium-dark garnet brown color and a big , frothy , light beige head .  not sure what 's going on with this one . smells and tastes like a bucket of water with household cleaner thats been laying around for a couple of days . try for yourself , but i guarantee you wont want to try it again . also , ive read about people paying upwards of $ 9 for a 22 oz . bottle . i paid $ 6.49 . pay no more ...

head is small and bright above a hazy , pale body . not much , nasally . taste is unremarkable , to say the least . hops come in very late and unimpressively , like a pinch-hitter grounding out .  a- this is midnight black with really dark reddish brown head that consumes 1/2 the glass .  a fruitty flavor , like a pure english beer , i try this beer from carrefour , almost a year , a rare beer in my country , well ballanced ingredients , very flematic like english men , i visit its site regularly `` www.oldspeckledhen.co.uk '' , very attractive , its holding greene king , its famous for good beers ; recommended for a six oclock with a snack or american food .

smells very inviting ; i could smell this one while the glass was sitting on the table . a pleasantly sweet , hop aroma ... herbal , almost like honey or clover . very fragrant and very appealing to the nose . sierra nevada fans will dig this one but i do not like the kind of hop bitterness found in here ... that sharp citrus rind bitterness that takes too much attention to itself and shouts down other flavors that might speak up .  this beer has a beautiful pour ; two fingers of head that slowly deflate , leaving thick lacing on the glass .  light and effervescent , with a hint of caramel malty sweetness . i bought a six pack of this , and after drinking the first beer , immediately grabbed another six . definitely the best 5.99 beer in the store . do n't pick this up if you 're looking for a complex thought-provoking brew . but if you want a session beer that 's a good alternative to macro-swill and are n't into over-hopped domestics like sam adams and goose island , this is a great seasonal . similar to a leinenkugel brew . a friend said that this was what you 'd get if newcastle brewed an amber . drink straight from the bottle - not really enough nuance to bother with a glass .

smell - best smelling beer i have had yet ! the coriander mixed in really boost the smell of this beer .  a - a clear golden color , pores a thick head and tons of sticky lace that just never quits s - piny and floral hops and spices , with the yeast providing the earthy aromas that give it that saison style t - light malts and spicy with dry hop notes towards the end .  a bit too thin , and a tad over-carbonated . the body was n't quite there , but still a winner .

aroma is minimal and somewhat generic .  3 fingers of gorgeous creamy of white head . excellent retention w/ a little less lacing down the glass .  solid brew ... have had several river horse 's over the years with mixed results . by far this is the best beer that i 've had from this brewery . good amber/red beer flavor that 's slightly crafty but not overpowering at all . could not drink these all night but definitley 2-3 not a problem . do give this one a try , if tasty amber/red beers are your thing . you will be happy with this one .

s strong aroma of extremely floral , piney hops .  two inches of light brown head with nice retention . the thickest of lacing . this looks perfect .  mouthfeel was medium with a heat that would be completely incorrect for the style .

smell : sweet , coffee smell , kind of disappointingly one dimenional , but i 'm a hop head i ask a lot .  it pours a gorgeous deep mahogany hue with a small but very long lasting tan-colored head . excellent , excellent lacings remain after the head has gone .  5.5 % abv . fizzy off-white head . ) & ginger..macro-ish metallic attributes as well . plenty of sweet honey right off the bat..the combination of that and the tangy overuse of lemon peel made me feel like i was eating a pack of skittles . a ton of ginger thrown in for good measure.. wow , is my palate confused on whether or not this is a beer . certainly a bold taste from an interesting beer , but the flavors honestly do not blend together well at all . it 's hard to believe our forefathers would drink this stuff.. i hope they had better taste , because yeah , this one did n't work for me at all .

s- lots of cinnamon , pumpkin , nutmeg , and citrus . very aromatic t- lot of natural pumpkin , ginger , and nutmeg , cinnamon , seltzer like taste , and quite a bit of graininess . o- an okay pumpkin ale , the flavor was not nearly as robust as the aroma though .  a - slightly cloudy amber with an amazing , globular , dense styrofoam , duvel-like whipped head and tons of lace . impressive by any standard ; beautiful . s - pine , malt and ( believe it or not ) sweet cucumber .  mouthfeel was alright but nothing to write home about .

s : hops ! grapefruit , a bit floral , and hint of skunky grassy smell .  poured from 12oz bottle to pint glass a : pours a deep amber color with a beautiful two finger off-white puffy cloud-like head that has very good retention and a nice amount of lacing all the way down.. s : smells quite bold .  m : very medium-light body and a slightly bitter but almost watery finish .

curious light white setiment around the middle of the glass . smell : incrediably faint , so much so that it was hard to make anything out of it .  appearance : coppery amber with an enormous puff of foamy head that lasted until the liquid was gone from the glass . very , very impressive .  bready malts and a faint aftertaste of alcohol is also present beer is way over carbonated . only thing that got to me was the over carbonated .

crystal clear pale ( maybe a little too much on the pale side ) nutty amber body that pours with a great 3 finger off-white foamy head . s-lots of hop aroma almost overshadows the solid caramel malt backbone .  lots of stouts look black in the glass . total darkness black hole . creamy dark tan head , a level three fingers . good lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for my liking .

s : initially , i get a wet dog smell but that fades quickly into a nice nutty coffee flavor . very nicely done , minus the wet dog smell in the nose .  a : pours an extremely dark ruby-brown with a billowing khaki colored head that took forever and a day to recede into a thick oily film that left epic sheets of lacing down the glass . great head retention .  it smells and tastes like a cheap beer . it is not worth the money that a premium beer can ask . i ca n't think of anything good to say about this beer other than i 'm hoping it will be gone soon . i 've tried pawning the beer off on people and they did n't want to drink it either .

the smells were of cherries and corn malts .  this looks great . perfect amber color with a steady one inch head that stayed the whole time .  gorilla vanilla was billed as light in body & alcohol and it was exactly as described . my wife that hates beer said she could drink this with no problem .

not a fan of the aromas here , not unappealing but not particulary good either .  appearance : copper amber with a very nice caramel tone thicket of head , lacing forms a thck collar that continues to leave intersipping full rings .  mouthfeel is on the thin sider , and a bit oily , but there 's enough carbonation to keep it pleasant .

a - orangeish tan with almost two inches of head s - mild smell , not offensive but not appetizing either t - a bit sour and very bitter m - sharp on the tongue , you can tell there 's a lot of alcohol in this beer .  pours a mostly clear medium amber with plenty of thick , cream-colored head . great head retention and lacing .  the lack of flavor is the most important part , it 's more like a watery , sour drink with a bit of beer added . i guess that is malt , but it 's ... light . on the bright side , it 's refreshing at first and there is no really offensive `` off '' flavor 's , i 'm not picking up any metal and it 's rather clean .

not much of a smell . taste is quite nice . all in all , a very nice blanche . it 's a straight ahead , good blonde beer .  a - pours a beautiful dark amber with a two-finger , dense , off-white head . head stays intact all the way down the glass and leaves behind a big wall of lacing .  smells slightly watery faint tones of chocolate malts and coffee good although slightly watery tastes of slightly toasted coffee and powerful malts chocolate is also in there mouthfeel well carbonated yet slightly watery some of the best drinkability i 've experienced in a stout however this comes at a cost and the cost happens to be its mouth feel , taste and smell overall its a pretty good drinkable stout it really is not very good unless it is poured from the tap i 'll order at a pub if i want a stout and they do n't have a good micro brew on tap

the aroma is juicy citrus hop with some sweet crystal malt .  poured from a `` nitro-can '' into a guinness pint glass dark brown/black in color , with a beautiful `` reverse carbonation '' cascading effect , that leaves a moderate , off-white , creamy head of foam .  m - mouthfeel was alright ... carbonation was high and body was light .

the aroma is soapy bubblegum with a little spicy hops .  huge creamy off-white head . an awesome caramel color that lets you know this is a serious beer .  mouthfeel- a tad thin for the style but still got a nice solid body .

despite the dry hopping , the aroma is very faint . ive honestly never had a beer that tasted quite like this .  deep burgundy color with a gigantic , creamy and rocky head of foam . this looks like a belgian for sure .  102 ibu ... tastes sweet , like honey and ginger ale with a touch of malt . little too syrupy to be super refreshing but still awesome .

smell is toffee , a little biscuity maltness soghtly spicy and a hint of yeast , probably due to the bottle conditioning . some fruits as well , but i cant put a finger on what fruits ... the taste here is sooo much more than the weak smell . taste is dominated by a fruity fudgy maltiness , imagine a not-too-sweet piece of fudge , but instead of being fudge-brown , it 's violet , and has faint but oh so noticeable hints of blueberry , raspberry and apples cooked in sugar syrup .  pours a beautiful hazed gold , reminiscent of belgian witbiers and not exactly the german hefeweizen .  m : for a stout the mouthfeel is awfully simple , though the sweet notes add some much needed depth .

grass , burnt bread and stale coffee on the nose .  deep , black-coffee brown with an incredibly dense burnt sienna foam cap , just thick as all get out .  m - feels very smooth going down . nothing too speial about it .

smell - floral hops mix with a nice malt aroma .  superior lacing & head retention s : bready with hints of brown sugar t : bready & fruitty ( dates ) with a little too much boozeyness up front .  moderate carbonation and a light , slightly watery mouthfeel .

s : very little aroma . a hint of sweet buttered bread and a tiny bit of earthy hops .  the beer looks great , dark brown very bubbly brew with a tan creamy chunky head that sits nicely through out the expierence . nice lacing - very impressive looking beer .  a light to medium body , with prickly , active carbonation . the carbonation was just a tad bit higher then i would have liked , but was still enjoyable .
s - soapy and grainy aroma .  great looking beer .  [ postscript : 18 months later , and another 6-pack of this enjoyed , the mouthfeel was much less sticky , but way too carbonated .

i was mildly surprised to see a stout on draft in the netherlands , but the bar came highly recommended . nonetheless , a very tasty stout , with nice dry tones and not much residual sugar .  a- very dark in color , amber with hues of maroon . pours with a luscious strong head .  somewhat substantial body , nothing too heavy . if any hit , a little too much carbonation but that is stretching it .

streaky lacing after every sip s- very under whelming aroma . im picking up sweet fruit smells but they are muted .  dark black with one of the darkest 1 finger heads i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel was much lighter than expected with a slight buttery feel .

the beer smells nice .  a- perfect . deep ominous black body with thick creamy dark tan head . the head retention is excellent and a coating of lacing is left all the way down the glass .  i think that it is a bit overcarbonated and that the body is a bit thin , but the smell and taste are absolutely wonderful , and i could drink this all night .

smell - has a faintly sweet smell , with a floral hoppiness .  poured into a glass with an incredibly dark and thick pour .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , pretty amazing for a beer of this gravity , making this dangerously drinkable .

poured a 12 ounce bottle in a snifter a : black , brown frothy head s : coffee , bittersweet choclate , a hint of heavy cream , malt t : toffee , roasted malt , coffee , chocolate , cream , the bitterness is sharp and nicely balanced between roasted malts and hops .  it pours a stunning clear amber color with a tightly bubbled white head .  it is perhaps on the thin side and sweet side and is not too complex , but has good character that hold up well .
faint aroma of hop and florals .  nitro produces a wonderful cascading effect .  mouthfeel : very light/somewhat watery with a high degree of carbonation .

the smell is wonderful , fruity at first , and then chocolatey , with maybe a hint of coffee .  a- pours a cherry color with a thick off white head and sparce lacing .  body is a little thin for an oatmeal stout , but it still has the smoothness . carbonation feels a little too heavy for this style i think .

smell - slight malty aroma , not really that much of a smell to it taste - malty , smokey , delicous .  dark amber hue with red highlights . nice one and a half finger , frothy , off white head .  m - started off smooth but had a monster tart kick . really the only element that was a bit rough .

smell : nothing special here . it 's smells very light and grassy ; underwhelming .  a : pours a wood stain brown with a perfect off-white head s : smells of cloves , spices , breadiness and booze .  after my first taste i really was able to feel how refreshing this beer truly is , and i enjoyed ever sip . not your normal fall seasonal , due to the lack of heavy sweet notes , but none the less one of the better seasonal beer i have had .

because it is great stuff . i like this boulevard pilsner . so this is pilsner .  pours a gorgeous black with a monumental ( and extremely audible ) rocky brown head .  it 's a bit thin in the mouth .

s - nose is rather subdued , pleasing but plain . overall it has a faint belgian dark ale sense to it with hints of fruity caramel . the nose is a bit of a letdown but flavor and the overall experience of brew pick it up entirely .  a : it pours a completely opaque black color with two fingers of white nitro froth that laces incredibly well .  m : an average , slightly crisp mouthfeel . however , once the taste of it hit the buds on my tongue , i did n't care much to think about mouthfeel .

the smell is faint even with the boston lager glass ( which btw is incredible ) .  *takes breath* appearance- four fingers of light chocolate brown head grace this ridiculously fabulous looking beer . the sheer density of the crown is stupefying , with large craters rather than bubbles marking its surface . like some object from space , it looks like a chunk of ice or rock from the outer limits .  sweet maple syrup aroma with herbal hops and some yeast . the malts have a very sweet taste and also there is a toasted bread taste that really develops in the aftertaste . very good ale !

malty smell , but other clean .  a- this is the funnest beer to watch while it settles , as it morphs from a caramel colored , bubbly state to a completely dark brown/black brew with an amazing tan head that has an incredible retention from start to finish s- deep roasted aromas ... cocoa , coffee beans , black tea , kind of earthy .  m- medium body , definitely unfiltered .

this is my first time that i test this beer and for me it taste a little like a high class budweiser at the end , the head last longer than an averege lager , love the color is dark amber , a bit of hob/malty flavor and a far sweetnes at the end.what i like about this beer is when it gets about 58 degrees the the aroma become a bit more intense bit the flavor still the same not like the some lagers that become undrinkable .  a truly great looking beer .  very good beer but does lack with a thin somwhat over carbonated mouthfeel for a stout .

smell was a little simple , but ok. vinegar , cherries , malt mnn great smell . the flavor starts out just as the smell , but there is a dark secret .  a : what can i say ... perfect ! ! ! white one-finger head with a dark gold color . carbonation was visible and the beer itself was somewhat transparent . filtered quite nicely ! ! !  m : very light . a bit over carbonated but not overwhelming .

s : slight roasted coffee , and burnt sugar or caramel .  pours dark black with one of the best foamy heads out there and there is nothing like the cascading effect smell : slight smell of roasted malts taste : very smooth and creamy .  m -- maybe i should n't have drank this after sipping on a j.w . its not quite what i would call `` watery , '' but it could use a little more body . carbonation levels are fine .

very enjoyable .  appearance - a very appropriate pumpkiny-orange pour capped off by an incredibly full 3-finger , subtly orange tinted off-white head . cloudy appearance . very impressive .  it was a bit thinner with more carbonation than i would have liked , but overall very drinkable .

smell- had a sweet almost candy like smell . subtle floral tones . taste- sweet brown suger , caramely taste .  pours a jet black . great lacing on my glass .  mouthfeel - thin and mid to low carbonation .

fruity grape and honey aroma . floral note , but really strong wine-like grapes mostly . it smells a lot better than it tastes .  call me weird , but i thought this was a beautiful beer in appearance . a very cloudy apricot color , half a finger of fluffy head and very sticky lacing .  m : somewhat chalky d : high

smell : aroma from this beer is very faint . smells of chocolate , toffee and coffee are present .  beautiful ruby red color .  m : really carbonated , even a bit much . thin body otherwise , however -- just a bit more oomph here and this would be epic .

it also has a nice earthiness to it . the smell is however a little subdued .  this is a great looking beer - substantial off-white head that lasts throughout the consumption , and a glorious , rich red color . it really looks like christmas in a glass .  body is light and mouthfeel is fairly thin and bubbly , with a very clean finish .
s - fruits , malt , mild not pungent smell .  appearance- beer pulls a hazy golden with a spiderweb pattern across the top .  the feel is alright but it does n't matter at this point .

i 'm really blown away by how complex and phenomenally enjoyable this is . wow . o : yet another stunningly good beer from the kernel .  a light brown to dark mahogany ale that pours with a voluminous , rocky off-white head .  m-lighter , a little thin and the finish seems flat as well .

s : delicious mix of citrus and floral hops aromas with smells of mango , pineapple , and orange backed with mild sweet maltiness . t : the taste does n't quite live up to the smell , but it is still very good with big-time floral and fruity hoppiness smoothed by caramel sweet malt flavors .  a- pours a deep cloudy orange color with a massive white head that slowly dissapates into tons of lacing .  acceptable in the mouth . horrible beer .

aroma was mild grains .  pours a deep black with a dark chocolate head . one of the darkest heads i have seen ! head comes alive from deep within the beer mountaining up to build a three finger head . as the head falls , a thick sheet of head remains on the glass , legs for days .  this has got a lot of hop bitterness to it , this reminds me a little of hopslam . i did n't really notice the `` hop backbone '' like everyone else has mentioned . like hopslam , this is best drank slowly due to the high abv .

s- the aroma really is fantastic . there is a lot of sweet malt and caramel along with some citrusy hops .  the beer has amazing retention and great lacing .  still , it seems a little light in body and the carbonation is low . without a doubt another quality beer by dogfish head , but i have a feeling that the pricetag of a 750 ml bottle would scare me from its purchase .

nose is classic stone yeast with a great floral hop kick . overalll , it was damn good . i thought it was almost an ab light with some added pine and less citrus , and no hop double kick to the palate , which works well .  served in its own urthel glass from draught , on to the beer : beautiful ! shimmering golden color with a huge , billowy head on top with excellent retention and lots of creamy lacing sticking to the glass .  m - carbonation is on the low end of high with a sturdy medium body . i do n't much like the huge carbonation and the taste suffers because of it .

not really breathtaking , but worth a whiff . t - delicious !  appearance : gorgeous amber brown ale with tan bubbly head atop . clarity is slightly cloudy . head lasts and lasts but does n't pour so big as to dominate the glass . flawless appearance as allagash beers typically are .  it 's medium bodied ; watery , but smooth . the finish is a little watery .

a rather dark lager , and has a look of being `` heavy bodied . '' smell : not a lot to pick up off the aroma ... a very slight smokiness when agitated , but giving away very little . clean lager ... taste : smooth , clean brew with lingering smoky aftertaste and only a hint of smokiness during . truly delicious , un-challenging version of a smoked lager and very enjoyable , fresh beer .  you got to love the appearance of this , pours out black with a creamy body that cascades and rises to the top creating a tan immovable cream head leaving the black as day brew behind . though something with substance , these are as drinkable as bud light to me .  the mouthfeel is not a complex one and is rather unbalanced and nondescript .

aroma is quite mild , some light caramel and raisin notes and a strange dustiness .  never saw this one before , so i decided to give it a go ... a : awesome look .  its not a bad mouthfeel , just a bit light in the ass .
taste was very delicious regardless of there being poor scent .  the ring and cloud on the beer is very thick and makes for a very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel is oe 's strongpoint .

the smell is malty with a bit of a banana scent apparent . a somewhat sour smell is there as well . for an imperial ipa , there is not alot of hop aroma ; just barely noticeable .  pours a very black with a beautiful 2 finger milk chocolate colored head that leaves sticky mapping on the glass as you drain it .  mouthfeel is average , not too thin , and i think appropriate for this beer .
very strange .  the beer pours a beautiful deep hazy ruby color with a thin white head .  mouthfeel is about average , very drinkable to anyone that enjoys a hoppy bitter beer .

a nice rich , pale brown color . barely there for more than a minute . smell : not that great . smelled metallic and a tad bit sour to me . in my opinion bass is a wonderful ale .  a : fantastic pour , dark loaded with ripples of brown to an excellent creamy head s : roasted malt and alcohol dominate t : water , more water and some roasted malt .  i 'm 90 % sure this is the same beer as their `` gretchen 's gold '' , which is really what i 'll be reviewing . the bottled version leaves much to be desired vs. on draught . i 've not tasted such a difference between tap and bottle in any other beer . extremely refreshing and drinkable , pleasant sweet malt w/ barely discernable hops for structure . scant head . overall a great beer in its style , with no real flaws . if you can get it on tap , it 's well worth it .

not a strong smell of light nutty malts . ah yes ... a taste i thought i forgot ; a fantastic malt and hops balance .  the pour was pitch black with a good , beige choppy three finger head that slowly dissapated and left a thick beige lace on top of the beer .  flavour is incredibly light , almost nothing resembling either a smoked stout or an oatmeal stout . i do n't know why i bothered buying another trafalgar product . i 'm tried of drinking this after a few sips .

i did n't get much from the nose , mostly alchohol and sweetness , but my , once you actually drink the stuff , it is a real winner . good stuff .  i 'd been eyeing this one at the store and then it appeared on tap at american flatbread so ... off the tap the beer came to me a deep garnet color leaning towards brown . the tan head was about a finger thick and retained very well . gorgeous curtains of lacing .  m - on the lighter side of medium body with a good amount of carbonation . this is the biggest problem with the beer , it is just a bit too thin and light .

smell : it 's disappointing to say the least because i do n't get that much hops . very faint citrusy and piney notes . it 's still a very good beer . very good , but maybe a bit over-hyped in my opinion .  this dark lager looks beautiful with its clear dark amber body and good-sized beige head .  i have been drinking a few imperial stouts and imperial ipa 's recently and thought the mouthfeel was a bit thin , but .

not much for smell here . a bit sour and malty . the flavor is awesome with big hops and a subtly paired malt .  appearance : gently hazed champagne body with a soft , stiff , enormous , airy , white head with great retention .  mouthfeel was unremarkable , which is as much as can be expected of any pilsener .

but when i poured the ale , i detected a biscuit like maltiness as well as some fresh fruit odor .  the beer poured into the chalice crystal clear ruby red with a white frothy head which rose and retreated slowly to lace the chalice from top to bottom .  mango , lemon , bretty funk , carbonation is light , only thing i 'm really missing is the dry hops here . mouthfeel- i have a feeling this bottle is a little old , could use more carbonation .

12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - fridge temp - 2008 appearance : pours a golden brown with orange highlights . smell : instant forefront of butter cream with some sharp malt aromas . sweet smelling rum makes it 's way into the fold .  bottle , a : pours black with a frothy tan head , gobs of lace , great retention .  m : thin and light with average carbonation .

s - almost no nose here .  bottle marked best before 22mar11 , served in a tulip glass pours a beautiful black with ruby highlights where light touches it with a light brown moderately dense head that fades to a persistent outer ring with patches of thin foam in near the center .  man talk about pleasantly surprised ... after the last two i wasnt expecting much from this random brew ... glad i picked the best for last ... pour couldnt get much better with a great levitating head and awesome lacing ... nice floral hop aroma , slight alcohol tone not obnoxious at all ... taste is almost all nutty malt , somewhat dry ... alcohol is amazingly well hidden ... one of the easiest drinking malt liquors ive ever had ... too bad the turks got it right before we did ... keep in mind that this four is rated in accordance to other euro strong lagers/malt liquors ... cheers !

served on tap at washington commons in brooklyn , ny . great choice for a wit/white ale session beer . highly drinkable yet full flavor and mouthfeel . would definitely recommend if you 're looking for wit beer/white ale that wo n't fill you up but never let you down .  poured into a pint glass and i most say one of the finest looking stouts i have ever seen . thick creamy heading that left a very creamy fluff when i finished it off . opague black and light brown heading .  the feel was unremarkable .

nose is ... wow ... strange . maybe it 's the hops i 'm detecting , but this one smells soapy and metallic , neither of which are good in beer , me thinks . i am a saison fan , and this is a good tasting saison .  pours perfectly with two fingers of rich sticky off white head that retains quite well .  the taste is about the same , with a distinct nut flavor . goes down pretty easy , but there is a lot of carbonation here , and you can distinctly see many small bubbles rising up from behind the brown color . overall , this is a pretty good beer , and a nice looking one . i recommend it .

aroma is pungent and acrid . when i compare my notes with those of other reviewers , i find that i must be missing something with the aroma , because to me it was the least appealing aspect of this otherwise very excellent beer . very nice .  appearance : deep thick jet black , with a big fluffy medium brown head that leaves huge lacing . pretty much exactly what an imerial stout should and can be .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , otherwise nothing special .

s : spicy and herbal with a little bit of fruit ( strawberry ? t : interesting beer ... better than the smell and lack of protein might lead on .  a dark caramel brown body under a 2 cm head which took several minutes to dissipate but it leaves nice lacing on the glass . a solid look for my favorite style of beer .  mouthfeel is light bodied , light carbonation . smooth , but average .

the aroma is rather mild , it has some spiciness to it , but is fairly unimpressive . nice complex taste -- some spiciness , but also tastes of sweet malt , bitter hops , and fruit .  a - very dark and long lasting tight head . m - for how dark it is and the solid foam i was expecting a much heavier brew .  m : very light , slightly watery , lower carbonation .

i got the floral hops and some citrus . it looks good , but it does n't smell like much . i ca n't smell the same hops that i taste right after .  pours black with a huge cascading head that filled up most of the glass and left tons of lacing , one of the best looking beers i 've had .  m- mouthfeel is carbonated and a bit watery .

smell : a bit of bitter and citric hop presence that holds some lemony aspects ; a dry , powdery , biscuity maltiness ; nose is a little faint , but i feel this has a little to do with the colder temperature that it was served at .  the head is an amazing display , a full inch thick of off-white foam that does n't shrink at all hardly . the beer is quite black although some light peers about the extreme edges .  mf- resinous and sticky with aggressive carbonation . not as soft and luxurious than great traditional belgian ales but rather sharp due tothe load of hops . some powdery yeast feel . it 's so hoppy that i might not have noticed the belgian yeast .

h : 1/4 '' head a : beautiful dark amber s : light , hoppy t : wow , perfect balance of hops/yeast/carbonation m : rico suave d : i can drink this all night this is a great beer to relax to over dinner or in front of the idiot box .  very high carbonation . about 2 '' of tan head forms that has phenomenal retention and lacing .  m : this is light-medium brew that is a little thinner than i imagined it to be . although the mouthfeel is thin , the look , aroma and taste make up for it .

pours golden with a little haze , 1.5 finger of head , leaves beautiful lacing . smell , a little hops , kinda watery some yeast , ca n't make out anything specific taste : piney hops with some bite , pretty much just hops , finishes with alcohol notes that remind me of rum , warms a little body is medium , carbonation is pretty high , very crisp . leaves a little oily finish .  pours a brilliant deep amber with some red hues and amazing clarity . two finger head stays around for at least five minutes , pretty impressive in a scotch ale .  m : thin viscosity ( bordering on being watery ) and moderate carbonation seem out of place here .

the mild malt and spice nose should be stronger .  s- bottle a- looks delicious . just a beautiful looking saison .  the smell is overtly sweet with grain and a touch of honey . it 's terribly sweet with no hops note and truly no redeeming qualities about it . one of my generous gulps actually had me thinking it might come right back up .

smell- a very fruity and a little spicy nose .  hold it up to the light to see something really incredible . an amazing looking beer .  think prunes and raisins , but more complex and infinitely boozier . i ca n't believe that this beer is appearing thin on the palate and i think that it has to be with the insanely high abv . even though it 's clean , it 's still very sweet . i am loving the taste but i am certainly not digging the mouthfeel , that is into the moderate strength liqueur territory . a brewing achievement but not beer like ; delicious nonetheless .

aromas are malt , sugar , slight hops and slight medicinal . nothing strong or offensive , and nothing too exciting . taste is very smooth .  black as night , with a head the color of chocolate milk . it 's a full pint , so it fits the glass perfectly .  smooth and sweet , this is pretty nice . carbonation is a bit low , even for my liking .

light floral .  beer is yellow , mildly hazy , heavily carbonated , nice white head , small bubbles , nice lacing , great retention , this is the perfect witbier look .  mouthfeel was pretty average drinkability was pretty good i could see myself having another one .

rich , medium amber color topped by a large , bubbly off-white head with lots of staying power and a good amount of thick lace left on the glass . smell was mild ... malt with a bit of hop spiciness . an excellent choice when everything else on the menu is a fizzy , yellow macro brew !  appears a pitch black hue absolutely no light shines through when held up to the light , although it does form a large tan moccha frothing head rising at least an inch above my gulden draak chalice .  m : carbonation balance is nothing special .

smell is muted but piney , some citrus , some flowers .  extremely solid ipa here . nice dark amber color with a huge head .  mouthfeel was fine . a little thin - i think that a big , thick mouthfeel would accentuate the pumpkin pie-like characteristic that i think they 're going for .

s - i 'm not picking up a lot here , malt , some fruit and caramel .  750ml capped and sealed bottle . appears jet black .  the amount of flavor packed into something this thin and `` refined '' is unusual and noteworthy . it feels a little creamy on the swirl , but i do n't really like where it stimulates the tongue . however , the mouthfeel leaves something to be desired , so how many will you want to down consecutively ?

aroma overall is fairly subdued and faint with some light malts , bready , toasted nuts , not much of hop aroma to speak of . a nice replicate of the nose with some nutty and toasty malts and a mild hop bitterness throughout . nothing to blow your socks off but very drinkable overall .  a : pitch black beer with a charcoal greyish-brown foamy 3-finger head leaving plenty of lacing all the way down .  mouthfeel is pretty thin , nice a smooth carbonation , but just feels weak .

the smell is tangy and yeasty . the yeast aroma is reminiscent of other belgian beers . there is a medicinal quality to the smell , and some wheat and alcohol aroma as well .  ( a ) - pours a clear yellow/orange color with almost a minutes worth of cascading action followed by a ridiculously thick pure white billowy foam that is sticking everywhere and was still present down to the last drop !  m= body is medium/average but probably a little too thin . i was hoping for a little thicker in the body as well as taste department .

drinkability : a great smelling beer , but the extreme head of the first beer and the sub-par taste makes the beer a bit of a chore to drink .  appearance : golden yellow in color with a thick 3 '' head that lasts a long time . nice lace paints the glass .  m - moderate beer body , strong carbonation . just seems a little thin at times .

the aroma it gives off seems to be mostly malt with some underdescribeable fruit notes from the hops . the taste is best describe as clean , malty , and slightly bitter .  ruby red beer with a light pink head . head has good retention and leaves a layer of sticky bubbles down the glass .  mouthfeel is a bit grainy , again , like the bottom of a cup of coffee .

a - pours a deep dark rust color with a half inch of foam that left plenty of sticky lacing s - citrus , orange and grapefruit , hops dominate the incredible aroma t - slight citrus flavor , but malts dominate with an alcohol burn and a nice hop bite m/d - medium bodied , a bit thicker than i expected .  a - nice dark mahogany color , very thick , ca n't see through it . excellent character and all that i expected coming from stone in a porter .  this beer is exceptionally thin in the mouth however .

smells a bit like wet golden retriever and flowers .  pours an almost opaque black with faint reddish highlights .  it 's quite amazing how such a simple beer can be so good ! perhaps it is its plainness that makes it such good lager . this is not a fancy schmancy beer . the best way to describe this is just plain beer . the smell was slightly grainy , with a hint of barley mash . taste was excellent . this is a very good beer .
the smell is very grain heavy , ugh .  appearance - large offwhite head with a thin lighter colored lace on top of that the head .  mouth : very light for the style , heavy on carbonation .

nose is lighted roasted/carmelized maltines and brown sugar . no hops noted , but a little of the alcohol strength is .  appearance - super pale straw body .  review to style as they say and for a mass produced macro swill this is my favorite for just chillin and enjoying some beer thats not gon na get me too wasted . the appearance on all of em ( macro swills ) is pretty nice gold straw with continued effervescence throughout and a good carbonation level . extremely drinkable and the flavor is a very mellow german or czech type hops . they arent making it strong but it still tastes like one of the beers i grew up with .

s- really not picking up much here besides grain and maybe some malt , my buddy confirms this so i 'm not crazy here .  i was really impressed with the overall appearance of this beer .  there 's a really nice level of hopping in this one , that becomes apparent in the middle and finish . could do with having a bit more body , but its okay as it is .

very fresh , clean , and aromatic . the aroma is very tantalizing and one of the better smelling ipa 's i 've had the pleasure of sniffing in a while .  i loved the way this beer looked in my glass , beautiful amber/red color , nice head , and lacework was plentiful.not really like a scottish ale except in color , but then the labelling on the bottle acknowledges this .  t- hop fruitiness up front , not particularly citrus from the big c hops but just fruity . aftertaste brings up the rear with a hop bitter whollop . m- average for this style , not great but definately not bad .

1 finger head with great lacing , very fresh bottle . s - smells like pine , citrus . if you have access to this beer try it , if you do n't , trade for it to compare it with other stellar ipa .  appearance : the head is massive , dark brown , sticky and lasting . looks like meringue .  m : carbonated and thin .

a very quiet `` pop '' of the cork ... pour was carbonated and good ... whew . light yellow/gold ... decent bright , white head . good lacing ... nothing spectacular . aroma is a touch dissapointing ... was expecting a bit more spice and smells ... a tiny bit of spice and a little wheat ... taste is very good ... bitterly balanced ... slightly citrussy and quite malty .  wow , good looking beer . pours with my favorite waterfall type head ... ( forms from the bottom ) 2 fingers of creamy tan head form and clearly let you know they are going to stay a while . lacing is everywhere .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated for the style .

s : oddly neutral ( perhaps because it 's on draught ? ) with some buttery tones and firm malts deep underneath .  a gorgeous deep , reddish iced tea colored beer supports a wickedly alive bone white head ... three to four fingers easy , and five minutes later it 's still huge and thick . lacing is ridiculous beyond description ... more sculpturous than just sticky .  the beer poured into the glass to reveal a nice copper color . the aroma was slightly bready with a mild hop character . the taste was mildly malty at first then gave way to a nice hoppy dryness in the finish . the is a nice quaffable beer .

pours a deap amber with a 1/2 '' of white head , that dosent leave much lacing . the smell is faint , of grains and honey .  pours a thick black with an equally impressive brown head .  m/d - light body that could stand to use just a slight bump in carbonation imo .

s ~ toasted bread , sweet roll , chocolate-covered espresso bean .  it pours a really pretty reddish brown with a nice off white head that just lasts and lasts . very pretty , lol .  super easy to drink ... just a little thin on the mouthfeel .

subtle aroma is earth and cereal malt . not much going on .  a - a vigorous pour brought out the captain 's true beautiy ; a fat cream head with great retention and absolutely superb lace that covered the entire glass like foamy suds from the tides of the sea . the beer also featured a beautifully clear copper color with mild carbonation action . d - how a beer can look stunning , possibly the best amber i 've ever seen , and still be this bad is astounding .  m - moderate beer body , strong carbonation bite .

s : nice , malty , dark schocolate with a winey alcoholic overtones , really not bad , no hops .  excellent starting , off-white head . it leaves a beautiful blanket of lace as it recedes slowly . cloudy . very close to the perfect appearance !  mouthfeel is an average apa .
sugary syrup infused dry fruits , essential hop oils and something dirty and plant-like .  a- beautiful rising 2 finger head with moderate retention .  mouthfeel is ok .

color of whiskey and iced tea . danged if it do n't smell a little like iced tea ; tastes a little like iced tea , too . grade d+ purchased at stoney 's -- $ 4.99 each  an absolute beautiful presentation in a snifter that words truly fail and fall short in description . spongey patches of lacing leave a nice calling card .  my in-laws bought a leine lodge and this one was in it . leinie 's has a lot of good beers , this one looked interesting so i tried it . i drank if from the bottle so i could not see it but it smelled pretty good . the first sip was in your face nut flavor . too much nut flavor in fact . i kept drinking it because i though it would settle down the more i got used to it but it did not . i actually could not finish this beer . there are n't many beers i would pour down the drain , but this is one of them .

the aroma is quite nice . nice blend of the pumpkin pie spices ; nutmeg , cinnamon and allspice . very nice .  a hard pour produced a 3 finger head . excellent retention . color is a dark ruby brown . impressive head retention .  m - light to medium body , medium carbonation . very slight harsh bitterness lingers on the back of the tongue .

smells of toasted malts , quaker oatmeal , and just a touch of cabbage .  bottle poured beautifully . the most beautiful head i 've ever seen formed at least an inch tall with nice puffy cloud-like lumps . the beer itself was a very nice rusty brown color . easily the most beautiful beer i 've ever poured .  well done porter ... .looks the part with a creamy tan head atop a black body ... a very nice aroma greets my nose..roasted and sweetish ... milk chocolate as well as some subtle coffee notes milk chocolate and roasted malts are the big players on the taste but the java notes become a little more pronounced ... body is creamy and smooth and slightly thin ... i do n't exect regular ol porters to be high gravity monsters so this is fine with me ... it really drinks easily and quickly ... .

eyes ... light caramel hue , one finger of white foam that recedes quickly , lacing is very good , just a very average looking brew , which is not a detriment really nose ... nice piney citrus notes right off the bat , grapefruit ... amarillo hops ? underneath they smell a little green and herbally ... and really fresh . for just a regular ipa the smell is very nice taste etc ... the carbonation is a bit lacking which impacts the mouthfeel negatively , mild hop oils flow , barely any ibus felt.. i wonder how this is rated in terms of ibus but the bitterness is missing , ditto the hops for the most extent , this is also a bit watery for my tastes .  a : pours a dark , nearly impenetrable black body with a perfect finger 's worth of light tan head . it 's exquisite , in the way that all nitro-tap dark beers are : watching the suds coalesce into a dark body as they cascade up the beer is nothing short of eye-pleasing .  m - mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for my liking .

the nose was light overall .  a very large head , especially for a barley wine and one about a year and a half old . this thing rivals the best of the belgians with that head . with the fuzzy lacing , this is a very attractive beer .  mf- medium/light bodied with kind of a watery feel compared to other porters .

smell : old damp wood , barnyard , swine pen , rainy forest .  toward the end of the pouring , the beer did n't even make it beyond the head- it hit the foam and just created more . beautiful dark golden color , the head dissipates slowly , and leaves lacing all down the glass . beautiful .  `` bottled in 2009 '' pours a nice red in color , a hue i have n't seen in beer before , with no head , though it is carbonated . there are also weird vegetable flavors that are not that pleasant . noticeable alcohol flavors and dryness . the more i drink of this the worse it tastes , actually . this beer just does n't do it for me , and it hurts me to give a bad review to a beer from such a great brewery . this is the least distinguished ( a polite way to say `` worst '' ) dogfish head beer .

s- ca n't find much of anything on the nose . t- generic 'beer ' taste . better than some other macro lagers .  this wicked brew is topped with a big creamy , frothy , three finger head . outstanding appearance !  mouthfeel is a bit sticky , like a pretty good ipa .

s - very impressive aroma - chalk full of pine and complex citrus hops .  reviewed 7/12/2007 ( 550ml bottle ) : pours a dark park brown/black colored body , with a tannish colored head , huge and lasting .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation , almost light body .

the smell is incredible . after smelling the first time , you ca n't believe what you just smelled coming out of this beer . it 's like you 're 6 years old all over again . gobs of peanut butter , wheat bread , slight hint of strawberry jam .  appearance this was black and thick like engine oil with a giant head that showed great retention . the foam was like lumpy shaving cream and covered the inside of my glass as it went down . awesome !  that smokiness carries over abundantly into the taste . the lesser side of this is the feel ... bit to far on the light end of things . overall though , solid rauchbier , though probably my least favorite so far of the aecht schlenkerla rauch 's .

since this beer moved out of latrobe , it left the slightly bad taste back the old rolling rock 's used to have back in western pa . the new beer is the most refreshing and lightest beer out there . as others mentioned , its great to quench thirst with food or to pound several in the summer heat .  amazing retention and wonderful sticky lace abounds . this is a very exciting beer to look at .  m : mouthfeel was just okay for me , a bit thin .

s - ca n't smell anything unfortunately t - wow , lots going on .  a : it 's a dark amber or bronze color that is brilliantly clear . the head is a foamy eggshell white that stands about a finger and a half . a whole lot of lacing !  good beer with alot of taste . i unfortunately drank this with a meal so i feel i may not of appreciated the taste of the beer independantly . but the unfiltered armoa and golden look was your typical hefeweizen . beer has a strong character and is a summer favorite

aroma is too weak . light fruits and wheat . in all seriousness , this beer is very poor in the aroma department . but i do n't drink beer for its aroma alone ... the taste rules over all .  beer looks substantial . fantastic retention ... a full finger half way through the glass and excellent lace .  m - a bit flat . mouthfeel is so far the best part of this beer .
- very fresh , brown-sugary light water ... hidden subtle bready grain.. light grassy hop notes .  amazing clear honey color and a sweet smell .  the mouthfeel is medium/thin .

smell : some very mild bread and grassy tones are hard to pull out of the glass , but pleasant . taste : mild bready maltiness with some apples , sweet green grapes , and some soft grass in the background .  awesome rocky head with great lasting power ; the color is a deep red ruby . perhaps the best head i 've ever seen .  never having any of post roads products , i decided to give this brew a try . the taste on the other hand was a smooth pumpkin & hops infusion leaving my mouth only asking when it can have more . overall this is a very drinkable beer from a brewery i knew nothing of before now and now only hope to know more of ...

aroma was a bit of a letdown . however , the aroma was just so flat & bland . i had a ng moon man afterwards & it popped aroma-wise , so it was n't me having an off aroma day -- it was just not ipa like . so much better than i was expecting from the aroma . mouthfeel was nice . overall , this is a hard beer to judge because of the aroma weakness . but the flavor is certainly more important to the drinkability & i enjoyed this beer pretty well .  a : moderate pour yields one finger of just off-white head with good retention . cloudy red-gold is gorgeous when held up to the sunset !  funny , my first craft beer since wv popped the cap and its under 6 % lol nice copper pour.clear and clean leaving pretty rings of lacing with every sip . love that for sure . malty in the nose , not so typical of sierra nevada and i dont mean that in a negative way . sweet , caramel and mixing hops . taste leans towards malt , not tons of hop flavor but nice bitterness . liking this one for sure !

the smell is wonderful . grapefruit and pine . love the smell , but let down by the taste .  this is by far the best looking wheat beer i have ever seen poured into a glass . the head is a very thick frothing white foam that slowly resides , leaving an ample amount of bubbly lacing .  on tap .a creamy hazy orange color with loads of yeast swimming around , small white fluff head.aroma is somewhat heffish , with some mild banana , cloves , orange zest , and grassy notes.flavor is wheaty with loads of banana , bubblegum and and spice , maybe even pineapple . very drinkable , refreshing after a long days work . would make a solid summer brew too .

nice clear light cherry wood color . smell is faint , but mild nut aromas and whispers of grain and earth . this beer is a good example of the style , bitter-sweet , smooth and malt heavy .  appearance wis is is a fairly typical black brew with a very nice brown head leaving a good lace . the high gravity of the stout adds to the aroma with a whiff of alcohol .  not exactly a esb by definition but a good beer by my standards . a dark beer in color , with a fruity hint on the nose , of apple and a strawberry sort of smell . the taste is smooth fruity and a bit hoppy all at once . my only complaint was a bit of a bitter after taste , but hey it is a esb

a truly unique aroma . t : the fruit ( grape , sour apple , banana ) and bread-like malt are present up front , a decidedly sage-ey wave hits in the middle , and the finish is clove , spice , and a bitter herbal finish .  the color and appearance of this ale is perfect ! it 's a deep dark chocolate brown w/ a thick dark tan head .  i must have a bad batch of this fine ale . the last time i drank it the hops were far more bitter and noticable . in fact , it tastes a bit watered down .

very good , very drinkable o-fest . malty with a clean finish .  poured into a snifter with laser etched bottom appearance - the classic obsidian shade of a imperial stout . topped with a creamy , mocha shaded , full finger , head of foam : this is the beer 's lingerie , working some awesome visuals and coaxing me to proceed .  it has a light body and goes down fairly easy which i guess is average for the style . overall it 's just a cheap beer meant for mass consumption by others , not me .

not overwhelming aroma . familiar malty sweetness of a typical belgian dubbel . not the best of the style , but still very good .  color is a deep reddish amber and a thick tan head leaves exceptional thick rings of lace .  elements of pine , citrus , resinous elements too -- slightly oily but in a very pleasant manner . the biggest flaw i can find with this beer is that it wastes too much of the carbonation in the beginning when it is first poured . it is slightly flat in the mouthfeel although i have tasted some other ipas recently that were far worse in this department .

appearance : pitch black with low head retention smell : hughmugus creamy caramel aroma . amazing ... roasted malt , subtle coffee/chocolate , taste : tastes liek it smells and reaslly does capture creme brulee .  pours a deep brown with two fingers of bubbly mocha head and spider web lacing .  the carbonation is very low . almost negligible . and that 's an understatement .

smell average and looked real thin . if you told me this was a bad version of a belgian dark ale i would n't be surprised and would have rated better to its style .  the cask-conditioned punjabi poured a cloudy , copper-orange with a thick , creamy , white head that had excellent retention ( lasted the whole way ) and some lacing .  m- good carbonation . a little watery for an imperial stout .

the aroma is decent . it boasts primarily of pale malts and lager yeast with a mild hop scent .  pours a gorgeous pitch black in my duvel tulip , with a thick creamy two plus fingers of espresso colored foam . truly a beautiful looking forward .  kombucha is usually very vinegary , but this was more in line with a reserved lambic . carbonated to the tongue , but low head retention . m+d- it is a touch watery .

nothing much in the aroma , somewhat earthy i guess .  bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass like the other beers in the latitude 48 deconstructed ipa series , this one poured a glowing , orangey-amber color with a near three-finger tall head of khaki colored froth . outstanding retention .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4

smell : slight citrus notes with some earthy smells mixed in .  pours a hazy pale golden yellow with sky-high , frothy white head with great retention and generous lacing . beautiful beer !  m : medium , but thicker than expected , this is one of my first lambics , but it really steps up to the plate and is a home run .

smell : the wheat creates a pleasant aroma that combines fruit characters with a slight spicy note from the light amount of hops . a lot of complete fruit smells are noticeable .  appearance : spitfire has it all - a gorgeous red-amber colour and a huge whipped creamy head , over an inch upon pour and lasting throughout the session .  if there 's a downside , it 's the watery mouthfeel .

2010 vintage aroma : a big toffee-like maltiness , some chocolate cake batter , a bit of vanilla , and some floral hops . definitely a brew that kept me smelling for a while before tasting ! very strong , well-carmelized brown sugar supported by an extremely hoppy foundation . i also noted a bit of bubble gum-like phenol , more smokiness , and some alcohol toward the finish . overall : definitely worthy of its reputation . i think i learned with this one , though , that i definitely prefer the fruitiness and complexity of a british barleywine more that the american style .  this brew has an impressive apearance , bright orange with a lot of enourmous carbonation bubbles ( unibroue beers always have the most amazing carbonation ) . once the sediment is added it becomes mysteriously opaque but still very orange . the head was 2 inches and fluffy , leaving copious amounts of lacing down the glass to look at .  crystal-clear , pale golden body with a few lonely bubbles of carbonation wandering around ( needs a bit more carbonation - mouthfeel was rather 'watery ' ) . mild malty flavor , with enough hops for balance . great thirst quencher , and overall a pretty damn good summertime brew .

smell is pretty mild , orange & hops but not the monster head i 'd half expected .  pours foaming from the nitro can medium amber with a huge boiling white creamy head that settles to about one finger of white creamy head . plenty of lacings .  carbonation seems a bit low ; it may be the swing-top cap , as i 've had bad luck with them lately . in any case , it gives a bit too watery a mouthfeel to my taste .

looks great from the get-go : an inky black with a small amount of foam so you can dive right in . not much for aroma , but has a nice promise of chocolate with a heavy malt smell . taste is fantastic , everything you 'd want from a chocolate stout .  appearance : pours a very nice hazy rust color . it looks like rising bread dough .  ( m ) medium bodied and a medium mouthfeel .

the smell though has always bugged me a little , the sour yeastiness makes me think of the old half-full cream container you end up finding in the back of your fridge . all in all , the more stouts i try the farther this creeps down my list of favorites , but still good stuff , and a great `` old standby '' in nyc where it 's always on tap , even if you 're stuck in a sh*thole .  bottle it has reddish brown color with a khaki colored head . this beer has some of the best lacing i 've seen . fifteen minutes after the beer is gone , lacing still lines the glass .  the carbonation is moderate high .

this beer brings me to the rare occasion where it smells better than it tastes . the smell had me anxious to take the first sip , but i was slightly disappointed by the taste .  pours opaque black with a 1 inch creamy tan head that lasts for a lifetime after the cascading brown bubbles stop and settle ; great looking stout that sets the standard for stout looks with great lacing that leaves thick rings . guinness is always impressive to look at when it poured properly from a tap .  smooth and not too powerful , ripened bananas and muffiny taste was not as dark as it looked , tastes of ripened fruit , sweet malts and hops would seem nearly obsolete if not for a brief tish of citrus fair amount of carbonation , bit of dryness , the finish was short and forgetful one of the easier brown ales to put back , not too sweet ( as many are ) the over 6 % abv is n't apparent so be careful , however i drank this before dinner so it went down exceptionally quickly .

sweet , but not too sweet honey aroma . taste , goes downhill quick , funny aftertaste from whatever honey they are using , does n't do well with the high carbonation , just a fizzy honey aftertaste and corn left over . a neat beer to smell , but not much else going on here noteworthy .  perfect clarity . everything i look for in a marzen smell : sweet caramel malt dominates .  original rating date : september 4 , 2008 smells great , lots of light fruity , flowery aroma . pours a copper/amber with a bubbly head . taste reminds me a lot of sierra nevada 's brew . lots of light fruit , citrus , apricot , some peach . lots of malt , only a bit of hops . very good stuff here .

unstoppable hop aroma . grapefruit and citric character invades my nostrils and inflicts a pleasant sting . good double ipa .  poured into a pint glass a : gentle pour ( in case there was sediment - there was n't ) yields 2/3 finger creamy cream colored head with great retention .  this one strikes me as kind of flat . needs a tad more carbonation and i think it would be leaps better than it is . nice creamy smooth mouthfeel though .
