s - raisins , apples , carmel , complex malts , nutmeg and cloves . t - taste goes bland very fast , sweetness right at the beggining resembling dark cherries which gives way to a blandness very quick .  darker than i 'm used to with a iipa but this looks nice . brilliantly clear .  the taste was even worse , vinegar , old cardboard , just really gross . i do n't know if the keg was abused or really old but this was one sorry-ass beer . this was truly bad and i only finished it because i wanted to catch a buzz before my flight . i should have asked for a replacement .
smell is pretty much average with hints of sugary lemon and citrus fruits .  great looking beer , with chocolate mouse colored head .  of course . a little high in the effervescence .

being fairly new to the style , i expected much more fruitiness up front , but got the earthy , roasty bitterness of the darker malts at first , and not until later , when the beer warmed , did the flavors begin to blend and the sweetness begin to come out . the nose was muted . the thing that stood out most was an aroma like grain that had started to turn into a bit of wet fungus .  ..on the open , thick cream like tan foam started oozing out of the bottle . the head is quite good , but the lacing is exceptional ! .  mouthfeel is slick , but a little too thin .

aroma was pretty wimpy too , just some subtle notes of chocolate malt and coffee .  poured from bottle into tulip a- beautuful thick off white head . stout like . head lasts and leaves perfect rings of lace . body is pretty dark .  mouthfeel : light to medium body , creamy with just a little astringency .

nose is very mild , but what there is present is light breadiness with a touch of grass . 3.9 look : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | feel : 4 | drink : 4 1246  dense opague black with a lovely one inch creamy mocha head . easily rivals any rogue stout in appearance .  lighter in body than i anticipated .

on tap @ the blind tiger 10-29-08 a : deep dark ruby color , small head that fades quickly , and leaves behind scattered lacing s : the aroma is floral some caramel , not real strong t : begins with burnt caramel malty flavor , sweet in the middle and finishes with a citrus hop that lingers long after m : pretty good hop flavor for a pale ale and a little on the sweet side d : fairly easy drinking pale ale , may be a little to heavy for some people used to lighter pale ales , really enjoyed this one .  a terrific looking beer .  this beer really needs to sit a while before the mouthfeel is anywhere near decent . when its freshly poured and a bit too cool , it 's thin and prickly , but just letting it sit a while and come closer to room temp. , it becomes a bit fuller and mellows out a bit . really drinkable ris that has tons of flavor and a decent mouthfeel , once it warms up .

s- light toasted grain and malt sweetness , some floral/sweet fruity hops . really fruity stuff here , though . m- lacking hops , malt is very nice though and makes this an enjoyable beer nonetheless .  poured into a new belgium snifter a - transparent blood red , half finger head , off white almost tan/brown and some serious lacing s - sweet .  m : very carbonated .

smells of light sweet malt , floral hops , caramel , corn , and grains ; a very , very weak nose that has some basic sweetness but that 's about it .  taken into my notebook large brown bomber style bottle with nice looking label . like their northern hemisphere ipa , the head and lace are unbelievable . very luscious in appearance .  the hop character , however , does n't overpower the malt and barely-there vanilla . m : not that noticeable to me , but certainly not offensive . the malty taste with a little bit of hops really helps the beer .

maybe the best beer smell ever to wander up my nostrils . this stout sit below a thick vapor that is sweet and boozy with anise , chocolate and coconut . smells a little grapey , like a heavy red wine . goodbye , beer , down the drain .  white thick foam across the top of the beer with lots of lacing ( strands and walls of it ) all over the place . truly a nice beer to look at .  this is an above-average premium bitter that , with a little more body and a less watery mouth feel , might have been a masterpiece .

lovely , just lovely . the aroma is overall fresh . it 's slightly floral on a base of chalky , round belgian yeast . the flavors pickup up from a pleasant but not exceptional nose . i wish for more hopping and perhaps a stronger nose , but very well done .  uncaged and uncorked , this poured with a nice sexy yellow-orange and a poofy , survivable foamy head .  a little grittiness in the texture . m - a little weird and overcarbonated for a porter . it would be better off less carbonated and as creamy as it appears .

a very nice mixture of the woody hop aroma with a sweet malty background .  appearance - pours a very dark , rich brown , almost black , with a finger of dense , khaki-colored head .  mouthfeel medium -light mouthfeel with prickly carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my taste in a mild , but not too far off .

330ml bottle served in a pint glass.enjoyed on mar11 orangish light amber.yellow froth , dense & lasting.small bubbles.chill haze.high & intense perfume profile.on palate lemon zest & resins.very smooth bitterness at first sip but increasing in the middle.medium carbonation.abv is not felt.good & refreshing drinkability .  with a vigorous pour you get a beautiful effect . almost two fingers of rich foamy milk chocolate colored head , that lasts long and leaves lace as it fades .  kinda liked this one , the guy at the beer store said the bottle was sitting there for awhile but it held up great.real hazy-orange color with a good head , smelled fresh and citriusy , body was a little thin to me for the style.refreshing taste with some citrius-yeast note very easy to drink.i also think this would be a good warm weather ale .

although i picked up a sweet caramel odor , i am disappointed that prelude does not have the richer smell that i would expect from a winter warmer .  very dark . pitch black ; even when illuminated . the head is thick , tan and creamy . this is what you want a stout to look like . you can watch the head grow as the bubbles make their way both up and down the glass .  mouthfeel was decent but a bit thinner/watery than i would have liked .

some sweet , woody malt but thats about it .  this is just about perfect appearance . the deep dark red , 3 finger off white cream head , lacing , lots of bubbles , just well done .  unfortunately , the flavor and mouthfeel do n't fully deliver on what the aroma suggested . this is still a tasty beer but it 's a bit thinner than i hoped for and has a much stronger roast presence than i prefer .

seems like a lot of the winter warmers i have been drinking lately have been a little heavy on the hops . this one has a large malt body with just enough hops to keep rom becoming sweet .  a - pours dark brown/black , but with medium body that is n't so thick that it appears syrupy . 1-finger creamy beige head with medium to large bubbles , good retention and good lace .  s. rich brown sugar , molasses and smoke t. quite complex with molasses , roasted malt , smoke , brown sugar , cinnamon and clove in the front with a touch of hops in the back m. surprisingly clean , with lingering malt behind medium carbonation d. very drinkable for anyone who likes malt i first tried this beer at a local liquor store 's beer tasting . this is a great example of a fall seasonal for the relaxed craft drinker .

but i was at grapevine and the olde ale had just arrived that day . but the aroma is , surprisingly , not bad .  jet black coloring and pours with a think caramel-colored head . kept a solid layer of foam on top as i drank the entire glass .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the finish is a little odd tasting .

smell : slight scent of caramel and hops . taste : hop presence , malty and some caramel .  i 'm very impressed by the white billowy head . now 5 minutes after the pour , there is still a half finger of head lingering with streaky lacing .  feels a bit thin , where creamier and chewier would 've done the trick .

the thing i love about tripels is they always have interesting and unique scents . the taste is a bit more subtle , but it is fantastic .  bottle courtesy of jjpm74 : poured a clear dark black color ale with a big foamy head with perfect retention and perfect lacing .  an astoundingly good dark beer for the price : 10 bucks for a 12-pack at wegmans in state college , pa . it brings some of the unique flavors found in yuengling porter to a slightly lighter beer , but make no mistake ; the stuff is not weak . it might not be the most delicious beer on the planet , but the combination of good flavor and low price are unbeatable for me as a beer-enthusiast college student ( not a drunkard ! ) everyone else has described the taste well enough . my review is mainly economic .

smell is almost non-existant . if not for a light corn odor this beer would n't have an aroma .  a : this brew presents a perfect appearance , with a massive , rocky head , great retention , crystal clarity , and a light copper tint .  m- not a bad mouthfeel i just felt it to be average . light on the tongue , a little too dry and yet somewhat of a lingering aftertaste .

fairly good on the nose with roasted dark malts , faint touches of hopps .  poured from an 11.2 oz bottle into a stemless wine glass . a ) pours brown , and resembles apple cider in color/consistency .  the mouthfeel is average , medium-bodied , watery ( even slightly oily ) in texture , with soft carbonation .

lagers get a bad reputation thanks to the macros , so i fear that this little beauty has n't gotten the attention it deserves . floral hops throuhgout , but none of that comes out on the nose . strong barley malt presence goign down , finishing up clean . damn refreshing , like any good lager .  the appearance is just stunning . it pours like silk , just this great smooth 'motor oil ' type liquid pours so so smooth . both brews came to a two finger head that was the color of light chocolate . it left a really weird lacing that is sticky and spread all over the sides of the glass .  fairly light bodied and easy drinking .

s : a little lacking . t : the fruit hits you first . very nice . very nice .  this brew pours with a beautiful deep amber body topped by a thick off-white head with a good amount of lacing .  m : carbonation comes on unexpectedly crisp , but it drinks smoothly .

smell - sweet , almost candy-like malt with a touch of corn in the smell .  very classic appearance on this oatmeal stout , with a jet black body and a good inch of tan head that laced well .  m : medium body with hardly any carbonation d : drinks good all the way thru that makes it seem like winter in the summer .

the aroma is difficult to pick everything out ... mainly chocolate notes . i 'm not original here and have a difficulty getting anything else than chocolate .  this elegant saison poured a rich , cloudy orange color . thick , pillowy head ... like cloud tops .  split with the wife at the eccentric cafe in kalamazoo , michigan . looks like a wheat beer with absolutely no odor coming off the brew . very , very wheaty , to the point of being a bit of a turn off . more cherry & less wheat would have been a better combo , methinks . this got actively unpleasant as it warmed - the aftertaste was a killer .

smell is a bit sub-par , not too strong , pilsner malt comes through , but it a bit unpleasant . i 'm sorry for the blasphemy , but i was reminded of pliny the elder when drinking this one -- hoppy with little malt backbone . maybe not worth the $ 3.49 , but definitely worth a try if you can get it cheap .  served in a pint glass this beer pours a motor oil black . it may be categorized here as a smoked beer , but this has the rich sexy dark brown foam and black body of an amazing stout .  aroma of allspice , nutmeg , figs , apples , leathery yeast , and pepper . flavor of dark fruits including plums and cassis . slightly sour . palate lacks expected richness . good but not great like the previews ( appearance and aroma ) lead you to believe .

aroma is very mild with slight grainy notes and a hint of hops .  beautiful clear mahogany . fine tight beige head settles to a thin complete cap . just a beautiful beer .  ( m ) - a very high carbonation level .

s : a little skunky , as is expected from this style . actually smells a bit gross compared to other pale ales .  poured into a tall tulip glass a dark brown/black color with a dark reddish tinged mahagony brown head that left thick sticky lace all over the glass .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel on this beer is kind of harsh , due to the huge amount of hops and alcohol .

the only thing that i really got out of the smell was some of the barnyard funkiness and maybe some yeast . overall i thought that the aroma of this beer was muted , which was disappointing until i tasted it . overall , this gypsy ale is mother fuckin cash money ! i would have liked to have had a stronger aroma but the taste and mouthfeel more than made up for it .  750ml bottle poured into a cervoise , inferno ale is a murky gold with lots streamers forming a large , very rocky white head that leaves lots of spidery lace . wow , very nice .  mouthfeel is a little thin with very little carbonation .

s - subtle bread , slightly sweet with caramel richness . t - malty and rich with caramel and a hint of brown sugar .  pretty awesome looking beer , you can definitely tell they took full advantage of the blood oranges .  m - medium body , could use more carbonation given that they went for more of a standard strong ale vs a true winter brew d - very drinkable .

very little aroma - bit of bread , a smidgen of vanilla . little but nice , but i 'm going to take in foam if i sniff any harder .  i love mcewan 's scotch ale , i love its dark hue , its smooth , carmelly rich goodness , and although i never do , i could easily have more than one .  medium body , but maybe a bit thin , moderate carbonation .

the taste and aroma are not disappointing but not exceptional . we can expect more from such a beautiful beer . it 's very drinkable , although .  the look is just outstanding . full orange unfiltered goodness with a clingy head . beautiful beer .  the mouthfeel is low carbonated almost syrupy , not what i expected .

s : not a lot jumping out at me on the smell . maybe a little banana and wheat . i definitely could taste the banana though .  poured a massive deep mocha colored all-head which took a long-long time to recede and which refilled the glass with every subsequent refill , a rarity for such a dar beer . body is dark as coffee .  the mouthfeel is light bodied , but a little thicker than i would expect from a beer with such little taste and aroma .

if you know you ca n't get past this , pint 's pub 's own scottish style ale , the gael force ale , has a very similar rich malty taste to the dark star , but it is served chilled and carbonated . not too much hits the nose , but upon tasting , a rich deep malty flavor ensues . enjoyable mouth feel , not heavy and creamy like a stout , more like a medium porter , but flat of course . quite a unique brew , not like a typical brown ale especially since it is cask conditioned and has stronger yeast and malt flavors . certainly something to be tried at least once- and again , if you like a good rich malty brew , but you happen to like it served up cold and a bit fizzy , then you 're in luck , get the gael force ale .  utterly gorgeous appearance , from the deep clear bronze hue to the big , thick , contoured tan head that stuck around for a long time and left magnificent lace .  the aroma is hoppy and earthy with some fruity notes , reminds me a bit of orval in this sense . the flavor has a nice character of fruity hopes and a mild malt sweetness , but the beer is dominantly dry . there is a very mild tartness here but generally the beer is dominated by a blend between some spicy yeast notes and pleasant hop bitterness .

what makes this beer stand out , both positively and negatively , is the chocolate taste . the highly malty taste complements the very potent chocolate taste . in brief , this tastes like a milkshake . if you want a light cocoa taste in your beer , this is not for you .  pours a deep cola brown , almost black . tan head that sticks around for a very long time with great lacing .  m - medium bodied with higher than average carbonation . it looks and feels a little chalky .

s : kind of weak with faint coffee grounds odor with sweet raisins and vanilla . t : pleasant and grabbing coffee presence immediate with a ton of chocolaty sweetness to boot .  this is one of the darkest beers i have ever seen . it pours with a big head that is a medium brown , quite dark for foam .  fairly dry with ample carbonation and a lighter body . a bit coarse in texture .

the aroma is more malty with some pine notes .  pours pitch black with not even a hint of light coming through . has a large billowing dark cocoa colored head that takes forever to go down - nice lacing on the glass .  m - medium body with a pretty smooth texture , but mouthfeel is a little thin for a porter . body is a little thin , but the aromas and flavors are quite pleasant .

smell- faint roasted coffee , chocolate , and hazelnut .  after a sip of beer , the sun came out from behind some clouds and a ray of light from a high , transom window knifed down and lit up my beer with an angelic glow . it was the best looking beer i 'd ever seen .  the body is light and the carbonation is very high .

smell in the glass does n't amount to much when chilled , only a faint roasty malt . when swirling the dregs in the bottle , there was a plummy smell , like a baltic porter . this is a perfect session stout if you are so inclined .  thanks to throwitallaway for this masterpiece ... poured a deep , deep brown with a huge brown head . lots of lacing and great carbonation .  a good pale and pretty cheap . $ 4.99 a six and 5 buck pitcher specials are easily had . full flavored and nicely hopped w/goldings .

s- lime , some sort of ... hmm , it smells like ginger ale a bit .  kona pipeline porter is an opaque beer that 's the darkest brown . it has a big , fluffy , light brown head that shows outstanding retention .  very easy to drink ! it has the feel of any other wheat beer , but the watermelon taste is so unique that it simply floored me . initially , i thought the color seemed very artificial which made me expect an artificial flavor . there is little up front beyond a generic wheat beer , but in the aftertaste lies a brilliant watermelon flavor ! it is easy to drink and not very filling . it is slightly more alcoholic than your run of the mill macrobrews making it possible to drink a great many of these at any given time . it 's a good beer to give to new beer drinkers . it 's an excellent example of how diverse craft beers can be !

smell : very nice complexity in the nose . spicy , fruity , yeasty , and sweet all at once . more rustic in character than la fin du monde , which is not necessarily a bad thing .  a - a deep golden ale with good clarity and a thick creamy head . loads of lacing .  thin in the mouth , which leads to great drinkability . would make a good session beer .

pale malt and light floral aromas . crisp pale malt with light caramel and floral hops all in subtle balance with a light grassy bittersweet finish . at first i was not entirely impressed as it seemed to be just another amber style beer . however , the subtle qualities of this beer are so nicely in balance it creates one heckuva drinkable beer .  the head was high and mighty , a nice contrasting eggshell color .  taste malty upfront a touch hop metal finish . not very heavy rather light on the carbs . this beer really scratched my spring beer itch .

a very interesting beer that sat really warm in my stomach -- the `` winter warmer '' is definitely the best way to describe it . appearance : dark coppery red ; a nice 2 finger head that was thick and pillowy -- the carbonation was clearly visible and looked like it was going to last throughout the drink . smell : could n't get much out of it at all -- there was a very slight hoppiness to it as it warmed , but nothing overly discernable . taste : bitter , cinammon is very pronounced and that added to the slight sting on the tongue from the bitter . the spiciness was very interesting and the physical effect of it on the stomach makes it more worthwhile -- definitely a seasonal drink though .  extremely hoppy , and a beautiful colour .  one slight criticism is a somewhat lighter mouthfeel - thinner than i would expect .

it left no laing as it dropped , but lacing was later seen on the sidewall as i tipped it for a swill . s- this fizz in this beer penetrates your nose leaving me with reminders of new years ... champagne and sparkling cider . faintly smells like beer . t- very unique with only hints of what i expected from a triple ( i had to double check the bottle , and yup , its a triple ) . i has flavors very reminiscent of a wit beer . no spice , no banana .  looks like big red in a glass .  a smoked lager from fort collins brewery . 1.0 liter bottle for $ 8.29 . i was somewhat skeptical about this beer especially because i thought there two other beers edgar and doktor were an abomination , but i opted for it and was it ever worth it ! a slight smokinness stimulates the nose as well as some alcohol , caramel and citrus hops . the palate was dominated with notes of butterschotch , smoked malts , cedar , citrus notes , light fruits and the flavor was very lingering on the palate . i did polish off a 1.0 so obviously this brew was pretty damn drinkable !

s : the first think i can think of when i smell this beer is chocolate covered coffee beans . it is one of the best smelling beers to me .  a : the beer pours a dark brown/red hue . a big , pillowy head sits on top and leaves some nice lacing on the glass as it recedes . it is a beautiful beer .  m - i 'm finding myself rather indifferent towards the mouthfeel .

towards the end of the beer , i begin to get a lot more maltiness and some sweetness coming through . t : taste is citrus , malt , some lemon zest maybe ? wish the nose was better but if i had my choice , i 'd just pop the cap , throw it in a cozy and sip away all day mowing the grass or hanging outside sans glass .  pours a hazy copper to orange color . very nice head retention . great patches of lace left coating the glass .  aggressive fizzy carbonation .

the taste is equally as enjoyable as the smell . very fresh taste , crisp taste , great hop to malt balance .  ) my ba 1 year birthday beer a - absolutely jet black used motor oil color , yielding nothing else no matter how close i held it to the light . dark brown head , one of the darkest i 've seen , fades to a patchy eighth inch . lots of little lacing bubbles .  crisp malts , light fruits and near indiscernible hops all float to the nose . a bit dry going down with some malts , a surprising hoppiness , and a good , somewhat delayed fruit hit at the end . light-bodied and highly drinkable , but still tasty , which is what i look for in a good summer sessioner .

s : sourdough bread , yeast , dry alcohol esters akin to a chardonnay , a little bit of nail polish . i was underwhelmed by the nose and the mouthfeel was nothing to write home about .  bright amber body topped with a thick creamy head leaving plenty of lace .  i just think it 's amazing what ab will do to make a quick buck . hopefully this will quickly go into the grave along with new coke and chrystal pepsi .

love it . my type of stout aroma . t : more balanced than the smell .  the head color in particular is incredible with a kind of dark chocolate brown that resembles ice cream . s - i think if there was a weak point on this beer , this is it .  mouthfeel : at first slightly carbonated but then becomes smooth . one thing though , it kind of stays in your mouth for a while .

served from a 12oz bottle a-nice amber red color with great clearity and head/retention s-cereal grains , slight hoppyness , honey and toast . t-yeah buddy . tons of crystal malt ranging from caramel to light raisin , nice deep hop bitterness . m-great full body viscous brew d-not hard to finish one  poured into a snifter , revealing rich brown body and a very thick , very tall tan head .  it was a bit thin on mouthfeel , but the aromas & wheaty , yeasty taste more than made up for this .

s - a very spicy aroma with a little bit of citrus hops coming through .  on-tap at toronado sd a : the pour is almost black in color with a fluffy tan head that leaves sheets of lacing all the way down the glass .  it has a surprisingly thin body for such a bourbon and malty beast . also the carbonation is a bit higher then i would like for the style .

s : a great tart cherry aroma with chocolate malts and some coffee notes . t : i have to say , i 'm very disappointed in this beer 's flavor .  a : looks exactly like the hefeweissbier , dark golden color , hazy , massive 3-finger foamy head that lasts forever and leaves good lacing .  mouthfeel is medium to full-bodied .

the aroma was of faint malts with a hint of fruit notes .  pours a cloudy ruby amber topped by a thick , bubbly head that just wo n't die and sinks its claws in to the sides of my duvel tulip and wo n't let go . gorgeous .  pretty average looking . somewhat listless and a touch thin although i would imagine that it could translate better on cask .

originally i was going to give the smell a 4.0 but after hovering over it , just enveloping the aromas i give it a 5.0 its just amazing , so full and complex it makes my mouth salivate over it .  a lovely brew .  the body is bit off with a moderate to fuller body . good carbonation .

the smell is tangerine overdose ! huge tangerine and fruit juice smell along with a bit of hop presence as well .  wow there is more to this version of the yeti than i thought , cayenne ... hmmm.poured a jet black with a fluffy mocha colored head that left a creamy mass after leaving multiple sheets of lace as it settled very slowly.aromas of vaniila/oak and bitter chocolate and some roastiness.flavors start out with hefty roast and bitter chocolate with cayenne hitting in the finish wich is very noticeable by me , not sure how others have felt about the cayenne presence.not sure if that cayenne presence is welcomed by me , its a bit annoying.i like the complexity and the uniquness but not my thing so much , although its not bad just for the record .  nose ... oh , that great `` red '' smell ... hops and spice with some sweentess thrown in for good measure , west coast floral represented well , just a great pleasant hop aroma caresed by cinnamon.. delish.. mouth etc ... carbonation then the real bite of spice and hops , a little watery at times but the flavor is fantastic , refreshing and crisp as it gets toward the end of the glass.. very enjoyable verdict ?

s - bananas and bubblegum jump out . i 'm missing the hops for lagunitas ( haha ) , but this smells on point for the style . decent overall , but nothing overly impressive . m - body and carbonation are both on the higher end .  pours a cloudy golden color with a massive head that nearly spills over the top of my giant snifter . foam recedes ridiculously slow leaving nice lacing and creating big rocky tops .  m - carbonated ... a little too much actually .

kind of malty , a real beer smell to it that i 'm not very fond of .  this poured the most amazing red with un-ending pinkish head .  m - very thick and full . very prickly and effervescent in the mouth - too thick to be a soda , but the carbonation is quite reminiscent . high carbonation is the only detractor to drinkability .

in retrospect , i would have aged it , but i was way too eager to try this one . regardless , it tasted magnificent with the roasty malt flavor making itself very evident . a bit on the high priced side , but i 'd give it a try if you have about 13 bucks you 're willing to drop on a spectacular beer .  it poured a cloudy burnt orange color that was beautiful to look at . it was like looking through a stained glass window . there was also a nice light tan head but i was too busy looking at the brew .  m- thin to medium body- highly attenuated- with a coarse carbonation which delivers a slightly bloating feeling . could stand to have some softer carbonation .

s - slight whiff of coffee , roasted malts , and a touch of chocolate t - surprised at how tasty this is given the fact the smell was ok , it has great sweetness mixed with roasted malts , great hoppiness in the middle , very well balanced .  from a 650 ml brown bottle , black wax over the cap and neck . massive pillar of tight spongy tan head upon initial pour . settles to a loose sticky cap with swathes of sticky lacing .  mf : there could be a bit more of a body to back up the full flavor of this beer .

smells ... well , like malt liquor . strong grassy aroma that i generally associate with pilseners and euro pale lagers , but without the clean undertones . no hops present at all , and no subtlety to aroma . overall , this is fairly drinkable , more so than many macro lagers , but obviously not something i 'd seek out .  pours a nice hazy dark copper with a three finger white head that subsides to one finger .  mouthfeel : i 've never been a big fan of the body of almost all american porters as they just seem thin , a tad watery , and big on carbonation , and this one does n't break that trend .

the aroma is sweet and inviting , very nice aroma . the sweetmalt is there in the front but a bold/robust roasty flavor powers through to the front of this brew .  a slow pour reveals deep shades of copper , mahogany and gold capped by a thick , billowy head of white foam that just wo n't quit .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4

the aromatic flavor in the nose is quite intriguing -- some kind of english hard candy with menthol and fermented prunes ( footnote : `` gravity 's rainbow '' ) .  super dark in color , allowing no light to pass through .  on-tap at surfrider caf in santa cruz , ca . on to the beer : there 's is n't much life to the look of this beer . the hops have a dull bitterness and a green veggie flavor . lemongrass notes all around , but especially in the aftertaste . pale malt sweetness is not found easily . very `` raw '' , but in a bad way . even compared to the regular bmc 's , american standard fails to even meet that . i struggled to finish my pint , but at least it only cost me $ 2 .

i drank this out of a 12oz stein glass ... pour is a darker than amber/lighter than copper hue with an off cream colored head that settles ... .nose is unremarkable ... slightly perfumed with a touch of floral hop aroma but nothing of particular note .  dark black in color with garnet highlights . huge , cascading head of super-thick foam that does n't back down for several long minutes .  this is a good straightforward ale . light golden yellow color , a little fizzy but nothing a little harder pour into the glass did n't take care of . lighter flavor but has a nice balance for whats there . nice little hop background that comes through the nose.it 's drinkable also .

smells buttery , biscuity , and toast . flavor has much more to offer than the aroma .  a : 1/2 '' cream coloured head that left a nice lacing over amber liquid with excellent clarity .  this porter is a little watery .

looks a bit intimdating , or maybe i just read into the marketing to much ... s : hop smell is dominant , with stong caramel notes . not as intimidating on the nose . t : this is where its at .  the apperance is exceptional , gold honey in color , the usual amber color . the head was a gorgeous cream color that lasted the whole way through .  the mouthfeel on a doppelbock is a tricky thing -- too thick and you wo n't be able to drink your half-liter bottle , let alone your full liter mass .

essentially it comes off as a baby mcewans scotch ale , but it has its own personality . midway is the classic hard and cruchy ale water . it finishes ( waaay back in the throat ) with a hop-like pop , but i think it is the roasted malt doing the dirty work on this one .  when this porter was poured into my glass , it poured with a dark brown head that unfortunately did not last very long .  tastes great , but the mouthfeel is a lot thinner than i 'd like for the style .

some carbonation present , as well as a good deal of yeasty goodies at the bottom of the glass . smell : the aroma is incredibly complex and refreshing . up front you get that belgian spicy yeast character , but i 'm also detecting some tart fruits like apricot , orange , and maybe some grape in there as well . there is some alcohol detectable and some underlying dark fruit presence that gives the smell some serious depth .  a great looking brew .  the mouthfeel was thin-to medium with a lightly smoky taste on the palate .

smell was faintly fruity , but not particularly strong . taste is extremely hop laden with a significantly dry finish . this beer is robust enough to border on a porter or stout , but exceptionally hoppy and dry to be true to the ipa style .  12oz bottle poured into a tulip . appearance - black body and thick medium brown head with good retention .  mouthfeel : on the lighter side , lots of carbonation .

smell : the nose appeal is a bit mild but has a great pine scent with some orange lemon-like citrus . i was expecting something intense , given the name torpedo , but it 's incredibly balanced but flavorful . the dryness is n't overbearing and makes the mouth feel a bit relaxed but not shy to receive more .  very nice retention and great thick sticky lacing . excellent appearance .  overall mouthfeel is okay , but not great . it numbs my tongue a bit ( and not because i 've overchilled it ; i have n't ) .

smell : typical porter . a little chocolate , a little coffee . a good porter with typical notes of most porters with nothing special that leaps out .  the toffee head is absolutely massive and rocky . retention and lacing are both out of this world , probably the best looking brown ale i 've ever seen .  it finishes very clean with a hint of carbonation lingering on the palate .

faint hop smell and malt . a lot of the aromas do n't show . what i do get is a little bit of bread and a floral smell . sweet and bitter right away . this is probably the smoothest lager around ; incredibly easy going down . the taste is unlike any of your macro beers and blows a lot of craft lagers away .  smuttynose- s'muttonator a- deep ruddy brown with the thickest foamiest head . heavy lacing down the glass .  only bummer part , was a bit too thin and carbonated .

s : subdued yeasty aromas with a bit of spice and citrus . not very strong on the nose . t/m : the taste is spicy , yeasty , hints of spice that liven up the front end .  bottled on : 2011/09/09 pours a nice clear medium-light bronze hue , tons of white foamy head - lasts forever .  mouthfeel is tough .

s. i get some citrus and floral hops and rye t. first thing i taste is floral hops followed by some sweet malts and finishing off with some citrus , primarily orange and grapefruit .  jet black with a livid light brown head that remains for at least five minutes .  m- a thin body- highly attenuated with a nice spritzy non-bloating carbonation .

s : pretty subtle . dark fruits and juicy grapes and plums . mouthfeel and smell are a bit weak , too .  this beer is very nice looking . poured into a lindemans glass , this beer is very red and is topped with a short pink head that leaves sheets of lacing on the glass .  m : the body was actually not terrible , medium , we 'll say . and the carbonation was moderate as well .

s : rather muted scent of grains and light grassy hops . t : wow .  bottle poured into a straight sided pint glass a- dark , dark brown . big , fluffy tan head , and very sticky lacing down the glass . i do n't see how a porter could look better .  appearance : high carbonation , 1/4 inch head , cloudy , yellowish-green smell : wheat , and melon taste : very watermelon -- almost like a watermelon jolly rancher , bready wheat , with some small hops near the end mouthfeel : sweet , light/smooth body , high carbonation , slight bitter taste in the end .

colour is dark red with a not so big head and do not smell that much . ok. i got a flu not so long ago .  looks really nice .  mouthfeel great carbonation . perhaps a little thin , but not a detraction . a bit sticky on the aftertaste .

whiffs of cotton candy and sweet cinamon bread come to mind . sweet cookie dough and biscuity malts . great aroma . the mouthfeel seems a little empty . the taste does not follow through to the extent that i 'd like with the aroma , but some nice qualities to exist . sweet candied tones and the `` menage a trois '' of figs , raisins and dates .  a- nice head , great retention , unbelievable lacing , beautiful caramel color .  a nice well put together beer that is easy drinking with medium carbonation and a light body .

for a euro pale lager , this example holds up quite well . nose is on the light side with a suggestion of skunk , hops , and cereal grains .  this beer pours a true opaque black with a nice amount of creamy tan head that leaves tons of lacing on the glass .  not your typical ipa , but you could call it a great hoppy amber with a very fruity , floral melon ball hop character . maybe it 's bitter like an east coast ipa , but the moutfeel does n't stand up to most california ipas . still , there was a bit of balance with bready , toasted

the smell has always been interesting and intricate , but unable to carry over to the taste , which i find is a rare , and unwelcome , achievement .  poured with a huge e finger head that settled down with an excellent pillowy top and a tan color , body was a dark dark brown but not quite black .  medium-high carbonation prickles the tongue , feels heavier than it looks .

after a trip to the pacific northwest and imbibing a great swath of cascade laced ipas , the sprecher variant on this style is a shock ... .but a very pleasant one . a beautiful redish amber with a creamy white head that leaves sheets of lacing in the glass ... gorgeous . the aroma is very subdued , particularly since it is dry-hopped twice according to the sprecher website . none of the grapefruit blast i have grown accustomed to from pacific northwest beer , but a hop spice is evident , lingering over a deep biscuity base . the more i think of it , i would put this beer in the category of a strong ale , along the lines of stone 's arrogant bastard , but not as citrusy . this is a potent beer , but a very good one .  was jet black with a bit of ruby shinning through on the edges . had a creamy tan 2 '' cap that stuck to the glass the entire ride down .  taste and mouthfeel : medium bodied , mid level carbonation .

s : wheat and faint peach smell .  it pours to a dark golden amber color with a few continuous jetstreams of bubbles rising to the top to support the delicate off-white head .  and a bit thin d-easy and enjoyable , drinks almost like a session ale .

rich bacon fat . rich and lively . more like eating a brisket than drinking a beer . very smooth . a bit of alcohol warmth at the tail end .  pours dark with a large tane head .  m : it doesnt give the mouth a longlasting tingle that some ipa 's give but gives a tasty coat on your mouth that lasts and gives the chocolate taste as well .
smell is dusty coco and irish cream , lactose ?  outstanding lacing , even if it is pink foam .  mouthfeel : extremely light feel considering the alcohol and massive aroma .

the smell was thin and hard to pick up , what i could pick up was very fruity with an even thinner malt aspect hidden in the rear of the nose . it should be noted that as the beer warmed the smell got stronger and easier to pick up on .  dark orange . lofty , creamy bubbles clung together above the liquid , showing very good density .  smooth light finish . good flavor and average abv .

wonderful buckwheat bready smell . sweet faint black strap molasses notes in there , too . very rich and deep . the taste does n't quite match the look and nose of this , but it 's still quite good , bready-malty , some nice slight sourdough sourness .  a= jet black color with a huge head leaving not lacing but actual sheets of bubbles on my glass .  mouthfeel has definitely lost some over the years unfortunately , its almost still and lacks life .

smell was slightly resinous and a bit bready , okay i guess , but very mild .  nose : deep fruit , clove like spice , dark malts especially some coffee/chocolate notes , and maybe a slight hint of oxidation appearance : black , viscous , with a lasting brown head flavor : chocolate/coffee from dark malts , a bit of candied cherries , some slight oxidation , but not much in the way of typical bourbon barrel flavor .  mouthfeel : a little high on the carbonation and not as thick as i 'd prefer with a stout .

smell : heavy on the blackberries . just one notch lower is a beautiful lemon-infused sweet-bread tone . very good mix here . a deceiving nose , as the taste is mostly grass and stale bread .  black in color with a head that looks like meringue .  body was a smidgen thin , but it held the 8 % back quite well , i knew it was more that 5 % , but thats what i perceived from this great brew .

not too much in the way of aroma . i noticed a tiny amount of rich malts but not much else . beautiful taste . extremely rich malts , extremely sweet but not at all cloying .  served in an imperial pint glass from a 22 oz bomber bottle a- black as night with an off white head very nice s- roasted hops and coffee t- very nice roasted hop taste with a deep coffee flavor and a clean finish .  on tap the the brewery . all american hops . pungant and resiny . big hop flavor with rye spicyness . caramel , and good bitterness . quite dry and refreshing . my first founders beer every . pretty happy so far .

smell is very feint , sweet malt with hints of chocalate and lactose/milk notes . overall , nicely done presentation of this style .  had this beer at the brewery poured into a 6 oz plastic cup a- i love dark beers ! the head is tan and looked great in my plastic cup .  they float the lemon in the beer , so you do n't have a chance to yank it out before it imparts flavor . great example of the heffeweizen style , with banana and clove aroma and flavors . a light beer that can be quaffed in copious amounts .

the smell malty , and nothing too spectacular . the flavor is amazing .  avery mephistopheles stout bottled on november 2008 without a doubt the darkest beer i have ever seen ! this vivid black beer also has the most appealing head on any beer . it is very frothy and looks like thick chocolate cream .  it feels a bit thin and overly carbonated for a strong english ale .

smell was rather sour , really did n't smell too appetizing at the start , but once i tasted it that all changed , it is bitter , but has a somewhat butterscotchy finish .  a - it does n't get any better looking than this ; a brilliant golden color with nice clarity and a dense three-finger off-white cream head . sheets of lace cling like webby veils on the glass .  m - interesting flavors dance around but actual feel is pretty standard light ale d - fun , interesting , pairs well with peppery steak or cheese , not too strong .

as soon as the bottle was cracked , a huge aroma poured out of it . but it was so repulsive , i did n't want to get close enough to it to describe its character . very disappointing .  from the bottle . poured black with a medium tan head .  smells quite strongly of roasted coffee beans . if you chilled an espresso drink and made it into beer , this is how it would smell . then , this transitions into a bit of a licorice taste ... .finishing with what i would classify as an odd citric acid tangy sourness that 's quite pronounced and just seems out of place . my verdict here is that it has a great aroma and starts decent enough ... but in the end , i 'm turned off by what i 'd consider to be `` off flavors '' for a stout .

aroma : dark fruited malt base and hints of alcohol . mild overall aroma appearance : bruised purple brown color , good clarity when back lit , small but plucky tan cover that fades to a thin ring without lacing . if the aroma is mild , the taste is not .  crystal clear burnt orange with a generous head that clings lacy and lasts well down the glass .  low , easy-going carbonation .

aromas first of alcohol , then sweet malt , then as the fumes dissipated , tropical/ floral hop aromas . now a mix of tropical fruity hops and alcohol . congrats - we wanted to be fancy and respectable like wine , and now we have an over-rated napa cabernet scene of our own .  probably the most beautiful pour i 've seen . sizable chocolate colored head almost `` rolled '' up the pint glass and stuck around for a long while . black as night , a little deep coffee color at the edges .  m : medium body and carbonation . it is a little sticky . some sharpness on my tongue as i swallow .

aroma is negligible , no matter how many times i check .  a nice bright and golden color , white head is two fingers thick and very dense . plenty of carbonation bubbles scampering for the top of the liquid .  carbonation is just a bit higher than i like ... .and the liquid is a bit think to be really pleasing . a bit more body would be a good thing .

too muted and even as it warms , it does n't really open up too much . some citrus leaning towards grapefruit , very nice . overall : a nice unpretentious ipa . nothing too exciting and a little subdued but i liked it .  scored this at goebels in wichita pours copper/auburn with 2 fingers of tan head . superior head retention & insane lacing s : faint breadyness t : caramel , breadyness , earthy & herbal hops , dryness up front , plus just a touch of woody hops well .  it somewhat lingers on your tongue .

smelled excellent , almot identical to ( the amazing ) hop rod rye .  pours a very nice burgandy with a tan head that is thick and rocky . in certain lights this brew appears to be brown , but i like it better as a burgandy .  taste-taste 's like water . mouthfeel-very light , crisp .

nice amount of hop haze with excellent lacing . s- i get big bitter resinous notes backed up by a small amount of sweet grapefruit/tropical scents . not the greatest ipa i 've smelled , but not bad .  l : clear straw yellow , white dense , creamy head with great retention and amazing lacing .  palate is a little cloying from the fruity sugars , but ends dry . finishes with a parching pinesness and slick fruit punch .

the aroma was nice , but it was just watered down whiskey with carbonation .  this brew pours a very deep golden with a very nice white head .  the body seemed a bit light , and maybe a bit more weight would have made it more satisfying , but that 's a minor quibble .

s : sweet honey malts and grain . t : a sweet and fruity honey flavor with some grain .  a two finger head is pale biege in color and holds very well leaving marvelous spiderweb lacing .  m - not bad , but a little thinner than i was hoping for .

when i pored it into the pint glass it was a little on the pale side for my taste and the smell was a tiny bit weak .  huge cream colored head with excellent retention and impressive lacing .  the looks are not deceiving , in that this beer goes down very easy . the finish is semi-clean with a hint of flavor left on the tongue . p.s . i like this beer better on tap than from the bottle !

m - good carbonation almost too much but its still very good . nice and smooth too . d - extremely drinkable . while its got a lot of stuff going on it retains a great level of crispness and smoothness that means i could drink this all night with zero complaints .  picked this up today at the cellar in olathe , ks ... appearance : pours a startling contrast of yellowish at the bottom moving towards a dark orange copper near the head . it quickly recedes , but there remains quite a film around the tops of the beer and sticky lacing all down the sides of the glass .  body is a bit lacking , it 's creamy carbonated but a bit light , almost like a light porter or english stout .

yup , even at arms length while pouring this i could smell the skunk . after a couple minutes the skunk started to fade and there was a pleasant grain scent underneath .  very nice looking beer .  the only disappointing part is the mouthfeel , which was more thin than i would have liked .

s : it almost has a little hint of a skunk scent though i think it is something else . yeasty , sweet , fruity . not amazing though .  ominously dense , fluffy white head . perfect retention .  mouthfeel is average , not much to say one way or the other , except , i guess it was smooth .

to encapsulate my sample : this beer 's drinkability number is off the charts for its style , since this is a malty beer with smoke accents instead of tasting like you 're face down in a fire , or snuffing some lucky strikes out on your palate . the smoke in this rauchbier is a tinge on top of a strong malty base , instead of an overstrong , overbearing nature . the aroma seemed a bit unidirectional considering .  poured into its own glass , this beer displays a deep reddish-amber hue and soft , thick head of foam .  i really enjoy the smell of this beer . i do n't know where you buy the nitro-release cans but i 'd like to know . i bought this in texas but i forgot where . apparently this beer can not be bought in kansas so i 'm glad i tried it . i made the mistake of trying this beer when it was cold .

a very narrow smell profile . the taste is much better than the smell . m- nothing outstanding .  looks incredible . the smell was a bit disappointing .  mouthfeel was a bit too thin and a bit overcarbonated .

n : i 'm not getting a big nose here . it really is n't prominent , i 'm surprised .  great clumpy off white head , with impeccable retention . the body is light copper in color and has only a slight haze to it .  m - well balanced , but thin and slightly sweet . was hoping for a medium to full-bodied saison .

nose is raspberry central ... good raspberry aroma , pleasing and as natural as can be . i think that the hops have done the raspberries in , and all that is left is a hopsie ale with a raspberry nose that has nowhere to go .  pours a cloudy brown with a three-finger off white head . great lacing and retention throughout .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts almost sweet but hops dominate , boring , finish is dry and slightly bitter . brewed aug 12 , 2005 . $ 1.79 for a 330ml bottle from lina 's beverages painesville , oh .

nose is wonderfully syrupy sweet with great complexity . showcases notes of vanilla taffy , honey , soft spicey slchol and banana .  pretty damn good looking beer .  m- mouth is a little on the light side for a stout .

the aroma seems really am . beer based more than european in nature with the sour quality am .  amazing fluffy tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  shortfalls are slightly thin , flattens out fast , washing out the complexity , and slight sour aftertaste -- which is fleeting . but perfect balance is why i give this super-smooth coffee-style beer a high rating .

aroma was not strong at all , but the taste of it makes up for that quite easily .  a - poured into my duvel tulip a really nice deep and dark ruby with a big , creamy two finger light tan head that fades ridiculously slowly and leaves amssive side lacing . for a barleywine , at this abv , the amount of lacing and head retention is crazy .  excellent flavor , with a great two-row maltiness up front and a great pine and semi-citrus hop flavor at the end that sticks . there is a bit of hop roughness to the beer that hurts the finish , but it 's still not bad going down .

hope it 's not old !  pours a sizable , 4-5cm head of medium sized bubbles , light tan in color . beer is dark red-amber in color , transparent , and with lots of carbonation . lacing is a sheet of bubbles that fades to a thick string over time .  m- much too thin for the style and something this big .

nothing terribly impressive about the aroma ; in fact , there was n't much of a smell to it at all ( or , at least , none that i could detect ) .  almost perfect lacing , like somebody painted it on the glass .  m & d -- mouthfeel was only average as i felt it stung a little more , was a bit more astringent , than i would have expected .

looks good , smells good , no taste !  rich ruby beer with hints of brown .  the hops are n't super astringent and they finish well . mouthfeel : medium-bodied .

i detect a slight citrus nose , not unpleasant at all .  perfect black color and slick creamy head ... mild aroma with hints of dark cocoa and roasted coffee beans ... .this is a flavorful dry stout with a dry toasty finish..it is considerably more flavorfull than guiness .  little helper is a good beer . defining it is a bit difficult , i would call it a hoppy but light ( er than normal ) red ale . very drinkable . nearly no head . good beer , but the malt flavor is not very interesting , and not pronounced considering the color . but i am a hop fan so that is just fine . all around great , hoppy , and drinkable red . wish rogue made less expensive beer !

the aroma had a slight fruitiness to it . truly awful .  a-deep red , beautiful with a red tint even on the head ... pours really beautifully s-rasberry , cream , sweet candied fruits t- rasberry and malty , nice slightly bitter dry finish m- very soft .  as mentioned before , my only knock is the carbonation and mouthfeel . this is a great beer , i just think it could be even better with a softer and thicker mouthfeel .

a deep caramel with a hint of amber . the initial smell did n't impress me much , and lowered my expectations for the taste . very tasty . all in all , a pretty darn good beer .  a great dark lager that reminds me of yuengling porter when it was made at the old brewery . the color is dark and when poured into a glass creates a nice white/gray head .  m- kinda thin , but full of great flavors that wrap around your tongue .

it is pretty pale , but much more vibrant than a macro adjunct lager . s : grainy and sweet . other than that i am not picking much up , but the beer is pretty chilled.a t : hop bitterness is most certainly throughout the entire sip , and at its strongest on the back of palate and aftertaste .  this black beer lets a little red through when held to the light . it has a creamy , frothy tan head that fades and leaves excellent lacing .  m : nice carbonation ... but a slight gritty feel .

aroma is not great . slight sweet malt , and no real hop presence .  sunday 's chores are doen and looking to rest up for the start of the week ... decided to tap into the dogfish iba ... .and it is quite nice ! the color is supurb with a deep dark rich amber ... basrley can see light through it .  mainly a flattish mouthfeel .

i do n't get too much aroma but it 's certainly a pleasant coffee presence . the flavor is wonderful . there'the typical fruity sweetness you come to expect from an alt .  pours an absolutely gorgeous orange hue that is impeccably clear and just a tad bit of pale head and some effervescence .  m : very light carbonation but there is just a bit to give the beer some levity .

nose- the belgian yeast is quite strong imparting a significant spiciness . very strange stuff ...  a very attractive beer : clear , clean ruby-amber with a strong frothy head and tons of lacing .  feels too carbonated and light in the mouth . just an average mouthfeel though , not too bad .

smell is faint to my nose . fist sip : blew me away with the flood of hops . in fact , it 's quite good .  excellent retention and lace .  maybe this was chilled too much but it seems to have a little too much bite , which might also be the carbonation .

surprised to find that the reviews were somewhat poor and the beer was classified as an irish red rather than a pale ale . the appearance obviously resembled that of a red more so than a pale , even if i had n't have done my research the color and accompanying smell ( which had an odd sweetness and was quite underwhelming ) would have clued me in .  pours a dark dark dark brown ( pretty much black ) with a crazy thick inch of dark brown foam/head which leaves a boat ton of sticky brown lacing .  sharp and light bodied .

the head , as with most belgians , leaves very nice lacing . the smell is weaker than i expected with a only a small hint of candy sugar present . the taste is sweet with candy sugar , dark fruit , and malt . a decent tasting beer , although it is alittle thin .  this is a beautiful looking beer , it pours a dark brown with ruby highlites . 2 fingers of off white-tan colored head that takes forever to settle to a nice creamy looking film on top . gorgeous thick heavy lace left clinging to the glass .  again , this beer was a bit thin for my taste .

pale gold color , fluffy white head , just a hint of skunk familiar with green-bottled european lagers that you get here . there 's still that light sweet grain , but there 's some honey and a little bit of spice , too . really good lacing , too .  the color is a deep , mysterious chestnut brown , topped with an astounding , off white head . theres not so much lacing , as a thick growth of foam trailing down the sides of the glass . the appearance of this brew is exceptional .  huge pine and citrus blast . a bit too abusive in the feel for me . a beer for the s & m crowd , i guess . i 'm not too sure many people would want to pound these given the bitterness and tongue numbingness ( though i 'm sure i 'd do just that if this were available here ) .

the aroma is quite light , a lightly roasted malt porter aroma with some sprucy characteristics .  lacing is awesome and so is everything else .  m-a little thinner in the body than i expected , but does n't ruin it by any means .

from twety-four ounce can : aroma sweet malts floral .  this brew looks very enticing . there is a massive amount of milk chocolate looking head , with great retention .  body is on the light side , ends acidic and dry .

very inviting . flavors were mostly sweet , with fresh-from-the-vine honey crisp apples , nutmeg , cinnamon , and a touch of marachino cherry juice . solid on the drinkability meter for a 9 % beer - good combo of aromas and flavors , but the aromas were the real winner here .  a : pours a brilliant , hazy gold . one of the creamiest 2-finger eggshell heads i 've ever seen , with excellent retention .  carbonation is a little bit higher than i prefer .

the aroma this beer emits is utterly repulsive , imo . my first impression was a skunky smelling tortilla chip ... eeesh .  a -- deep dark mahogany with killer amber red head and tons of lacing , beautiful , scores a perfect 5 .  its has a light mouth feel for a stout .

lots of malt on the nose . getting a hint of something sweet and flowery , like fresh cut hay . something else too , that reminds me of `` dessert '' .  watching the cascading effect is truly one of the pleasures of a beer drinker .  m : mouthfeel is a tad thin and , possibly , a little overcarbonated .

aroma is not strong , but is spicy and hoppy and inviting . flavor exceeds the wan aroma , being hoppy but not bitter , with nutty and malty undertones and spicy and horehound hints .  this pours magnificently with a huge white foamy guinness-ish cascade that ends up in a thick head . the beer itself seems brown , but with a reddish cast . the head retention is amazing , with long patches of lacing .  mouthfeel : murky and low on carbonation . 4.0 mouthfeel : better carbonation than the batch 1 but still fairly moderate which is fine for this style .

'' unpalatable if not cold .

s- roasted malts , peppercorn ? and caramel , a bit of hop spice and baking chocolate .  the beer poured brownish black with ruby highlights and a huge tan/brown head that lasted for days .  i would have expected a little more body in this beer . a little skinny for my tastes .

this smells vaguely hoppy , not super hoppy like many ipas . very bready malt in the nose .  appearance - pours a golden honey with a thick , pillowy head . the half inch head eventually recedes , leaving beautiful bands of lacing around the glass . the carbonation is moderate to high and gives the beer a lively lift .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for a stout .

s : nose is burnt malt , a slight coffee bean sourness , faint chocolate , and liquorice . not anything out of the ordinary and not particularly aromatic . t : dark fruit flavors engulf my senses from the first sip .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : a really beautiful beer with dark brown hue and thick , two finger tan head with lots of lacing .  the disappointing : wow , what a highly carbonated brew , almost champaign in the fizziness .

s : aroma is almost zilch . really tried hard , too ... t : slightly sweet , light bready malt .  best by date : 03/29/2011 a - a crystal clear beautiful rosy copper color with a medium off-white head that settles to a thick ring and some bubbly patches on the surface . this looks fantastic . s - creamy grapefruit , pine , and some balancing malt .  mouthfull - not very thick tasting , watery would be a better word to describe this . very freshing beer . very well rounded beer , i 'm not that fond of the mouthfeel as it seems to be sometimes a tad to watery but overaul its a good beer .

this brew pours up a murky reddish brown color with a nice off white head ... the nose is sweet malts and a nice funky aroma ... the taste is funky ( get down !  pours a deep dark brown with thick creamy dark khaki head that leaves lots of lacing !  mouthfeel is not quite as full as it could be , but still does a good job delivering and distributing flavor around the mouth .

the aroma was what i will describe as `` fun '' , candy-like sweetness , fruity yeast , lemon and green apples similar to a jolly rancher candy . tart , tart , tart but refreshing . the acidity was very high which made sense given the flavors but definitely took away from its drinkability . the mouthfeel was ok but slick no doubt due to the varieties of citrus-inducing hops , the body medium and the carbonation the same .  much darker too . gorgeous beer . big craters make it look like the dark side of the moon .  mouthfeel : a little thin , but not bad .

american pine needles and german hop nose , matched with a caramel and butterscotch malt aroma .  bottle courtesy of hogtownharry : poured a deep hazy light beige color ale with a big white foamy head with perfect retention .  this harp was brewed in canada by moosehead . this is a very satisfying beer ; especially when all the over-hopped , over-malted , extreme productions . become too much ... which is the true beauty of this harp . it is straight forwardly flavorful without making great demands on the palate . lively with a clean finish . this is the first harp i have sampled in a few years , and is easily the most tasty i have ever encountered .

on the plus side is the yeasty aroma and cloudy white appearance . i do n't like over-the-top corriander .  bottle : poured a murky brown color ale with a super huge foamy head with good retention .  i would recommend this beer both as a meal beer and a drinking man 's beer , versatile and a solid wheat ... not too fruity , but not to plain ... too carbonated , but i imagine a great american/bavarian weisse on tap .

not much of a hops taste more malty aroma which comes thru on the tsate . a very drinkable beer that i would recommend ... ... ... ... ... cheers  appearence : pours an oh so gorgeous creamy orange with a thin , sustaining nearly white head .  light bodied and hardly any carbonation to speak of .

skunk aromas and skunky taste . the most prolific flavor in this beer is skunk . by now i guess the green bottle and the skunk flavor and aroma is their trademark , so its too late to change . *note* i 've been told by certified beer judges that the skunk taste and smell disappears when this beer is drank from can of keg .  750ml into duvel glass north of 40 degrees . pours with a thick , soft , and pillowy peach-colored head over a deep maroon colored body , with plenty of carbonation flowing up .  i was not impressed with the finish at first , in that it was slightly watery . however , as beer warmed at mid-glass , palte was much more full and smooth , and the alcohol gave a warming sensation on the way down .

big fragrance , banana , malty sweet , hint of caramel . very tasty brew , a good beer to sit and sip . vol . rating .  pours super dark black with thick tan head . this is stellar !  a pleasant flavor but it 's hard to pinpoint what citrus flavors are making their way though m- carbonation was a little overbearing the first few sips , but the remainder of the beer had a nice , slightly creamy mouthfeel o- a bit more carbonated than i like my ipas , but it 's hard to hold that against what 's an exceptional beer from cigar city .

smell is ok . the sweet caramel malts cover up a lot in the nose . i pick up the slightest bit of hops and orange peel when i really get a good swirl .  ) poured into a pint glass pitch black with two fingers of thick , dark tan/grey head that lingers like light pancake batter and laces nicely - if i did n't know better , i 'd think it was a solid stout so far .  tart up front , with ample carbonation clinging to bitter noble hops . mouthfeel is medium bodied with a lingering puckering finish . a decent overall tripel here .

appearance : this is definitely not a pitch black stout . smell : not much . taste : awesome . the first thing that jumps out at me is the roasted flavor , then coffee , then creaminess . this is definitely a relative of left hand 's milk stout , but jacked up on imperial steroids .  pours a nearly black color with a thick and frothy mocha hued foam . retention is superb , as is the lacing . for a non-imperialized stout , this is about as good as it gets for appearance .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . kind of a mild coconutty taste , almost pina colada like ? i 'm going to revisit this one for sure whenever i get a chance .

s : the smell is much weaker than the taste . in fact because of this the taste surprised me a bit . t : a bitter-hoppy start , then a nutty/sweet-caramel finish .  dark mahogany body ; semi-translucent but pretty dark . large , thick , creamy tan head with amazing retention .  watery feel for a stout but with just enough body to get you through .

could n't seem to get a whole lot outta the smell ... a bit sweet i suppose . tasted light caramels , hints of raisins and malts .  appearance this is a brilliant , crystal clear lager halfway between orange and brown with a nice , off-white head that left lacing on the inside of my pint glass . i just couldnt stop staring at it the color was so brilliant and perfect .  m : sharp at first , fizzy , but lights up as you hold it . still , a bit strong and that cuts down on how much you can have . d : i had 10oz with no problems , but a second might have gotten bothersome due to the fizz .

aromas of cranberries are very strong up front with a slight grainy smell as well . ca n't say that i enjoyed this brew much , i think they would have been better off foregoing the lambic and just making a cranberry ale .  interesting lace and amazing retention .  m- even though it is lighter with the smoke , i still think that it could use more malt body .

the smell was wonderful . the taste was very nice .  quite solid . body is dark , and head is plentiful . the beer had this cool nitro-tap look to it when i poured it - tan head on top , but a level of raging-rising bubbles below the head and above the body .  silky smooth in the mouth while maintaining a very lively carbonation ... .just amazing .

smell is almost non-existant . any sort of detectable smell is merely mediocre , and mostly uninspired . taste is decent for the style . very uninspired and not welcome in my mind .  the crusher from hoppin ' frog poured motor oil black topped by a short , creamy brown head . this stout has the look and feel of a top-notch imperial stout .  wonderful feel .

smell - probably turned me off the most about this beer . no depth to the smell . taste - bits of caramel , citrus , and a woody aftertaste that does n't linger for long .  hazy , with a massive head of white foam kept alive by abundant streams of carbonation erupting like strings of xmas lights . a very beautiful appearance .  mouthfeel is outstanding . the extreme thickness adds to the buttery flavors and is really a high point of the experience .
smells sweet and ... .murky somehow .  carbonation looks extremely well done , and the streams are impressive . good appearance .  perfect carbonation for the style .

no real lacing but it does have some legs smell : smell is decadent ; probably one of the best smelling non-sour beers i have encountered . overall/drinkability : one of the best-smelling non-sour beers i have encountered , but the high abv and hugeness of it really detracts .  poured a beautiful deep amber with a tiny head .  high carbonation . probably the silkiest body in a dipa i 've ever encountered .

smell is a big whiff of dunkel bananas and bubble gum . not to sweet and the banana taste practically punches you in the nose . mouthfeel is watery .  terrific retention , heavy lace . gorgeous lager .  mouthfeel is exceptional and creamy . this is what makes this beer so spectacular imo .

excellent . the beer is the color of honey , and since this is a honey ale , it succeeds in this area as well . the taste and mouthfeel are light , pleasant , and ultimately forgettable .  bbd of 4/27/07 07 version pours copper/orange with 3 fingers of fluffy head . superoir lacing & very good head retention s : nothing up front , but then earthy hoppyness & whisper of fruit .  really a great beer that has it 's hops really balanced , and the silky smooth malt mouthfeel balances wonderfully with bitterness of the hops .

leaves a single ring of lace from the initial pour stale and earthy smell . there 's also a medicinal , band-aide odor of phenol .  and of course the very cool cascading bubbles which build the creamy tan head , which dutifully hangs out for the duration of the beer .  mouth is light-medium bodied excellent carbonation .

s : huge hoppy smell . really fresh smelling , i thought it was pretty floral , although most other people seem to be picking up on citrusy flavors . m : really lively , although it settles down somewhat quickly .  this pours pure black and thick . nice head .  m - carbonation cleans the palate nicely , the tartness and funk does n't linger long . the carbonation is just spot on , love it .

citrus and a boatload of creamy ripe bananas . the yeast and the wheat smells really are resounding for such a pale looking 'belgian ' .  this brew pours a beautiful small dark brown head with bubbles of all sizes and a pitch black opaque body with some carbonation seen rising up the side of the mug .  mouthfeel : absolutely fantastic . smooth , dry , and thick .

stunning citrusy orange-grapefruit-lemon-passion fruit and pine aroma . could sniff this one all day . exceptional aroma carries the day here .  upside down bubble action , excellent creamy head with good retention and lace .  mouthfeel : very smooth body , easy to drink . nicely carbonated .

it does n't smell all that great , and does n't taste much like a dark beer .  it pours a lightly hazy , yet radient honey amber orange color . three inches of off-white head explode towards space , settling about a half inch above the rim of my pint glass . this is one of the most impressive heads i 've seen in all my years of beerdom , earning it a 5 in appearance .  moderate carbonation with a strong sticky pine aftertaste make it very very enjoyable . very strong , flavorful , and pleasant .

huge bourbon aromas . this version , like the 10 dl in my opinion , is not thick and motor oil like as previous years .  burgundy color , with a full and creamy foam that lasts .  m : spot on with the mouthfeel - very thick and almost chewy , with just a hint of alcohol towards the finish .

nose : grapefruit with sugar tones , very tempting and one of the best smelling beers i 've had in a while .  it pours an inky black color impenetrable to light with a very thick creamy and slightly frothy head that retains like crazy and billows against the glass . lots of lacing evident to boot . the head is a nice chocolate brown color .  there ' a great mouthfeel , it just makes you think that this is the perfect body and carbonation for this beer 's taste and aroma .

smell : is it just me or does this smell fantastic ? i got an incredibly complex sweet/sour fruity scent that had aromas of dry hops and caramel malts .  a vigorous pour yields a fast-falling one finger head , large bubbled . it forms a nice glass ring . the body is a wonderful near-opaque black , with ruby highlights only when potently backlit .  the mouthfeel on this beer was truly exceptional . i 've never had a beer with such great viscosity that managed to avoid being sticky .

s : huge hop aroma . big citrus hops and inviting sweetness . smells as good as any dipa i 've had yet .  a : beautiful nearly black with milk chocolate brown edges and a baking german chocolate cake head , 2-3 fingers , with prodigious amounts of lace .  m : medium-bodied with a soft , silky mouthfeel . the thick , creamy head gives a great texture to each sip .

a light yellow seen with a not impressed head on a 1l glass . atleast this beer taste better than allot of the cheapest beers they serve on can in sweden . drinkable .  22oz bottle poured into a mexican tulip - fridge temp - 2008 appearance : pours a semi cloudy golden orange with a towering 5 '' yellowish head . it shows great retention .  m : leaves a nice stickiness that is not overpoweing .

amazing aromas of strong caramel , maple syrup , coffee , chocolate .  beautiful translucent amber-orange beer , with some great head retention/lacing .  it was medium bodied and the carbonation was perfect . it was very enjoyable to just hold it in the mouth .

s - piney , resiny , hop aroma predominant . light , crisp malt aroma , as would be expected from the style .  straw yellow in color , decent head of small bubbles . great lacing and tons of bubbles coming up from the bottle . looked super d duper .  d - i love the dessert like chocolate and cream notes , and the mouth feel is outstanding . a really well done brew , but i do n't think that i could take more than one ... it 's a hair to sweet imo .

smells of passionfruit , peaches , apricots and strawberries in no particular order . smooth mouthfeel , very light , this is highly drinkable if you like the sweet stuff .  has a huge , foamy tan cap that recedes into thick clumps on top of the brew , and leaves substantial lacing with register marks down the glass .  smooth , crisp , dry , and satisfying medium body . clean in the end yet enough texture to let the flavors linger .

smell : this is where this beer really shines in my opinion . loads of spices that dominate the nose . cinnamin , nutmeg , gloves , ginger and oddly pepper . highly disappointed on this one .  pours crystal clear dark red orange color with a nice 2 finger dense khaki head with incredible retention that reduces to thick lacing cap that lasts forever . overall this is an absolutely outstanding amber ale/ipa .  mf : masterfully fizzy but light and balanced .

it 's the first winter warmer i 've had that actually smells like christmas . nutmeg , allspice , cinnamon , pine , and a touch of sweet bready malt . this was definitely better than i expected .  appearance - a rich , cloudy red-brown with a two to three finger head of creme foam .  velvety smooth creamy mouthfeel , moderate level of carbonation , medium to thick body .

the aroma is wonderful flowers and pine very nice . the taste unfortunatly leave the nice bitter bite of its little brother into the taste of pine resin .  a : pours a bright glowing golden with a huge frothy bright white head that slowly faded into a thick rocky film that left patches of sticky lacing down the glass .  the mouthfeel is superb : sticky and chewy but also very creamy , with fluffy carbonation .

smells of toffee , faint citrus , light hops and toasted malts , with an undeniable scent of wet dog* . * 3 out of 3 agree , it smells like a wet dog .  this is on tap at hard times cafe in bethesda . what a beautiful bright orange color .  this exhibited a creamy mouthfeel .

smells like a lemonade/orangeade mixture but in a really inviting way . not sweet or sugary like the aroma would suggest but that just must be from extreme dry-hopping and the oak somehow . bitterness is perfect , no traditional hop aromas , no earthiness , pine , woody , flowers , just fruitiness . crazy .  a : vigorous pour yields a 2 finger semi-coarse deep chocolate head that holds steady at about .5 fingers . beer is opaque black and thick . lacing is frothy , like a painted tidal wave of brown on the side of my glass .  mouthfeel is the best part about the rasputin - just the right amount of chewiness and the malt and alcohol linger heavily on the sides of your tongue .

the smell is extremely aromatic and floral . a very pleasing taste , you can definitely tast crisp apple as well as the hint of wine . this beer tastes exactly like it smells , crisp and clean . easy to drink .  appearance- a huge fluffy head rises above my weizen glass and very slowly recedes . a nice amount of lacing remains . this is by far the fluffiest head i 've ever seen . the body is straw colored , cloudy , and has ample carbonation bubbles .  mouthfeel was exceedingly smooth .

s : the smell is rich and full of sweet caramel , molasses , toffee , and vanilla . the brandy blends in seamlessly with the base old ale and the dark fruits such as raisins , plums , and some others that i ca n't quite pick out . t : the flavor is rich and sweet , featuring brown sugar , caramel , toffee , and vanilla . m : the carbonation is non-existent , but the body is quite full and rich . d : sure , you ca n't sit down and enjoy the full 750 ml bottle of this beer , but you could certainly get yourself in some trouble .  ) topped by a majestic light brown head that shows truly noteworthy retention and leaves tons of sticky brown lace - this is exactly what i want an imperial stout to look like : exactly .  m- oh so crisp and so damn smooth over the medium body .
