s : big amarillo fan tbh and this one delivers like no other . very juicy and strong with the tropical fruits . strong smell . could n't ask for anything better . but , the lime zest and red grapefruit is a bit stronger than in the smell , which is perfect for the taste department . o : this is a damn fine tasting rye/ipa beer .  beautiful night black color with a nice tan head . about 1 pinky thick head with good retention . fades to a nice white ring . good lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel on this is full and creamy , absolutely perfect . very soft carbonation .

aroma is sweet with notes of cloves , candy , and overripe pear . it 's a very nice belgian , but it 's certainly not a dark ale . that they grow all the ingredients themselves is very remarkable . it is a very nice effort at a belgian , but the lack of a real hop profile makes this simply too sweet for my palate .  displays awesome retention , forms a mesa in the middle of the glass and shows off an impressive formation of 3d lace . an awesome appearance and nice aroma save this one from finding the 'c ' range .  body is refreshing yet almost full in its thickness and rich , creamy carbonation . overall it 's damn delicious and a great collaboration ; no surprise that there 's yet another beer with the dogfish head logo on it that i love .

all supported by a lovely smell of pale malt . superb nose . t : : orange peel and lemon are huge in the foretongue .  12oz served in a snifter at the bavarian lodge - lisle , il poured a deep , rusty , orange-amber color with a foamy off-white head . with each sip , a new ring of lacing was left around the glass - definitely nice to look at .  creamy mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is very creamy and chewy .

s - pungent , fruity hops that are reminiscent of jaialai ipa . d - very nice , the malt and hops are perfectly balanced , especially in the aroma where the fruity notes perfectly compliment the sweetness of the toffee and caramel .  black as nite . amazing layers of stacked , brown foam .  m/d - full bodied and very creamy . lively carbonation carries the beer through your mouth .

the smell is off the hook ... piney hops that just are incredibly inviting . the taste is more subdued , with a mellow citrusy hoppiness that just begs for another sip .  a= pours a nice deep amber color with a huge off white head . holds great retention and lacing .  really excellent creamy mouthfeel .

looks really good in the glass - just what i want from a brown ale . the smell is just okay - there 's some nuttiness there , but it 's not overpowering ( which i prefer ) .  exceptional appearance !  the mouth feel is outstanding , to the point of being lip smacking and among the best i 've had .

the aroma was amazingly sweet , smooth , rich and creamy with a robust coffee presence . on smell alone , i might have mistaken this beer for a rich and complex oatmeal stout . this beer had an aroma that was to die for , yet the flavor profile was far too acrid for my palate .  i loved the color . the head is nice and big , white , creamy , fluffy , and beautiful .  mouthfeel is about the creamiest i 've ever had a beer feel . drinkability is great too .

when i openned it , a strong fruity smell came out from the bottle , berries and berries and more fruity berries flavours came out . a very dark ruby beer with a shy white head that comes out quicky to say hi . smell is deeply fruity and berry like , some shy hops smells are present followed by yeast and end with a shy malted presence . very nice  pours a pitch black color with a beautiful brown head into my glass . definitely the color of the style . roasted malt greets the nose followed by grassy hops that do n't jump out too much in the nose .  leaves very thick lacing , almost like a nitro s_toasted bread , caramel , not very strong t_burnt toast , chocolate coffee beans , no real aftertaste m_ultra-smooth and creamy , so mellow , balanced , very little carbonation .

the smell is rich with fermented fruit .  a : thick orange hazy body with an amazing bone white head with rocky peaks and absolutely massive lacing .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it just goes down that damn smooth !
s- the aroma is not that pleasant . sweet grain and a really off caramel aroma .  nice looking beer .  fairly soft but noticeable carbonation , thick creamy mouthfeel just like chocolate milk .

its massively enticing and one of the best i 've come across on an imperial ipa or any other type of beer . the flavour is very good , but not as vibrant as the nose . that said , this is still a solid four out of five in my books . this is a very nice imperial ipa , but i 'm gon na go against the flow and say its not in the very top tier for the style . the nose held huge promise , and while the flavour delivered on some of it , the vibrancy was a bit lacking . i 'm sure this would be a killer fresh on tap .  a - an absolutely gorgeous cloudy golden amber with a tall , frothy pillow of foam on top with great retention . my mouth is watering just looking at it .  the carbonation was perfect , often porters are too carbonated and heavy , this one hit the spot .

very appealing . mouth : taste is fruity but too sweet .  reviewed from notes a - poured into a standard pint glass a wonderous midnight black that had a one finger mocha head resulting in massive , massive side lacing .  m. good body with a perfect level of carbonation .

no aroma at all . no initial flavor , but some malt when it goes down the tongue and a little hop bitterness on the finish .  the beer pours into a gorgeous cascading whirlpool of goodness . it really is a sight . the head is snow white and thick .  mf - this it where this beer shines the most to me . very nice carbonation that tickles your mouth as you savor it . also reminds me in some ways of an eisbock albeit less vinuous and more carbonated and roasty .

wonderfull beige head and anorangeamber beercollor with fine haze . nose shows mega brettarome , sweety horse in flowery fields and wonderfull balance between the freshness of esters & spices and on the other hand the bretty arome . thinking this brewery just started gives me good hope and wants me to try more of this newcomber .  i love watching the nitro separate out into the espresso looking foam . the beer itself is a nearly opaque black . looks great . the smell suffers a bit from the nitro , it seems .  really impressive mouthfeel with carbonation that really makes it finish well .

the aroma is heavenly ! ..think sweet , dark hazelnut coffee , maple syrup and vanilla . really amazing aroma . taste is initially brisk flavor hops , dark sweet malt , some burnt sugar , giving way to a chocolate and coffee finish .  the head is a lovely frothy brown that pours big but collapses to a crescent of film . very nice .  it has a very `` oktoberfest '' flavor which is n't my favorite but really excels with mouthfeel .

smells incredible , like hickory or mesquite smoke and just a hint of the malt reminding me this is a beer and not beef jerky .  pitch black color , topped with a very dark tan , thick head .  this lingers for a few seconds before a bit of spice segues into ample , but never overpowering , bitterness- joined by a ridiculously intense fusel alcohol character which adds its own bit of astringency , ensuring that the beer does n't end too sweet but not once interrupting the incredibly smooth texture .

biscuity sweet aroma on the nose , faint floral hops .  pours a pitch black color with a small brown head into my tulip glass .  body is creamy and rich , with mild carbonation , pretty strong abv , but alcohol is not dominant in the taste i enjoyed this beer the more i drank , very impressed .

huge cherry and oak on the nose , followed by an earthy mustiness and barnyard funk . a bit boozy . a damn fine flemish sour ; ranks with the best .  superior lacing & head retention s : bready notes , some lemony notes , not as much as i hoped for ... t : grassy & lemony hops , plus sweet grainy notes , slight grapefruit hop smack as well & some honey notes up front .  mouthfeel- excellent palate coverage , really covers the entire tongue .

smell- a malty aroma is abundant in this one . not suprising with most winter warmers .  this brew pours a medium head of fine creamy light brown bubbles that leaves a fair lacing and a dark opaque black brown body .  thick and silky with a medium body . velvety smoothness characteristic of only a handful of the best belgians . clean finish keeps me wanting to drink more .

no head whatsoever s : upon pouring the room filled with the aroma of dark caramel , toasted walnuts and cookies , with a foundation of oxidized , sherry-like sweetness . t : sweet sherry flavors and oxidation hit the palate first , followed immediately by strong toasted walnut and nearly burnt caramel .  this beer is a beautiful , deep golden color . produces a moderate head that dissipates pretty quickly .  m/d - mouthfeel is great , this beer briefly coats the mouth but then almost cleans it 's own flavor out of your mouth and has a slight aftertaste .

smell : the aroma of this beer is definitely its strongest attribute . great hop/floral character with the typical grapefruit and citrus notes . i thought that the smell of this beer was also a bit sweeter than most ipas ; there is almost a bit of honey detectable resulting in a nice balance between sweetness and bitter hops . taste : the first thing i noticed was the nice creamy texture of this one . again , i could have used a bit more malt presence to balance things out . drinkability : very refreshing .  georgeous dark amber brown with an amazingly thick and creamy bubblebath of khaki head sitting on top .  very smooth and creamy mouthfeel with a nice medium body .

smell is somewhat lacking as i do n't really smell much of anything , maybe a very slight sweetness . still a sweet/malty smell . mouthfeel is good although there is very little carbonation this beer goes down good .  looks great . moderately clear , dark amber color and reddish hue .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and thick for the style .

the rich smoky aroma has strong tones of roast coffee and molasses and just a whisper of unsweetened chocolate , demanding a taste .  the body is a thick pitch black , impermeable to light , very impressive . thick chunky tan head , dented with large bubbles .  mouthfeel is so soft and smooth , and drinkability is very easy .

pure single aroma , not complicated , just good . bright clarity to the deep gold colored glass ( oversized chalice at the moment ) . the levels of hops needed to pull such a heady nose takes its toll , deep bittering hop leaves go very earthy and cancel out a lot of the citric over time . prickly carbonation in an oily rich body yeah , lagunitas sucks .  the color is black with just a hint of brown when held up to a light . the tan head looks quite creamy and appealing , and it leaves plenty of lacing on the side of my glass . this beer could not look more attractive .  feel is a nice creamy smooth medium-full with an excellent soft tickling carbonation .

smell is a wow factor , very complex . deep cocoa scents combine with biscuit , sugar , espresso and cream cheese . chocolate , coffee , more cocoa actually , with a deep berry embedded , blackberry perhaps . feel is smooth and luscious , dessert-like yet without the fat .  it poured with a finger 's worth of lovely ecru head that experienced good retention . the color was a deep honey-gold with ne-quality clarity .  m : perfect ! the carbonation melds with the beer in such a way that makes this a one-of-a-kind experience to drink .

it has a smell of pumpkins and spice , almost exactly like pumpkin pie . i seem to come back to this every year and it 's probablly just because it smells so good .  this beer pours almost black with deep mahogany highlights , topped by a rocky tan head that fills my pint glass . the head slowly fades , leaving a thick , sticky lace on the glass .  mouthfeel was silky smooth with a mild bitterness on the tongue .

4.0 smells like a crappy adjunct lager . not really a whole lot going on here .  dark brown body , very clear with a one finger tight head that lasts the whole beer and leaves huge amounts of lacing .  smooth and full mouthfeel .

smells luscious and pineappley with a hint of coconut .  pours very opaque black , the tiniest touch of brown from the edge , seems to have some decent floaty chunks in the bottom of it ( which of course makes them sinkies ) . head is deliciously huge , ochre-coloured , sinking steadily and consistently but leaves some pretty shit-hot beige lace sheets behind . yeah , it 's a stunner .  superb feel .

smell is very strong and pleasing . i get big raisin notes with oatmeal , allspice , nutmeg , and cinnamon . pretty incredible actually !  it was a very bright golden color with just perhaps a bit of haze . great lacing . i ca n't imagine a better looking specimen for the style .  taste : really complex with an extraordinary mouthfeel and a dry finish .

holy smells this one has a nice nose ! sweet and meaty with burnt caramel and some smokiness . excited to try this .  pours out of the dark clad bottle pure black with just a few hints of ruby around the edges . the rocky tan head lasts forever and leaves a lot of lace patches behind .  carbonation is pretty much perfect , and adds just the right element to the brew .

very enjoyable . the taste is sweet at first but then the bitterness hits .  the brew is bright light gold with a magnificent , thick creamy head that slowly dissipates to leave thin bubbles and a slight lacing around the glass .  great carbonation rounds out a very good-looking beer . no one flavor takes over , its a combination of them that gives this beer a great mouthfeel .

the aroma was the high point for me : very sweet malts , sugary candy , caramel , and mocha coffee . can smell it from a good distance away . small , light brown head that sticks gorgeously to the side of the glass . i highly advise trying this one .  pours a deep brown . no , dark brown . black colored brown . a coffee colored frothy head appears with decent retention and lacing . outstanding .  medium body with a thick and creamy yet mineralic texture . perfect combination of lively and fizzy effervescence . finish is dry and tart with just enough lactic sourness .

smell is fantastic , floral hops and a sweeter citrus smell fill my nostrils with goodness .  a uber-carbonated beer , took the barternder a good ten minutes of pouring to get me a full glass . huge white head , fix fingers of head with an awesome swirl on top sticking up sevearl inches over the glass , reminds you of a ice cream cone swirl , so gorgeou . head falls in chunks , great lacing ... the aroma is light caramel on the nose with corn , light finish , i was expecting to get skunk where is it ?  m : quite thick and mouth-filling for an ipa , with enough smooth carbonation to keep things fairly clean . just lovely .

incredibly complex , balanced , and appealing .  on tap night of a million zillion speedways o'brien 's pub san diego , ca dark as night black with brown edges , thin head but the body of this beer is just spectacular . it 's thick and oily and leaves the glass absolutely covered in sticky lace . unfortunately , the appearance is one of the few fine things about this beer . while there is still a bit of the coffee and roast combination left from the untreated version of speedway , the dry hopping has given this beer an incredibly woody character .  mouthfeel is very creamy and fuller than i was expecting . i love the way this beer just coats the mouth .

exceptional clarity with some visible carbonation s : ridiculously intoxicating with raspberries and milk chocolate . this really smells like some exquisite , high-end candy . despite being served at cellar temp , i 'm not getting any alcohol , it 's beautifully hidden . mildly vinous , caramel and vanilla are noticeable .  the beer poured pitch black with a ruby highlight . the head was brown and large and coated the glass on the way to lacing the glass . the whole enchilada on appearance . the lacing and head were second to none .  mouthfeel was incredibly creamy .

it hits you hard with the cinnamon upfront , and some ginger , nutmeg , and malt ... it smells like a gingerbread cookie ... also boozy especially when it warms and then maybe some citrus peel and some brown sugar t- lots of flavor ... cinnamon , pretty boozy , and bready ... again like a cinnamon/gingerbread cookie ... a tiny bit of dark berries on the finish ... the cinnamon sticks with you throughout ( like their pumpkin ale ) m- more carbonated than i anticipated ( a good thing ) ... creamy but also crip enough to keep me sipping d- would n't be able to drink too many of these because of the richness but then again you can never complain about too much flavor right ?  in my opinion , this is one of the best looking beers in the glass that i 've ever seen . great balance of color , bubbles and head . absolutely clear - no chunkies from belgium .  the piney hops dominate the flavor , but a snappy finish makes it 's hard to gripe too much . exceptionally well balanced . in spite of the bold hops , it drinks with amazing ease .

the smell is strongly like pumpkin , some spices , very similar to pumkin pie .  a : a dark brown color with and of white head that sits two fingers high .  mild carbonation , super creamy body , smooth .

but the aroma is fantastic . definitely worth trying , especially since they used a brettanomyces strain from maine .  appearance : black as pitch with coffee-colored head . however , if placed to the light it emits a reddish glow , like blood .  very creamy and full bodied , perfect carbonation to keep it moving .

prunes , prunes , prunes and a hint of burnt chocolate espresso/coffee with a huge amount of hop-less goodness ! one of the best smells i 've ever had out of an american stout . you can taste the burnt coffee and well , that 's kind of it . there 's really no huge taste that i expected out of a beer with such a huge nose . feels pretty good like going down with a carbonated and light thickness oil like liquid . quiet drinkable but i 'm disappointed in the flavor . still not a bad pick up .  a - poured a hazy gold colour , with a very attractive pillow of white head that retained forever , and laced extremely well s - citrus hoppiness , with that stark unmistakable belgian style smell , and some light biscuity malt .  very enjoyable , with a medium body and creamy carbonation that is perfect for this beer .

fantastic . i could just smell it all night .  a vigorous pour shows amazing carbonation for an oak aged beer . the result is a huge three finger rich tan head with big fat bubbles . leaves lots of lace .  the richness and weight is perfect for me .

pours a clear yellow pils color , great big chunky white head at first , but it goes down and there is n't much lacing to speak of smell is pretty interesting , grass , flowers , tons of belgian yeasts , dust , some slight lambic smells actually not sure if that is brett or not , i think the flower may be elderflower as it smells similar to the cantillon mamouche , some lemons also , it smells awesome taste is a slight letdown from the smell , i was expecting some bold flavors but it is quite subtle .  the belgian style pale ale came out cloudy , deep golden , and bubbly , and readily formed a rocky two finger head , that kept rising up until it was sticking above the glass in a volcano shaped cone of bubbles .  i do n't find much to be said really , excellent balance , medium body shows a perfect carbonation to my liking , quite creamy lager , pretty crisp dry herbal hops finish .

beautiful aroma . taste is also excellent . bourbon , cherries , dark fruit , caramel sugar - but not overly sweet . not terribly complex , but delicious . mouthfeel is dissapointing .  pours a hazy dark golden orange with a medium creamy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  this beer is creamy , smooth in the mouth with absolutely no harsh swallow or bite .

s - wonderful citrus hops .  for a large-scale macrobrewery known for a rather unremarkable mainstream beer , this one 's a terrific offering . appearance is excellent , almost shimmering and golden in the glass , with a haziness reminiscent of unibroue 's `` blanche de chambly '' . large , active , bubbly head , with some very exciting lacing . overall , a wonderful beer to look at .  incredibly easy-drinking and gentle on the tongue . the penultimate english pale mouthfeel . there is so much to love : subtle and well-rounded , both quenching and engaging , plus the mouthfeel is impeccable . i feel foolish for not having tried this sooner .

no discernable aroma . this beer is good , but not outstanding , i like it , its probably be good with a red meat .  an electric yellow beer with a moderate haze , the lightning white head billows to charmin-like proportions and even the inside of the bottle has a rocky , well-puffed lacing .  mouthfeel 5/5 medium bodied , appropriately crisp , and clean finishing , the mouthfeel of this beer is spot on .

the aroma is a hedonistic cherry immersion , and the flavor is more of the same -- tart , fresh , delicious . malt and hops are undetectable , as is the alcohol .  the color is gorgeous ! deep ruby with a rocky off white head .  mouthfeel - perfect , the creaminess remains with a twinge of bitter , very hearty and drinks like a filling snack .

a - pours a golden yellow with a white head that foams up to a 2 or 3 fingers and slowly dissipates leaving a thin ring on the edges s - pretty freakin amazing , super funky , earthy funk , lemon tart , sour apples , maybe some woody smell .  pours fairly clear light amber color with a nice 3 finger white head with awesome retention and some nice glass lacing .  this is a full bodied beer , the soft carbonation lightens it up creating a pleasing experience .

definitely one of the top 5 hop aroma beers i have ever consumed . it is so so so inviting from the aroma . i totally love beers with this full citrus hop aroma . the taste is totally different than the nose . it makes you think initially that it will be bitter and hop centric but then the malt character makes a huge stand and controls the main flavors your tongue perceives . it is quite pale malt dominated and i really appreciate this because overly resiny beers make me gag . i could pound this to no end which is dangerous considering the abv , lucky it is quite high in $ $ $ so this will limit my consumption . this is a very tasty and simple straightforward dipa .  good retention and great lace .  silky smooth , nice carbonation , and thin enough to drink a few of , but not so thick as to let you notice the 7.4 % .

very pleasant smelling beer . very fruity with citrus and maybe a pear or apricot smell to it as well .  '' really dark with a thick and creamy dark brown head . nice head retention and great lacing all the way through .  mouthfeel is wonderfully thick .

smell is awesome . smells like a freshly baked pumpkin pie is in my grill as i sniff away .  pours a clear golden with a huge frothy white head that can not be beaten back .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

smell- flowers , belgian hops , honey , and candi sugar . extremely fragrant and balanced , with a superior fullness to the aroma . taste- a most graceful and balanced display of all ingredients , with not a single element outdoing the others . very good , but not perfect . outstanding and well worth the money .  the beer in my shaped pint is black , with some brown around the edges . fluffy tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  head retention is poor , almost non-existent , a little dissapointing smell is not what i was expecting , surpisingly subtle , with a nice malty sweetness taste comes as a wave , roastiness , coffee like , followed by mellow sweet malt , bitterness like dark chocolate lingers in the mouth , pleasant after taste wonderfully full mouthfeel , thick , fits the beer 's complex flavor the alcohol is apparent , but not overpowering , easy to sip , not exactly quaffable , but pleasant

s : smells delicious ! funky , belgian yeast and and cloves with hints of citrus , fresh fruits and sweetness .  appearance : as expected this beer pours ink black and easily forms a rich nut brown head with good retention .  it has a perfect mouthfeel and it is extremely drinkable .

enticing aroma . probably the best aroma of any beer i have ever smelled before . vibrant fruit notes ; apple , pear , berries and cherries along with a maltiness of cookies and caramel .  pours out to a thick opaque black , forming a nice whipped dark espresso crema head with amazing retention and one sticky sheet of lace .  exceptional body .
wow ! ! ! nice . on second sip the honey really is apparant , very nice .  lace just about as extensive and impressive .  m - very smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

this smells wonderful . i 'm in a field - no ! fantastic . taste is a balance of the citrus , resiny hops , and a malty sweetness .  the pour is beautiful . thick like motor oil and `` black as midnight on a moonless night . '' a dark head on the beer which eventually disappears into a ring around the edge of the glass and eventually becomes headless . nevertheless , this is one of the more beautiful beers i 've seen .  mouthfeel - full-bodied , velvety smooth , and creamy with a semi-dry finish and moderate carbonation .

the beer itself is a dark mahogany color , and i did n't know it was bottle conditioned , so i got some yeast haze on my pour . s : the weakness in this beer was n't the lacing , it was the unfortunate lack of aroma . absolutely nothing when it was cold , and even when it warmed , i could only detect a touch of sweetness like molasses . t : if the weakness is the aroma , the strong point is it 's flavor . its like drinking a cup of mixed herbs and spices with some tropical fruit .  appearance - pours a pitch black color with a 3 finger dark brown sugar colored head with real nice retention .  mouthfeel : no real aftertaste ( remarkable for a malt-heavy beer ) , carbonation is excellent and it plays well on the palate .

the complexity is through the roof , the balance is perfect . and it just smells so quality . coffee and roasted nuts as well as chocolate , caramel , and molasses , still with decent hop bitterness . nice ! i really enjoyed drinking this , and i really wish we could get it locally .  appearance- beautiful two finger head .  mouth feel is great . a beer to sip on a cold night .

nose is delicious , really quite extraordinary , giving that lovely oaky vanillin american stout character of coconut sweetness , obviously without the straight oak . it 's a phenomenal nose . so full , so complex and so incredibly luscious and delicious . i 've rarely had better . taste is smooth and full , and again extremely well mingled between the sweetness of coconut and chocolate , and the slightly more astringent roastiness . overall , a fantastic beer , and a wonderful drinking experience .  this is a perfect looking ris .  mouthfeel : extremely smooth and crisp .

smell : again , in winter warmer fashion , the beer even smelled good . it smelled like nutmeg and cinnimon ( maybe , in hindsight , a little too strong in those categories .  a fine , steady stream of carbo rises within , making its way towards the healthy , billowy , white , mousse-like head . lacing is top-shelf !  m : exceptional . nice , full-bodied creamy / velvety texture with a low carbonation that provides just enough fizz to cleanse the palate before the next sip .

in the aroma , a faint fruitiness .  appearance- pours a large , fluffy 2 finger head that very slowly recedes into some nice clinging lace and a fluffy cap . the color is a nice red/brown and i am pretty impressed to see just a slight amount of bottle sediment .  mouthfeel is perfection , smooth , crisp , with just the right amount of carbonation ... and the tartness in the finish leaves you wanting to pour more of that big bottle .

the smell is faint and unremarkable . grain , corn , rice maybe ?  this beer poured into my pint glass absolutely beautifully . it was a brilliant , clear , amber color and the head pillowed over he rim of my glass like a thundercloud .  mouthfeel is very rich , smooth carbonation .

the smell is all hops .  not much head at first , however after setting the glass down the head flows down into the beer for an awesomely presentable beer . color is almost black with a dark head .  just phenomenally satiny . in the mouth : satin , silk , creamy , smoothness embodied in liquid .

big peat and smoke that many american versions skimp on . excellent . m/d : a big full body that is low on the carbonation . incredibly smooth , creamy , and decadent . this is really exceptional . maybe the best american version of a wee heavy i have come across ( founders backwards bastard is the only other that comes to mind ) .  big substantial head . nice reddish-brown color .  the mouthfeel is outstanding . very creamy and smooth , but with active carbonation as well .

the aroma is simple , but robust and immensely enjoyable . the flavor is nicely balanced and brings out the best in the coffee .  poofy head unceasing and belgian in quality , this is a gorgeous looking light-colored ale . give this to someone drinking bmc just to watch their face pucker up .  mouthfeel is fantastic , super thick and syrupy , perfect for the style .

smells fresh , and inviting . appearance : painfully clear pale yellow , almost white , with a nice fluffy white head kept alive by moderate carbonation flavor : well , the hops come through loud and clear , but the fruitiness is very subdued , a minor note in a busy taste .  this beer was very attractive with its thick head and red color . it felt as smooth as it looked , which was delightful .  quite nice mouthfeel on this brew , very soft brew .

pumpkin walks hand in hand with musty malt down the spooky nasal alley , when out jumps sweet heady spices ; clove , nutmeg and cinnamon . the trio beat up the other two and leave them in a ditch . the haunting cries of cinnamon become more evident as this beer warms , as does the toastiness of the malt . o : great witches brew with a lot of soul .  bottled on 7-10-04 best before 7-10-09 a- pours a great looking , barely cloudy , luminescent liquid . it is a great golden color . this looks great in a duvel tulip .  rich , full , thick , round mouthfeel , with a soft carbonation that is really terrific .

the aroma was simply amazing . sweet and complex with strong notes of green raisins , dark fruits , figs and molasses . slightly woody and `` old . '' compared to the aroma , the taste was a bit of a letdown initially . brown sugar and molasses notes came through strong . raisins , prunes and dried figs were also quite apparent . this beer drank like a charm .  two-finger brown head on top settles quickly into a dense , creamy cap that has ridiculous retention . this one looks simply amazing .  an exquisite mouthfeel for a baltic porter .

the nose has become heavily and enjoyably influenced by the brett with a earthy hay scent . the yeast plays the biggest role of all and i 'm loving it . the taste is slightly more subdued as the earthy yeast tones seem to have recede as the hops and spices combine for a quick zip of flavor .  dark reddish-brown with a full light brown head , good carbonation , and sheets of lace .  full bodied with a great creamy mouthfeel .

smell is musty and damp , rubbery phenols and a hint of buttery diacetyl ! ! ? ?  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass . crystal clear pale gold color with a 1 '' firm , fluffy white head .  the mouthfeel was full and creamy with a light carbonation .

very well-mixed scent , an nice malt/hop combination . great taste ! goes down extremely smoothly for a hoppy beer .  appearance : pouring creates a swirly cloud of foam that looks like milk being poured into espresso , in beautiful , downward-moving cascades of soft , creamy bubbles . foam comes to rest in a luscious , impossibly dense and creamy almond-off-white head with incredible retention . a very , very attractive brew .  mouthfeel is perfect , thick and creamy but not too syrupy , and with none of that trub you sometimes get in the bottle , maybe im just not used to drinking from a tap .

really good . t : pumpkin pie and spice again .  pours a cloudy orange color , with small tints of yellow . the carbonation on this ipa is insane . thousands upon thousands of bubbles streaming upwards . the head was also unusual for an ipa , massive bubbly white head 2 inches thick .  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel and medium/full bodied .

s : smells very fruity : orange citrus , strawberries , kiwi , guava , mango , passionfruit , its like smelling a pack of tropical skittles , an unbelievable cornucopia of exotic fruitiness . the flavor isnt nearly as exciting as the aroma , but its still good . if skittles made a beer , it would be a lot like this one .  damn fine looking beer- translucent brown with rusty orange highlights and a kick-ass tan head .  thick and chewy with all the perfect elements . the real stand out for me was the mouthfeel .

estimated at 200 c purchased at : super saver pennington , nj for $ 3.00 aroma : amazing , chocolate , syrup , heather . visuals : beautiful design , deep brown , mostly opaque , thin white head , little lace . overall : a real disappointment , more of a brown ale than an imperial stout , not a repeat , not a favorite , little value , medium craft .  a : the beer is a deep dark brown color with a reddish hue , creates a dense , foamy , tan head that fades slowly and leaves a very thick lace on the glass .  this is the mouthfeel i yearn for in every brew o- very glad i got to sample this one and will most likely re-review it once i have more barleywine experience .

this is a pleasure to smell . dark earthy chocolate , booze , oak , breads , and subtle spices . sharp dark bitter chocolate flavors , creamy malts , bready , with a tart , crisp , biting and boozy finish . the alcohol is hidden pretty well for such a strong beer , it 's there , but it provide a nice warmth and balance to the malty sweetness .  excellent looking beer .  the light body is remarkable . it seems so very neutral which i figure is what makes this beer so very drinkable .

man , this stuff smells great . i think i 've been smelling it for 15 minutes now ... taste . starts out good , but there 's an herby , floral bitterness in the end which i did n't enjoy very much . after being one of the best smelling barleywines i 've come across , i was bummed to find that the taste did n't live up .  pours black as night with nice ruby highlights around the endges when held to the light , has a nice thick tan head .  perfect creamy texture and good body and carbonation .

s : roasted grains ... not much more . t : this is the best way to have your guinness . d : guinness on tap is always a good , safe choice and always beats out the bmc competition .  pretty much black , with nice darkish beige head , fluffy and dense with stunning lace . retains amazingly well . pretty damn close to looking perfect .  perfect consistency neither thick nor thin , but to silky to be described as simply `` medium '' .

beautiful fruity citrus aroma of hops . fresh and ripe .  absolutely gorgeous . bright polished-copper body streams bubbles to feed the large , light fluff of a head .  the mouthfeel is very smooth & silky . goes down very smoothly . nothing to improve on there , really .

floral bouquet of american hops . grapefruit and biscuit in flavor . the most striking part of this beer is the aroma . put your nose in a glass of liberty and enjoy . anchor liberty is still a beer to be revered .  pours a really beautiful , off white head . sticks around the entire time , leaves a substantial bit of lacing on the sides of the glass . color is golden amber , looks fairly well carbonated .  m : i do n't think i 've commented on the feel of a beer 's head before , but here goes ... super soft , silky , airy foam . the head has an ethereal , other-worldly feel ... tremendous . the beer itself is of light-medium body . soft and clean feel . d : definitely a quality brew and one you should seek out now , but i have to say it 's not one i 'd label as exceptional .

nose is amazing like crisp suger glazed perfectly ripe cherries .  the head is very nice , about 2 fingers high of medium tan heat that is just beautiful . it is full and creamy and lasts forever with nice lacing .  carbonation is comfortable and helps the round mouthfeel to build an authentically belgian mouthfeel .

huge aromas with clove , banana and bubble gum on the nose . all these show up on the tongue as well . there is a ghostly chocolateness floating in the distance .  pours a huge tan head , with nice retention throughout and good lacing . very dark brown in color with lots of carbonation smells of roast copper malt and some sweet toffee .  mouthfeel - super smooth and silky . low carbonation and a big body .

immediately after opening the bottle , a strong chocolate smell emerges .  a very large billowy head follows the pour . holding this up to the light , you get a unique pale yellow with all kinds of bubble action . the frothiness is very white and has excellent retention .  appearance : in between brown and black , boasts mocha colored beautiful head , constant bubbling , displays real `` activity '' smell : pretty standard of a lighter stout , slight coffee , chocolate , and malt aromas taste : subtle chocolate flavor and very smooth mouthfeel : very smooth and creamy , excellent finish drinkability : very drinkable , has good flavor and excellent mouthfeel i 'd recommend this beer , especially if mixed with a back road brewery blueberry ale .

smell is n't remarkable and nothing really sticks out . there 's better stouts but this is n't bad .  pours a bright amber color , with an awesome head . great looking ipa .  rich , creamy , and smooth mouthfeel . a bit of alcohol bite , and an excellent overall russian imperial stout .
the aroma is wonderful , which was my favorite aspect of the beer .  a- a brilliant copper color , this is a very nice looking beer .  light-medium in body .

s : this smells right one the balance of the bourbon , chocolate , and vanilla bean are perfect . the nose on this is really inviting , there 's trace of any off aromas you sometimes get that overpower what trying to be represented . the bourbon is really tame in this one , its lending a nice charred backbone that helps to really life the vanilla to the front .  a 22 oz bottle picked up while in illinois this one pours a black body and medium tan head . a really nice head with lacing and very foamy .  the body is medium with one of the finest , creamiest , super fuzzifyingly , silky-slippery-zippery carbonations i have ever encountered .

easily the best pumpkin beer , ever ? mayhaps . but the aroma ... oh my lord , the aroma . this is awesome . this is everything aroma in a beer can be . the taste is almost as shocking as the appearance in how it comes across ( frankly , after the aroma , a deep , hazy , dark brown color would have been my guess if i had n't seen it first ) . it 's a pleasing and easy drinking experience .  appearance : guinness is the archetype for stout , especially in appearance .  this is an interesting brew indeed ... the main feature is the exceptional mouthfeel ... blindfolded i would have expected this to be a very good sparkling wine ( if not a standard champagne ... ) ... smell and taste however lack a bit of outlines and aromas ... on overall i would say this is a very noble brew , which needs a bit of connoisseur spirit ... .

but , geeeez , what a wonderful aroma lurks underneath the mess . tangerine and grapefruit along with rock candy and toffee . pears and apples , raisinbread , and a meadow of wildflowers add to the divine nose . mouthfeel lacks carbonation ( it must be on top ) , but is medium bodied and has a unique fruity apple hops bite . taste is well balanced and very complex . much of the aroma is reflected in the taste , so i will simply say that this is one unique pale ale .  bottle into tulip . pours deep brown to black , with a beautiful , creamy , dense tan half-inch head on top with amazing , solid walls of lacing . beautiful from top to bottom .  mouthfeel is damn perfect for a pils .

smell- glorious . if you took all the best smells in the world and combined them , this is what you would get . fruity and peppery , along with a little hoppiness . malty , but it 's the mix of fruit and peppers that i really notice . drinkability- excellent !  appearance : pitch black body with a tall , dense , pile of brown foam on top . great lacing . perfect !  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and coating , leading to an extended finish that eventually coaxes out some espresso and a final touch of nuttiness .

a good solid swirl leaves a thick , oily sheet along the sides of the glass . hugely complex nose with chocolate , smoke , vanilla , earth , pine , citrus , and licorice .  nice head and great retention .  the mouthfeel is amazing - as good as don de dieu .

s - really really appetizing . i do n't know what rutabaga smells like , but for some reason that word pops into my head when i sniff this brew . just delicious and creamy .  the pour produced a clear ruby/mahogany color that was beautiful and reminiscent of a dark scotch .  thick chewy mouthfeel that coats the entire tongue and a little burn as it warms .

awesome aroma . pine and citrus , candied orange , grapefruit , resiny , fresh hops . for such a great aroma the taste is very dull . d - very strange combination . everything great about the aroma just disappears .  pours a ruddy dull deep reddish brown , minor coffee colored head .  m - thick and velvety ; very pleasant . for a ris , this is just about perfect . coats the mouth and then recedes without overstaying its welcome .

the aroma was delicious , full of pineapple , citrus hops , floral hops , tropical fruit esters and a little alcohol . the complexity of chinook , columbus and especially the citrusy simcoe hops was quite enjoyable . the mouthfeel was semi-smooth , the body medium and the carbonation medium as well .  yards extra special ale ... .out of the yards variety pack appearance-pours copper red , a small two finger head fizzes and goes with relative ease , ok clarity , this beer is clearly not as carbonated as other yards ' releases . overall-a passable bitter , better as it warms , very malty as it should be , nothing of the style that leaps out and wows me but a very solid attempt at the style , another solid part of the variety pack .  very nice .

fruity aroma - awesome aroma ! smells just like a small brewery .  pours a light hazy golden color with a small , lingering head .  medium body with a wonderful rich texture that is soothing in the mouth . just enough carbonation to keep things lively .

big aroma of spearmint , grapefruit , lime zest , and wild flowers from the hops ... hint of bready caramel malt and esters in the back . hoppy after taste with a fume of alcohol . this beer has a full on grasp of the style , a great beer all around .  this bottle was bought sometime during the summer of 2005 ... a carefully decanted pour into my la moneuse tulip raises a slight glass ring for a head , no more . the body is a murky ruby brown that is utterly opaque in the center .  m - getting better , as advertised it 's super smooth . lovely and creamy .

brett funk t : very tannic . overall a very very good beer .  i got no head on this pour , that made me a little sad . o- other than how this looks ( lack of head ) this is a world class porter .  the body is amazing and really makes this beer absolutely stunning to go along with its big hoppy flavors . it 's oily , greasy , beefy , big bodied , and largely bold , with a crunchy , grabbing , snappy , zip line long bittering tone of a ton of orange oils and pine oils .

smell is absolutely fantastic ! ! lots and lots of bright , fresh fruity smells .  a trace light in color for the style , but it has decent head retention and a nice fruity/malty nose and palate .  amazing balance in this beer . mouthfeel is full , and this is very drinkable .

the aroma was very malty and sweet .  tequila-esque bottle , bought at the total wine in glendale , az , a : pours a muddy burnt orange . no head no bubbles , like a liqueur .  mouthfeel is medium and very smooth with the perfect level of carbonation .

aroma - monstrous amounts of roastedness , wonderfully intense coffee and chocolate syrup . a heady layer of alcohol floats underneath it all , pushing the flavors , enhancing them .  not familiar with helles bocks so take this with a grain of salt . i might say more about the nose if i knew the style better . nothing wildly distinctive about the flavor , nothing that calls out to the palate , except for good balance between hops and malty-ness .  the mouthfeel is excellent . nice body with a smooth finish .

quite a unique and pleasing odor . tastes very hoppy , with strong floral hops that give off a spicy taste , piney hops , sweet malt , caramel , grass , flowers , orange peel , grapefruit , apple , brown sugar , pepper and spices .  pours dark brown with a slight tan head .  m : mouthfeel is very nice .

smell - not too strong . faint smell of cinnamon and nutmeg . taste - the smell of the cinnamon and nutmeg definitely are the most powerful flavors in the beer .  a : this poured a cloudy light straw color with quickly dissipating white head .  smooth creamy mouthfeel , it 's a satisfying brew for my palate . very good stuff .

s : lemon and melon aromas with some sort of unpleasantness ( bathroom ? ) t : chalky , zesty , light phenols , slightly minty , mineral-like .  pours a clear light gold with a bunch of little floaties from the bottle conditioning . not the best looker .  m - perfect carbonation .

s-the smell of this beer is amazing ! having had perseguidor 3 , i would say this is the only trait that is better in 4 . insanely complex nose , smells of wood , funk , dried fruit , chestnuts and roasted malt . truely exceptional . there is virtually no stout flavor , i tastes similar to an old bruin , but thiner and less acidic , a sipper to be sure do to the tartness , but very tasty . d-another great offering in this series , captain ron is a master at blending his styles .  2005 bottle , fun graphics , from spiritus fermenti amber and red body , looks prety nice but poor head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is really very rich : like a good stout on the palate , smooth and full , thick and chewy , but it 's got that pilsner crispness .

i love that as soon as i removed the crown of this beer the aroma of brett seemed to permeate the kitchen , and then the house as soon i poured this in a glass . the aroma really explodes with brett , but i also get a bit of lactic notes and a slight tinge peppery leather . the flavor here is the low point on this beer , as the aroma can not be topped and it really looks amazing .  two finger white head with average retention . leaves very little lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel on this beer is superb . very creamy with subdued carbonation and a medium body .

super strong and good smell , maybe the best unibroue smell i 've ever had . t : biscuit malt and tart pretty much dominate . super disappointing after the great smell of the beer .  drinking pretty darn good right out of the bottle . murky brown color . nose is slightly sweet , burbon with a super thin head .  its awesome ! as smooth and creamy as you can get . an absolute delight for the tongue !

the nose is super fresh and fruity , floral hops and mango . there 's a nice roasty finish that just seals the deal for me .  it poured golden with about a half inch of stark white head that quickly dissolved into a light lacing on the surface . light carbination could be seen rising from the very bottom to the surface .  mf : silky and smooth but without compromising its thickness , which is needed as a foundation for the abundance of flavour . not too wet or dry , but the perfect balance between . not a unique mouthfeel , but an expressive suitable one .

s- very fresh pale cereal grains and fruity floral pineapple and fruit blossom aroma . i appreciate pilseners with ale complexities . t- very crisp and perfectly bittered and balanced .  this beer had a brown/deep copper color with a thin off white head .  a pleasant crispness from the hops and the smoothness and creaminess make for a great mouthfeel and extreme drinkability .

grainy smell , along with yeast and slightly grassy .  dark brown color where light shines through ... barely . solid two-finger finger that dissipates slowly and leaves nearly no lace mild aroma of soft semi-sweet chocolate ; reminds me of fudgesickle .  the mouthfeel is super thick , and coats the mouth and lips .

smells fucking amazing . giant sticky hops , pineapples , roses , and marijuana . like mixing centennial and cascade hold them up to your nose and breathing deep . tastes good . very good . the hops are more aromatic than anything , and the smell serves to blot out much of the amazingly sweet maple syrup malt that takes over most of the start and lasts throughout the middle .  a- by the looks of it , it does n't look like much . above average lacing .  m : so so so smooth and soft .

a great smelling beer , the best i have smelled for an old ale so far . t : dark dark plums , moderate acidity , spicy alcohol , and more bitterness than i expected . tame the alcohol a little and it would be heavenly .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a deep amber color with an almost non-existant head .  the mouthfeel was amazing , drinking the beer it had the typical bite of aftertaste that normal ipas have , but i took a drink right when we left the pub and i still could taste the hops about twenty minutes later .
the nose is pretty subdued .  poured a slightly hazy gold . average white head .  the body is perfect . honestly .

the aroma is strong . there is a lot of dark fruit , caramel , flowers , oak , and the right amount of bourbon . once i get used to that i can detect caramel , more bourbon than there is in the aroma , not as many floral notes , more oak , no fruit . i like this taste , but it is nowhere near as harmonious as the aroma . the mouthfeel is full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture . very nice feel . unfortunately , whereas the aroma is a harmonious blend of strong smells , the taste is a bunch of in-your-face flavors that work together but have no real grace .  bottle poured into a pub pint glass , cloudy dark red in color with a small , tan head .  mouthfeel/drinkability- just when i thought the perfect mouthfeel of a belgian ale was locked up with tripel karmeliet , this beer dazzles with a sublime , gentle texture that lasts throughout the entire duration in the mouth . absolute perfection , it further emphasizes the already impressive quality of the beer .

what a nose . a stalwart exemplar of everything gueuze . all those wonderful , musty earthy , funky characters are powerful , unique and rich . a truly phenomenal gueuze nose . excellent sharp sour entry , very acidic . this is an exceptionally good gueuze , full of funk , acidity and character , but staying crisp and drinkable .  2 finger head that reduces to a thin crown , lacing is pretty much non existent .  mouthfeel is dead perfect for the style , full and solid .

this stuff smells incredible , the fresh coffee and sweet dark fruit work so well together . finishes with a lasting coffee flavor , very nice . mouthfeel is medium bodied and oily , but thin and fairly flat .  vigorous pour reveals only minimal head , which dissipates .  m : as great as the bottle was , as you can expect , the nitro-tap was a homerun . so incredibly smooth and creamy , one of the best mouthfeels i 've had .

smell : faint grassy aroma . nothing too pronounced .  a- great clarity in a very red copper beer with a little carbonation bubbles . almost no head , just a thin white film .  palate- chocolate milk with some espresso , toffee and campari bitterness , a touch of winy acidity , and a very creamy mouthfeel .

s - smells of faded citrus hops and faded pine . very weak and lacking . a major step up from the nose . m - medium body and low carbonation .  poured a much oranger color than i expected -- not too different from the color of their twilight ale -- closer to an amber than a traditional brown ale . very nice initial khaki head , but it dissipated to almost nothing -- a thin ring leaving some tiny sudsy bubbles on the glass but no lacing .  m : wow , this beer has one of the best mouthfeels i have experienced .

from the bubbles emanate a glorious woodfire aroma that dominates , without obscuring , sweet roasty malts . oh man , that smells good and oh boy does that taste good .  now this is a strange beer . very light in color slightly hazy and pale orangey yellow in color . after a few more sips , a light bulb turns on above my head and i finally realize what this tastes like a gin and tonic .  mouthfeel was great , pretty drinkable , but not that high of abv for a stout .

i popped the top off , and right away i got a whiff of skunk , disgusting .  pours a coppery gold with a white head that disappears in a hurry .  taste is also quite yeasty , lemon zest as well , the carbonation is bubbly and soft , not harsh , incredibly creamy and smooth for a hefeweizen .

exceptional aroma makes my head spin with all the hoppiness : foresty pine ( simcoe ? ) , grapefruit zest , sugared pineapple chunks , fresh grass -- it 's all in there , and it 's all insanely enticing . tea leaves hit the palate first , throwing me into more of an english ipa mindset . overall , red racer is an immensely enjoyable , drinkable brew .  pours a small white head with a clear orange body and fair lacing .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a doppelbock .

the aroma was awful , reminded me of a gym bag , kind of no wait very gross .  somewhat dark amber bodied brew , two finger cream head ends up disappearing without much lacing . nothing amazing here , but its a pretty nice light beer that would be nice to have during a nice hot day .  m : very smooth , sticky , and thick . light to medium carbonation .

smell is of vanilla , brown sugar , light tartness , caramel , notes of cherries and raisins . taste is of the aromas but a definite drop from the excellent nose with the cherry note becoming more evident in the mix .  12oz bottle poured into a guinness pint - fridge - 2009 appearance : a twist off cap whispers as i crack it . the beer pours a brown color with red highlights . a 1/2 '' light yellow/ivory head surfaces and shows a little bit of retention . not much lace left behind .  m : i must say , this beer feels great in my mouth .

pineapple , mango , wheat , yeast , flowers , toasted grains , very sweet smelling , lots of resin , alcohol is n't very high but you can smell it t - the taste is a more pungent form of the smell . there is a toastedness at the end as well m - sticky , coats the mouth in sweet , bitter fruit flowers that last for a while , so does the resin d - for being 8 % it 's pretty nice and balanced . there is tons of hops and tons of malt . despite that , it is still very balanced final thought - $ 9.49 is way to much . but it is excellent !  a quarter inch of tan head makes a hasty exit as soon as i finish pouring , leaving no trace behind .  bready yeast also comes across the nose t : again sweet sugar , yeast , dark fruit like notes of raisin or prune , just a hint of the kirek in the backgorund m : mouthfeel is super smooth . beer has a medium body and nice carbonation . finishes extremely clean .

off aromas , an odd sense of faint white vinegar and ammonia . theres just not enough here ( and the smell was not pleasant ) for me to say that i would ever drink this beer again .  poured into a pint glass pours an amber orange with a minimal head that leaves no lace on the glass .  very tasty indeed mouthfeel was very alive great carbonation with it 's light in the ass body and a very easy drinkability can enjoy anytime of the year .

the orange peel and candied sugar aroma was quite intriguing . the flavors were dominated by the sugar sweetness , hints of the alcohol , and that crisp glbc house flavor ( pilsner malts ?  pours a clear burnt orange with a mist of big floaties , half inch of clingy foam .  mouthfeel is wonderful . creamy with smooth carbonation .

low amount of head and a carb laced ring around the snifter where i got this one at pickled pig pub in rohoboth . s- bright floral notes with grapefruit and piney wood . t- as per usual smell leads into taste with a sweet caramel big body forefront and earthy grapefruit hops ( hallertau ? ) massive hop aftertaste which i love balancing out the massive malt bill m/d- lovely .  wonderful farmyard stench and strawberries , some public toilet smells ( but in a good way ) .  thick , syrupy and silky smooth with just enough carbonation to tickle the tongue . goes down so easily - incredibly smooth .

smell is gorgeous . the look of the brew is light not too murky .  golden and murky , with a rapidly dissipating head the smell is typical of wheat beers ; bready and mild fruit notes .  first thing i notice when drinking it is the fabulous mouthfeel - so soft and creamy yet a rather thin body .

smells absolutely fantastic . super-hop odor with sugary sweetness too .  a : pours a very dark brown with a two-finger light brown head with poor retention but sticks around on the edges .  light carbonation and great coating mouthfeel . d- yes .

the smell was my favorite part of the brew . lots of vanillia sweetness up front blending nicely with dark rich coffee and dark chocolate . taste was much like the smell . the vanillia added a sweetness to it that i really enjoyed . great balance though with the coffee slick mouthfeel , full bodied  colour is yellow ; the liquid got some chill haze . the high head is off-white , firm and compact .  mouthfeel is the star of this show -- thick , rich , round , full , all very slurpalicious .

i 've never smelt a beer like this before and really enjoyed it .  i had this beer poured from a bottle into a goblet ... a : the beer pours a pitch black color with a small wimpy tan head ... s : the smell is hoppy , strong c-hops to be sure ... t : wow .  m : great mouthfeel , one of the first things i noticed after drinking . it really coats the mouth .

smelled of mild blackberry as expected with a bit of apple scent , kind of alot like sweet juice with a bit of mild earthy hop hiding in there .  a- large bubbly tan head sits atop a very dark brownish red beer , it is almost black .  mouthfeel was exceptional with just the right amount of body .

very faint citrusy aroma .  a - fairly clear medium brown , not much head at all . nada on the lace .  the cherry tartness and barrel-aging really do some nice things here , and combine for a wondrous mouthfeel .

pine , earth , grapefruit , lemon , orange , touches of coriander and spice , straw , various golden grains , and a bouquet of floral aromas all great the nose in the most appealing thing i 've encountered in some time . mouthfeel is spot on ; crisp and light on the tongue , a refreshing , invigorating swallow , and clean finish . overall , this is much more hopped than i would expect an apa to be ( i think this is more aptly labled an ipa ) . regardless of how it 's labeled , however , this is a damn fine beer that deserves recognition .  a : muddy reddish-brown body with a half in chi of coarse tan foam . ok , but uninspiring .  ( m ) - really smooth and creamy . the carbonation has subdued to a really nice level that balances it out to a totally silky beverage .

the aroma was just amazing - sweet kandi and floral elements i can only assume were from the hops .  appearance is really nothing too special , particularly . below average head , golden straw color .  stellar mouthfeel .

the smell is exactly the same as a pumpkin pie coming out of the oven ; it 's not so much a question of the spices associated with autumn , i detected an actual baked pumpkin aroma .  pours a cloudy gold with a small head .  smells great , coffee and chocolate notes right up front chocolate & coffee flavors , dry and bittering at the end mouthfeel is very smooth . much smoother than i remember when i had it last .

i have no idea what to rate the look ... rich caramel and honey aroma , with hints of aniseed and sweet licorice ( yes they are different ) . it has an amazing aroma , and big characteristics about it , but the bitterness from the hops just leaves a really , really strong taste in the back of my mouth . definently worth it for something incredibly unique .  appearance : pours a bright cloudy amber color with just a layer of off white head .  the palate has great carbonation interlaced with a strong , dark malt profile with well integrated hops .

wonderful hop and caramel aroma that i enjoy so much i could use it as an air freshener in my house .  a : pours deep dark brownish black hue . there was no head , no carbonation , and no lace .  the mouthfeel is wonderful for a beer that is this bitter .
this smells simply phenomenal with its myriad of odors .  fraoch is a light amber ale with a bubbly white head that mostly diminishes .  extremely thick mouthfeel .

beautiful fruity citrus orange hop aroma !  the body is opaque topped with a tan head of small bubbles . little retention and lace .  good with food , good standing alone , and a wonderful , creamy mouthfeel when on tap .

love the aromas . sweet tropical fruits and florals . a little malt as well .  the appearence seems a little dark to be a pale ale as it is classified . it starts with a barrage of fruity flavors , then a bomb of beautiful hops . an excelent beer to drink on college football saturday .  it is very smooth with a nice medium to full body . i was most impressed with the mouthfeel . every part of your mouth will be involved in the feel of this beer as it awakens all your nerves right down your throat .

it honestly almost smells like a pasta i have had once at la madeline , very nice . t : again i am getting the basil and spices that i got in the smell .  spritzy light white head that basically surrenders . unfortunately , to be consistent with other rankings i 'd have to say the appearance is rather lackluster and drags down an otherwise solid brew .  mouthfeel is great . really nice body .

it gave off a nice hoppy aroma with some hints of pine and floral notes .  pours a dark chestnut brown . not much head from this pour .  has good slight citrus notes with a full hop oil and hoppy feel and body , a good finish mouthfeel- very very smooth , it has an extremely soft and smooth body that really helps it going down , the mouthfeel is a real strong point of this beer drinkability- a very good beer that i would definitely want to try few more times and see how it matches up with some other ipa s certainly worth another look .

this stuff smells great . decent frothy head . deep winter beer red color . love the smell , the taste is n't impressive .  a- 1 finger deep tan head . it doesnt stick around very long . the beer is a really dark brown thats just about black .  absolutely perfect . drinkability is very high as well . even , balanced flavors with that great mouthfeel make for a nice combination .

very strong fruity aroma ... possibly bananas , from the onset throughout the entire bottle .  12oz brown bottle , i really dig the graphics on this one . quite frankly im a bit too eager to drink the bastard to look very hard , though . not as opaque as i had expect , looks like a decent ipa . a very clear burnt orange with just a hint of amber . not a whole lot of bubbles coming from the bottom of the glass , but theyre definitely there . not a whole lot of lacing action , but there is some . the amber is almost an afterthought .  body and carbonation are perfect for the style .
almost perfect balance on the nose .  pours a deep hazy brown with a thin quickly dissipating tan head .  superb medium body with just the right balance of cream and carbonation .

immense citric notes of pineapple , orange , & grapefruit overflowing from this beer . candied ginger & spicy yeast perfume along thanks to the alcohol .  a - dark ruby red color , black as night in the glass . nice mocha head , that disapears much to quickly .  m : super creamy mouthfeel . damn this is smooth .

aromas of sour cherries , malt vinegar and rhubarb come across very strongly with subtle notes of vanilla and rich chocolate fudge ( likely from the oak ) in the background . as it continues to warm , i pick up some definite cheese aromas as well ( fresh gorgonzola comes to mind ) .  the beer is a hazy pale golden color , not quite as cloudy as some wits i 've seen . head was about 2 and a half fingers thick and pure white with poor retention .  mouthfeel is creamy , perfect for this style .

bland aroma with very faint earthy hops along with a pale malt presence .  a - real dark brown/almost black body with a couple bubbles but not much in the way of a head .  the mouthfeel is unlike anything i can recall in recent memory . such a thick creamy texture like i 'm drinking thickness of marshmallow cream with the weight of a large marble .

no mountains of bubbles , and a low low carbonation factor in the body smells yeasty , with a sour citrus tinge.. very much like a gueuze . very different , unique aroma for a beer of this style . what a shock after the delicious nose . lemon , butter , yeast and malt . nothing impressive here .  very pretty . clear .  thick consistently , but again not overly sweet . very good beer . hides the alcohol well and drinks smooth .

smell is of fruit , and roasted carmels .  on the back label is a somewhat disturbing picture of a drunk german man pointing at his stein . deep copper hue , very clear with a head that disappears quickly , i guess the more this ages the more the head takes a hit .  the mouthfeel is exceptional -- thick , chewy , syrupy , andincredibly smooth .

tough soapy and sticky white head hangs onto the glass and aroma is piney and deep resin with sticky citrus , sweet orange oils and a light alcohol grand marnier like finish . overall an excellent example of the style that would drive most of the drinking public running towards the nearest case of keystone .  a-amber color , no head retention , not perfectly clear s- big time biscuit and victory malts with some hop aroma , some caramel aroma , slight roast aroma , slight smoke aroma t- big malty and balanced with nice hops .  m- great carbonation , perfect balance .

faint malty nose . flavor reminds me of honey cough syrup .  the beer poured a cloudy golden/honey color with only a finger of white head and only minimal lacing .  viscous , sludgy , creamy , and slick . pretty swell carbonation as well . more bubbly than expected .

smell - somewhat fresh and slightly fruity . oddly enough , the first thing i thought about while smelling this beer was a good cigar .  a-pours a dark brown much lighter at the edges with almost a orange/red tint . no head present at all .  there is nothing very `` complex '' about it , just a bitter hops taste and perfect mouthfeel . as mentioned , the mouthfeel for pale ale is perfect ... . perfect amount of carbonation and easy to pour .

the smell is fantastic . rich , sweet pumpkin pie aroma which is almost better than the real thing . spices of cinnamon and nutmeg balance well to make this the best beer i 've ever smelled . t : i wish i had the same enthusiasm for the taste as the smell . it started off well enough , after the build of the beautiful sweet aroma , but it faded quickly for me after that . that being said , this beer had the best aroma that i 've ever smelled in a beer .  reviewed 2/3/2006 ( 750ml ) : pours a dark-reddish colored body , with a medium-sized white head , diminishing .  it possesses the best mouthfeel i 've yet to come across , rich and velvety , it just rolls over the palate and tongue , and goes down incredibly smooth .

the smell was fantastic . strong piney hops and woody resin . i would not turn this one down due to the wonderful nose .  the bartender poured this one into a glass for me , and it was a nice rich caramel color , but no head to speak of .  mouthfeel : best mouthfeel of any wit i 've ever had ; this has the milkshake-thick , smooth mouthfeels i 've heard described as ideal for the style .

highly aromatic with a very robust nose portaying notes of blackstrap . this has a salty , bittered char effect , but in a very pleasant way . oh , this is very nice to drink . looks like a big stout , smells like a big stout , tastes like a stout , but drinks like a porter .  unfortunately , little lacing is left as i drink .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . silky smooth .

a- choklat imperial stout pours jet black , no highlights with a small dark brown head . s- the aroma is the highlight of this beer i think . it smells unlike any other beer i 've ever had . the first thing i noticed was the huge chocolate presence in the aroma . but its not like a chocolate malt smell , it just smells like a candy bar or freshly baked chocolate dessert . there is a mild nuttiness in the aroma and maybe a little bit of hops hidden somewhere .  500ml bottle into wheat glass a : hazy straw color , high carbonation , good tall head , but does n't last long .  appearance - dark brown/eggplant color with some brown head smell - this one is faint , picking up hints of coffee , cocoa taste - wow , this is good , these flavors really burst , i 'm picking up dark chocolate , a bit of expresso and hazelnut mouthfeel - this is smooth and creamy , high amount of carbonation , medium to full bodied , flavors really linger on the palate in the aftertaste , no hint of booze at all drinkability - this is going down nice on a chilly night , for $ 1.89 a 500ml bottle , this is really good value .

in particular the genuine hoppy aroma ( i think i detected cascade hops amongst others ) , was sublime and a true feat for a new zealand microbrewery . big floral and herbal bouquet with some yeasty and grainy notes . there was also a sourness in the finish which was n't very appealing .  black like used diesel oil , head was small ( despite a pretty rough pour ) and brown , did n't last that long and left decent lace .  gentile mix of flavors , not super complex , but with an incredible silky mouthfeel , and an oragne glow that makes it look great .

nice big assertive citrus aroma heavy on the orange comes out of the bottle from across the table . delightfully drinkable .  a : dark copper amber , poured with a nice head that died to a thin collar .  m - wow . so creamy and light .

the scents are amazing ! i notice a woodsy , kind of floral or piney smell , with a great hoppy undertone . man this smells good . mouthfeel is definitely better than average for an ipa -- balanced , yet light , intricate nonetheless .  sort of ruby brown . no head , no lace .  this is a tasty beer ... m - a good thick and creamy full bodied beer ... d - a little expensive for my liking ; however , definitely something worth picking up if you have n't tried one before .

s : nice malty , hoppy aroma that seemed fitting for the seasonal .  a simple golden colored brew that is perfectly clear and bubbly . the head on the other hand is less than with a not very showy cream colored froth that seems to evaporate .  soft , creamy mouthfeel smothers my tongue with flavor .

smell : malty sweet , with rich dark fruits and nuttiness . very appealing . taste : malty and nutty , lightly sweet .  nothing special , just looks like the average stout .  awesome mouth feel . thick and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

very nice . t- the taste is kind of a let down after the great smell . the yeast comes through stronger than in the nose . d- a decent beer , especially for the price .  water vapors rising from it after and very aromatic of the tart cherries , mulling spices , and a little malt . color is maybe suffering as it 's got some brown in it - kind of a reddish brown .  the mouthfeel was awesome . just perfect subtle carbonation .

s : compared to elder this is much less piney , however has a much stronger fruity/citrus aroma . strong notes of various citrus , pineapple , and mango . strong fresh hop smell like no other . t : not quite as mind blowing as the aroma . flavor includes strong tropical fruit and candy notes .  pours a murky dishwater brown color , not much of a head - just some off-white with hints of brown .  the beer looks thick and chewy , but the texture is perfect for a brown ale .

s-very good . the smell of toasted grains hits you right off . traces of caramel , chocolate malts , as well as some grassy hops . t-not what it smelled like . very disappointing .  picked up a growler last night - poured into a pint glass - first brew from mad fox , i 'm excited . a - a slightly hazy light orange body . the head starts at about a finger of white foam that dies to a thin film that leave little lacing .  full frothy mouthfeel . incredibly smooth and easy to drink , yet still intense and full in flavor .

s : slightly sour , mixed-fruity aroma upfront -- sweetish lemony+tangerine , figs , melons , preserved pineapple , etc. , with a deeply , exotic fruity-perfumy nose which is so profound but not bursting , mixed well with an overwhelming candyish backdrop ( like chinese green-bean paste ) and `` floating '' floral hoppyness ... complex and simply sublime~~ t : a deep flow of candyish maltiness hits the palate first , followed by equally profound fig-dominated fruitiness laced with slightly sour citrusy flavour running deep ... the initially soft but sour texture gradually thickens , bringing out an intense fruity+floral hoppyness on top of a perfumy , yeasty taste , leaving warmish alcoholic mouthfeel down the tongue and a flow of dryish bitterness lingering towards the med-length finish with overwhelming aftertaste of sour-sweetish fruits and a touch of spice . medium-bodied and medium to full-flavoured tripel , it 's tasty enough but somehow falls short of the promise of the complex and evolving aroma ( quite like several other tripels , come to think of it ) . still a nice beer in its own right .  pours an effervescent caramel with some sand colored head . average lacing & head retention s : superb oaky bourbon notes , then a a whiff of dirt ?  mouthfeel is where this beer stands out -- it 's superbly balanced and dangerously more-ish .

appearance : pours a hazy copper body with a thick foamy light tan head smell : very ripe banana and dark fruit scent taste : like a concentrated hefeweizen .  while the idea of a four and a half year port barrel aged imperial stout with cherries and brett sure sounds intriguing , it 's actually one of the most godawful concoctions i 've ever imbibed . this might have been interesting minus the brett , but i have to wonder if this stuff was n't funked up due to some accidental infection . the yeast is all-consuming here , with an overwhelming funk that covers up any flavors the barrel , the fruit or the malt may have added . not an impressive beer .  t & m : mouthfeel is very creamy and enjoyable .

overall : the smell of this beer is fantastic , but the smokey taste and alcohol cover up all the delicate flavors .  average appearance . not much foam or retention to speak of . very brite beer , i was at least expecting some proteins or sediment to be in here . in these regards the appearance is very average .  mouthfeel : awesome ... .crisp , clean , enough of an aftertaste to seduce multiple sips . plain , yet glorious in its understated beauty .

s : rich , sweet , and slightly toasty caramel with a delicious spicy , floral hopping . on of my favorite noses of recent memory . very flavorful for 5.5 % . d : leaves me a bit underwhelmed ... i 'd rather have a dipa anyday .  opaque and dark with a thin ochre head . slight flash of brown ( which is n't very flashy ) when held up to the light .  it has a very soft and thick texture but it 's not weighty at all . a pleasure to the whole mouth .

it looks good enough , and has decent aroma but has terribly unbalanced flavour .  difficult getting a head . pours an attractive cherry brown .  exceptionally viscous and savory body starts creamy and full on the tongue , developing a wheaty wetness and light carbonation , ends dry .

) the smell is outstanding , not just for its magnitude but its spmlicity as well .  pours a deep amber with little head that quickly becomes a good lace . there is also visible carbonation bubbles and a quick swirl brings that nice head back .  m - this has a medium body and medium carbonation .

canned pumpkin and nutmeg . like other st big beers , a tremendous smelling beer . t : somewhat heavy on the spices and less on the actual pumpkin and earthy squash but the sweetness is far from artificial . maple syrup , graham crackers again which is fantastic . best way to describe the taste of this one is a well made pumpkin pancake .  a - a nice light amber color though it has very poor head retention s - smells like bananas !  i love the creamy texture and the suprising full body .

smell does not take one too far , but the taste is a bit more distinct , with hints of cherries and birch bark . does not finish particularly well , but holds the flavor in the mouth long enough to warrant another few sips .  pours a cloudy yellow .  a light bodied beer but incredibly smooth . leaves the palate feeling dry , making this an excellent strong summery beer .

interesting . t/m : this is really not an oktoberfest brew in my mind .  a - pours a clear amber with a decent white head .  m - thick and creamy , very full bodied . complemented by the right amount of carbonation .

excellent aroma of walking into a candy shop with the sweet smell of fresh chocolate and caramel in the air . finish was a little watery , but overall , a stout beer well worth drinking .  a - pours a dark copper or brown body with a two finger off white head . bright .  mouthfeel : a very creamy , very smooth ipa . carbonation is perfect . body is malty and medium-bodied , and aftertaste is mildly dry .

considering how bitchin ' the venom was , i wanted more a- deep amber with a thick creamy eggshell head s- smell was amazing ... .had a little more complexity than dfh 90 with with some etoh kick t- not as strong as the smell led me to believe .  brown bottle ; $ 1.79 for single bottle ; best before 09-14-05 , brewed on 04-14-05 pours a crystal clear golden-orange color with very little head that disappears quickly . absolutely no head retention .  mouthfeel is smooth and fantastic as is the drinkability .

the aroma is incredible ! i 'd heard that nelson sauvin smells almost wine-like , but this is amazing ! ( looking on the label , it actually says that . ) delicate , fruity , floral , this is a beautiful aroma hop .  kudos to great divide for creativity . anyhow , belgica pours a non-threatening pale gold ( like a lager ) , but the sweet and spicy floral notes are prominent and welcoming . with an outlying hint of citrus underneath .  it 's pretty full bodied and very smooth with a clean , dry finish .
