very clean . simple but nice .  very minimal head . pretty average looking .  very smooth and creamy on the palate .

for a fruit beer it is exceptional in smell . smell is of pure fresh blueberries .  a-a murky cola color with very little white head .  on the palate , this beer is nearly perfect with medium carbonation and a nice long bitter hops finish .

appearance : baby diarrhea or bilge water ( take your pick ) - either is unappealing to drink ; but big beautiful beige head compensates a little smell : yeasty , bready , faint hops , very pleasant , possibly the strong point of the brew flavor : the clean , crisp apple-like quality of the flavor of a typical hefewiezen is masked by molasses in this dunkel .  pours an opaque light yellow with not much head to speak of .  mouthfeel is absolutely spot on .

s : honey , holiday spice , and cherries . the smell of christmas . d : great winter beer .  in a pint glass the beer was a hazy apricot color with a small white head . not very visually appealing .  one hell of a mouthfeel with this beer .

bomber at mad mex in pittsburgh ... a- deep golden color with a nicely carbonated head but not much lace left in the glass s- big , fresh hop aroma ! mf- lots of carbonation and slightly oily d- the bomber was plenty . i was n't big on the bitter finish - if you like earthy hop flavors , this is your beer .  pours a very thin , beige head after the pour . but very quickly recedes . the color is the best part of the appearance of this beer .  mouthfeel is divine , creamy and a velvet finish .

very nutty aroma with some surprising chocolate smells . t : caramel malts with some surfacing hops that balance the sweetness nicely . o : very good , i only had a single 19 oz .  very clear thin yellow . low fizz , but a decent looking fluffy little white head .  felt great , and was easy to drink .

nose is strong , intense , dark fruits about to rot which someone spilt port wine upon - wonderful , very interesting . full bodied chewy mouthfeel . i 've no idea what the six herbs and spices are but i applaud the choices , excellent complexity . phenols can be the bane of a belgian , here they are aggressively , exquisitely blended .  poured from a 12oz bottle into a tulip pint glass a : not terribly impressive to look at , at least not compared with many of the other ipas i 've seen/drank of late . pale , golden yellowish in color , very little head , though nice lacing . s : considering the appearance of this beer , the scents are more of the malted biscuit variety , without a lot of the obvious hop presence coming forth .  m ) rich , almost slick . rich , long mouth coating .

the scent of this beer has spilled all over me and it is pretty good . the fruits range from grapey to tropical to lemon citrus , a great smell on this one . this is very good belgian craft , love it .  this beer has an excellent ruby red/maroon color to it . it has no head whatsoever except for a few lingering bubbles around the edges .  mouthfeel is surprisingly smooth and creamy for such a sweet beverage . very nice .

open bottle and pour into glass and immediately catch the great aroma . pours a nice , lightly hazed , dark orange , with a decent head , leaves great lacing on the glass . this beer has an incredible aroma , a great , bright , hops/citrus/grapefruit/floral smell , very strong , but not too much for the style . great hop dominated flavor , with a decent malt backbone to support the hops , very nice . leaves a nice hop aftertaste , not too bitter though .  the widmer hefeweizen pours a slightly hazy light gold color and comes with that light citrus aroma you get with most hefs .  medium bodied and creamy smooth , the carbonation was really kept in check leading to the great texture .

s- super funky , nose hair curling , acidic vinegar . amazing . past the sourness is an amazing plethora of red wine , green apples , sour cherries , oak , berries , lemon , sweet grapes , more oak . smells amazing . t- not as tart as the nose suggests , but sour as shit nonetheless . o- another amazing sour from avery .  poured into a tulip . the beer pours like a big solidmass of oily black with no head . no head means no lace .  mouthfeel is exceptional and there is nothing objectionable here .

smells incredibly delicious . taste reflects the smell up front ; vanilla .  a : a lot browner than i expected . actually , more like a deep copper , with very few red tones if any at all . tiny rim of head , with not much lacing to speak of .  love it.5.0 d fair plus drinkability as this is a huge beer , one that i could probably only have one of .

s- rich and malty backbone with some fresh , citrus-and-pine hops thrown in the add to the lovely bouquet of malt , honey , caramel , faint metal , a hont of peat , grapefruit , grape , barley , white bread ... excellent aroma . t- the malt character and hops are well-balanced and enjoyable , and there is a slight caramel tinge to the malt flavor . d- very good . i could have several .  this beer poured a clear copper color with a thin head that dissipated quickly .  body is big and very creamy and smooth . mouthfeel of melted velvet .

nice , but not excessive , lacing all the way down the glass . smell : light yeasty aroma , with a belgian spiciness and sweetness . very smooth nose , without being overly mild or harsh . the look and the smell are amazing , but the taste is only just above average .  white , frothy head dissipates cleanly .  luscious creamy mouthfeel .

had this 4 weeks ago , putting down what my notes are heard only good things bout ' this hefe so i gave er ' a go . a- nice hazy yellow-gold color with white head s- smells great i give this beer that ! t- found this beer very tasty buttt the taste at the end/aftertaste was kind of crazy intense to me like a reallly wheaty clove taste .  appearance : pours a light amber with a soapy looking head that fades fairly quick . no lacing .  it is a very crisp mouthfeel , perfect carbonation .

served in the trusty karmeliet goblet , which shows off a good head and allows for good aromatics to form . s : the coriander and citrus aromas are there , but the coriander has a dull edge to it , missing the crisp wheat zing one can find in a wit beer . no hop aroma present .  appearance - 3.0 pours a finger of loose beige head that gradually reduces over a clear , dark reddish brown body . head retention is less than impressive .  the mouthfeel is full , warming and fabulous . flavor is full with lots of yummy esters holding hands with the sweetness and the fininsh is where i get the coriander .

absolutely decadent . the taste is not nearly as decadent but still very good . the oak really stands out as a great flavor here .  22oz bomber into 12oz mug a = once i opened it and saw thick , cloudy vapors pouring out i knew there were problems . tough pour .  the mouthfeel is full bodied with a silky texture , and low carbonation . overall , this is a really good dipa , but i would n't quite call it great .

s - coffee beans , liquorice , coal , raisins , cherry .  a - pours a clear copper / brown color . it does appear to be lighter in color than i would expect from an amber ale . got almost an inch of head that disappeared pretty quick .  its mouthfeel is incredible ; obviously this is enhanced by the nirto-tap . the positive was creating an amazing mouthfeel that fits perfectly with the style .

loads of coffee -- reminiscent of pch mortel , one of my all-time favourites -- and sweet , dark chocolate are utterly captivating . t : is there such a thing as too much coffee bitterness ?  yellow amber/brown color . maybe half inch head .  very creamy , smooth , and full bodied mouthfeel . this is definitely a stout that i could drink quite a lot of given it 's mild but good flavor and fantastic texture .

upon popping the cap of my first bottle of brrr ( before the pour even ) i was greeted with the splendid aroma of love , hop love . i knew this was going to be good ... clear antique copper color with nice creamy head and lace . simcoe ? very nice beer that drinks like an imperial red . wow widmer , you guys really surprised me with this one !  given the strength , this is very drinkable . colour is deep-red brown , not much head .  m : perfect ! coats the mouth great ... slightly creamy , with the right amount of carbonation to bring out the flavors .

smell : a punget bouquet of citrus ( orange , grapefruit ) and herbal ( wet grass ) hops comes together . taste : totally flat and boring ... .massive disappointment after loving the nose . mouthfeel : thin drinkability : too sad to have anymore .  a big thanks to tim ( sliverx ) for hooking me up with this . a-cooper amber cooler with very thin carbonation . thin head no lacing . reminds me of a great barleywine that ages well .  the mouthfeel is great . very thick and creamy with a gentle and soft carbonation .

there 's no hop aroma to speak of , so that fits with the english style , but there was a roasted , bready sort of smell .  pours a cloudy dark amber/copper with a small light tan head , good lacing .  m - smooth , a delicate sudsing that tickles the palatte , and quite refreshing with a subtle warming effect from the alcohol .

smells really quite nice , with a distinct bit of yeast , tea-like hop , and honey-cake malt sweetness - much more interesting than your average mexican lager .  it has the average golden color was the lowest point of fat tire .  palate : full bodied and medium carbonation . great feel . full bodied and enjoyable .

bottled on 9/12/02 sampled 2/19/04 aroma has slightly sour notes but it 's got a stale flat empty not good smell too .  a hazy golden colored brew with a faintly reddish-orange middle . one-finger of white head dissipates quickly into a thin sheet above the brew . there 's little to no lace to speak of .  medium/full body with an extremely creamy texture , assisted by the fine carbonation from the bottle conditioning .

s- smells delightful . i can smell the maple in the pour . very good .  appearance - the six pack i had was full of floating yeast , while this is basically harmless , i generally do n't enjoy things floating in my beer . the pour is a dark maize with a thick head that shrinks down to a nice lacing .  i bought this beer because some chi ba 's would n't shut up about this beer when the map room had it on tap . but as it warmed up the coffee bean aroma mixed with a creamy , roasted malt and noticeable hops . mouthfeel- good and creamy and malty . inky , oily and silky all at different intervals . just drinki the whole glass by itself and then eat myabe a chocolatey dessert .

s - aroma is near perfection . there is definitely some underlying jp funk in the beer with slight tart notes . the belgian aspect to this beer is awesome in the nose . hints of banana bread some cinnamon rolls and gingerbread . awesome nose . t & m - wow .  pours a pale copper color with a nice beige-colored head . after careful pour , lots of flaky particule suspension even with a small amount of yeast sediment left in the 33 cl bottle .  mouthfeel was exceptional .

tasted may 18th 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - pale amber , three finger white head and some serious lacing s - oily , alcohol , hops , hops and more hops ! sweet fruit , earthy flowers , sugar , yeast , sweet malts and awesomeness t - super hoppy !  poured a dark murky brown with a small head that turned to film rather quickly .  the mouthfeel is excellent . very smooth , with just a little effervescence that gives it a certain crispness . good taste and a perfect feel make this a very drinkable beer , but with the high alcohol content , you 're going to want to take it slow with this one .

s : this is one of the best smelling brews i 've come across in the summer ale category . i 'm not sure what kind of hops they added in the aroma portion of the brew , but it 's outstanding . unfortunately , it 's the best thing about this brew . t : really good . for a summer ale , it 's great .  a murky orange , not particularly attractive .  a semi-dry chalky exit that counterbalances the heavy malts quite nicely . i believe the heavenly mouthfeel has the most to do with this .

damn this is a good ipa . lots of citrus and flower with a hint of grain coming thru . t - nice full bodied ipa with tons of hop character . more towards the bitter side of ipas but its just what the doctor ordered .  appearance : cloudy . medium off white head .  mouthfeel - thick , smooth , well-carbonated . right on .

s : lovely perfume-like odor .  notes appearance : nothing too distinct here just a nice golden look .  m - refreshingly tingly , with a slow and steady rise in volume , ultimately becoming quite creamy and dense . very appealing .

wow this really has a lot going on in the aroma !  growler poured into a tulip . ( a ) - pours a clear rustic colored orange color that produced some white and transparent bubbles .  the mouthfeel is medium-full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture .

s - no lie , one of the best aromas on a beer , ever ! tons of resinous , sappy , piney hops along with pineapple , grapefruit and lemon . basically a massive fruit salad of smells ! t - juicy grapefruit and grassy , piney hops meld well with the doughy caramel malts . damn good beer !  had this beer several times this season , so had forgotten that i actually had n't gotten around to reviewing it ... a : poured with a small head that dissipated quickly to a thin film . no real lacing to speak of . body is an amber/brown color , and almost completely clear .  m : quite thick moderate carbonation , love it .

smell : this one has a fantastic scent to it . i 'm not sure if a brown ale could smell better than this . it 's very tasty and the smell is superb . nicely complex but still would make a fantastic session brew .  appearance : pours into glass a dark full brown color with a good sized tan that dissipated fairly quickly , not much in the way of lacing was left behind on the glass , smell : sour smell of fruits with a sweet/rich carmal-coco tosty smell , plesent aroma , taste : taste has some complex depth , slightly nutty , sour fruit taste balanced out with an engaging coca/malty flavor .  first sip reveals a silky smooth texture and very fine , rolling carbonation .

the aroma was amazing . smells like a perfect roast of coffee . also lemon zest and coffee bean aromas . overall , this beer is awesome . i really enjoyed this beer and i plan on buying more of it , if i can still find it .  pours a murky brown with a thin head .  burly , viscous , lusciously dextrinous mouthfeel . outstanding .

one of the best smelling beers i can remember . those citra hops really bring it on the nose . tons of tropical fruits . just great stuff . taste- follows the nose . it 's downright tart . however , it gets a little muddled . i had one and really wanted another . this is a very good beer .  average sized soapy white head that fades quickly to a ring over a very clear ( initially ) , golden body with plenty of carbonation flowing up . with 2nd and 3rd pour , it got considerably more cloudy with the yeast coming into play .  mouthfeel is awesome and is what makes this beer for me , this is a good tasting beer that is enhanced by a perfect creamy smooth feeling as it passes over my palate .

such good fresh tastes and aromas . great easy drinker , good session , could sit back with tons of these on a warm evening .  poured a clear , light amber color . a 1 1/2 inch white head formed and diminished quickly . looked very viscous . inspite of what looks like a beer with low carbonation , it has a really nice fizziness on the tongue .  silky , creamy , smooth mouthfeel , the hops are not overly bitter they 're well balanced with the malt . mild on the carbonation .

beautiful perfumed floral , spiced , orange and fresh peach assertive nose . mouthfeel is creamy and seemingly rich but with no character .  dark orange brew with some small particles in suspension and a fairly thin white head .  mouthfeel : chewy , full bodied . low carbonation , which suited the beer nicely .

the sulfur smell is almost unbearable and made me think this beer was spoiled . this sulfur smell is exactly like what we smelled when a batch of our beer got infected at the brewery i work at .  a - poured a deep orange with visible sediment and a thin tan head that settled quickly with minimal lacing .  love the feel in my mouth .

3.5 s mostly citrus and florals , but also grains & yeast , reminds me of saison more than ipa 3.5 t hmmm lemony floral and herbal bitterness , does not flow well and is a work in progress 2 m loads of carbonation is very excessive , light body , ill drain pour what is left in my glass 1 o drinkability is not good , difficult for me to believe that this would sell well in spain or the us , ill not buy this again nor would i recommend it 2  pours a cola brown with amber highlights and little head and bubbling .  just about perfect for me .

i love the dark coffee and chocolate aromas . toasted malts and rich deep chocolate fill the nose . i can detect a light hint of alcohol as well .  appearance : hazy golden brown . the beer had a very active head , intense carbonation that disappeared about 3/4ths the way through the beer . a small ring persisted , but did not lace the glass . some citric flavors come through as well , as the beer warmed , i noted an orange taste that was pleasing .  mf : smooth and silky , perfect for the style d : another delicious brew from one of the best breweries in the world !

incredibly balanced aromas . t - there are so many layers to this beer , each so definable .  kind of a murky rust color with a thin cream colored head that clings to the glass on its way down .  magnificent . drinkability is only average , as this is one once in awhile brew , not intended for or enjoyable on a regular basis .

the aroma is very weak and does not add anything to the experience .  pours with quite a bit of fizzy foam that settles quickly leaving little lace .  the mouthfeel is awsome , slick , thick and coating , perfect for a winter warmer .

smell - absolutely wonderful hops smell . its best qualities are appearance and wonderful aroma . taste and drinkability are a little challenging but tolerable .  pours a muddy , amber color . somewhat low carbonation level but considering the abv i am not suprised .  generously carbonated feel . goes down like nothing .
wonderful floral hop aroma right off . appearance is just above average .  a : caramel color with large head that disappears quickly .  the mouthfeel i think is perfect for the style .

s : wow , seriously ? this is as tropical an ipa as i 've smelled . tons of citrus , namely orange , mango , and grapefruit . a good amount of pine encompasses the aroma providing much of the body with the pale malts . t : a little less fruity than the nose . i get a solid dose of orange , pineapple and grapefruit up front riding the wave of pale malt . good citrus flavor .  blurb from deschutes : `` easy-going and easy-drinking session beer for the thirsty masses . '' pours a light yellow and hazy .  mouthfeel is crazy smooth and thick .

s : huge coffee nose ! awesome nose . m/t : slightly watery to medium body .  a- looks like fall in a glass . murky orange/brown just like the leaves on the ground . little bits and chunks of floaties .  the mouthfeel was awesome . very heavy and smooth feel .

s- amazing , like dark roasted coffee + stout beer t- good , although i did n't like the bottom end . overall- as much as it was talked up , i was pretty disappointed as a stout lover .  beer poured out a pale , cloudy yellow with a small cream head that dissapeared quickly and left some lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional , is medium to heavy in body .

i would recommend dale 's pale ale as it is the best can i 've had courtesy of the wobbly postage dude !  crystal clear , brass color , tiny amount of head with no retention or lace .  the body and finish are absolutely luscious considering this is a 4.5 % abv j-beer out of a can .

3.5/5 s : ahhh ... the lightly funky smell of brett and mold that is unexpected in every other cascade beer shows up here .  dark brown in color with reddish mahogany tinges . thin , bubbly , off-white head which dissipates in no time . nice carbonation , with a bit of haziness .  very creamy mouthfeel . again , marvelous mouthfeel , probably one of the best i 've ever enjoyed in that regard .

a - pours very-cloudy unfiltered golden , with a huge , overflowing white head ... - great lacing . s - big hops and sweet citrus - some orange & grapefruit with hits of pine tones ... t - pow ! m - a bit too much carbonation , which creates an unbalanced feel ... o - this one is good ... i think what make this beer so good ( yet kills it in the ladder components , such as 'taste ' and 'mouth feel ' is the unfiltered , ultra carbination ) .  took a growler of this home from john harvard 's in pittsburgh . a : pale golden in color , very clear . seems a pretty solid pils .  m - creamy , silky mouthfeel , with noticeable carbonation .

the aroma was stale , dry corn , pale malt and generally rather boozy .  moderate head with average lacing , subsiding into a cloudy golden-orange color .  mouthfeel great creamy thick milkshake like mouthfeel with medium-light carbonation .

not much aroma .  whoa , looks like a macro lager ! not very appealing to me , and dangerously misleading - i can see a coor 's light drinker drinking from your glass by mistake at a party really being thrown for a loop !  quite smooth and creamy with a good level of carbonation . feels great going down .

lively ( could still see a bit through the red haze ) smell & gt ; caramel , sweet grasses and malt . excellent taste & gt ; true to its style , it started sweet before bursting with barley flavor .  12oz brown bottle . ) poured a hazy gold . fine bubbled head about one finger .  fine carbonation bubbles and a full body give an excellant texture . coats the palate beautifully . more of a bourbon lovers beer than a stout lovers beer .

s- i really liked the smell of this beer , giving off hints of oatmeal , caramel and light coffee scents . almost sweet smelling .  god bless scotland pours up a red amber color with barely any off-white head .  mouthfeel : medium to full bodied and incredibly smooth . just a hint of carbonation tingle .

pours a hazy golden color with maybe the best aroma of any beer i have had wild tart raspberries waffle batter , man it is right on with the aromas how did they do that ?  pours a clear golden-orange with a loosely-formed white head , very little lacing left in the glass .  mouthfeel was excellent . very slick and smooth , almost oily in fact , with a medium/thick body .

smell kills the idea that this is a stout right away . big floral hops smell that just blows me away . this has to be one of the best smelling beers ever . some sweet malt comes through in the background but it is really the floral smell that stands out .  date : 24 january 2011 glass : sierra nevada xxx snifter type : 12fl oz bottle poured gently , 1-finger head , reduces to nothing , lacing is a little runny , color is an amber orange with lots of sediment . i heard a lot of hype about this beer , i 'm just hoping this is as fresh as possible .  an excellent mouthfeel .

smells good , like fresh brewing grains .  beer poured a hazy brown into my mug .  the most enjoyable aspect of this beer for me was its mouthfeel . just so smooth , with a medium to full body and a higher level of carbonation that keeps this beer formidably sippable , in a good way . all in all a richly decadent , mouth enveloping , alcohol warmth soothing , special imperial stout , that i had the pleasure of enjoying with a friend .

not sure what i was expecting from this brew , but the nose was a big surprise . overhwelmingly bitter and floral , with caramel sweetness singing backup .  a - pours a cloudy pink-orange with a small-moderate , not overly impressive head .  mouthfeel is just superb . satisfying .

s - big juicy citrus hop aroma . i love ipa 's that smell like this ... big fruity nose with almost nothing else to it . a very easy drinking and tasty ipa , just like every other hop project of theirs i have tried .  a : really dark brown with a little bit of reddish tone . the tan head disapears quickly leaving a patchy , floating foam .  a perfect medium body that felt nice on the tongue , and carbonation similar to what one would expect from a top rated wild ale .

smell : the aroma of the beer is a cleaver blending of caramel , vanilla , suggestions of hot fudge , brown sugar , melons , berries , banana , dark toasted and roasted aromas , spicey earthyness , its boozey but in the way that a nice single malt is boozey . taste : this beer taste good but not nearly as good as its smell . the beers flavors bring an undefinable fruityness to my mouth . sweet honey brown sugar , vanilla , the alcohol comes across as boozey .  this beer pours nicely , but comes up short in appearance due to a head that falls fairly fast .  thick smooth mouthfeel , very silky .

and it smells fantastic ! a truly great smelling beer . t- wow .  clear yellowish orange in color with a thin head that produced no lacing .  mouthfeel is nearly perfect , with a refreshingly light and crisp body .

a range of hop smells from sweet and citrusy to floral and piney . truly a treat for the nose . taste is surprisingly sweet , nicely balanced with the intense hops . not a bad beer otherwise though , worth trying if you love hops .  pours a murky dark amber/brown with a minimal bubbly off-white head that leaves no lacing after fading almost instantly to nothing .  mouthfeel - 5.0 silky smooth , with very fine , lively , almost creamy carbonation .

fantastic beer . very creative and an extremely complex , layered aroma . i need this again .  fairly average in appearance .  the beer has the perfect amount of carbonation and aftertaste , bringing you back for more .

i would drink this with a spicy sausage covered in peppers and onions at tony 's and it was just about as close to beer pairing heaven as it gets . love this beer 's heavy pine nose and taste along with its more citrusy side .  deep ruby brown ale here with little in way of foamy head .  body is smooth , lightly creamy , and beautifully sparkling .

amazing if i could turn this into a scented candle i would burn it all the time , pumpkin nutmeg cinnamon and allspice flood the nostrils reminds me of new england in the autumn medium bodied malts and allspice are strong throughout well balanced with hoppes to finish pumpkin rind also has a strong presence nice effervescent carbonation which keeps keeps the brew extremely interesting however , overall i would say the beer lacks body i really liked this beer i will surely enjoy it for the rest of the fall the light body and delicious flavor makes this beer easy going down  i had this on tap and it poured a nice and copper with a decent thin head .  mouthfeel is near perfect with carbonation playing second fiddle to the robust malts .

low carbonation , no head retention , but this is a cask . s - wow . what a nose on this . vanilla , caramel , sour notes , dark fruits ... it was quite a complex nose actually.. t - i was expecting sour notes.. but the front really took me by surprise.. very puckering .. i taste a lot of whiskey and burnt sugar notes on the mid palate and some great oak and deep vanilla on the finish . very interesting . but a tad too much lactic acid coming through . d - like i said . pretty darn sour , but the sourness played well enough against the vanilla .  it is slightly cloudy . it has a nice 2 finger head with nice lacing . this is a wonderful beer for any hop head .  mouthfeel is also top notch . low carbonation that goes down very smooth .

wonderful . t : slightly sweetnened grapefruit , a touch of spiciness , and a bit of spearmint on the finish .  appearance - dark purple color . nothing too great to look at .  m : full bodied with an awesome carbonation feel .

pours a clean deep amber color with an off white head . in the aroma , small roast and a small hint of hops .  appearance - typical brown ale look . laces ok .  mouthfeel - very creamy and smooth . great body without a sense of heaviness .

smell - wow the hops are amongst us . taste - very hoppy mouthfeel - very hoppy very american in the hops that i taste .  not much lace to write home about . an amazing light amber ale ... .the 6-pack will certainly not last the week .  m- full bodied with medium carbonation . thick and almost chewy in the mouth .

the nose gives me a little cause for concern , as while there 's a certain spiciness to it the predominant aroma is of alcohol .  baltus poured a murky/cloudy reddish-brown with very little head . baltus was my favorite of the heavyweight beers and i am sure i 'll purchase this brew again in the future .  body is rich , creamy , smooth , and damn near perfect . another excellent offering from d'achouffe .

not much in the aroma . some grain and yeast , a bit phenolic . faint apricot notes . probably better on cask .  12 oz bottle served in standard pint glass a - orange-tinted amber ; hazy ; scant but lasting off-whit head m - medium body ; nicely carbonated .  the texture was excellent , not too thick or thin .

s : very fruity nose . some dark fruits mixed with candi sugar and sugared candy fruits . strawberries , raspberries , pineapple , tart white mango . grape juice .  pours a hazed apricot with a thin , cream-colored head that quickly recedes .  mouthfeel is on the dry side with effervescent carbonation that contributes to the crisp clean finish . its a fascinating brew that manages to be both crisp and refreshing yet still rich and satisfying .

this is one of the most balanced beers available . the bitterness of the hops is just enough to counter the sweetness of the caramel malt . it is not quite as drinkable as a typical lager , but is about average for an amber ale .  a ~ pours pale amber/orange . head descends quickly leaving the typical belgian ring around the glass that does n't leave , with a cluster of tiny bubbles in the center .  much better balance on the palate . crisp , clean feeling with just a bit of drying on the finish .

carmel candy smells , with some vanilla , and winter spices come through . this smells great ! t- some of the same tastes come through that you can smell .  pours a ruby color with a moderate head that falls fast and does n't leave too much lacing on the glass . the color seems wrong on this one .  ever so rich and creamy in the mouth with soft and forgiving carbonation . medium-full in body .

the aroma is breathtaking . a beautiful balance of oak , sweet malt , and dark fruit with a layer of very clean smelling whisky gently overlaying the rest of the aromas . just marvelous . unfortunately , the taste fell a good deal short of the ethereal aromas .  pours an opaque black with an incredibly thin tan head and tiny bits of lacing .  good moderate carbonation and a crisp , dryish , oily slick , chewy , creamy smooth full bodied mouthfeel .

the aroma is perfect with great nutmeg , cinnamon , and clove notes . aside from that , delicious . rarely do i feel that i can drink two fruit beers back-to-back , but i certainly could have done so with the pumpking ... that is , if i did n't have a breakfast stout on deck .  pours a murky dirty brown with a 1/2 inch foamy tan head that quickly fades to nothing .  the mouthfeel was incredible . very creamy and smooth .

s : piney and earthy hops up front , followed by a large pork and onion presence . no other aromas detectable . d : the best thing i can say about this beer is that it is n't as bad as i was fearing ... it tastes alright but the smell wears on you and the mouthfeel is pretty far from what it should be .  it tastes exactly like the beer equivalent of sauternes . lightly carbonated . no noticeable head .  thick and chewy in the mouth - one can definitely understand the allusions to barley wines in previous reviews . hops tingle as you swallow . is it an old ale ? compared to other old ales that i have seen reviewed , i 'm tempted to say old ale ... but a marvelous cold weather beer in any event .

bottle says brewed both with vanilla beans and flavoring , which is disappointing but economical . aroma is a great mix of almost smokey brown malt , pure vanilla , and coffee . i think the coffee does it for me in terms of appeal and adds a great amount of complexity to the aroma . like smelling a cappucino . taste is just a bit watery at first and too dextrinous .  dark mahogany highlights with thin tan head and no retention .  the mouthfeel is perfect . the carbonation , weight of the brew , taste and viscosity are all well matched .

toasted coffee & touches of chocolate on nose . gentle upfront , dry nut bitterness & subtle sweetness .  hazy gold , with some sediment ( my bottle could 've been aged -- no `` best by '' date present ) . thick , slow head and decent lace .  although this beer is fantastic it is a little powerful to garner a high drinkability score , but its pretty tasty .

first thing i notice with the smell of this one is how hoppy it is - wow , the huge blast of citrus makes me think i 'm smelling an ipa or something . awesome . i had a hell of a hard time trying to find anything i did n't love about this one .  the beer pours a very dark black with hardly any light showing through on the edges . it looks very oily , and pours with no head what-so-ever which is disappointing .  m : very nice . well carbonated , creamy , smooth , and very full bodied .

i smelled chocolate on dark fruit . overall , a very nice porter . not quite the most complex porter i 've ever had , but it was extremely drinkable .  poured from a bottle into a perfect pint a- pours a cloudy shade of orange with a paper thin white head that immediately fades . the lack of a head is really disappointing , but the beer is a nice vibrant color s- citrus !  mouthfeel : creamy smooth medium body with superb carbonation . swallow is velvet . tasty and the mouthfeel is truely a dream . goes down easy when you enjoy slowly .

s : the nose is full of some of the best fruits ive ever smelled . this one smells amazing ! t : never had i have a beer that smelled so good taste so completely different . its good , but a definite letdown compared to the nose . o : fabulous nose , above average taste ( just barely ) , but a disappointing mouth .  appearance - near-black body with a little bit of a head before fading to naught but little islands of bubbles . short 's seems to have issues with head retention .  before i get to any flavors this beer has an amazingly creamy buttery mouthfeel amazing . very bitter chocolate character with big bittering hops on the finish.layers of bitter bakers cocoa , black fruits , just thick cocoa tannins and a forever finish .

but this beer , the bouquet is fantastic ! and let me set this straight , `` bouquet '' is not a word i use normally but this beer has brought me to a place where `` bouquet '' was the word i needed to use to get my point across .  looks really ruddy/cloudy , an amber/brown .  nice syrupy body , carbonation is moderate - perfect .

aroma of strong carbonated peaches , fresh from a can-like . sweet syrupy taste , peaches and sugar . refreshing . does n't pair necessarily well with spicy pizza .  served in a weizen glass . poured an opaque chestnut with a half inch , loose off-white head the quickly settled into a broken skim of effervescing foam that eventually dissipated into a thin thread-like band ; no lacing present on this one .  the mouthfeel is smooth though not super thick , it is a great texture for this style .

the smell is an incredible medley spices ( nutmeg , clove and cinammon ) , gingerbread , pine needles , vanilla , brown sugar and toasted bread ... awesome , one of the best smelling beers ever . the flavor is a bit more subdued , with notes of christmas spices , gingerbread , molasses , toasted bread , vanilla , cinammon and some licorice .  a - poured from a growler about 2 hours after purchase . minimal head . copper brown with a slight haze and a red tint s - grassy , yeasty but also sweet t - hoppy at the start that moves to malt and leads to a sweet finish with a little note of alcohol m - extremely pleasant mouthfeel , the previous reviewer said it best , its silky in the mouth then warm on the throat .  the carbonation and head give this an exceptional mouthfeel .
smell was hershey 's chocolate syrup .  hazy yellow orange .  this is a big bodied , chewy brew with medium carbonation , and a full palate .

s - smells just like creme brulee .  poured into my carolus chalice . the appearance of chill-hazed sparkling apple juice . a spritzy , pasty-colored head sizzles out just like a soda would . i would welcome a touch stronger overall wheat flavor in this , but it is still very nice as is .  mouthfeel is full and round .

aroma is a very fragrant load of citrus hops .  a : pours a murky brown with amber highlights , capped by a one finger off white head . retention is solid and leaves some spotty lacing .  m - mouthfeel is great . a medium-full body with good carbonation . perfect . d - the thicker mouthfeel makes it slightly less drinkable .

aroma - kind of skunky and familiar corn adjunct appearance - pale , plae yellow no head and very little carbonation .  dark copper color with a thin beige head .  m : this is one of the thickest stouts i 've had in a while - very similar to dark lord in it 's heavy , cream like thickness that coats the mouth very well . d : good drinkability , but it 's definitely a sipper .

s - lemon pepper zest , pine , more citrus in the background . having a hard time getting past the lemon pepper , but i rather enjoy it , so i 'm not sure i 'd like to get past it . once i get deeper into it i can pick out orange peel as a distinct scent through the rest of the citrus backbone . the lemon pepper that was so apparent and appreciated in the nose is merely a muted background note in the mouth .  orange amber color , good clarity , mediocre head .  mouthfeel is incredible , maybe an even better quality than the taste .

dark mahogany brown in the glass , not quite black ; on the light side for the world 's strongest stout . swirling reveals thick , syrupy legs not unlike a spirit or liqueur . it smells intensely of alcohol , peat , oak , faint roast - a hell of a lot like scotch . it 's simple and unimpressive .  a bit more flavorful than most american pilsners , stella is a nice , light beer that is good for all occasions , with almost any food .  mouthfeel : light and airy . the perfect match to the flavor profile . well done .

from the second i cracked open the cap , the room filled with the sent of vanilla , as far as smell goes this the best smeling beer ever ! the tast is good but not as good as i had hoped this one is sweet with a fair vanilla kiss and a carmalised malt flavor . i think it might be the hop aftertaste on this one , i would rather have this one finish sweet .  3.0 a : lightly hazed dark orange amber color . just half a finger of frothy beige head that fell quickly , leaving no lacing .  the texture is perfect , though .

overall it has a very appealing smell . flavor : a little spicey with subtle hop bitterness and moderate alcoholic heat at the finish .  pours from the bottle a cloudy red color that is quite appealing if not for the haze .  mouthfeel is pretty great . full bodied , full flavored , slick and oily . carbonation is great . super job here .

aroma is outstanding , filled with sweet oranges and caramel , not caramel malt , but candied caramel . mouthfeel is a bit cloying , maybe a bit too heavy on the malt , but it coats extremely well .  pours a hazy golden color with a frothy two finger white head which gives way to some lacing .  m - nearly full bodied but despite that and the abv , it is extremely smooth and leaves just the right amount of flavor behind leaving you wanting another sip .

smells of an intense ale yeast and very strong bittering hops . it 's wonderfully balanced , but not all the complex .  a- pours a deep brown with a thin head and not much lacing . i remember this beer pouring & looking better than this .  truly velvety on the tongue . the mouthfeel is second to none , it 's that good . this is a very good stout .

aroma is of a divine nectar , exceptional even when compared to any other belgian ale . banana , mango , cotton candy , honey , spiced fruitcake , cookie dough , and some woodsy mushroomy yeast . i spent several minutes inhaling these divine aromas before moving to the sipping stage . aromas get no better than this . bread dough , warming alcohol , and yeasty barnyard add to the likeable complexity . an odd note of fresh popcorn was picked up midway through , but was very fleeting . i ca n't explain the mediocre appearance , but the aroma and taste more than atone for this mild fault . the complexities of this belgian mask the high abv just enough to make this very drinkable .  the bottle is individually numbered -- neat ! a tiny white head foams up briefly , then runs to the outside edge of the glass . up front banana really shows off the wheat character .  finishes warm and fruity gain with a very sweet exhale that is not quite cloying but just perfect . thick bodied with a light carbonation , goes down easily .

pours beautifully . medium cloudy brown . aroma did n't do much for me . maltier and good bite , some lemon . very enjoyable drink .  pours a very hazy light chestnut amber , with a tan head that really puffs up .  mouthfeel is perfect . low carbonation lends to an incredible full body and smoothness .

the aroma was intensely pumpkin-pie like . sweet , spicy and yummy with lots of nutmeg , allspice and clove . the flavor was similar to the nose yet a bit dryer and more subdued . malty rich and a touch sweet up front . super spicy ( nutmeg and allspice once again ) in the center . pumpkin and brown sugar notes came through as well . a touch of hoppy bitterness was noticeable on the very dry , spicy , lingering finish . this was a very tasty and enjoyable pumpkin ale that hid its alcohol content remarkably well . i am a huge fan of pumpkin products of all types , yet for some reason i am usually disappointed with pumpkin beers .  a - clear amber , with about a finger of light tan head . retention is moderate with moderate lacing . i was definitely expecting more in the head/lace department .  a beautiful dryness on the finish that makes it pleasant to drink .

smell is enormous floral hops , lots of fruity citrus . one of the best i 've ever smelled . taste is fruity and hoppy like the smell , but without the maltiness i wanted there to be . i 'm glad i tried it , though .  notes from 5/14/10 pours a hazy dark brown with a slight red hue . head and lacing are nearly non existant .  mouthfeel is exquisite . creamy as can be from the oats , thick and chewy , slick , with a remarkably dry finish . strange carbonation that sizzles like really mellow pop rocks on my tongue . this gets a high drinkability score even though one bomber is enough , because the mouthfeel is so remarkable . glad i got it , and glad i waited to pop it open .

s : fruity notes of sherry , some alcohol , fresh fruit , cherries , peppers , some wood and spices . biscuits and toffe , and also some strawberries . very hoppy .  a- pale yellow , little head .  carbonation is perfect and really adds to the beer .

arroma : what a bouquet ! this is one of the freshest , hoppiest noses ever to come out of the bottle . if i could drink this through my nose i would . taste : this is basically a stronger , more full bodied version of arrogant bastard ... which is already pretty damn strong and full bodied .  the beer pours a deep amber , forming a very thin head , with light lacing .  mouthfeel - great mouthfeel .

a little deceiving `` macro '' smell came to my nose when i took a wiff from the glass . furtunately , a sip was much more rewarding . hops and malt flavorig with a shy but lingering floral/bitter aftertaste .  a deep copper color with a meager off-white head and fair lacing .  mouthfeel is excellent ; creamy with just the right twinge of foam .

lovely aroma of raw oat , malt and the sour creaminess of a milk stout . the look of this brew is solid , the aroma is excellent and the flavor/mouthfeel are well made and weighted for the style .  appearance : amber color with 1 finger of head that fades quickly with minimal lacing .  good body and perfect carbonation .

i thought this was a great beer and gave the smell a 5 for the style for the amazing chocolate smell . a - dark small foam head really brown s - rated as exceptional because it nails the style it is going for a deep dark chocolate . it really does nail it too . t - great if you like chocolate not so great if not it is sweet but well blended and tasty . m - again chocolate , smokey , nice .  appearance - yellow . very cloudy . medium height white head that quickly dissipates to a thin film .  mouthfeel/drinkability : this beer feels pretty creamy in the mouth , and is just a touch heavier bodied than i expected , actually . excellent .

the smell is very sweet , it smells like candy kind of . also smells faintly citrusy and a little scent of alcohol .  pours hazy dark yellow , but not quite gold in colour . lots of sediment .  mouthfeel is terrific . great , rich , creaminess . completely coats your mouth .

smell : i detected some berries and citrus , good hops , some grain , and a light malt .  good lacing & below average head retention smell : slight leather & iron notes up front , followed by some fruittyness .  the mouthfeel is clean and soft , and actually just perfect .

the smell is overwhelming , right out of the bottle . there is a dryness to it , with some good , balanced alcohol burn . the aging in cabernet sauvignon oak barrels , coupled with the addition of currants ( and perhaps lactic acid or brett ) makes this a beautifully crafted beer .  ap . pretty , clear , golden brown with minimal head .  mouthfeel is medium heavy bodied and sticky as fuck , wonderful . the drinkability is very high for a beer of this strength .

s- bananas and clove ( like with a wheat beer ) , and a big nuttiness . duh , it smells like fresh baked banana nut bread .  pours hazy orange amber with a 1/2 inch beige/off white creamy head ; very pungent floral hops up front , with a massive hop aroma followed by sweet malt and caramel , as well as citrus and orange peel .  m/d - full bodied and incredibly smooth and easy drinking .

it left sudsy trails of lace on the glass . s - it actually smells like christmas , if that 's possible . really an amazing aroma that comes through in taste , too .  on-tap at bootlegger 's , glad to see this one back on-tap as i did n't get a chance to try it previously , a : pours a medium-dark amber . mild head , no lace .  absolutely fantastic mouthfeel , creamy and oily without being cloying .

very understated aroma . it is a project to pick up anything on the nose besides a bit of booze and a hint of herbal hops .  served a dark dark brown color bordering on black . no head , just a thin ring .  just the smoothest mouthfeel ever , talk about an angel crying on your tongue !

the smell is very plain with almost no hops but the color is a nice deep red-brown with a nice tan head .  served in a huge rapscallion brand snifter . i was disturbed that of the huge snifter only 1/4 was filled with beer , 3/4 head . the body was a clear medium brown , i could see though to the other side of the glass .  mouthfeel : oh mouthfeel is right on . perfect carbonation .

nose is phenomenal , it 's very fruity and floral , dank and spicy . not sure how he does it with these ipas , but they all smell amazing . wow , this is so creamy and juicy and dank .  i was surprised to see a couple of really negative reviews for this beer . i think what i like best is that it 's got a great aftertaste , and is -- to me -- very drinkable .  the mouthfeel is some kind of amazing . this brew is thick , chewy , ultra creamy smooth and goes down like heavy cream . if you like your imperial stouts with an unapologetically brash , bold , slightly raw taste , but with a refined , well-mannered mouthfeel , then you 'll enjoy expedition stout immensely .

straw yellow with a nice white head . smells really floral , fruity , white peaches , juicy . not really intricate , but fruit forward and a solid sour . not much funk overall , but a really nice , crisp and well done sour .  pours to a brilliantly clear dark-amber with garnet highlights , forming an average-sized frothy light-beige head with poor retention and minimal lacing .  i honestly would think this a stout or porter , rather than a bsda ... m : this is soo smooth and nicely full bodied , its literally coats your mouth , and leaves your mouth wanting another sip , just perfect ... d : well this beer is still a little hot , a year or two would make this even better .

'' the scent is amazing . floral , extremely hoppy , and thick . taste is a little odd after inhaling that wonderful scent . i expected much more of a kick than i got . very interesting . flows smoothly over my tongue .  it 's biggest fault is poor head retention .  m ~ refreshing and spirited mouthfeel . truly exceptional .

from a 22 ounce bomber - $ 3.99 . s. holy cow - lots going on here . belgian yeast , citrus and pine hops , wild flowers , graphite and candied malt . killer nose . t. plenty of hop goodness without being overly bitter . d. this is one fine beer . the nose alone is worth the price of admission .  poured into a shaker pint glass bbe dec 2008 a- mahogany body with lots of floaters , creamy 1 finger head that reduces to a crown , minimal lacing .  m - the best part of this beer .

fantastic smell . sweet , flowery , hoppy smell . cool . i bet most ipa lovers enjoy this one . too much pine , which always reminds me of pinesol and other cleaning agents .  clean amber in appearance , with sizeable foam head . and , notably , the carbonation seems to congeal after dissipation into clusters in my glass .  it almost tastes like an ipa , but with a darker malts and a more complex sweetness . the citrusy hops balance it out nicely . the beer is quite heavy , i guess it is following its `` scottish ale '' description here . it is so creamy and goes down nicely . almost perfect drinker .

the nose is beautiful . molasses , coffee , oats and almost a berry-like aroma .  dark ruby color noted with 1-1/2 '' head that dissapated quickly but white lacing remained .  mouthfeel : silky smooth and creamy . does n't bite too hard , but you can definitely feel it . superb .

crystal malts provide the body and structure that supports the intense centenninal and chinook bitterness . the snappy hop finish is topped only by an intense cascade nose . all in all , this beer is typical of the bj 's approach : bigger and bolder than the style calls for .  opaque black with a muddy brown head . weak retention for a stout .  big , smooth , and slick . this is a particularly rich baltic porter . very dark , dense , and well crafted .

prunes , leather , light oxidation , and a vinuous aroma join together to suggest a well aged barleywine . esters are potent and complex , and the alcohol serves as a vector rushing the scents into your nose without getting in the way itself . deeply fruity on the palate , backed by a wave of malt . quite unusual , though reading earlier reviews , i think this has benefited from some age ... dial up the hops and dial down the alcohol and i 'd bump the taste score a half-point .  leroy ... the king of colorado brown ales ? this is a light coloured rendition of a traditional brown ale . this is designed to be an easy-drinking and light brown . hopefully , oskar blues will find a way to market this full-time and lower the price for a six-pack .  incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth .

smells wonderful , a sweet raspberry smell , mixed with the yeasty mustiness of a hefeweizen . nothing over powering , all the good smells of beer without any sourness .  the nice little head is the saving grace but to be honest not a very enticing looking beer .  fantastic , soft , supple bottle-conditioned mouthfeel .

4.0 s : the nose on this beer is really nice . its a great looking and great smelling beer . however , the taste and mouthfeel come up short .  beer pours golden with large head that soon fades to thin and transparent layer .  first sip reveals a light to average body with minimal , almost cask-like carbonation and a silky texture . very enjoyable mouthfeel .

smell is of roasted malts , and both dark and fresh red fruit . all in all , quite a good experience in the smell . for the rest it 's decent , not exeptional .  a-crystal clear rich golden body bordering on amber . not much head and it dropped quick , no lacing .  the palette on this is excellent thick and creamy not to much carbonation flavors of toasted malts sweetness almost but just enough bitter to balance this perfectly .

s : wow , that is the greenest nose i have ever smelled . huge fresh/wet hop aroma ... i ca n't stop smelling this beer . i have put my nose to the glass at least 20 times before tasting this one . t : wonderful crystal malts lay down a biscuity flavor which is very nice . very `` green '' hop flavor .  on tap at american flatbread poured a deep brown with almost no head to it .  for the style , mouthfeel was superb , and drinkability was too .

i was able to enjoy this one , but i really wish the taste had lived up to the aroma .  appearance- pours a murky orange color . very small amount of beige head that returns with a swift twirl of the glass .  medium bodied with low carbonation . amazing mouthfeel with one of the most balanced , robust , and pleasantly malty flavor profiles of any barleywine .

on tap @ tph in brookline for $ 5 on 4/13/06 . the bourbony oak flavor is pretty distinct , but far from overwhelming . the hops are very mellow , and i keep having to pinch myself to remind myself that i 'm drinking arrogant bastard . the kick just is n't there ; rather , there is a wonderfully complex taste that is nutty , fruity , and just overall delicious .  i love trix and i really enjoy this beer . i have poured it in a glass and there is nothing unique about it 's appearance .  mouthfeel- super creamy , lower carbonation and silky smooth .

s. a very pleasant scent of raspberries , raspberries and more raspberries with a hint of hops and sweet malts . one of the best smelling beers around . t. the taste starts off with some earthy floral hops , followed by some sweet sugary syrup and than some tart raspberries and finishes off with a hint of more hops . it has a nice smell and mouthfeel , but the taste was a let down , so unless i get it as an air freshener i know i 'll never buy this beer again .  a - pours medium honey , .5 inch white head reduces to ring . persistent foamy lacing . d - like this better than the ale , and that was very drinkable .  mouthfeel is very nice , i enjoyed it a lot .

a -- probably the most remarkable thing about the beer : oddly fruity , apricot notes . t -- caramel , light hop with heavy malts , almost syrupy .  poured a deep brownish amber into a duvel tulip with a thin ring of off-white head .  very soft carbonation that makes it feel creamy and silky smooth one of , if not , the thickest beers i 've had . love it .

it 's hard for a high original gravity beer too look great.. smelled of tons of maris otter malts , syrup , brandy , grapefruit , roses , and tiny hop leaves . lots going , but mostly toward the sweet side . had some strange creamy but earthy notes too , and also some strange alcohol and hops flavor in the finish .  appearance : hazy amber with little carbonation and little ( shortlasting ) head .  the mouthfeel is super thick and heavy , just awesome . the drinkability is pretty good for an 11 % brew as well .

the most impressive thing about this beer was the aroma , and i can not even describe the complexity of it ... fruit , nuts , and deep molasses is what comes to mind .  12oz bottle poured into a sa glass a : light straw and cloudy with a fairly thin white head and that does n't last long .  mouthfeel is excellent . it 's creamy and almost chewy .

wow the roasted aromas burst out of the glass as you pour it out .  a - clear dark brown that 's near black in the glass with dark brown amber highlights . a quiet pour gives off a small off-white head with little retention and a thin right left over .  m : outstanding , deliciously creamy , thick , rich for an ipa .

absolutely fantastic ! taste : very mild in the taste , but with a strong , strong oatmeal component - stronger than many oatmeal stouts . every other `` stout '' aspect is pretty subdued : there 's milk chocolate chips , some simple sweetness , a regular malty note , and a little bit of coffee , but the coffee definitely is n't too prominent .  a : ruddy red-orange with half a finger head that recedes quickly s : lemon , strawberry .  mickey 's ice has an amazing mouthfeel to it , one of the best in my opinion . the carbonation comes on strong then fades to a creaminess .

aroma - dark chocolate dominates the nose . overall - it smells much better than it tastes .  a- a fluffy three finger head sits atop this honey orange brew and fades rather quickly , barely leaving a trace of lacing . really decent carbonation , and a load of black little floaty bits throughout the glass . nothing special to look at and admire .  a very big complex beer that is very well made and has exceptional mouthfeel .

s : wow ! really fresh pliny smell , citrusy fruits , smell does not fade when you inhale , just what i 'm looking for in a dipa . really nice blend of hops used in this if you like them ibu 's . overall , underrated .  the head after the pour is very quick , and no residual foam .  good carbonated bevy . the mouth was superb . top tier of coffee stouts although i do n't know that its the best i 've ever had .

aroma is outstanding . everything that is good about hops with a little backdrop of sweet malt . the bitterness is actually pretty scathing for an ipa . jagged and rough .  thanks go out to my secret santa deuane my growler poured into my selin 's grove pint glass produced very little head maybe a wisp of lace . this was on top of a hazy amber colored brew .  a : jet black , no head s : traditional russian imperial stout , dense , licorice , oxidation , great t : dense , true russian imperial stout , cloying , deep burnt caramel taste , great beer , tastes like it has been aged for several years d : very good m : excellent

in the nose , cocoa powder , yeast , coffee grounds , olives , piney hops and wood smoke . beautiful nose . the taste is initially smooth , with notes of dark chocolate , black olives and an oakey sourness .  a-pours with very little head which i have come to expect from barleywines .  great mouthfeel , full bitterness balanced with light maltiness .

a very interesting barleywine . the nose is typical barley wine - some caramel , candied fruits , and a host of other goodies . truly unique - nice job to weyerbacher .  this beer pours a cloudy golden orange hue , with some stringy chunks of sediment , and a thin cap of soapy white head , which disappears in an instant , leaving no lace .  very dark with no light coming through and light head n : nose has lots of chocolate and sweet malts and a touch of hops t : starts with lots of chocolate and coffee , some sweet malts but very slight , a touch of hops are prevelant , some oatmeal taste as well , it 's got a sweet earthiness to it which is somewhat unique , a slight bitterness shines through m : it has a velvet feel in the mouth as it slides around , very thick and smooth f : a touch bitterness comes out in the end with the nice stout and oatmeal taste , coffee lingers on the back of the tongue , it has a sweet quality to start but gets drier as it fades and finishes really dry , its got a great smooth feeling in the mouth to go along with the great taste final thoughts : a great stout , it would be great if it was labelled as oatmeal or irish stout since it seems to have qualities of both , but listed as imperial it makes me wonder since its lacking a lot in the hop category .

despite pouring aggressively and receiving a big fluffy head , the aroma has trouble making any real impression . it 's more on the pale ale side of things than an ipa . much better than the aroma , but far from the greatest ipa ever . still has enough likable characteristics that i had no problem getting it down and even enjoying it .  gold color , with no color from the fruit addition . sorry for my undetailed notes , but with each cantillon lately , i usually wish i was drinking drie fonteinen .  mouth- full , creamy mouthfeel . fine carb .

odor is light and grainy with a bit of toasted malts flavor has a light toasted grain taste with subtle hints of molasses , brown sugar , and anise .  a - pours a nice , clear amber , with a finger or so of head . barely any retention , and not much in the way of lacing .  mouthfeel : fantastic . so smooth in the mouth and goes down easy .

) pours an opaque black with a short cinnamon head smells awesome . chocolate covered pork rind ? road tar , smoked ham , alcohol , milky malt , and cheap bacon .  appearance : the beer had a nice nitro head when served but the head discipated and left a little lace . i was n't sure why the head did n't last that long with the nitro .  chewy , and creamy , a perfect mild carbonation level for this style.. a lil warmth on the finish just to let you know , as chris rock would say `` slow down !

an excellent lambic with an wonderfully pungent black currant aroma . the flavor is full of fresh crushed fruit and herbal notes .  appearance is a bit disappointing on tap as there is no head .  great body and nice hoppiness on the finish .

s : dark and milk chocolate . some dark fruit .  batch 006 a : pours a reddish/chestnut brown with mahogany highlights . very thin head that dissipates quickly .  m : actually leaves nothing - quite remarkable for a style that literally erodes the parts of my body it comes into contact with .

s : weak . could n't smell any hops .  appearance : dark amber/caramel in color -- no head , minimal carbonation smell : raisin , cinnamon , alcohol , and sugar taste : raisin , cinnamon , caramel , alcohol-especially towards the end , and sugar mouthfeel : medium body , smooth and sweet , then a harder alcohol tasting finish drinkability : this is a another unique tasting beer that needs to be drunk slow because of its high alcohol content .  m : man this just feels like it belongs in my mouth . o : excellent taste , exceptional mouthfeel and just an overall amazing experience .

lots of grape/apple/ and cherry scent . amazing scent ! is there funk ? t - slight `` homebrew '' flavor ... kind of off-putting . very unique . lots of big fruit flavor .  definitely lighter than i would expect for an american amber . good carbonation and nice lasting head though . it does n't look like an amber , but definitely tastes like one .  lightly carbonated with a great aftertaste of wheat & blackberry . other than that this beer is tasty , the malt shines through , the hops are just mild enough to notice , mouthfeel is amazing ... but the blackberry is just overpowering .

it smells exactly like wisconsin belgian red , no stout scent whatsoever . it is a nice sweet cherry pie scent with a hint of oak . interesting . i like it better than bell 's take of the style .  appearance : pours an almost clear amber color with a small layer of off white head that goes away completely .  incredibly smooth , and fairly easy drinking for it 's strength . absolutely excellent .

has a pale yellow color with a wispy head that doesnt stay long . not to much of a smell other than grains .  ( on a second pour into a flute , got very nice foamy head , but it fizzed away quickly ) . hazy yellow-golden color .  damn this is one thick beer ; milkshake is about the best way to describe it .

the way these smells mix together is really impressive . the flavor is based on a dry green apple sweetness and a touch of pale malts , but this is taken away by a fantastic dry oak and calm citrus rind that brings out an herbal muskiness .  appearance 3/5 very dark brown and clear with garnet highlights and a medium head that dissipated into a thin collar rather quick and left some lacing .  it was lush , creamy , smooth , rich , decadant and full . a very full bodied stout with a low carbonation .

sweet and quite pleasant . p/m : emptiness .  pours a nice dark brown with amber hilights , a decent-sized beige head that faded away .  m : by far the highlight of this brew for me . rich and creamy with a perfect level of carbonation . nice feel here .

i cant agree with the smell of this beer which is somewhat medicinal , but it gets friendly before long .  color is a copper color , lighter than the ipa is . a very solid , above average tasting apa .  the mouthfeel is impressively creamy .

rather strong and `` fuzzy '' , that same fuzzy scent you get if you were to put you nose directly on a fresh peach and sniff . an interesting nose for sure . i liked it . flavors of apricot and citrus fruits , peaches , light bready malts and a kiss of hops melded together to form a really nice , above all refreshing beer .  pours a deep , wine-like burgundy with no carbonation or head .  m - very creamy . just a small sip seems to coat the inside of the mouth very well .

smell is dominated by lovely oats , backed up by sweet and rich malts . notes of coffee , too . but the really amazing thing about this beer is how much complexity is built into a fairly small package . i ca n't put my name on all the things in the smell , but i can feel them all there .  i had this beer throughout the summer and it never disappointed me . it 's easily drinkable , light bodied , highly carbonated , and has a great lemon zest of flavor . it 's also low abv which helps because you can easily knock back a bunch of these.. a very easy drinker .  mouthfeel is perfect , goose island is the best of the best in this regard .

s - toasty malt with a citrus hop notes . t - good toasty malt taste .  pours a nice gold color , with a one-finger off-white head that settles into a thin , soapy cap fairly quickly .  a : as others have said , its an opaque black ; the head is tan , and leaves a very slight lacing along the glass s : coffee , dark chocolate , spices , and alcohol ; only wish the smell was a bit stronger t : the flavor is intense with chocolate , caramel , and dark fruits followed by a spiced aftertaste ; it is only slightly bitter and there is no alcohol apparent in the taste m : carbonation is perfect ; definately does not feel watered down d : at 13 % alcohol any more than two drinks is excessive , and one may be the perfect number overall , its a great beer .

smell : wow . loads of anise , port , dark chocolate , espresso , cabernet sauvignon , and raisins . awesome . taste : alas , my nose seems to have misled my tongue . overall , fairly acrid and not very good . mouthfeel : flat carbonation and surprisingly thin body . but from this experience ... i can not recommend it , no matter how pleasant the aroma .  honey-amber with a lot of sediment floating about . not much lacing .  incredibly smooth , despite lingering bitterness .

a good ipa with amazing nose , too bad the taste does n't follow as intensely .  bomber , a : pours black with a fizzy medium tan head , average retention , some lace .  thick , creamy , velvety , perfection . the mouthfeel in big stouts is key , and this hits spot on .

the aroma is really interesting here . wonderful aroma . not quite as complex or intense as it could be , but this is instead a refined , subtle , sophisticated , and very approachable lambic .  another solid offering from viking . this doppel bock pours a thin head and offers up minimum carbonation , a quality a enjoy in viking products .  '' the mouthfeel was silky , the body full and the carbonation perfectly soft . enjoyable , but it 's really an american stout contrary to the label at the bar .

s - good lord , this reminds me of my grand 's lemon tree in florida . the citrus characteristics are colossal , this smells freakin great . smells of fresh squeezed lemon , a bit of lime , orange , mango and tangerine with a bit of fresh cut grass . to reiterate , this is an amazing bouquet of citrus with a hint of sweetness and biscuit/caramel in the background . the malt profile is really subdued , i 'm wishing there was a little more to it . this finishes very light and clean , with hardly any bittering at all , some of that juicy lemon and grass lingers into the finish , super refreshing . m - body is medium and spot on , the carbonation is on the high side , but i 'm enjoying it the carbonation feels like it 's scrubbing my taste buds . d - so drinkable , so clean , so light .  brown , mahagony , russet , with ruby highlights . head is miniscule and lacking . what is present is a tan ring around the collar ( or rim for this matter ) .  chocolate nutty goodness md - smooth and perfect off the cask .

beautiful aroma and drinkable , especially for the high abv .  i remember the beer being a bit too much for me then thus the less than stellar review . taste : spiced banana , clove and wheat notes . i could really sit and drink this all day . slight wheat presence . ap : a clear light gold . the head disappeared quickly and there was hardly any lacing .  mouthfeel - this is superb . a little sticky ; its creamy and thick with the perfect level of carbonation .

a - i love pouring stouts and porters . either way , it 's friggin dark . i love the smell of coffee , but besides that , there are smoky notes , and something mellow in there like warm cream . t - love it . definite coffee ( obviously ) , but also a little of a hoppy twang , and a zip of charcoal . d - i loved this beer , but i would n't drink to many .  the hoppiness is very apparent from the moment you open the bottle . the hops and the carbonation synergize excellently with the milky texture . very well balanced quality beer , very drinkable  taste the weizen gives way to the bock as it warms mf : medim/heavy bodied with low carbonation & nicely balanced drinks very easy for the abv , a really nice weizen bock .

pours very pale golden with small head that almost immediately dissipates , leaves very nice looking thin patchy lacing all over the glass . aroma is almost none - very weak lemony malt in the beginning , later absolutely nothing can be felt .  poured a medium amber color with a one finger off white topper which soon turned into a thin film and left no lacing to speak of .  silky smooth and creamy mouth feel . such body without being cloying .

s : yeast and mild kiwi-type fruit . not much going on here .  a - pours a beautiful golden copper , hazy thanks to the unfiltered status of the beer . unfortunately , the 1-finger head vanished without much of a trace , leaving a small collection at the top of the beer to remind you of what once was . no lacing ... s - surprisingly sweet at the first sniff , with a bitter , hop kick backing it up .  medium bodied and oily . simply exceptional .

the aroma is fantastic with rustic , yeasty and wheaty notes complimented by a pungent , floral hop character with tropical fruit and citrus as well . the flavor is very good , just not as awesome as the aroma . mouthfeel had the right amount of carb , but just was n't terribly convincing .  `` double chocolate coffee oatmeal stout '' poured very aggressive leaving a quarter inch of tan head that dissipated somewhat quickly and did not retain well at all . black color , minimal carbonation .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy , which is what smooths out the bitter roast flavours so well . carbonation is not overdone , just right .

s - hop aroma is wood , not necessarily pine as some others are . exceptional smell . t - just as it smells the hops and malt blend perfectly .  l - black color with a thin brown head that vanished in a few minutes .  the mouthfeel really shines here , it 's bright and crisp and creamy . good body .
the wonderfully strong raspberry aroma is all i can smell .  poured into a tulip glass . dark golden color with a quarter finger of head .  mouthfeel is thick , chew , viscous .

very enticing ... s- thank you surly for this aroma that i have now gotten to experience . in your face grapefruit , pineapple , oranges , and just a tiny bit of pine/wood to add some complexity . i literally sense no malt sweetness in this to back up the hop aroma like you get in other beers , and that is great by me ! t/m- very bitter forward . o- very good ipa .  a : fairly pale yellow color . poured with a finger of white head . looks kind of like a macro .  feels like velvet on my tongue and one of the smoothest stouts in recent memory .

s : wonderful , joyous sultry oak scents .  about a 4oz pour served out of a cantillon flute . served with a 1 finger foamy white head with poor retention . no lace . decent but average .  the body of this beer was exceptional , thick , clean , and enjoyable .

the aroma is strong and awesome . tons of malts attacking my senses . overall , this is very good . one of the best oak aged ris with tons of bourbon flavor .  a - pours a slightly hazy orange/copper with half a finger of tan head and one incredibly disturbing looking floater . head has decent retention , but does n't leave much lacing .  maybe a peachlike taste in the mix , but honey and herbs are the main ones i sense , mouthfeel- super smooth and low carbonation . very creamy and velvety . nice !

smell is filled with citric fruit , grapefruit and oranges .  bottle served in a portsmouth tulip . pours a clear , dark ruby . a quarter-finger yellow-brown head with loose bubbles fades quickly .  this has a wonderful mouthfeel which i absolutely love .

what a fantastic smell to this one . a bit lost there ... it 's a good ipa but it 's not quite as well rounded as i 'd prefer .  disappointingly thin , creamy white head falls to thin layer over a dese , cloudy , honey-colored beer .  t & m- impeccable smoothness within the lush full body .

very balanced . easy drinker .  pours dark mahogany with a 1.5 '' tan head . not much lacing or head retention smell : big malt roastiness and cofee notes taste : fruitness is quickly overan by toasted malt assualt .  wonderful mouthfeel .

the smell however is n't anything to call home about .  poured into a sam ultimate glass . clear , golden color with a wispy white head that dissapates quickly . hey ... i thought this was a wheat beer- all i can smell is hops !  palate is sticky and smooth . wondrous ...

a nice toasted bread , and caramel malt aroma for an excellent balance . just a big and powerful nose with lots of nuance . t : again , floral and grassy hops are big and up front . very nice and well balanced . m/d : a medium body that is perfectly clean , dry , and crisp .  pours a hazy pale gold , with a moderate but very dense foamy head .  its actually really tasty ... hints of booze throughout keep you honest but this is really nice ... one of the most luxurious mouthfeels ever in my opinion ... it feels thick and creamy and coats the mouth on the finish very nicely.. overall , another winner ... i do n't like it as well as the first one of the series but this is really nice
smell : no cherry aroma at all .  pours a faint yellow , with very little head , and absolutely no lacing .  m - i had it on tap , carbonation was perfect . a refreshing balanced beer .

poured into a 16oz widmer glass , i wanted some of the aromas to come out on this one . a - dark , deep brown fading up to a pitch black . s - weak point of the brew i must say . i can only pick up some smoke , a metallic sting , and some sour mash . t - much more flavorful than the aroma leads one to believe . massive roasted caramel malt profile , toasted chicory , and some mild bitterness .  a : poured golden amber with a thin off white head w/ no persistance / lacing .  m big for sure with high abv , grapefruit hops but surprisingly smooth mouthfeel which is made that way by a consistent and thick carbonation .

the aroma is wonderfully complex , with notes of dark fruits , spice , yeast , molasses , bubblegum , and caramel . beautiful . on the palate , predominantly fruity , with big spices coming up toward the end , along with a growing alcohol burn .  appearance was a little lacking .  m - exceptional . creamy , medium body with strong carbonation .

s : really light on the nose . i 'm getting some light malts , some cereal grains , and that 's about it . good , no . better than bmc beers , but not a great beer by any stretch of the imagination .  appearance : pours a orange gold with creamy white head that leaves lots of spotting . notes : first off , i 'd never buy this based on the package if i had n't heard of it - it looks cheap and designed for tourists .  creamy and luscious body and wonderful layered complex flavors . pale malts , lead into corainder and tropical fruits with a yeasty belgian spice induced finish that lasts into a tingly carbonation with some hop bitterness . very nice .

interesting . t- a little underwhelming . the nose was the highlight but didnt translate to the taste .  pours a very hazy copper/brown color . nice thick head that dissipates quickly with a little lacing .  i love it .

it 's the smell that 's the stunner on this one . absolutely gorgeous aroma ; one the best-smelling beers i 've come across .  this beer had a smooth pour and a good head , but not a long lasting head .  m : medium to full bodied , lightly carbonated , and just the smoothest beer i have ever had . absolutely perfect .

smores aroma with loads of fuit and jumping freshness . huge bitterness . bitter chocolate aroma ( amazing ) heavy coarse bitterness followed by chocolate . as it warms , the taste turns to what fermented sweat may taste like .  pours black with a thin tan head . it left a little lacing at first but not much overall . my only criticism is i would have liked a little more head retention and lacing .  creamy medium-full body with soft carbonation .

the smell is like chocolate and fresh ground coffee beans.what a great taste .  dark brownish copper with a thin but steady head , clarity is fine .  it 's full bodied and smooth with a very clean finish .

head dissipates at a quick pace , and lacing is nonexistent ... s - lots of sweet notes come through . caramel , vanilla , oak , and toffee . very smooth and well balanced ( especially considering the abv ) .nothing is over the top or out of place ... m - goes down extremely smooth . medium bodied with a medium/moderate amount of carbonation ... o - one of the better american barleywines i have tasted to date . definitely something that i am looking foward to trying again in the near future .  into a tulip courtesy of alexd3891 , pours a small quantity of head that dies quickly , nary to reemerge atop an impenetrable black body .  mouthfeel is luscious and creamy , very well done there ; average carbonation .
