s - awesome . delicate balance of dark fruit .  appearance : pours a pale , golden , hazy color , like a witbier or other wheat beer . has a small , white head that dissipates quickly and leaves some spotty lacing .  good balance of sweetness and alcohol warmth full body creamy mouthfeel rich is a good word sippability is great would n't mind having a few of these for special occasions

the best part about this beer though is its aroma . just plain hoppy goodness . citrus with some pineapple , maybe a touch grassy .  poured an orange amber with a white head that barely lasted .  mouthfeel is great , really silky and smooth , perfect carbonation , very dry and a nice warming sensation .

the aroma from the sadly spilt beer is delectably complex and strong , and off the nose of the glass the primary smell i get is one of raw hops .  cloudy , the color of hay . full of very small and rather large bits suspended in there . bone-white head goes quickly .  its thick and syrupy and full of body and character . the alcohol warmth is soothing as it makes its way to the back of the tongue , leaving a sweet resin .

this beer has an absolutely intoxicating aroma . just a spectacular aroma . the flavors in this beer do n't quite live up to the aroma , but they are still quite tasty . notes of honey mixes with nice malt notes and the finish has notes of higher alcohols that somehow do n't reach harsh , but ultimately provide some sharp balancing notes to the other flavors .  a - black with a tan head that dissipates quickly s - smells of sweet chocolate and a bit of burnt malt .  velvet mouthfeel ; tongue coating and heavy .

s : absolutely intoxicating . for a beer called double chocolate , it certainly smells like it , with a backbone of nice roasted malts .  pours a thick , milky look . black with a brown tinge . no head . brown film on top .  pure velvet mouthfeel here , no better bock .
s- this beer smells of tart cherries and a hint of musty basement and a soft oak note .  a - pours a nice golden color but with almost no head .  mouthfeel is full and round .

the golden amber color is not far off from palm . i find the smell short . having to really search for an aroma .  oily jet black with a short lived head and no lace .  mouthfeel : wow this is a big beer with some nice carbonation on it . drinkability : well the alcohol taste was a little bit too much , but its wonderful mouthfeel just blew my mind .

s - smells fantastic - sweet malt , dark fruit ( raisin , plum ) , spice ( perhaps cinnamon ? somewhat disappointing following the aroma . nonetheless , it is enjoyable and worth a try .  pours a clear , mild amber with little to no head .  gorgeous mouthfeel .

although it smells amazing , fresh , and hoppy , there is little to no initial flavor ... wait for the lingering hoppy finish ! appearance : clear , golden , light foamy head smell : incredible . piney , earthy , hops .  poured from bottle into tulip glass a- another dark brew with a decent head that disappears quickly .  mouthfeel : a perfect amount of carbonation .

this beer tastes like soap - similar to blue moon . this did wonders ... not so bad ... it is now on the same level as squaw piss with some sugar added ; i 'll drink it .  this darker chestnut-amber brew had very little head formation .  perfect mouthfeel , actually .

it looks like urine after you 've had a few too man steelback draughts . it smells like the dumpster behind a mexican restaurant in that there 's a somewhat alcoholic scent with undertones of corn tortillas . make that rotting corn tortillas .  short lived head and virtually no lacing .  m : lovely viscous feel . perfect .

s : the most delicious hops aromas that i 've smelled to date are pouring from this brew . this is balanced nicely with a sweet candy/bubblegum aroma and hints of citrus and alcohol . the taste is better than many beers , however , i felt let down after the great aromas . m : full bodied with just the right amount of carbonation .  good little head dies a little quick .  m- surprisingly creamy with the visible amount of carbonation . very smooth . d- very drinkable and smooth .

smells fantastic . loads of caramel , toffee , dried fruits , nuts , and earthy hops with wisps of roasted and toasted malts .  it pours a nice amber , with a nice bit of white head that soon fades into obscurity .  the carbonation is medium and perfect . mouthfeel is great .

strangely enough the combination works to produce a pleasing aroma that is lactic with sour grape notes through the back . this brew smelled awesome but fell a bit short in the flavor .  a rather pale looking yellow beer , with not much carbonation evident .  the feel is smooth , full , creamy and rich ( without being overly thick ) . nice texture , coating .

smell is just exceptional . a sweet juicy hop aroma fills the air above the glass .  12 oz green and yellow aluminum bottle . pours out golden yellow , with a creamy marshmallow white head .  taste : toast , caramel , white pepper , coffee bean , tons of malt , chocolate , banana , vanilla bean , ripe strawberry - the most flavor i 've gotten out of a brown ale mouthfeel : soft , calming mouthfeel with nice smooth tannins leaving the mouth coated with a slowly vanishing flavor profile that 's rather fun to dissect .

a very average looking ipa , the selling point is the flavor and aroma , fresh citrus and pine engulf the senses with much pleasure . some super hoppy brews are n't easy drinkers but this is n't one of those .  i 've been drinking beer for 20+ years now and always come back to heineken.i 've brewed my own for years in the late 80's.the taste is exceptional.some call it skunky but i feel it has hoppy and yet a malty flavor that is light and somewhat dry.what can i say , i like it.i 've also had better but i feel this one deserves credit.it is entirely smooth.i enjoy stout and pale ale also but heineken ca n't be denied .  also was surprised by how creamy this went down . this is a pleasure on the tongue .

smell : that great balsamic vinegar aroma was present , but with an extra spicy cinnamon in a quelquechose kind of way , with a touch of musk and just enough alcohol to make me think i was smelling an old bottle of perfume i found in some dusty attic .  a : clear amber . not much head - could be due to pour .  mf & d - sticky and delicious . just the right amount of carbonation and alcohol content to keep the porter balanced .

a : pours a very dark amber , can barely see through it , thick white head , copious lacing around glass s : loads of aromatic hops in the piney variety , some citrus , little to no malt presence ( dominated by these delicious smelling hops ) . this has an excellent smell ! t : taste pretty much matches nose , a walloping of piney hops with a little more depth than what i could smell . has a nice spicieness to it .  a fairly vigorous pour gave a small , light brown head that dissipated quickly . the body otherwise looked like cold coffee .  creamy , almost soupy mouthfeel .

rich aroma of chocolate , coffee , dark fruit and a hint of alcohol . the aroma is every bit as good as any other ris i have sampled . absolutely enjoyable ris from weyerbacher .  thanks for the opportunity ... poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a minimal 1/4 '' beige head over the amber brew . head fades to a layer of bubbles , with scant lacing as well .  very nice on the palate a very full and pleasing mouthfeel .

i thoroughly enjoy this beer , and i think i might rank it among my favorites , ( although it would be towards the lower end ) . ( this review reflects solely the bottle ) a- nice brown colour , pours translucent brown settles with slight off white head that vanishes fairly quickly . s- i dont particularly care for the smell , i find it to be full of mineral notes . d- a very nice beer as a whole .  disappointed head formation , just a few bubbles on top . light copper colored body , nice and clear , not much carbonation coming to the surface .  the lack of carbonation really helps the mouthfeel of this .

it smells roasty , the way a brewery smells when you take a tour . inviting . spicy bitterness up front , and not too much else .  the beer was pretty normal looking but did not smell like an ipa .  perfect . overall , i think it 's really nice beer and i 'm enjoying it .

very much exceptional . incredible ; this stout , like parabola is just ace with the chocolate .  poured into a pint glass from he bottle very average looking beer light off amber with a nice head that disapates quickly leaveing a nice laceing down the glass smell is supurb big hop nose with some sweeter fruit notes and come more lemon citrus flavor is amazing as well the hops are huge in the front and middle that gives way to a nice bitter finish and a small hint of sweetness at the very back end .  wonderful body .

the smell is divine . i hope it tastes just like that . very nice . coffee up front , but not overwhelming everything else , a solid amount of hershey 's kiss in there ( the dark chocolate ones , ha ! ) , then the roasted malts come roaring in like a posse of fbi agents in a bad climax to an episode of miami vice .  on draft @ funky buddha no carbonation , head or lacing , the reason for average on appearance .  mouthfeel is a regal velvet ( likely due to the oatmeal ) , coating the mouth with a smooth creamy layer . so smooth . excellent .

s : honey dominates the aroma with floral notes toward the end , not bad . the aroma got me hopeful but the flavor was just awful .  beer pours a cloudy middle-brown like the ice teas you see in the plastic bottles . head is active and fizzy , like a coke , and it fades just as quickly . following the tart shock i picked up a nice blend of spruce/juniper and pear .  mouthfeel is creamy and exceptionally full , yet really heavy , on the lighter side , and very soft . mouthfeel was clearly the biggest beneficiary of the addition of the bivalves .

wow . there 's plenty going on here . i literally sat here sniffed uncovering a new scent every time . amazing ! tastes of nougat initially . the entire mix is quite curious , but begs you to drink more to uncover further complexities and intricacies . comes off as a highly unique english barleywine to my tastes .  thanks to eric for busting out this rarity ... light black that still has brown on the edge . hardly any carbonation ... the aroma is super buttery , actually pretty good .  the mouthfeel is great , perfectly coating .

the smokey aroma is noticeable already . the taste is so heavily smokey , it is overwhelming any other tastes and aromas . mouthfeel is ashtray-y .  pours a deep mahogany with very little head and no lacing .  mouthfeel is a great chewy , creamy and smooth ale , the way a brown ale should be .

every sip is beautifully complimented by the floral , sweet scent in the glass . more of a beer experience than a beer indulgence ... nice to say i tried it , and enjoyed it , but not at all drinkable on a multi-bottle level . i see it 's charm , and i 'll bang it.. but i will not propose .  pale golden color-touch of haze . great aroma-really `` catty '' as the brits like to call it . grassy , straw-like . a very drinkable beer-one of the better offerings from magic hat in my opinion .  mouthfeel- creamy and a bit thick . super smooth and very drinkable .

skunky nose .  it poured a dark yellow , more like brownish color that was hazy . the head built up quickly and then dissipated just as quickly .  there is the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

smell-like a slice of pumpkin pie as soon as i opened the bottle the aroma of nutmeg , cinnamon and of course pumpkin , exactly what a pumpkin ale should smell like .  pours a clear and crisp very pale straw color topped by a fizzy there-and-gone white head . enough funk to make things interesting .  m : surprisingly light and smooth . excellent for style .

went down to spuyten duyvil and figured i would have a gueuze during the night . the aroma was the big prize here . i could have kept smelling it all night , but i really wanted to taste it as well . i got a big whiff of apricot tartness in the smell and a large amount of barnyard funk . flavorwise this was quite nice , sweeter than i figured it would be , but it also had a sour quality that was much appreciated . this was the fruitiest gueuze i have ever tasted .  a - pours dark brown with a tan head that dissipates quickly . a bit underwhelming , visually .  mouthfeel is amazingly smooth . almost creamy , but not annoyingly so . very good . overall it 's pretty good , the mouthfeel is great .

a : creamy tan head , almost like a rootbeer float , lots of lacing as mentioned , but not the sexy kind ; deep , deep auburn color s : not much aroma to speak of , honestly ; banana bread combo of spice , malt , but i found myself wanting more t : buttery toffee , hints of a plumlike fruitiness , very nutty and a lingering bitterness that reminds me of ... molasses ?  this beer pours a mysteriously dirty brown color , almost reddish around the edges , with a thin head .  excellent mouthfeel .

it 's very similar to pliny in aroma and i consider that the ultimate compliment . great flavor to complement the aroma .  pretty much pitch black with a light tan head that is fairly compact and somewhat persistent .  $ 11.88 a : near opaque with ever-so-slight deep copper color peeking through , poured nice brown head that dissipated within time s : mild nose , treacle , roasted malt and oak t : mellow , well-aged with leathery oak up front and nice , deep roasted malt with a bit more hop bite than expected , etoh is noticeable and deep whiskey is dominant m : chocolate , oak , velvety and creamy with a nice light hop bitterness finish o : very good beer

smell - intense . can smell the malts with a hint of hops and definitely the bourbon . a bit dry and the oak lingered over everything .  the beer pours to a nice coppery amber color . very little head .  feel is very nice - medium bodied with plenty of carbonation . the carbonation makes the beer feel so smooth in the mouth .

very pleasing smell . t : again , very sweet and boozy .  pours a nice hazed-copper with a finger of dissipating white head . not a lot of lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky , creamy texture . the mouthfeel of this beer is one of the best i have encountered in a beer .

aroma is absolutely great . big chocolatey sweet roasted malts and complex floral overtones . quite nice . chocolate and some whiskey-like flavors .  the appearance is nothing special , dark black , no head to speak of , but looks a bit syrupy .  m : really nice and unique .

smell & gt ; absolutely fabulous . i want to eat the nonic glass . it 's malty and rich . sweet like turbinado sugar , with a smidge of alcohol .  pours off-yellow with a little orange in it - no head whatsoever .  touches of carbonation throughout , the mild breakups of tingling yield a remarkably smooth bevvy .

fruity ( mango/guava ) oak and earthy undertones . an amazingly complex and enjoyable ipa thats sweeter than your normal ipa and could use a dose of bittering to completely round it out .  a - hazy medium to dark brown . not much head at all .  this has a very good mouthfeel .

taste- sweet , tropical fruits as in the nose , hop bitterness . feel- medium carbonation.. creamy ... yummy overall this is a really good ipa ... kind of reminds me of union jack .  poors a much clearer copper then i would expect with a big clingy head .  full bodied . perfect . the oats add some awesome smoothness .

smell - not a very potent odor . smells of alcohol a bit with a little bit of fruit possibly , but not very strong at all .  bright golden beer that has a slight haze . moderately tall white head does n't hold for long .  mouthfeel is exceptional , very smooth and soft carbonation and is not cloying or sticky on the palate , has a relatively dry finish .

nose is rich thick and chalked full of browny like chocolatey sweetness , which is a lovely experience all its own .  from a brown bottle with a artistic painting of mostly naked people . in a word , wow . pours a somewhat unatractive poopy brown , the only negative .  mouthfeel is amazing . velvety .

smells . awesome . bourbon leaps upon the nose carrying licorice , vanilla , molasses and raisin . honestly my first thoughts ( following `` wow , this is good stuff '' ) were this is founder 's kbs done belgian style .  pours from a 375ml bottle into a cantillon tulip . pours a very deep dark ruby/plum dark purple color that is completely opaque and still with only the faintest bubble or two of carbonation .  the mouthfeel fits this beauty of a beer - it is thick and pleasingly rich . the full amount of suggested aging did this beauty wonders .

it is a pleasant smell though , let 's see how it tastes .  faux hazed golden rod beer when looking through it at an angle , with good clarity when viewed at eye level . not much of a head at all and what there is is white .  mouthfeel is silky and full with a dry finish that reminds me of a light red wine .

s : this beer has a overwhelming aroma . it 's extremely rich , yet smooth . one of the sweetest beers i 've ever drank , but it is still well balance and taste exactly how it smells . definately a sipping beer .  this is a good solid beer.good thick mouthfull but goes down smooth.and it has a very good taste very well balanced.plus its hard to go wrong with a sam adams product..taste good from a bottle but is much more enjoyable from a tap.either way this beer will help take the edge off a bad day .  the mouthfeel is fantastic , crisp , clean , refreshing , but tasty as well . highly dirnkable , i think drinkable best describes this beer .

a wonderful , piney smell with alcohol that is balanced well with the malt . exceptional taste , which is similar to the smell . does n't taste like a double but a well balanced , very hearty ipa .  p : ruddy brown body , darker in the center . very small , light brown head . very fizzy . right up there with hazelnut brown nectar as my favorite brown .  m - the shining characteristic of this brew is the well-balanced mouthfeel that 's thick and viscous but nice and smooth . i wish more stouts had the balls big john does , in terms of the mouthfeel .

a very delightful smell . some traces of malt in the background , but this is all about the hops .  pours a dusky , golden-peach hue with a bit more yeast haziness than is appropriate for the style . plus , the minuscule egg-carton white head recedes quickly to a thin wisp and ring of foam ... not much lacing or retention .  t/m : a silky mouthfeel , with a smooth mellow finish . the finish is a crazy good bold , non-carbonated brown sugar smoothness that can not be beat . a mellow body with the sweetness of brandy , this is truly a great brew .

beautiful nose t - great complex flavor comprising smoked meats , dark fruits and apples and various barrels .  can , generously donated by a buddy of mine , as a cloudy , amber-brown . one inch head of dense , rocky foam that settles very slowly . the only drawback from this beer 's appearance is that it 's color seems a bit too dark for an ipa . smell is very hoppy with spicy , evergreen aromas .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy and everything i could ask for . the tartness keeps pulling you in like a siren , and i am totally captivated by her song .

the smell is sweet and grainy , but i noticed no distinct honey scent in the smell .  into a pint glass this yields a very dark brown , black really , with not much of a head .  all things considered , a perfect mouthfeel .

s : the smell is pretty poor . wheat , straw , malt .  a : pours a hazy golden/orange color . a small white head forms , and recedes in a second .  mouthfeel plays a big part in the taste , with the just-right amount of carbonation spreading the tastiness around and the nice medium body giving the brew a very creamy character .

aroma is of bitter orange peel and spicy yeast . smell is wonderful . upon sipping , the first thing that struck me was the medium to heavy body on this one .  porus a rich chestnut-amber color with a minimal head that is reduced to a soapy rim after a couple seconds . mild lacings and no retention .  m - fantastic mouthfeel ; one of the best imperial stouts out there in this respect .

complex sour with tropical aromas . nice lacy appearance in the chalice with good carbonation in the mouth . what is that suddenly familiar aroma ? i flashed on cutting a passion fruit in half and smelling it . more nose of pineapple guava . one of the best and most interesting beers i 've tried this year .  rather flat pour , with poor head retention .  exceptional mouthfeel - almost perfect , no , actually perfect ! smells & tastes great - nice carapills caramel sweetness after a trip on the c hops ( cascade for sho ' ) train .

the aroma is just exploding with flavors , very nice ! t- the taste starts out smooth with some roasted malts .  33 cl bottle into an orval chalice , a : pours a ruddy sepia with small white head , solid retention .  mouthfeel is top notch though , smooth as hell , velvety , chewy and creamy , medium-bodied and showing a perfect amount of carbonation .

what a wonderful smell ! very nice . this was n't the easiest beer to drink , probably because of its high alcohol content , but it was certainly very , very tasty .  pours a light rusty-red color with a few bubbles on the initial pour and not much in the way of a head or lacing .  m : this beer is full and lush . it is almost chewy . the carbonation is noticeable .

smell : a smorgasboard of aromas starts attacking you from the moment you open the bottle . chocolate ( s ) , coffee , caramel , alcohol hitting on you with no mercy . fantastic ! i love it anyway .  small white head , poor retention , and no lace .  this beer is full bodied and velvety smooth . it is a little high in alcohol , but the smooth mouthfeel and nice flavor would go a long way .

actually quite complex when i dig deeper . vanilla makes itself present as well as a little wine musk . t= really really nice . great tartness in it that is a refreshing bite but it is n't the only component of it .  pours like 15,000 mile motor oil with 1 finger of cocoa colored head . average head retention & lacing s : dark chocolate , raisins , & a touch of leafy hops & then some figs & oak notes as this warms t : rich dark chcolate , a touch of roastyness , a bit of leafy hops & charred grains up front .  m : great silky smooth feel . definitely a creamy feel .

s : beautiful , juicy , pungent , and slightly spicy grapefruit oils . nice fruity esters throughout and a fresh floral hop scent . d : the taste was a bit of a let down after enjoying the smell for a few minutes .  wow , finally flying fish released this ambrosia of the gods ! flying fish , please makemoreof this and more often ! the pint glass came to me without a hint ofhead or foam , which lead me to believe what 's up ? after a sniff of the top of the glass the sweetness came back , and after a long , deep sip , the maltiness and the hint of bourbon traveled to my satisfied belly ! ! !  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

well , without being rude , i 'll just say that i 've been smelling a lot of really good beer lately and the smell is ... dissimilar . unoffensive .  exhibits a golden body with a reddish tinge . not a lot of head , but plenty of dancing bubbles as i tilt the glass .  mouthfeel : full-bodied . medium carbonation . very soft and velvety on the tongue , like the texture of melted chocolate ice cream .

s : great smell , oak , vanilla , wine grapes , brown sugar . t : taste is outstanding as well .  a : pours a dark mahogany with sightly less than one finger of head which quickly dissipates .  m= really smooth tastes really smooth . really nice . smooth crisp clean and sweet at the same time .

guinness is the original starter for any stout fan for sure , was the very 1st stout i have ever tasted and is what got me started for being a stout fan . smells has a bit of coffee icecream smell too it with bit of a alcohol kick .  a : pours a dark amber color with a half-finger of head that recedes into a light film on the brew . no lacing to speak of .  a big dose of chocolate . so let 's do up the chocolate . some malts and some hops , all to support the chocolate . smooth and creamy .

the smell has a bit of a harse tone and i am not a fan .  the head dissipates quickly and leaves no real lacing . this not a very attractive color for a beer .  mouthfeel is superb , creamy , velvety , perhaps the best i 've had for this style .

this brown ale drinks like a light beer . it has almost no carbonation , it has no bite , very easy to swallow ( which i must admit is refreshing ) if not for the near perfect balance of bitter/sweet after-taste i could almost flunk it .  on-tap at beachwood i , a : pours a ruby plum brown with a mild white head , fair retention , no lace .  creamy palate , just awesome . not as cedary as i 'd expected given the title , but i like the subtlety .

there is something `` fresh '' about the aroma that makes it so memorable , a fresh breeze of mint and pine . superb . taste is very sour with a nice red berries twist but not very funky with a very dry finish . a lambic for the purist , maybe a little bit too sour and dry for me but still excellent .  serving type : 11.2fl oz bottle appearance : pours a extremely dark brown ( almost black ) , sadly w/ no head though .  mouthfeel , on the other hand , is superb . medium thickness , outstanding creaminess and richness .

damn , this smells good . big roasty malts compete with all that chocolate on the palate for quite a while , with nondescriptly bitter hops and a little alcohol warmth bringing up the rear . while the chocolate on the nose smells sweet and milky , in the mouth it 's an equal mix of bitter and sweet , which is just awesome . very well balanced , and you could drink it until the 11 % abv says otherwise .  appearance : no head retention , dark amber colour , not really pale looking at all smell : delicate flowery hopps , very inviting taste : immediate strong bitter taste which eases off after a few seconds , and then the malt begins to show itself .  mf is creamy , and quite nice .

s-not much to speak of , a little malty . t-pretty darned good . rich malt followed by a nice soapy hop bitterness . very well balanced in the malt to hop ratio .  a - it pours a transparent golden amber with a thin white head that disappates fairly quickly s - fruity , citrusy hops upfront balenced fairly well by a mild , but sweet , malt backbone t - a great balence of pine and citrus hit you up front and quickly fade into a semi-sweet finish m - light bodied and refreshing .  effortlessly coats the mouth completely and finishes sticky & sweet with a bit more of the peppery hops .

i 'm most impressed by the incredible aroma but i 'd buy this regularly if it was available in my market .  pours a hazy brown almost an amber color with good head and some lace .  m - beautiful mouthfeel and impressive balance for such a powerful brew .

smell : not a lot of smell to it , the orange got in the way of a proper sniff . some grain notes , and citrus , but that last could be from the orange . mouthfeel : not that thick , and actually feels fuzzy , as odd as that sounds .  pours deeper golden color than others . very clear . thin white head dissapated to a ring .  feel is thick yet subtle soft and a fairly easy clean finish . this beer is a politician : drinkability talks an easy talk but once this gets going , the abv will lie and before you know it ... . thanks to our fellow ba resident calvinist geofffromsj who astutely taught me today that `` jesus saves , moses invests .

not in a bad way just not as unfiltered as i would have expected . overall it is extremely enjoyable . one of the better beers that i have had this summer .  330ml brown bottle , best before sep 2012 , poured into a 'hoegaarden grand cu ' stemmed tulip . good reddy brown colour , head soon left leaving a tan coloured collar and a few pieces of lacing as the beer level fell .  smooth on the way down and a very dry finish . this stuff is heavy and good .

nose has plenty of nice hops , lots of citrus , bit of tropical fruit , light fresh hop resin , grapefruit , pineapple , guava , lots of fresh tropical fruits . taste starts a bit creamy actually , a light malty base starts to come through , bringing a slight sweetness , but that is quickly cut down by the heavy hops , a strong bitterness starts to come through , lots of fresh musty hop resins , some tropical fruits , lots of citrus , light orange rind , hop oils , it even starts to get a little astringent , and the malty base has disappeared really quickly , leaving the hops alittle flat , almost like drinking hop water .  fizzy 2 '' head ... drops quick and leaves only spotty lacing ... hazy copper amber brew .  perfect carbonation , which i am growing to expect from oskar blues .

i get some raisin and vanilla in the middle and molasses , chocolate , and black licorice on the backend . awesome ! perfect !  a : red tan with no discernible head .  mouthfeel : excellent . thick yet balanced with the carbination .

appearance- a light clear golden color about a fingers worth of white head and good lacing smell- the aromas of this beer is just exceptional , the noble hops aroma is just perfectly balanced , it is everything i would look for in a pils in terms of aroma taste- the taste of this beer is clean bittersweet that is well balanced it is clean and refreshing on so many levels mouthfeel- this beer has good body and good carbonation balance drinkability- this is one of the best beers ive had and is a perfect spring/early summer seasonal beer it is very refreshing a must try !  the beer is cloudy and not see through . looks to be golden in the light .  supremely smooth . it 's just silky smooth across the tongue , the carbonation working to prevent it from becoming syrupy .

the beer malt character shows off with lots of chocolate ... the taste is not dominated by the bourbon sadly as even though it was strong i was excited . the malts show through here in a creamy fashion , cream , vanilla and some chocolate ... the beer is to light on the palate but pretty easy to drink . one of the better beers of the night .  upon opening the bottle i noticed a rather clear appearance , but the smell was heavenly . it was not pungent like a bud light or something along those lines , but light , and with a pleasant strawberry aroma . while i imagine pure drinkers might be ashamed to have this in their hand , i really recommend forgetting your pride for a minute and giving this amazing brew a shot .  medium bodied and very creamy . carbonation is perfect .

theres a wonderful aroma of sweet grapefruit . overall , this is an excellent and extremely enjoyable pale ale , with its low hop bitterness and strong citrus hop aroma . i love it . i highly recommend this beer .  some sour notes that make me think of dry white wine , spicy hints and some grass and gooseberries . the colour is gold ( 14 ebc ) , the liquid is clear . the finger thick head is off-white and compact . it sinks quickly leaving some lacing . a very refreshing beer with an unusual hop profile !  not as strong as i anticipated from the aroma and color , but the flavors pop out very easily m : very smooth , almost like milk and very full bodied with a low amount of carbonation . there is a creaminess that lingers on the forefront of the mouth for a few seconds d : very drinkable for a stout beer .

it 's about time i got around to this one ; pours a hazy deep garnet brown , with a exceptionally large tan head and lacing that clings to my glass ; wow smell is unbelievable great sent of hops , and as it warms a bit many complex smells occur , mainly a fruity , almost hot alcohol smell but a pleasing one , a darker fruit and caramelized malt undertone , some hop aroma present as well , a faint bubble-gum too ; a sweet , spicy , crisp taste , not what i 'd expected however , i may need to age a bottle a decent belgian malty flavor , i taste a bit of plum/licoriceish in that , but something not as pleasant ( cardboardish ? ) after the initial taste , a nice aromatic effect tho , i 'm not sure how to describe a blend of bread and toasted kiwi ; a dry , surprisingly light body w/ mad dextrins , and awesome co2 ; an extremely drinkable beer , i really wish i had more , although i think this one may be a bit overrated  a-poured a clear and slightly reddish-amber w/modest head .  rich , velvety mouthfeel , unctuous and puckering .

a- red brown body with an airy off-white head s- spices and fruit , very inviting ! sweet delicate fruit t- spices , bready malts , more sweet spices , alcohol warming m- medium-bodied , good carbonation and alcohol warming d- that nose is great ! a nice beer and the high abv makes it a sipping beer  pours a murky persimmon brown . not much head , just a thin showing of center carbonation .  much lighter body than the bottle of extra stout i just had ; also a little more tart which was what i was looking for . roasted malts and hard water . mouthfeel is where it really shines . smooth like silk . goes down like water .

i really like this scent , it has a very strong oak and bourbon presence with the malts giving it a strong backbone . taste on the other hand , lacks behind the wonderful scent . starts watery with some sweet sugars , oak and coffee . this beer had a lot going for it initially , a nice appearance and great aroma . at first i was pleased with the taste , but the finish and lingering flavors almost ruined the beer for me .  this poured a nice clear copper with a little white head .  first sip reveals a rich and firmly textured beer of elegant character . an encore presence by the hops closes out the taste in a long and seamless finish . faultless balance , beautiful complexity both in the nose and on the tongue make this beer , in my opinion , a perfect desert beer or soothing winter warmer .

it feels very uncomfortable .  it 's non existent . i do n't really care for wine but this smells great ! tast is very similar to red wine , though far more sweet .  superb . d - this is a tasty beer , but the fusel alcohol character and high alcohol in general make me appreciate it less fully .

smells glorious . definately a unique mixture of piney citrus and floral hops . very enjoyable . mouthfeel : a tad tart and carbony with a big soda style bite followed by big hop oilyness .  i 've had sam adams blackberry witbier , sam adams cherry wheat , lancaster brewing compnay strawberry wheat , and god help me bud lime but this is one fruit i did n't need in my beer .  very full , creamy body that 's quite impressive for the abv .
smell - delicious citrus high notes with an almost overpowering burst of hops .  poured a medium amber with a small head .  light and full in the mouth , just a lovely feel .
very nice complex , yet clean nose .  pours a cloudy light amber color , as with most beers of this style .  perfect for the style .

s : what a wonderful dessert smell ; a combination of vanilla , caramel and coffee ice cream . t : taste is super sweet roasted toffee malts with a generous helping of vanilla and some powdered cocoa , even . it tastes sort of spot on as a creme brulee , but i think i might have liked the aroma better than the taste here .  pours a cloudy murky reddish brown with a one finger bubbly beige head that slowly recedes .  m- the mouthfeel is fantastic . full bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

s - surprisingly little aroma , some spice notes and citrus sweetness , but it 's not very potent . t - very complex for an amber , i was pleasantly caught off guard by all the flavors .  a - black and thick with no head , no ring or cap ; very little lacing s - french roasted coffee or espresso ; slightly earthy smell from da base ; some light toffee t - wow .  dark coffee , bittersweet chocolate , toffee , dark wheat bread , smoke , spices that are tough to identify but clearly at work ... all mingled together in perfect measure . super smooth and velvety , although not what i would call creamy . largely because the body is n't a heavy one , but this texture comes with a terrific caress that does not leave me wanting .

s- big nose of hops mostly pine and grassy . hard to pick much else out through the hops but some roasted malt and caramel is hiding in there . t- big blast of floral hops right away that lasts through to the finish . hops change in character from floral to bitter at the finish . some notes of malt , chocolate , and caramel at the finish as well but hidden behind the bitterness of the hops . finish is astringent , boozy and with the lingering feeling of the hop oil .  bottle dated oct , 2011 ... poured into 6oz whiskey glass a- dark brown with blood orange hints , clear liquid and a cm of light cream head . settles quickly , leaving a bubbly liquid bare in the glass .  it has a velvety mouthfeel .

s : beautiful full barrel , whiskey notes . oak , great integration , complex . t : heavy , heavy malt , gets sweet at the end but never cloying . elegant . d : this is a magnificent beer and makes me wonder why i waited so long to open this . drinking beautifully .  a : slightly cloudy dark amber with lots of carbonation , with the head slow to dissipate . poured into a tulip .  incredibly smooth and goes down easy .

nose is very roasty . i 've been trying to place this aroma for a while now , and i 'm convinced it is a type of wheat , torrified or roasted or something , but its not roasted barley .  slow pour into a chalice yields a one-finger tan head over a dark brown almost opaque body .  there was a nice hop bitter punch right in the beginning , but then it just mellows out with a malty smoothness that is unreal . mouthfeel is one of a kind , smooth , chewy , sticky ... .very nice . this could be a very dangerous beer as it goes down ultra smooth ... would you like another ?

the look and smell are nothing , boring at best .  pours black & smells like a , a ... tootsie roll . not much head , but a meager swirl brings it , & the massive smell , right back to the hop .  creaminess only found in the most fattening of milk shakes . oppression at its finest . : ) one is perfect for me , thank you .

it smells great . there isnt much head on this one sadly , but the color and smell make up for it . its good but not very balanced . it 's not the most drinkable but its still enjoyable . maybe a little time would balance this puppy out . overall , a good brew .  pours a dark brown color with a thinnish light tan head , fades fast and does n't leave any lacing on the glass .  t - bananas , caramel , and mild dates swim around sour-yeastiness and vanilla , concealing well the alcohol that lies beneath ... m - very , very smooth , medium body massages the palate and dries the cheeks . d - nice , very nice , do n't know if i 'd get it again , but very nice .

this beer has an immense aroma , which sets a high standard that the flavor does n't quite meet .  pours an orange pink like color which is completely translucent .  mouthfeel : wow is this stuff smooth . very silky and perfect carbonation .

the aroma was nice .  undated 12oz purchased at holiday market in canton and poured into a tulip . light hazy blond with minimal head and no real lace .  the mouthfeel is great . what a light and delicate brew .

s - there really is n't a lot of aroma to this beer . a hint of roasted barley , but not very impressive t - there is n't a ton of taste either .  pours a distinctly amberish hue , with a thin head with moderate to low lacing and retention .  mouthfeel is ideal : medium bodied and a medium-high carbonation .

s : amazing , get a ton of hops . citrus and pine just exploding into your senses . t : getting a lot more pin than citrus in the taste , a great piney taste though .  there is no head to speak of nor is there any lacing .  on the first sip , the feel was like i opened my mouth , closed my eyes , and had someone pour silk into my mouth . beautiful . hence the 5 .

appearance - is pretty typical , small head , black and opaque smell - beautiful , vanilla chocolate , so rich and creamy smelling taste - similar to a chocolate malt with vanilla mouthfeel - creamy and thick and very drinkable , i wanted more .  appeared more distinctly ornage in color than many other ipas that day .  mouthfeel is super creamy , milkshake like .

light , hoppy , refreshing= excellent .  despite the seeming lack of head , the carbonation holds its own and provides a fresh , lively beer .  quite unique . perfect mouthfeel - enough creaminess and carbonation to soften the bitterness and create a warm , rich feel .

it smelled of musty and smoky dark malts as well as a deep woody scent . best were the aromatic coffee with bitter chocolate notes . with a medium-bodied mouthfeel , this beer was complex but a bit too rough and way too bitter for the malts and other dark notes .  a : pours dark brown without any head .  m - the feel is surprisingly rich for the genre , smooth and oh so drinkable , nicely done !

s : citrus , very bright ! spicy yeast , apple and pear cider smell , some nutmeg .  pours an amber with some bright white head that fades to a good lace and rebuilds quickly .  mouthfeel is exceptional . thick and rich but not too much .

i detect a latent ginger and maybe nutmeg , but nothing really pronounced . though the beer seems quite confused , it 's also quite elegant . the sourness is balanced by a gorgeous creamy finish that lingers with those ( odd ) spices .  appearance - light brownish red . appears opaque . thin off white head with little persistence .  mouthfeel is very soft and smooth on this medium-heavy brew .

n : nose actually has a lot of coffee , roast , some sweet syrupy malts , dark malts , a touch of vanilla , touch of chocolate . t : starts with a lot of coffee and roasted malts , some chocolate , some fake vanilla flavors , really fake infused vanilla ... very watery too , damn , i was excited thinking this was pretty good until the taste . terrible !  pours a clear golden color with a decent head that settles to a small lacing . typical looking pilsner .  smooth as velvet , i love what oak-aging does to impy stouts .

this beer smells exactly like that avery home blend . sour funk , some brettomyces and the whole barnyard crew jump in . i really like the flavor medium mouthfeel , nice light carbonation overall , heck yes ! i love when avery pulls out a winner and this is a good addition to their portfolio  '' poured a clear straw color , with a modest whie head that dropped in milliseconds . not a terribly great looking beer .  the mouthfeel is delightful . up front the beer is very rich and the oak really shines through with this age on it . nicely mouth coating , and the intense finish with a great deal of carbonation and bitterness refreshes the palate for another sip . love this beer , 2010 and 2011 review to be added another day .

the aroma was incredible and the taste was nearly as good . i will have this one again for sure !  pours dark copper with ruby highlights . when held to the light i get a look at a lot of suspended particles ( probably yeast ) which is a bit odd for the style . a thick , light tan head gradually dissipates to a stubborn lacing on the surface .  a very smooth and creamy cask ale , that goes down very well .
the smell is awesome . think if someone dropped a banana in a glass of orval .  has a light golden color with a 1/2 inch head .  very soft carbonation but a full , chewy body .

the nose is excellent . there are wonderful orange burst hop aroma , some piney evergreen citrus notes , some sweet maltiness underneath , and some hoppy florals too . the nose on the beer is very enticing and pungent , i only wish the taste were as nice as the aroma .  pours a rich golden color with a fizzy head , disapating to nothing , leaves no tracing .  m : thick , syrupy viscosity with light carbonation -- exactly as a beer of this style should be .

the aroma is faint , but has a slight yeast sent .  kate pours a few shades shy of black with abundant mahogany highlights that make up for the lack of pure darkness . not much in the way of a head to admire , but periodic gentle swirls coax the tan skim . lacing is sacrificed in the effort ; scattered streaks and splotches are it .  the mouthfeel is very much like drinking liquid chocolate or marshmallow fluff . so rich , creamy , and very full in the mouth .

weihenstephaner vitus | 500 ml . appearance : hazed , glowing , straw-colored concoction . the massive , wintery head and abundance of fine lace warms the cockles of my heart . aroma : big banana/plantain aroma , peppered with clove , on bready background . taste : nutty , lightly toasted bread , spicy alcohol , fruity banana and asian pear . mouthfeel : sticky , chewy , slick , prickly , sharp . good carbonation . harmony : you 're doused in flavor towards the end of the sip , though the beginning is a bit lackluster . i actually found the taste to be the least endearing aspect . i was blown away by the nose . it works cohesively , though i sense a strong and unfavorable imbalance of flavor towards the end of the sip . the bros. are absolutely right : this is fine on its own but would go oh so well with some fine bread and cheese ( i 'd call for some aged gouda or edam ) .  cracked the bottle and poured into a tulip . the colour is great , but the lack of head is not .  looks like a stout should , dark and opaque , not quite black , with a slight tan head smells like burned caramel cookies tastes like coffee with the forementioned cookies great mouthfeel , not too chewy i could drink a couple of these

s - as i mentioned this beer is pretty funky . great hay and corn husk aroma along with the traditional funky dusty horse blanket . nice grassy hops finish this beer off . t & m - wow what an amazingly delicious brew .  green bottle , a : pours amber with an initial 2 finger head but drops down to a ring quick . no lace .  mouthfeel is perfect , medium bodied with a champagne silkiness that is delectable when swirled .

s : though the body is lacking any type of foam on top , the aroma is very rich of dark fruits and berries with nutty undertones . it has a very pleasant balance between sweet malty caramel and bitter floral hops . t : very sweet and bubbly on the tip of the tongue with a nice contrast of bitterness on the back of the palate and sour on the sides of the tongue .  the cloudy , hazy yellow body on this one has some fairly active carbonation bubbles . this is a nice smelling beer .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is one of the most drinkable beers around .

there is a big creamy chocolate head that retains itself fairly well and leaves a nice amount of lace behind to enjoy smell : just an enormous roasty nose with a huge hop compliment ... basically this nose is explosive and overpowering which is much to my liking . bittersweet dark chocolate and smoky char round out the nose taste : i 'm not getting a whole lot of coffee despite the claim on the bottle ... the flavour profile hits with char , licorice , bittersweet dark chocolate , `` west coast '' grapefruit hops , moderate booze , espresso and cream mouthfeel : big and robust , spicy and boozy drinkability : pretty good  this beer poured a brown color with a thin tan head tight bubbles .  the texture , in its sublime perfection , is creamy like a milkshake ... unbelievable .

s - heavy allspice and orange with a solid yeast backdrop and flower accents t - citrus turns to spice/clove and a bready and apple finish m - very light on the palate if you are ok with the spiciness , too low carbonation d - almost not enough to it , dare i say too `` watery '' i 've had white rascal previously at the avery brewing tap room in boulder , and i do not remember that experience being anything like this tasting .  sighed when it came out , seeing it was a lager , never promising in canada . very pleasantly surprised . very thin head , excellent lacings marking each sip . for me , not a stand-out as far as looks are concerned .  whoa was it thick ! an outstanding beer , i was extremely excited to be able to say i 've tasted it . as it warms in the glass , the bite grows stronger . maybe this brew would be better appreciated by some experienced brewmasters , i thought it was a good beer but i ca n't justify rating it an a+ or 5 , because i would n't buy a bottle again . the two beers that ultimately create this beast are exquisite , but this monster was n't for me .

-a cream colored head sits atop the auburn hued body that paints a great picture of a beer from start to finish -the nose is a bit lacking .  nice beige head that dies too quickly for my tastes . nice reddish brown color , quite clear .  t & m- lush creamy smoothness in a heavenly full body .

aroma : smoky , burnt chocolate . in fact , i think the smell is a good deal more delicious then the taste -- i could enjoy this one from the scent alone . taste : burnt chocolate , roasted grain , some sweetness . honestly , it was a bit of a letdown given the intense chocolaty smell , to be greeted with a taste that had more in common with burnt coffee that cocoa . i could sit and take in the aroma for a while , but the comparatively disappointing taste means i probably wo n't be having these too often .  poured in sam adams sensory glass . color is a straw pale yellow .  this one is thick and chewy , coats the inside of the mouth , and the flavors linger , especially the burnt coffee .

sweet aroma overall , extremely enjoyable . probably one of the best smelling ris i 've ever put my nose to .  pours dark brown with a small quickly fading head .  mouthfeel is smooth and heavy bodied with a very light carbonation , excellent .

s- mmmm , ruuum . but , the smoke still comes through underneath the rum . t- this is really quite nice , almost liquor-ish because of the lack of carbonation ( there is just the tiniest amount ) nice smokiness upfront with the sweet tanginess of the rum dominating the palate in the middle all the way to the finish .  poured from a bottle into a mug , this looks pretty average at first .  texture is silky smooth and it does n't feel nearly as strong as it actually is .

smells simply delightful ! pronounced citric ( grapefruit ) hops and a modest sweetness . most impressive . golden amber with pert near 100 % clarity and a large creamy head . light dms / veggitation sensation , may just be the hops though .  almost no haze at all to this golden-ish brew . fluffy bright white head is `` to specs , '' but i want to know that this sucker is alive and well .  mouthfeel : omigaw , it 's so creamy . so very , very creamy . `` luscious '' is the word that comes to mind .

the scent of this one really is part of the enjoyment , it just smells great . it seems to give you a representation of the quality and freshness . it really is delightful . it feels creamy in my mouth without being too heavy .  nice head , but not long lasting .  the body is surprisingly thick and coating with a rich slick mouth feel .

aroma is a very nice mix of scents . sweet pears , apples and plums mix perfectly with citrusy and piney hops . quite a nice brew that i recommend to all barleywine fans out there .  it looks really flat , with a black center and brown edges .  mouthfeel is beautiful with sweetness up front followed by a sting from carbonation and finishing with a crisp dry bitterness .

quite a weak smell though . sadly though the weak smell makes the points go down .  appearance : pours an extremely dark brown , with some light coming through when held to light . less than a finger of light tan head formed after a pretty hard pour , and that dissipated pretty quickly . kind of disappointing in the looks department , actually ... smell : holy crap , this is a beautiful aroma .  feels great . 5/5 d : yes , for the style and abv , it is .

just like winter snow always seems to vanish too rapidly , this head diminishes to some spots of white around the rim of the glass . the scent is remarkably sweet , it 's actually cocktail like , or am i being blinded by the fact that it 's a caribbean beer . a tropical fruit juice mix describes it best .  on tap at the brewers guild fest , summer 2010 . spicy pepper heat , bell pepper aromas and some how some tomato . it leaves a nice tingly heat that builds and lingers all the way down the throat .  very smooth . mouthfeel is full and round .

there was very little aroma to sample with this one -- a little malty , but not strong at all .  a pale golden/amber ale with a decent lacing , sea dog opens with a delicious bouquet of fresh blueberries .  mouthfeel is top notch , so smooth and light yet complex at the same time .

ok retention and lacing ... the aroma is very unique and enticing . a great balance of some many things going on , smoke , sweet oak , scotch , vanilla and dark chocolate . however , this is still pretty good .  dark brown liquid with hints of cordovan - when held to a light , it is revealed as clear with fulvous highlights . very slight head despite a vigorous pour - more likely a fault of the serving type , though this is still quite fresh .  a nice , balanced beer with a clean taste and a smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .

this is interesting , very hoppy and bitter for the body , but clean , tasty , and light at the same time . the aroma is very nice and very german , bready very herbal with a little lemon and a hint of pine .  on-tap at fff . a- murky brown with a thin bubbly off white head . looks like apple cidar .  the mouthfeel is exceptional , big thick viscous and sticky and is amazingly velvety over my palate . really quite incredible .

o : this aroma of this beer is amazing . it is like diving into a basket of fresh raspberries .  pours a murky orange with a 1/2 inch white head that fades to nothing .  m : silky and creamy . d : i 've never had more than one chocolate stout at a time , and so i do n't know if i would get sick of a beer if i overdid it .

bottled oct 3rd , 2011 - consumed oct 19th , 2011 a : nice clear light golden amber with a thick creamy white head that laces the glass very nicely and stays around throughout the beer s : wonderful citrus and grass hop aroma coming off the top . very clean hop aroma .  live review 12oz bottle poured into delirium tremens tulip a-murky brown with almost soda like tan head that dissipated rather quickly into a thin ring .  m - the mouthfeel of this brew is really nice .

absolutely fantastic . taste is surprisingly sour .  the beer had a light tawny body , with a thin but persistent glass ring , but unfortunately had weak lacing .  carbonation is perfect . with such a fantastic mouthfeel and perfectly bittersweet flavor profile , this is a breeze to put down .

smell : not much to speak of . slightest citrus hops and a hint of dry malt . nothing terribly special , but enjoyable overall .  appearance : reddish brown colored . no head .  m- full bodied , creamy , thick luscious mouthfeel .

s : pine , soft citrus , christmas spruce/fir , grapefruit , smells a lot like the inside of a christmas tree , wonderful . t : piney definitely , this is the dominant flavor , some soft grapefruit , and citrus , and a little too much ethanol in the end for my tastes , but overall very good .  wonderful pale yellow color with big bubbles that disappeared as quickly as they usually do in japanese lagers .  4.5 m : thick , surprisingly thick and velvety , dry , warm alcohol , excellent . 5 d : easy drinking beer for the strength , excellent flavors , balance of spice and malts is nice , really a great beer .

the aroma is loaded with dark toasted malts with caramel , toffee and dark fruits . wow , the malts seem to explode into your nose . the taste like the aroma is dominated by the toasted malts with plums , toffee and caramel . wow , this brew is nothing short of delicious !  this is a very interesting beer from dogfish head . you 'll either love or hate this one . pours a very pale , clear , light yellow color , similar to a white whine or champagne . i 'm not a huge fan of peaches but this pleased me .  the mouthfeel is astounding . with all the charged up carbonation , i was expecting a soda like fizzy mouthfeel , but i am pleased at the silky smooth , well rounded and succulent body of this ale .

beautifully strong citrusy hop aroma . very well balanced taste , with grapefruit hops , then resiny pine needle taste and then a superb malt finish .  look , no beer snob is gon na score a malt liquor over a c something . a : nice looking , unique bottle . i like the bee with the stinger out , it 's for you , beer snob who is too good for this legendary beverage !  m- huge in the mouth chewy , creamy , and smooth . mild carbonation . nice clean finish , indicative of the nice alcohol levels .
s : sweet smelling chocolate notes that a very pungent .  the appearance was slightly cloudy with very little head but long alcohol legs .  m : feels great . perfect amount of carbonation .

beautiful translucent amber-orange beer , with some great head retention/lacing . fantastic orangey-lemony hop flavor , slight bitterness , a bit of pine , light spice . this is one of magic hat 's best ! about $ 8.50 a sixer .  poured black into a snifter . next to no head .  mouthfeel is light bodied and creamy smooth with a powerful refreshing carbonation .

almost no smell to speak of .  appearance : pours a slightly hazy deep gold with a thin , wispy head .  the mouthfeel is the ultimate strongpoint on this beer . it is ridiculously creamy and very chewy , complemented with the perfect amount of carbonation .

in the glass it smelled like sewer water and did n't taste any better .  not really any lacing to talk about and looks slightly watery .  mouthfeel is exceptional . big , small foam mouth , which smooths down , edgy all the way -- but never sharp .

not much in the way of aroma . tastes of dark roasted malt with just a little burnt bitterness .  dark brown/ruby colored . thin dirt brown head that vanishes instantly .  may be a bit heavy heavy for some people to consider for a session , or for a really hot day- due to the thickness of the mouthfeel , but this is damn freakin good .

surprisingly nice smell . nice balanced smell of hops with a finish of citrus and grapefruit .  big cheers to gnomeking for this pours a slightlty hazy amber/tea coior with a 3 fingers deep sand colored head . minimal lacing & zerohead retention .  mouthfeel is light medium and pretty smooth , crisp .

s : nose is barely detectable on any level and i really have to breathe deep to get anything . slight hints of lemon rind , wood , cobwebs , and cheesiness . not aromatic at all and this one barely smells of anything even after it warms up . nose could use some work but overall , a very solid lambic and one i would n't hesitate to pick up and age at some point .  pours out a clear dark golden with white head that goes down quickly to a small ring around the beer .  m- good smoothness in mouthfeel .

maybe it was just my nose or the particular can i bought , but there really wasn & # 8217 ; t any distinct aroma that i could smell . taste was fairly simple , some sweet malts with a hoppy aftertaste .  pours an amber clear color with nice initial size head . head dissapates quickly to a bubbly ring and leaves mild thin lacing .  nice and heavy feel . too big and lacking flavors from the malts to balance off the alcohol and bourbon .
the aroma is very hoppy , citrusy but flowery , not so piney .  a golden hue , with a small head and very little lacing .  m -- -medium bodied with good carbonation .
s - very complex smell . yeast , wheat , bread , bananas , and clay with a warming alcohol finish .  sits an opaque pale color with a thin white head in the snifter .  mouthfeel : heavy bodied .

a- hazy amber , nice white head , just a little bit of lacing s- smells like a pine tree ... almost like that spray christmas scent for fake trees t- very bitter , for an ipa i expect flavor along with bitter , but this brew finds a way to just taste bitter throughout the entire drink .  @ raleigh times pours dark orange in the dim lighting of the bar with a head that goes away all too quickly .  m - slightly oily , but not cloying at all , which is quite nice . the chewiness is enjoyable as well especially in the throat . i did n't feel ruined for the night from this beer , which i worry about with such strong flavors in this style .

smells pretty good with huge roasted barley notes that give it a coffee smell it also has a slight chocolaty note to it with an oceany note in the back . very pleasant indeed .  a hazy light amber-orange brew with lacy white head and lots of light , bubbly carbonation .  the bight of carbonation is very apparent and pleasing .

best by 3/13/2011 aroma : lots of grapefruit and pine . a weird solvently hair spray flavor lingering in aftertaste . overall : what is up with boulevard beers and this soapy hair spray flavor ?  growler pours more brown than red . ruby red with gold highlights when held to the light . some haze .  ever since , this has been a complete struggle to drink and one i wont go back to . it 's a good looking beer with good texture , and probably a valiant effort for people who do n't get onions from the hops .

s-smells of sweet cherry and cola notes with a bit of plum and some herbal notes .  a : i poured a bit into a cup and it poured an interesting light shade of orange .  the mouthfeel was nice , however - nice and fizzy and refreshing .

smell consisted of light citrus fruits that of peaches , grapefruit , apricots , and some floral earth type smells . malts can be smelled behind the hops .  sadly a weak copper head and semi okay lacing .  mouthfeel - very carbonated , but good smooth texture overall .

smells great , in fact .  poured on tap into a pint glass this beer pours a deep black in color , but where is the head ? said film is soon swallowed by the sea however , not to be seen again .  mouthfeel has a medium body with a slight creamy aspect . fits the style well and is enjoyable .
pretty edgy .  the pour did not produce much head or lacing .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

other qualities are herbaceous and slightly musty in the smell . making it 's least attractive features stand out even more is a bitter hop profile featuring juicy herbaceous qualities .  golden straw color with a thin , white head that fades quickly .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , medium to full body , a slight dryness on the finish .

the smell is a bit sour and even seems unappetizing .  cloudy . peach color with slight ring of bubbles.. probably a result of hard and fast pour . speaking of peach , the aroma is overwhelming with the fuzzy fruit .  whatever it is ( or was ... ) seems to take over , i can taste nothing else m ) fine carbonation , bottle conditioned efervescent .

smells like coffee with like a lot of hazelnut creamer .  a : pours a cloudy yellow to white color with a nice white creamy head which does not disappears totally and leaves many lacings in the glass s : smell is a must !  mouthfeel - light but not watery , possibly due to the big airy body carbonation .

nice sweet hoppy aroma with some citrus that even my gf liked .  pours a very cloudy golden orange . one finger of fine bubbles shows decent retention and leaves some patchy lacing .  mouthfeel is very smooth .

scents of wood , berries ( mainly raspberries ) , sweet dark malts and caramel . cloying , sticky raspberry and malty sweetness combine with a major lack of carbonation and a very thin body to achieve complete unbalane in my opinion . too fruity , too sour and too sweet .  a - deep , muddy mahogany with a small ring of bubbles around the edge of the glass . lacing is scarce , but that 's to be expected . the star of the show is the port , and the flavors from it meld flawlessly with the base beer . absolutely magnificent . carbonation is low , making this beer drink a bit like a wine . very impressive .  m : nothing special , but not bad either . nice viscosity and carbonation .

aroma was strong and solid , by far the best feature of this beer . slightly sweet bread with a very specific hop ( herbal and pine-like ) punch . i continued drinking it , hoping it would mellow out and i would find it 's wonderful hidden character , but all i can say is that this one is not for me .  appearance is a nice copper orange with a smaller white head . only drawback is a lower carbonation for an ipa but other than that near ideal .  their is a pleasant caramel base behind it with a good creamy mouthfeel .

smell is actually good with malt hints .  my first sampling was a pint at the pourover pub at the nantahala outdoor center , with subsequent pours from a growler fresh from the brewery in bryson city a - dark appearance for apa ; a dull copper that looked more like what i expect from an ipa than pa s- detect a hint of pine amongst the hop aromas , again more indicative of an ipa t- thankfully , taste did not match what i expected from the smell as it did not have the thick pine-resin flavor ; it was much milder than expected and more appropriate for pale ale style .  the taste is of a very crisp , dry lager . crisp as a cracker . someone said you drink this after cutting the grass .

s - smell is not very strong , but it does prominently feature roasted dark malt with strong espresso and dark chocolate flavors . refreshing for a stout with great flavor and appearance .  very thin head , ordinary retention .  mouthfeel : medium body with moderate carbonation .
aroma was very faint .  head extremely shortlived , no lace whatsoever .  mouthfeel is dry and crisp , with a medium-light body .
smell -- rich malty aromas , faintly sweet .  appears clear gold with little head retention .  m : smooth and nicely carbonated . the feel compensates for the taste .

smell : very mild roasted malt tones and hint of coffee are tough to pick up . taste : roasted malt , coffee , dark bitter chocolates , raisins , and a hint of licorice show up late .  clear orangey amber with a thin white head that 's quick to collar .  m : full , heavy body . really smooth .

there 's a bit of grapefruit on the nose , but ultimately the smells of pine and citrus dominate . relatively typical ipa notes -- -sort of reminds me of the north west .  yellow with an orange hue , and a thin white head that fades quickly , leaving some patchwork . decent lacing .  not if you like an imperial stout , no . there is a little too much pitch ( black ) in the brew . that is a yummy chocolate nose about half way through , but a little chipped too much with yeast over-all , and maybe a bit too much biscuit ? you can have both better beers and better baltic porters .

nothing exceptional about the appearance . sweet , malty , sugary smell . and the taste is sweet , and creamy .  dark brown pour with little head and little lacing , still not a bad looking beer but nothing too pretty .  mouthfeel smooth and creamy with a dry hop bitterness at the finish .

there is an immediate burst of fresh , flowery hop aroma with faint hints of coffee and malt .  a : poured bright orange with a filmy head and an unusual amount of sediment . odd brightness which almost came through like grapefruit juice .  average . m- very refreshing feel .

smell- very nice almost wine like scent .  a : pours fairly light for an imperial stout , dark brown , some deep reddish highlights , white head , some lacing s : nose features a heavy dose of oak , some molasses and maple syrup , followed by some mellow vanilla and chocolate .  m-really pretty rich and smooth in body with medium carbonation and a slightly slick mouthfeel .

good , malty smell , with a hint of white grapes .  bomber poured into my old rochefort chalice , mayhem is hazy , dull dark gold with an off-white head leaving light lace . murkier as i pour through the bottle , kind of dirty dish water .  m : wow , that nitro widget adds a lot . light bodied but sooo seductively smooth and creamy ... it makes me think of a milkshake .

smell : nice aroma right out of the gate . nice aroma , but not much else .  the appearance is that of your average brown ale minus the head .  it has a medium body and a smooth mouthfeel , with the sour flavor laying on the tongue slightly . inbetween a medium and high carbonation , but fairly drinkable .

s - cheap strawberry jam , syrupy malt , heavy alcohol , and spice .  a decent , light-bodied golden ale with a mellow spicy hop character that seems to come from noble hops like saaz . pours clear and blond with a firm head that settles to slight ring of bubbles . no lace .  you can smell the sweetness as well expressed in dark honey notes at the back end of the inhale , very nice taste etc ... the after taste is quit cloying and has my face contorted in all sorts of ways ( as if i aint ugly enough ... ) , the alcohol is a little hot also , this is at cellar temp and at only 8 % ( 8 aint what it used to be ) i was surprised . whew , have to take a break for a second and go grab some strong cheese to cut this with ... the sweetness on the second take was a little more negotiable but not exactly what i enjoy as far as my personal tastes go , this hangs out somewhere labeled `` just thick enough '' in terms of the ride through the mouth , the carbonation is dead on , it just rolls across the palette extremely well , the flavor is pretty straight forward ... this one lacks depth for me .

dedected absolutely zero aroma . i even had leslie pour it in a shot glass for me and let it warm up .  pours a cloudy , golden/maize color . decent retention and decent lacing .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , the carbonation was right on the button as soon as i cracked the bottle .

smell definitely of blueberry with enough malt to know that this is a beer . overall i do n't believe that taste lives up to the smell .  a - pours a hazy , rusty amber with a piss foam head into the snifter . this beer just looks unpleasant .  mouth was thick , not much alcohol , but that sour-grape aftertaste took control and finished as if it was champaign . there are a lot of flavors in this beer , but nothing really to rave about .

bomber poured into a gruss aus munchen mug ... both received from zorro in the beerfest bif a- deep orange with red highlights ... big pillowy off-white head that leaves great lacing on the way down and takes a while to subside ... looks delicious s- intense and complex with some elements atypical of the style ... big sweet fruits ... caramel malty goodness ... spices ... clove ... raisin ... and big earthy grassy hops ... smells like a great oktoberfest but bigger and hoppier t- similar to the smell ... but everything is soaked in booze a little too much for my taste ... finishes with a hint of toffee and chocolate ... burns a bit on the way down ... still tastes like an oktoberfest though m- tiny carbonation bubbles feels good on the tongue ... despite the heavy sweetness it does n't feel syrupy ... medium bodied d- limited by the booze and the burn on the back of the throat this is an interesting take on the style ... and one i 'd love to try a different version of  poured into a chimay glass appearance : 1 inch head that goes quick , cloudy , red/brown in color , high carbonation smell : grape , dark fruit , bread , and a touch of apple taste : dark fruit , apple , belgian spices , and bread mouthfeel : semi-sweet and tart , high carbonation , light bodied .  m : light bodied and crisp like a pilsner should be .

smells like a malt bomb . brown sugar , roasted malt , and loads of chocolate .  pours a one finger tan head that fades quickly , leaving traces of lace . opaque dark brown color .  m : full-bodied , frothy carbonation , pretty smooth , easy drinking for its size .

small is of citrus and oak , not much of a hoppy aroma .  long trail ipa pours a hazy golden color with minimal lacing and a quarter-inch head .  very rich , the sweetness pours over the tongue and almost demands a slow drinking pace .

smell - very hoppy and fresh . notes - a great looking beer with a fairly pleasant aroma , but it falls apart after that .  slightly hazy and light orange / copper in color with a very thin white head that almost disappears immediately .  light , crisp , refreshing body and feel- would be great on a hot day .

the nose gave me great expectations but for whatever reason this beer was very watery with a lack of hop presence .  southampton enjoys a well-deserved reputation for their belgian ales , and now i know why ... the cru pours light amber in color , quite clear and displays a low head that dissapates fairly quickly .  '' m- as with most milk stouts , the mouthfeel is nice and smooth . almost creamy with a little carbonation to add a nice spritz .

i like the aroma . nice west coast induced piney hop tones mix with the chocolate and nutty tones of the malt nicely . nice low key chocolate and roasted malt tones .  a- half inch light brown head , weak head retention and no lacing . the beer is a dark caramel red color that is beautiful in the light .  mouthfeel is full and mellow in the carbonation .

i must say that this `` java stout '' is by no means a traditional stout . light carbonation , nice light head , sweet yet coffee bitterness comes through . as easy as it may be to tear this beer down , i would rather note that those who may enjoy coffee and a dark beer here and there will probably find this stout to be worth a taste . whether bar chocolate or dark chocolate cookies , this pairing works . just remember , this is no stout .  a dark brown/reddish beer with a faint head .  m : medium body . moderate carbonation that finishes with some fizz on the tip of my tongue .
smell was quite nice with plenty of spice and i did n't mean for that to rhyme .  copper amber with minimal head and no lace .  very light nicely carbonated .

pours clear ( not appropriate for the style ) light straw with a dense white head . wonderful fragrent aroma of oranges and corriander with a little sweet maltiness in the background .  excellent , traditional german pilsner . my first `` all occasion beer '' that i enjoyed ( college days ) was miller high life ... regular old champaign of beers . this reminds me of that ( can drink it all day ) except with full bodied german flavor .  medium bodied .

smell was smokey and pleasant . i was a bit startled at the level of smoke aroma and it was all i could detect .  appearance is a very light copper with a thin head and spotty meager lace .  m 4 the best part . medium plus body , creamy carbonation .

smell : rich malt smell with a faint bit of hop/floral note .  the beer came out quite thin looking with burnt reddish brown color , and a body that was quite clear when held up to the light .  mf : light and carbonated well .

light caramel , sweet creamy chocolate , sugary chocolate biscuits and mocha coffee redolances play on this beers bouquet , hints of barley and molasses vie for attention but are not competition for the overwhelming coffee and chocolate perfume . overall , this is a good standby sweet cream stout .  comes in a 1l growler combo-bottle - has a swing-top cap , and a crown cap . interesting bottle . pours an orangey-gold , slightly hazy , with an orangey-tan head .  mouthfeel : nice well-balanced carbonation with little hop bite .

smell great , almost like opening a bag of hop pellets . however , good looks and smell is where it ends for me on this beer , i just do n't like the taste that much .  i had a 1oz pour from the nbt guys . take this review for what its worth , but there were n't many reviews , so i figure a review of a 1oz pour is better than nothing . the smoke reminded me of like a peaty scotch , but not really in a way that i liked ( and i am a huge ardbeg lover ) .  m- dry and crisp with good carbonation .

the smell is strong and pungent and rather pleasing . overall this is not a bad beer , but then again , nothing special either .  gorgeous barleywine . soft , cloudy orange amber in the glass with a small head that disappears rather quickly .  it does have a great thick mouthfeel and if i could n't taste anything i would enjoy this well enough .

smell was big on berry like fruitiness which apparently is the pomegranate . a bit too mild flavored for me overall , but interesting .  a : pours a hazy orangie with a white head that quickly dissipates into a small white lace .  best by 4/25/11 .

aroma is great and not your typical apa/ipa . elegant . very balanced , ending just a tad bitter .  totally amber and extremely transparent with no head , just a ring of scum .  mouthfeel : fairly heavy and smooth overall : i 'm not at all sure the whole 'double wit ' thing works .

the aroma begins as biscuits , then quickly morphs into a straight up electrical fire . and beauty shop perm solution . it 's downright painful to stick one 's nose near the glass . interestingly , none of the electrical fire hues so dominating in the nose really manifest in the mouth , but it 's hard not to smell them every time one sips this . but here , this godawful aroma simply masks a nearly godawful beer .  appearance-a very pale ale that pours a bit cloudy . you can mix it with another type up drink and create something called a `` dirty ho ''  m - light bodied and dry just like a dry irish stout should be . medium carbonation with nice carbonic bite to aid in drying sensation .

s - smell is made up of simple grains with a touch of citrus . barely anything here .  yellow with a small white head .  a touch of burning alcohol on the finish , shocker . mouthfeel : actually pretty full , smooth , and round drinkability : 1 can after two other beers ( earlier ) is gon na get me buzzed i think , but the sweetness means i could never have more than one of these ( even if i wanted to ) conclusion : we were having crappy beer night tonight as a joke .
s : crisp citrus aroma - definitely picked up the centennial aromas .  formed a foamy white head that dissipated after a few minutes .  taste/mouthfeel : medium body with nice carbonation .

smell : on nose , besides being lightly grainy and malty , it 's spicy and aromatic as well -- refreshingly spicy aroma mixed of wheatish note , kind of coriander seed , and even summer berry or strawberry 's lightly sweet aroma .  ( a ) - pours a fairly thick hazy brown amber with reddish highlights . surprisingly , it produced no head whatsoever even after a vigorous pour ; just some gray bubbles .  m : smooth , medium-heavy body with light carbonation d : pretty one dimensional in the chocolate note with little else there .

pours a reddish orange color with white head . nose is dominated by raspberries with a little grassy bits as well . very raspberry flavours almost tastes like slushie syrup .  got this as an extra from bigebeer , thanks btw . -poured golden/clear , a small white head . -quite crisp and refreshing , i will have my other one now .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .
