beer shares the bottle with yeast ( nice ) . smells of pine , grapefruit and a little grass , without much malt coming through . tastes interesting -- sharp , lots of hop oil , and strong grapefruit and pine due to the interesting mixture of hops .  pours a clear , medium straw colour with very little carbonation or head .  this one has a `` bottled on 8-5-08 om it . i like the dating of beers . taste is warming , alchohol burn warming the inners . malty , raisins , figs and woodiness . i am tasting the mettalic aftertaste in this.good beer if i could get paste the metal .

s : one of the best ipa aromas around with tropical fruit hoppiness of mango , pineapple , and passionfruit , coupled with pine resin and floral notes . pale malt with a little medium crystal sneaks in there to provide a little resistance to hop deluge .  12 oz bottle pours into my pint glass opaque black with a very small tannish colored head . very little retention , but some lacing hangs around after each sip .  it had a medium feel in my mouth and good carbonation .

give you three guesses as to what this brew smells like ( and the first two do n't count ! yes , lots of raspberry in the nose . the flavor is very mellowed out raspberry , along with ... well nothing .  poured from a 22oz into a pint glass ( shared with coastiefish ) appearance : quite dark , rich brown color , and poured 'thick ' but not too thick .  ah well ... mouthfeel is fine - it 's not as heavily carbonated as originally thought ( from the head ) . smooth and even .

s - roasted caramel , some grapefruit , light alcohol , and bittering hops . the smell was good , but there was no complexity in the malts and the bittering hops took over .  a - cork came out with a whimper . hope it is not flat . murky cooked cherry color , pinkish off white small head leaves very fast .  mouthfeel - a good mouthfeel . smooth and slightly oily , crisp carbonation , one of the better areas of the beer .

berry fruit and floral aromas , with a light malt and sugary sweetness , too .  above average head retention & some lacing s : nice bourbon & oaky notes , plums & raisins too .  m - highly carbonated with a medium-light body and soft , dry finish , the feel of this brew is still quite nice !

smell : the aroma of the beer is heavy handed citrus orange , lemon , grapefruit from the hops . this combines well with yeasty clove , bubblegum aromas . taste : the beer delivers my expected hop bitterness . the beer gives way to cloves and a very annoying mint flavor . in short the mint ruins my enjoyment of this beer . the drinkability of this beer was ruined for me due to an astringent minty flavor .  light orange/yellow . very minimal white head , not even half a finger with a pretty hard pour , fades to a this wisp with minimal lacing .  citrus is there but should be stronger m : a bit sticky as well as quite refreshing in the finish d : could drink this one all night .

s- bright , crisp citrus hops , on top of fainter but noticable bittering hops .  a-pours a cedar tinted amber . forms 3 mm head that disappears in seconds . no lace on glass .  banana , pear , perhaps a citrusy taste as well m : good creamy mouthfeel d : i think what throws people with this beer is the appearance to it , looks like a miller lite .

smell is hershey syrup , a whiff of alcohol , and some roasted malt , but by far the dominance is the chocolate .  one , it is inexpensive . it is a solid staple .  body is good and so is carbonation .

aroma of hops , caramel malt , and orange peel .  the dogfish 90 minute pours an orange honey hue with a very small white head , lacing is very scarce .  m : mouthfeel is creamy and slick . let me say would have enjoyed the mouthfeel a lot more had i been consuming , say , a milkshake d : so thick , so chocolatey , that it took a lot of effort to finish this off .

a- very cloudy with pulpish looking stuff floating in it . the head was reminiscent of diet coke , very fizzy and faded fast . s- hints of fruit , very wine like .  retention was short lived and a placid surface developed with no lacing to speak of throughout the glass .  very coating mouthfeel , stays with you .

the aroma is intriguing , as it has a huge fresh wheat character initially , along with some cheerios like maltiness , some fruity esters , and a touch of the banana/clove yeastiness typical of the style .  actually , its now easter sunday here in georgia , and like every other sunday , the liquor stores are closed due to the blue laws . a lot of reviewers talk about the head , the aroma and the mouthfeel . i do like the color though , kind of bright orange-gold .  medium mouthfeel .

light golden , lots of head smells like light beer .  a very curious winter seasonal out of kalamazoo , one doesnt normally associate the dead cold of winter with a nice refreshing wit but i applaud bells individuality on not limiting the style to a thirst quenching summer beer . poured a very light hazy yellow with a half inch or so of head that gave way rather quickly .  active , tiny bubbly carbonation and a crisp , dry , smooth light bodied mouthfeel .

s - delicious smell , lots of tropical fruits and some piney resin . the finish is good , and the carbonation is very pleasing .  the appearance is deep golden with a copper hue . the head is rather small but ok for the style .  carbonation was spirited making for a tingly mouthfeel .
smell : sugary yeast with a small hint of hops .  pours a very dark brown with a slight light tan head and not too much lacing .  effervescent up front , slight creaminess , good chewiness .

the smell is mild compared to some porters , but can is distinguishable by its combination of roasted and mocha scent .  i was already a fan of belgian beers but this revolutionised my ideas of what a fruit beer could be . there was not a great deal of head but fizzy enough.the character of the beer was like no other i had tasted .  mouthfeel is decent , not too thin or thick .

smell , wow never quite smelled a beer like this before , its spices are overpowering , can for sure smell the pumpkin spices .  black in color - no light coming through at all . no head or lacing , but this was from a growler shipped from nc , and could be different with a fresher pour .  mouthfeel is again average . fairly light with a decent amount of carbonation .

s- not a lot of aroma coming off of this beer . if anything i would say it smells like sweet toasted malt but it is very lacking in the aroma category . t- taste is a little thin , but not quite as thin as the aroma was . i taste sweet malts up front and the taste finishes somewhat dry and bitter .  a : cloudy amber color that was much lighter than i was expecting .  mouthfeel is good , chewy almost .

the aromas blend together perfectly , creating a smell that is , in my opinion , perfect . t - whoa . this is a pretty bold beer - i think this was the strongest first taste of a beer i have ever taken .  the appearance of the beer is very average . looks like just your basic beer and wasnt anything special .  fairly full in the mouth considering the abv .

s- the malts are much stronger than the hops in the nose of this american barleywine . lots of caramel and toffee . somewhat fruity as well .  the appearance of this almost reminds me of killians ( my old mainstay ) , due to it 's lack of head , and deep orange coloring .  the flavor may have been off but the body is very nice as it has a semi-thick viscous texture without overwhelming the drinker . the body allows the flavors to be conveyed more smoothly than a higher bodied beer while the carbonation is mild enough to not contribute any carbonic bite .

smells of sweet and doughy , much like pastries that delightfully reminds me of westvleteren , but it reminds me a lot of a creamy lager . nice . theres also a sweet marshmallow and peach beneath .  had picked this up last summer before heading off to a barbeque . saw an empty sitting in a cabinet that i had squirreled away and brought back some memories . when i had picked this up , it had just been delivered , so was very fresh . having this beer in hand while playing bags and eating good food on a warm night is what summer is all about .  m : medium-bodied , smooth , crisp carbonation , nice overall feel , but not a great finish , too bitter .

the aroma is full of sweet mirachino cherries with a slight hoppiness underneath .  poured from a 22 ounce bottle in a wine glass a : deep black , thin head , no head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , some effervescence and a lingering bite .
very little aroma to start . some alcohol and roast later .  with a helping of off white head . not the best retention .  mouthfeel is pretty good but at this point who cares ?

s : nose surprisingly not very strong . t & m : mouthfeel almost a little buttery .  throws a heavily hazed copper body . not an attractive oktoberfest . the sloppy presentation masks what truly is a great marzen .  even so , it was pretty decently textured and carbonated .

looks ok for a hefeweizen , but the smell is of sulfur , bandaids and hay . blech !  two streams of bubbling rising to the top , but a bit lack luster compared to other saisons . the color is a pale pale hay with a little sediment hanging around .  mouthfeel - smooth and full bodied with good carbonation .

smell is big and complex , much improved from the younger beers in the series . sumptuous creamy chocolate , sherry , vanilla , peaty smoke and oak . mmmm ... . earthy dryness in the finish .  a - pours jet black . not much head , ever .  mouthfeel : lightly hop-oiled , ample carbonation , slightly chewy .

very nice aroma on this one .  although disappointingly served in a 0.4l glass at an exorbitant price ( $ 9 ) , it was a tasty lager , but not completely ticking the boxes for a true munich style dunkel .  it is very smooth , though , although that 's one of its few positive notes .

very 'varietal ' nose with some sweetness and spice jumping out .  nice crisp refreshing flemish red . not as sweet as some of the flemish reds , but that helps the drinkability considerably . i would consider this the perfect beer to match to some seafood ( mussels , clams , ... ) for lunch on a hot day .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thick side of medium . the carbonation is tingly with a dry finish .

this is one spicy hell of a beer ; and i like really spicy stuff . the aroma is pure chile peppers .  burnt orange hue , the head fizzled and retracted quickly leaving a momentary wispy centre , no ring and no lace .  very very sweet . maybe the sweetest beer i 've ever had . i do n't taste any hops , and i ca n't say i really enjoy this one . chocolate cherry syrup comes to mind ( with some alchoholic kick ) . maybe dopplebock is not my favorite style . it might be good- its just too much and too concentrated for me to really enjoy . huge candy sweetness is not my thing , but if it 's yours - this might be good .
the smell may be the best part of this beer . the taste is something atrocious .  pours a nifty orangish color with average head .  well bodied for such a low abv beer .

s : fresh fruit like oranges and apples , dry hops , wheat and grains . piney and earthy undertones in the aroma . d : not very impressive , more like a barleywine style than a double ipa .  appearance ( 3 ) : a pale cloudy yellow that pours with a large , billowing head . it eventually settles to a thin ring .  because i found higher allcohol beers overpowering i struggle to find a lot of other flavours however this did have a sweetness and some toasted grains lurking about but didnt really asault the palate the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer being balanced smooth and sweet.the swallowing was the disappointment .

aroma : an absolutely phenomenal aroma , like a fine scotch ale .  750ml into a tulip . pours a somewhat muddy deep mahogany . minor medium bubbled tan head .  mouthfeel has a good medium body with a good hit of carbonation .

it was nice on the nose which gave my higher hopes than the label . i just bought it cuz it was kind of funny and it was a porter . it overall was very disjointed .  it was a nice mahogony color with a small half inch head that dissipated rather quickly . no lacing during the drinking period .  m : medium bodied , relatively light on the carbonation . it feels like a nice fall drink .
overall : good , but no scent  a : a hazy light orange color with a soapy head . can see sediment suspended in beer .  m- medium bodied with ample carbonation .

a strong bourbon aroma overpowers anything else , perhaps this was aged in whiskey barrels ?  appearance - slightly hazy amber body . medium small llight tan head with good stick and medium retention .  in texture , the ale is very weakly carbonated and quite smooth ; the overall impression is more like a pinot noir than a beer in this respect , and i probably enjoy it more than i should .

the first thing that comes to mind , when i think of fat tire is its great earthy smell . the smell almost reminds me of stilton blue cheese .  trying a 2009 bottle in dec , 2011 . this has all the qualities of a good loaf of pumpernickel bread : caraway seeds , molasses , cocoa , brown sugar . theres a thick presence of caramel , vanilla , and dried dark fruit ( raisins , dates , figs ) , slight booze heat , and a hop appearance for just a second that finishes each sip with a pleasant dry , sweet finish . a friend of mine who loves cask ales used to wake up , open an old stock in the morning and leave it out all day until he was ready to drink it after dinner when it was nearly flat . it must be the pricing that north coasts rasputin gets all the glory for this brewery , but old stock has been quietly superior . its north coasts best beer , and its better than just about any barleywine and old ale around . do the math : compared to most ( non-barrel aged ) barleywines that come in bombers , these prices are typically better and the quality of the beer is better . instead i hear about bigfoot ( put a damn leash on those hops , why is this called a barleywine ?  full bodied and nicely carbonated .

a pretty balanced aroma . very nice . t- roasted malts upfront followed by a earthy/spicy hop bitterness that carries through to the finish .  this is the second voodoo brew that is an absolute pain in the ass to pour . you pour , foam , let it die , more foam , it takes 30 min to pour this one and by the time you scrape off layer after layer of foam your 22 oz is barley 16 . once poured it is a murky light yellow hue with tons of floaters . the retention is ridiculous .  a nice mouthfeel , with plenty of creaminess .

slight caramel and brown sugar , very nice . taste : sadly , not as balanced here as the nose , and almost comes across as an ipa . not that that 's a bad thing , but the nose smelled really great . predominantly hops and strong lemon notes .  although in fl 32oz is what i got ... a : pours a transparent golden straw color which produces a bubbly fizzy head that is slightly off-white . minor lacing s : very metallic nose . slightly stronger than some of the other noses , with cereal , corn , and a sweet note , almost like corn flakes !  a-black color , finely carbonated off white head s-a hint of yeast , some roasted malt t-hints of bourbon with a touch of bug spray and brett yeast funk m-smooth bodied , very creamy , nice d-the bourbon sting is a little too much for me o-did not care for the combination of brettomyces and bourbon stout .

cloudy dark reddish-brown . s : dank and citrus hops . smells like an ipa with no malty `` redness '' .  aside from that , it pours yellow with a small , quickly dissolving white head .  m - feel pretty spot on for a wit .

the nose flashes bread and caramel before hop aromas take center stage . normally with these american pacific northwest hops i find that grapefruit is dominant , but refreshingly i find that pineapple is most prominent ( though grapefruit is certainly still there ) . the bitterness in hop rocket is unpleasant though ( and this is from someone who usually enjoys big ipas/iipas ) . the beer is remarkably light for the style , which i find myself actually enjoying , it makes hop rocket feel smaller than it is .  as this pours i 'm surprised by how clear and pale the beer is and after a vigorous pour settles in an a clear , pale golden yellow with a thin white head of large bubbles that quickly fades to nothing .  more like a cider , apple-ish and very sweet , low carbonation . mouthfeel is full and round .

it smells sweet and malty . this smells pretty good for what it 's worth .  let 's face it , this is a lawnmower beer which does n't taste like beer at all . it 's is a crisp , cold , and refreshing , highly carbonated , inexpensive gatorade alternative . very good macro-swill beverage . i do not believe it is possible to get `` wasted '' drinking nl - there 's just not enough abv .  mouthfeel has a pleasant sheen to it , but the flavour is either thin or phenolically unpleasant , so it does n't have much to work with .

it smells average at best ; somewhat farm-y ( hay ) atop caramel grain , with a faint herbal hop . it tastes good , far better than the nose suggests , with lots of caramel maltiness , though it winds up with a rather dry flavor for the profile .  ( served in an american pint glass ) a- this beer has a very light pale yellow body that is crystal clear showing off the very gentle carbonation of big bubbles . there was a soapy white head that faded pretty quickly .  some how the spices dont drown out the actual beer . m- light , prickly , crackly and drying . very crisp despite all the insane herbs and spices . d- not as drinkable as a normal saison . this beer is wildly herbal and spicy .

sweet fruity smell , with a bit of booze as well .  coors light has a decent flavor compared to miller light and bud light . its not that great though , and their are many beers the same price as coors light that i could recommend .  t - sweet taste , can taste the alcohol , malty , spice and gingerbread flavor m- medium thickness , coats the tongue , lightly carbonated once the foam settles .

s : great smell . sweet and malty .  but i was not impressed it had about the same color as miller altho a little darker and near the same smell and taste .  ... the aroma is super malty , brown sugar , bread , prunes , dark fruits and grape soda dominate , a hint of yeast and alcohol on the finish . a super malty aroma , taste crushes your senses with hops and alcohol . almost makes me gag . this is so bitter , like they confused a dopplebock with double ipa . the hops are totally misplaces , trying to be creative , just ruined the beer .

bit of a toasted and floral aroma , guessing from the malts and hops respectively .  grolsch blonde lager had very little taste and is a little lighter in color than a mgd . i think it would be unfair to judge this beer against excellent tasty crafts ... .for that is not the market of beer drinkers this was aimed for . it goes down like cool-aid after two hours of yard work ... and i found it to be light but sweet with very little ... if any ... unpleasantries . there is nothing special about this beer except that it may be the most poundable beer i have ever tried ... while being watered down , it does n't possess nearly as many off tastes and adjuncts ... it is unbelievably easy to drink . i threw this in a variety six ... just to try it ... i was pleasantly suprised ... .not a bad brew ! little to no head ... taste like a sweet hellas ultra light ... .a little grainy but no bad ... .moderate carbonation .  nose is a creamy butterscotch sweetness , and palate of creamy sweet butterscotch with a balanced bitter and a touch of gypsum . absolutely one yummy ale and a must try for anyone . bass pale ale has been on my list of beers to buy when the price is right . bass pale ale is a good tasting pale ale that has been around for a very long time . well , i just went through a twelve pack and lo and behold this brew has turned to banta podo , it is nothing at all what it used to be !

( s ) - dry , with alot of fruits of fig , cranberry , & cherry . light sweetness of honey & butterscotch . smell ; pretty bad but could be worse , just a cheap lager aroma , mostly of corn and sad excuses for hops . i feel like i had some corn on the cob 15 minutes ago .  this was super carbonated and produced way too much head . golden yellow color and smells of heavy carbonation with a touch of lemon .  mouthfeel : medium-thin body . medium carbonation .

aroma is quite pleasant . it has flavor with a nice european quality , just not enough .  half finger of bright white head that almost instantly went to a thin white collar . nothing massive by any stretch but in reality a good soda water with some malt and hops . more like soda water metallic but that is not a bad thing at all .  mouthfeel : very smooth .

s - this beer smells nice . citrisy , slight pine , a little earthy .  on tap at vagabondo in cph denmark a - pale golden color but frankly not much color to the beer .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy , however .

smells like porter heaven . great , spicy scents of cinnamon and sweet chocolate malt . it almost smells like they put some artificially engineered scents in there , in a good , science-is-progress kind of way . the balanced flavor and great smells make this a pretty appealing brew .  purchased in a dragon pack from world market in charlottesville , va - tulip - no freshness pours a really watery amber color with little head which is soapy and diminishing fast .  m - the mouthfeel is actually right on point .

s- nice english ale smell ; sweet floral hops piled on a firm foundation of hearty grains .  sadly this beer was not very good and barely resembles a saison in appearance , flavor or aroma . appearance is a clear light gold with a whitish head that disappears immediately and leaves no lacing .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy , not nearly as assaulting as i 'd figured it would be with the carbonation level .

smell - pungent aromas of sour wheat , a little banana .  looks bad . pours a very cloudy light brown color with a small head that falls fast and does n't leave lacing on the glass .  it has a good mouthfeel , with that silky nitro body .

s - holey smokes . wood . but i guess that could be a positive if you like something that tastes like a camp fire smells ? o - 9.1 % abv , ca n't taste a hint of the alcohol due to the smoke . for a grand cru its not living up to me personally .  i always am a little wary when the lettering on a beer label is n't in the roman alphabet , as generally the `` cyrillic beers '' like greek , ukraninan and the like are n't so good but lets see if this russian lager can turn the tide . baltica cascades into a very light color reminiscent of apple juice and also features almost no head and a strong , grainy scent .  medium to full bodied and smooth .

smell is thick fruitiness and a good amount of booze . actually quite complex , with notes of grape , clove , and a slight lemon .  appearance : not much head , even less head retention , and next to no lacing .  does have a nice , smooth mouthfeel , which would make it easy to drink , if i cared for the smell at all .

pours reddish light brown , appearance is closest to a belgian dubbel in my opinion , which may be a consistent characteristic . nose is strong on the bourbon which is a definite plus in my book - so often these bourbon aged beers dont carry as much of the characteristic .  *did not like would never buy* app : tarnished gold , ugly .  m : a soft and fluffy texture , no carbonation , medium body .

nice color and smell . smells better than it tastes , and becomes harder and harder to drink .  poured into a pint glass ... really wo n't even bother next time . just drink it straight from the bottle . about average for your run of the mill overly adjunct ( addjunk ) lager .  mouthfeel - i actually have no complaints in this department . it 's comparatively crisp and the carbonation is appropriate .
smell was yeasty , sweet and fairly mild .  clear straw with a fizzy short head and no real lace to speak of .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

otherwise , it 's nice . not have as pleasant as the nose was . i can barely taste the cinnamon , nutmeg , or orangey , spicy traces that i thought would be here .  of course , no appearance , but i 'm guessing its pale yellow . it 'll do for parties or a cheap ( er ) drink at the watering hole .  mouthfeel : it 's just about right .

it is oddly hoppy for a wheat , but this is the same impression i got from many of the flossmoor beers that i 've tried . it 's not cloudy enough to be a traditional hefe but its definitely not a kristalweisen . it was also a bit on the flat side and was n't spiced either .  a : cloudy brown copper color , no head at all or lacing . pretty pathetic .  mouthfeel is very thick but a nice amount of carbonation .

smell : pretty nice - fruity and spicy , with interesting topnotes of carraway , coriander , and mint .  this poured a very unimpressive light straw yellow with very little head and minimal to no lacing . appears to be piss in a bottle .  m- there is a very slight creamy note to the light body that gives it a nice mouthfeel .

smell had hints of orange zest , sugar sweetness , along with some nutmeg and wheat .  pours an extra clear light straw . thin and soapy head with poor retention and scarce lacing .  really good smooth , medium mouthfeel in this one , probably its best feature .

good strength on the aroma , although not very complex .  poured an amber color with no head , hardly any lacing , and very few struggling bubbles trying to make their way to the top .  at the least the mouthfeel is , typical of apas , nice and creamy .

smells strongly of cascade hops and light spices , which is contrary to the taste , very light in flavor .  had at the brewery tour , color was typical straw and had very minor head .  granted , i know this is cask beer , but would a little bit of carbonation be such a bad thing ? mouthfeel is soft and smooth , and this beer is very light and easy to drink .

aroma is pretty mild . light hops and a mild bready malt that gives it an almost dusty quality .  quickly-fading head on a very pale and transparent yellow color body .  decently carbonated beverage with a mild body .

it 's a pretty clear yellow color with no head , it does have a great wheat & blackberry aroma to it which is very appealing , and the taste seems almost watered down compared to say one of dogfish heads fruit beers .  what a deal , that 's two more than a similarly priced can of swill ! it pours a transparent yellow with a big head that does n't last too long and plenty of visible carbonation .  mouthfeel : nice carbonation level , medium body , smooth texture .

it smells nice ... the faint smell of strawberries over a clean american lager aroma .  pours a clear yellow with a fizzy white head that quickly diminishes to a thin collar that leaves a little lacing .  4.0 m : this is easily the best part of the brew . good carbonation , but might be a tad high . very nice creaminess on this , especially for the body .

sense of some bitterness , but this smells really good and inviting .  not bad for a light beer , that still has a littl personality . great when i want to drink something light but still premium quality . its priced as a premium beer when its beer quality real rivals a cheap domestic .  one saving grace for this beer is its mouthfeel , which i thought was quite good : light and not too carbonated . a poor geuze , overall .

the aroma is funky and fruity , with plenty of yeasty esters and mild phenolics . the tropical fruit aroma is balanced nicely by herbal , floral hops .  it poured murky copper brown , flat and with very little carbination .  fairly smooth . would n't be able to guess that it weighs in at 6.5 % .

nose is quite nice : lots of citrusy , peppery hop aroma .  pours like any other aal , real light gold with a big fizzy head .  medium body and syrupy with a good amount of carbonation keep the beer from being too heavy .

being a small beer made from old foghorn i expected a little more going on in the malt department . it is a bit thin , not a lot happening on the malt side but it dones have a nice hop bitterness to it . if i remember right the brewer said he was shooting for an authentic english bitter .  poured a pale yellow , dirty gold color with a sickly , broken head .  medium-light body with a pleasant carbonation and an apparent slickness and oiliness .

s - nose is of citrus hops and alcohol .  shoulda drank from the bottle so i would n't have seen the fact that this is not a stout . dirty brown water , hazy . medium head , not real creamy looking in the head .  one positive is the full bodied presence of the malt , although the carbonation comes across as lighter than expected .

smell : wow this is different from any other brew i have ever smelled . earthy , with red beets , and a vergitable quality and a slightly menthol like note . very yeasty and beet like .  ) pours a hazed chestnut with 1/2 light tan head . minimal lacing & zero head retention s : huge chocolate & cherry notes makes me think of cherry smash candy .  the mouthfeel is tasty and slightly creamy for a pilsner , but i am liking it .

the smell of malted milk balls , a touch of hazelnut syrup , & a ticklishly sharp edge of caramel & nutmeg .  a - on first pour , it seems and sounds almost like cola -- the head is n't huge , maybe a couple of fingers , but crackles angrily and falls away pretty quickly . it leaves pretty much nothing , not even really a ring . swirling does n't produce much at all . no lacing , obviously . this has just the right amount of coffee in a beer for me -- almost as if you added a couple of tablespoons to the glass .  the body is medium with a soft creamy feel to it .

it comes through in the aroma but not in the taste to any degree ... ..and i 'm not so sure that 's a bad thing seeing how strong a taste maple syrup can provide to a beer . distinct maple aromas ... sweet malt , slight waft of hop but the overpowering aroma is of maple ( and slightly smokey at that ) .  however ... when i poured this brew alot of sediment ( chunky hunks ) were floating in the glass .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy with low carbonation . has an element of smoothness to it .
much bolder than expected for an irish stout , but smells very nice even if not quite to style .  rough yellow appearance . looks like the return on rented beer .  medium bodied carbonation .

s- citrus and floral hop aroma with little to no malt charcterisitic t- light and lager-esk with a nice medium hop characteristic m- very light body with a spice at the front , malt covering about mid palate and hop finishing that is citrus and floral throughout d- very drinkable at around 5 % and very light for a nice summer session  pours black with no head . i mean zero head . i 've never quite seen a beer pour this flat ever .  good mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation . found the flavors to be very mild , and it took a lot of sips to really get the full feel of this brew .

the belhaven was floral , perfectly present : not too strong , not too weak .  appearance : a hazy , dull orange color , including scads of traveling floaties zipping about , and the head is short , white .  the mouthfeel was good with real depth .

the aroma was a little sweet but not too much .  pours a light clear straw like yellow color with an initially very nice and tall white foamy , full bodied looking head that all but totally dissappeared 2 minutes after being poured , leaving little to no lacing . it is easy to drink the same way seltzer water is . better than some of american macros i have had , certainly at least slightly better than budweiser ( one of the other line of beers brewed by anheuser busch of course ) the last time i had it , but certainly nothing special either .  medium , creamy mouth feel with light to moderate carbonation .

michelob 's entry in the growing pumpkin ale sweepstakes pours a copper/amber , and the initial nose is of nutmeg and clove . jack 's is a sweet and malty ale that is n't too complex or unique , and really seems a little overbearing on the tastebuds .  pours an orangish copper color , hazy , head dis . i swear american wheats have some kind of odd haziness to them that makes the appearance unappealing . it does n't make me want to vomit , but it does n't make me want to drink it either .  the willamette & tettnang hops gave it an interesting bittering character , although i 'm not sure i liked it that much . you do get some malt up from but the hop bitterness really overshadowed any malt character .

also a strong tartness reminiscent of lemon juice.. reminds me of nb le terroir with just a touch of sweet melon . o- awkward beer for sure- one of the most unconventional i 've tried actually .  the color is of pale straw with good carbonation . the head is below average in size and soapy .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation . pretty smooth here . it did have a very nice mouthfeel though .
the beer smelled of oranges and grape fruit and had a few spices .  pours pitch black with absolutely zero head .  a buttery mouthfeel which is unique and nice . medium body and medium carbonation .

aroma - light toasted grain , a vague sweet biscuit-like aroma . could use more but though faint it has some decent aroma . taste - sweet toasty grain , a little buttery .  there was virtually no lacing . the color was redish amber .  the mouthfeel is a bit creamy as the name implies . overall i 'd say the mouthfeel is the best part about this beer but nothing to get excited about .

juicy , insanely tropical fruity aroma dripping with notes of sugared orange slices , mango , pineapple juice , and pear . the belgian yeast is subtle in its spiciness , which i appreciate . malts are mild , with some bread and cereal notes . a bit soapy , but it 's forgivable , especially since the hop flavors are still big enough to linger long after each sip .  poured into a pint glass with almost no head and left no lacing behind .  the carbonation of the beer was good , like a pilsner should be . the beer was light , but not watery . an innocent beer that would offend very few .

smell is soft , sweet citrus and tropical fruit , light dusty brett .  here in nashville this is the favorite drink of punk rockers and other `` hipsters '' and in my opinion is a pretty trendy beer . however , i saw a 24oz can in a gas station yesterday for $ 1.09 and decided to see what this beer is all about . appearance = had this in a can , so no idea .  pretty nice texture for an aal .

the nose was solid , but boy does the taste/body suck .  poured yellow with no head retention .  the hops jump right out from the bottle and sting your nose as the beer pours into the glass . do n't get me wrong there are plenty of hops , maybe too much , but i think as an effort to try and dry out this beer , the brewer added a lot of simple sugars which created more alcohol , and then to counter or mask , he added more hops . the finish is dry and clean with very little lingering hoppiness at least for a iipa . i was very excited to see this brewery 's beer being distributed in ohio . we do n't see many style defining west coast iipas in the midwest so it 's a real treat to find something that stretches your palate . even though this beer deserves low marks for drinkability , its intense aroma was worth the eight dollars i paid for the bomber .

smell is faint ; of corn and mildew .  a - not impressed at all . pours a russet/reddish color with very little head and no lacing s - smells of roasted malts , cinnamon , nutmeg , and a little bit of rye t - almost all nutmeg , clove in the finish , heavy roasted malt ( almost burnt ) as well m - light/medium bodied with crisp carbonated finish d - goes down real easy , could definitely toss back a few it 's kinda like carbonated water with a lot of christmas spices ... or maybe burnt christmas cookies but its still fairly enjoyable  mouthfeel is pretty good .

smell is clean and clearly malty . pleasant citrus hop scent that is mild enough to let you smell a bit of toast and biscuit in the malt . i give this a little extra credit for maintaining a balance .  typical light gold pour with light head and smelled of corn like malt mainly .  it leaves a taste like fig newtons on the palette that 's not too enjoyable ... m : the mouthfeel is actually right on .

huge brown sugar aroma with boozy raisins and chocolate . like some sort of outrageous rum cookie or something . syrupy raisiny flavor , plenty of booze , cloyingly sweet .  pours with a very pale yellow body topped by a medium thick quickly disappearing head with a good amount of lace left behind .  the mouthfeel was smooth , creamy and fuller bodied with a fine , moderate effervescence .

s : plums , prunes , raisins , along with just a hint of yeast . very estery .  limp puny yellow , you can see the carbonation . meager white head .  it has a very thick mouthfeel and a kind of grapefruit like flavor .

s-crisp smell of a light macro beer .  looks like soda in general .  m - not bad ( if it were not for actually having to experience the taste to experience the mouthfeel ) full and smooth with active carbonation .

smell- it has a very well rounded smell . you can smell and equal balance of hops and malt . it is floral but sweet .  on tap at the petrol station in houston tx a : pours an opaque , hazed orange . unattractive murky , and dirty . at first a two finger white head forms , but recedes to nothing in a second . i think it is a combination of the really unattractive look and the bitterness that continues to build with each sip .  feels good in the mouth , mostly sweet to start , but there is a hint of bitter at the end of the swallow .

s -- nice citrus hop nose ... oranges , grapes , apples .  clear fizzy yellow beer with a small white head , looks like thousands of other beers in the world that look like budweiser .  m - very smooth with good carbonation , well rounded .

pint glass from cask . they used interesting hops in this , as the name implies : sunflower and fresh-cut grass dominate the nose .  this one pours a light pale straw colored lager with enormous soda pop carbonation bubbles ... weak head lasts seconds and disappears ... .  m - a bit fizzy and tongue-tingling , but develops well in the mouth . swallow is creamy and nice .

this was a very good ipa , but the aroma was n't overly impressive .  my friends always make fun of me for drinking it saying that it is worse than drinking old milwaukee warm , but i disagree . it is a good light bodies beer with a sweet kind of taste to it . very good .  m : thick and heavy , but not cloying .

the aroma is strong , reminiscent of a belgian ale . there are hints of citrus and pine , no hop to speak of .  clear yellow , foamy white head . more noticeable hops than some macros made it a bit more tolerable , but it is what it is , a macro lager .  mouthfeel : lightly crisp throughout . short and spicy aftertaste .

nice coffe/oat aroma . the taste did not live up to the aroma . good bold balance at the beginning nice full bodied oat flavors meeting a robust smokiness .  comes in the ugly `` stubby '' bottle . better than macro-brewed american lagers , but really more hype than substance .  appropriately carbonated and smooth going down with a little resiny aftertongue .

s - coffee , vanilla , slight amount of booziness . vanilla comes through the most . t - vanilla comes through in the finish .  pours a light , cloudy yellow with a thin to non-existent head .  nice , fairly full mouthfeel .

smell is actually quite nice . very yeasty with a wallop of banana and candi sugar .  bleck , tons of floaties even with a very calm pour , hands down the worst part of belgian beer is all the damn floaties !  carb level and mouth feel is actually quite pleasant , though .

s : sharp sour acidic aroma is the first thing that grabs your nose . mild raspberries , pool toys , modest wet straw and moldy funk . seems to lack any real depth of a typical lambic .  a : pours a cloudy amber-orange color , with lots of suspended floaties all throughout the beer . at least a full finger of frothy off-white head and decent lacing ; this beer gets marked down due to the floaties since for all i know , it could be a brand new bottle ( dear green flash , please date your bottles ) . nonetheless , i 'll probably convince myself to buy it again to see if it 's even better without the protein floaties missing from the beer .  m : despite the awful flavor of this beer , i have to say that the mouthfeel is fine for a porter . thick and creamy .

when i smelled the beer i was apprehensive because there is a prevalent scent of something like shortbread and whipped cream in addition to strawberries .  poured light amber , almost yellowish-orange with a smallish head with big bubbles that quickly dissipated except for slight traces .  i 've used pine to describe beers before but never has it been so true . smells like they really got the spruce tips going in here . lingering earthy bitterness and an aftertaste that kind of reminds of what it feels like when you eat something that is n't meant to be edible ( like for instance a pine cone ! ) somewhat crisp , drinkability only suffers because personally i am put off by the flavor .
smell is excellent with some defininte brown sugar present .  typical cheap pale lager .  pretty full bodied brew with moderate carbo .

i heard good things about this beer , especially the aroma . it smells like a sack full of buttholes . the beer smells alot like that nasty old cast .  pours clear , yellow and fizzy , nice head that lasts for 2.3 seconds and no retention .  the mouthfeel has nice carbonation but the smell is bland .

coffee , chocolate , baked bread on the nose . it has that weird taste that comes when you put sugar in good black coffee .  just looked and smelled the part of a yellow beer . cinnamon might make me think of pumpkin pie , but not pumpkin itself . tough to drink , and at the price , better options . seriously , blue moon 's is better .  good carbonation with a medium mouthfeel .

t-not as good as the aroma ... .kind of a flavorless muddled taste ... .some decent piney bitterness but not a lot more other than a mild oak impression ... m-medium to full ... .low carbonation ... .not as bitter on the finish as on the start ... d-the look and smell of this beer had me excited but it just does n't do much for me after that ... ok ... nothing more..  i 'm not a huge connaisseur of honey brews , and this might keep me that way . i was expecting a basic pale with a twinge of honey flavor , but i was only right about the `` basic '' and `` pale '' part . very thin when poured , not much aroma to speak of , and i had to close my eyes and concentrate to discern the hint of honey . boring beer .  mouthfeel/drinkability ; the mouthfeel may be the best thing going on with this beer . full bodied , and close to syrupy in feel , with a very low carbonation .

smells of of deep roasted grains , coffee and bits of chocolate and tofee . big toast character and faint hop aroma .  this is only like 10 % better than the typical american swill in a can , pbr has a better aftertaste than this , the flavors are not well put together .  m - nice medium-full body and creamy . low carbonation .

s- hoppy aroma . pine mixed with a grapefruit maybe .  this thing is pretty simple , not much there from the start to the finish.it pours gold , with a thin snow white head that dissipates in the blink of an eye , smells kind of like playdough.there is a faint biscuit taste with absolutly zero hop pressence , and the mouthfeel is very thin , and the carbonation balance is strange , as far as drinkability i could drink a bunch but it would not be enjoyable .  m - on the thin side of medium bodied , nice and foamy carbonation .

spicy pepper overshadows everything with a glorious `` bruery-like '' scent that 's unexpected . the beets add an odd but good vegetal aroma that subtly pokes out between the pepper . it 's far too powerful as it elevates the nice vegetal hint in the nose to astronomical heights . d - this turned disappointing quickly .  a very murky brown with almost no head .  moderate carbonation .

nose is sweet fruit with raspberry and pear tones ; hint of sour ; hint of brett ; mouthfeel is thin but the flavors are unique and a bit overwhelming such that mouthfeel is not of great importance here , although one 's initial reaction is that the beer is out of balance .  appearance : clear straw yellow with a thin , fizzy head . looks like your typical macro .  ) m : smooth , bubbly , crisp finish with a lingering dry hops spiciness on the tongue .

holy crap ... best normal stout in a can ive ever had , not including the double chocolate of course ... awesome pour , head and lacing ... .  i did not know what to expect as i did read some reviews before trying this and expected the worst . a - brown and still with barely no head even after an aggressive pour . s - mostly wet cardboard , metal and manischewitz wine ! a bit artificial but still i find myself wanting to drink more , at least it 's interesting !  the mouthfeel is fine could certainly session .

smells of some pumpkin pie spices : cinnamon , clove , allspice with a strong malty aroma . no hop character in nose .  color seemed surprisingly dark for a wheat , maybe when bud 's beer developers did taste tests the subjects said `` should n't something made of wheat look brown ? i got a little bit of wheat but not much barley malt , but there seems to be some other grain that gives it some flavor , not wheat though . i think i would drink this beer again if i really had to have a light beer and the alternative was just bud light .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with lively carbonation .
smell is pretty bad ; heavy weat/grain ?  pours without much head and the carbonation is low .  m : nicely carbonated lifting the sweetness making way for a light feel .

s- strong , and very appetizing , raspberry flavour . floral notes hiden behind the fruit .  appearance : pours a clear ( ! ) golden color with a head whose bubbles disappear as if it were a ginger ale rather than a wheat smell : distinctively apricot , but smells very artificial ; almost floral taste : a mouthful of artificial apricot from start to finish ; little wheat bear character ; more like an alcopop mouthfeel : light and fizzy drinakability : not at all enjoyable , and i kind of like certain fruit beers  taste : light body , smooth mouth feel .

i dont do fruit beers , typically . it smelled a little sweet , like raspberry candy , when i opened it .  this beer pours with a pale golden body and is topped with no head at all , which , of course , means there was no head either .  mouthfeel is full and round .

this one raised my expectations with the strong nose . the pour was mediocre clean dark yellow with an off-white head that lingered . the nose was strong with hops , citrus , and acidity that floating up .  this 12oz bottle from the sampler pack looks horrible in the glass . no head at all- looks like mud .  mouthfeel is medium - light with good carbonation .

the smell is pretty good . it is a bit syrupy but other than that it has some nice spice aromas , fruit , and a hint of hops of the herbal variety .  a - very pale yellow with almost no head .  pretty good body .

the smell is awesome . very complex without being overwhelming .  pours honey/bronze color with 4 fingers+ of eggshell colored head . no lacing or head retention s : light breadyness t : slight maltyness & some herbal hops up front .  medium mouthfeel .

smell : nice , clear springtime smell .  a - a pale yellow in color , reminds me of a witbier . a thin white cap is all that there is for head , the cap leaves no lacing .  low carbonation with a nice chewy mouth feel . very thick !

another entry into leinenkugels chick beer marketing scheme.it pours a cloudy slight orange with a somewhat fluffy head , artificial all the way through nothing seems to be balanced at all here way too fruity most people say it tastes like fruity pebbles and i agree virtually no balancing bitterness , smells very similar to how it tastes . just too fruity for me .  a - poured golden stgraw , bright , with good carbonation coming up . film of white head on top with no lace or retention .  mouthfeel is medium with very nice light carbination .

s - smells of sticky sweet dark fruits , chocolate , coffee , and some roasted malts . the smell was pretty good but was n't digging the sour taste it had to it .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  very good for the style .

s : not much there . very faint dark malts . t : the taste starts with dark roasted malts . i find the smell and taste lack a bit .  dear god , this looks like soda pop , same color and everything .  medium body , medium effervescence , good aftertaste where the malt comes out after the hop start .

surprisingly rich aroma . smells primarily of vanilla .  a : ca n't say much since its staying in the bottle , but from previous encounters i can assume it will be the typical pale color with little to no head and lacing .  the mouthfeel is full bodied for the style , with subtle carbonation .

clear pale gold in color , i was surprised by the aroma of pears . there 's some additional fruitiness to start ( i 'll guess pear-like ) , but it descends into grainyness that while not unpleasant is n't going to help the drinkability .  came in a cool skinny can , silver and black . this pours a pee yellow with no head .  mouthfeel : big exploding bubbles , thin , lots of good , filling , `` evaporation '' feel . very interesting .

s - very , ery flowery with cinamon and other spices . can smell it from 3 feet away . t - quite odd . d - kind of skanky and weird but i 'm glad i tried it .  poured a slightly hazy pale yellow . there was a very slight head that quickly dissipated and no lace .  the feel is actually pretty darn good considering . nice crispness in the middle .

nice complexity . i know this is a tripel , but the alcohol is the primary piece present , and it almost gets in the way .  paper thin head with low to decent lacing and no retention .  it starts off with a slightly fizzy mouthfeel then settles smoothly in the finish .

the aroma is nearly perfect , capturing the belgian pale ale style very well , with honey , clove , ginger , and lemon-pepper mingling with subtle earthy yeast .  the appearance was a watery yellow color , similar to lemon juice .  m - medium body , medium carbonation .

s - the nose is this is very nice ! dark fruits , sweet molasses , a bourbon ( ish ) smell ( even though i do n't think there 's any bourbon in here ) , some wood/oak . very rich and sweet .  from bottle : pours a pale yellow goldish , with a quickly diminishing head .  the mouthfeel is the strongest point , which is pleasantly carbonated if a tad slick .

no lacing s - smells citrusy , somewhat floral and a little sour . the smell kind of makes me excited t - not much of the nose makes its way into my mouth , which is a shame as i was kind of excited .  12 oz bottle poured into pint glass a : straw yellow , about 1/2 of head that disappears very quickly to nothing with no lacing at all .  the mouthfeel is at least good . very crisp and clean .

aroma of toasted brown sugars and sweet dark molasses and hot maple syrup . hmmm ... not a very agreeable first few sips , however , it may be from a tired palate following a pretty things black ale / that said , this one 's not tasting anything close to the fairly agreeable nose . a bit bitter , a bit sour even , with an acidic dirty hoppy bite .  the appearance is slighlty darker than your budweiser and coors lights of the world , when i say slightly i mean slightly . the smell is slightly more inviting also , nothing really jumps out at you so for a low priced beer thats actually a good thing .  the mouthfeel is a nice , decently carbonated , finishes a little dry , but overall good .

raspberry is much more pronounced in the aroma than in the flavor .  pours a very clear , slightly insipid pale golden colour , with a filmy head of nothingness that forms nothing more than a bubbly ring around the edge . extremely light body , slightly scummy and rather unappealing .  good body with a slight metallic underlay .

really nice fruit profile in the aroma .  poured out to a pale yellow color with a short lived foamy head that dissolved in mere seconds .  the mouthfeel is done well , pretty thick , with low carbonation .

moving on - aromas of mandarin and some strong yeast , yes we are in belgian territory taste is both sweet and sour at the same time , lovely complexity .  poured into a pint glass and it has a medium hue golden appearence with a one finger head that disappears fast .  the mouthfeel is thick and sticky , with little carbonation , as you 'd expect with a barleywine .

smell : after popping the top , a fruity aroma enveloped the area , and continued while i poured . during the pour , a light hop smell was also noted . pear notes could be found with deep breaths , though very small .  pours a fizzy light yellow with a little frothy head that diminishes quickly . pours like most macro beers .  taste : just as smooth as it is crisp with a creamy medium body , not too much on the clove spiciness but it is there and holds on through the finish .

aroma ( 4 ) : extremely sweet . candy apple , bubble gum strong . berries and plums can also be detected . liefmans provides a beer masked with fruit sweetness , for all those who do n't like the malt , hops , or yeast of beer . cheap-pricetag ( even here in canada ) and drives the fruit flavour home .  bought this cheap , and in mn of all places ( why is this beer here ? partially cloudy yellow-gold-amber with smallish head ( is there wheat in there ? there is a heavy yeast sediment on the bottom of the bottle , but it would n't be worth sampling .  mouthfeel was fine , not too thin , smooth going down .

nicely floral , with some well-blended spiciness to it . typical witbier citrus and coriander scents , nothing out of place . really not too much happening , but there is a nice coherence to it .  the yellow label says it all .  mouthfeel is good . it 's got a decent thickness with nice carbonation .

s : dates , fig jelly , kumquat rind , a good amount of sweet citrus . t : heavy amount of fig , marmalade , big fruit with a very yeasty classic finish . estery , nice mix of flavours . biting a bit at the end . o : a different take on a belgian christmas beer , but still very enjoyable .  in the appearance is a copper color , poor head of foam , and some bubbles due to the high carbonation ; the smell is fresh , some essences of roasted malts and carbonation ; in the are roasted maltas and caramel , some carbonation again too ; the mouthfeel have a little bitterness and a very refreshing end , beside the high carbonation again ; in the drinkability , its good with the food or for parties , but sometimes i feel is `` apple soda '' .  mouthfeel is light-medium and a touch creamy with low carbonation .

hard to beat this aroma : perfect balance of toffee and caramel malts combining with resinous , citrus hops . the body could use a touch more hops , but the greenery soon makes itself known , delivering a sticky , piny finish . overall , a solid ipa that ranks up there with some of the best .  a : super dark brown colored beer . even with super aggressive pour , near no head ( mocha colored ) with really bad retention .  mouthfeel is nice and creamy-thick .

a sniff reveals maple syrup .  pours dark brown , looks like something that came out of my 30 year old trumpet one day when i actually cleaned it . no head , no carbonation , flat .  m - carbonation is in check . light bodied as it should be .

s - sugary sweet malt is way up front on this one , blended with a heavy dose of caramel , some fruity esters , and citrusy/grapefruity hops . balanced way towards the malty side . very good - probably the best aspect of the beer . almost candy like in its intensity and ends up being somewhat cloying .  there 's no head , lacing or any other staying of carbonation at the top of the beer , coupled with the colour of apple juice makes it receive a poor grade . anyone giving it a good rating is probably drunk .  medium body with a nice mouthfeel .

smells distinctively malty , quite bready with aromas of apples floating around as well . the one thing that this has going for it is aroma , but that 's only in comparison to other light beers .  other than that , there 's no head at all , no lacing , it 's hazy , and has bits of sediment in it .  maybe i had chilled mine for too long , do n't know but i found very little going on in my mouth to make me like this . the only positive comment i can make is that the taste did surprise me in that it was far smoother than what i was expecting . m. light , clean and much smoother than i imagined .

a -- just what you 'd expect : very dark brown , virtually black s -- roasted coffee beans , chocolate , slight alcohol burn in the nose -- nice ! t -- wonderful flavors here , strong roasted flavors , chocolate , black licorice ... but it all seems very watered down .  i 've found that drinking the corona is a difficult task , due to the fact that it 's mainly water with little taste ... that is until you put a lime into the top of the bottle . just under the lip of the bottle so you do n't cop a mouth full of lime , but not floating in the beer .  there is a definite hop bitterness that tries to balance out any sweetness that is left over , but gets lost in the wash. that being said , it 's bold in the body and has a pleasantly smooth but lively mouthfeel .
a sweet hoppy aroma with hints of grapefruit shining through .  a : pours a deep brown with zero head .  f - medium bodied with good carbonation , refreshingly smooth .

very nice . t : slightly sweet and not much bitterness .  what the heck ? the label says `` angliskiy ale pilsner . a : dark rusty brown red , two fingers of light khaki head , thick lace webs remain s : sour cherry is the most abundant aroma along with a strong vinegar back bone maybe a touch of barrel t : light sweet cherry and vinegar mixed with a load of musty wet carboard and cough syrup , not much sour at all , actually rather sweet m : light body with a decent amount of carbonation d : overall very big let down , this stuff is not good , there are much better beers out there to represent this style , it will be a struggle to finish this bottle  looks pretty dead all around but it has a sweet toffee aroma with a hint of floral hop maybe .  a metallic bitterness just lingers on the back of the tongue ... but , the mouthfeel is good ... medium , high carbonation and medium-full bodied without being syrupy .

pumkin scent with strong doses of cinnamon .  the appearance is pale gold with a thin head .  smooth yet thick on the palate .

aromas of layers of sweet cherries and some sublter belgian yeast funk smell , with lesser bananas and clove esters . overall this is a miss for me , too alcoholic , unpleasant and even ended up being a drainpour .  this one poured into the glass a lightly hazed copper orange color . the head was a finger of fizzy white foam that was entirely gone in less than two minutes . no trace of a cap or lacing .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean , it feels more like a pilsner than an ipa , which , in my book isnt necessarily a bad thing , but it is unusual . overall : alaskan made a half-way decent ipa here , but it seems much more suitable for a hot night in georgia than anytime in alaska .

perfumy and very fragrant . spicy fragrant taste .  very clear and pale yellow beer with an occasional golden tone breaking through .  nice medium- to full body . smooth .

it smelled sweet and biscuity ; maybe even a little bit of fruit .  appearance was light golden yellow , with a thin , white head .  -original gravity : 1.052 -final gravity : 1.013 -abv : 5.2 % -abw : 4.06 % -attenuation : 74.2 % -real extract : 5.04 p -calories per 12 oz : 170 -malts : two row harrington , wheat malt , vienna malt -hops : east kent goldings , spalt spalter while i like the fact that bbc ( or anyone for that matter ) makes a kolsch style ale , i dont think this ones that great an interpretation . the fairly delicate , softly carbonated body is subtly malty , but even more subtle so that this lover of subtlety can appreciate . the slightly zippy , almost citric tail is pretty much what ive come to expect from american-style kolsch beers , though not having had a real koln kolsch , i dont know if this particular flavor is present in the classics .

smell of chocolate with a light coffee and smoked note .  the bottled rolling rock really brings out the adjuct flavour and aroma ... very corny with a steely after taste . the run of the mill carboantion gives some crips refreshing character ... other than that this beer is quite bland .  m : a light and refreshing mouthfeel that i feel was the best part of this beer . unfortunately , it is more alcoholic than malty , which takes away from its decent body and mouthfeel .

the smell is terrible . watery metallic chemicals .  very pale in colour , nothing special to note in the smell . the taste i would say is more like an above average macro lager , it lacks ale characteristics .  s- i noticed a very present woody aroma mixed with what i have to guess was agave and poppy seed . but since i dont know what either of them smell like alone its just a educated guess on my part thanks to the label . i clean freshening bite of hops and reminded me of pine trees . m/d- good sipper but faded as i continued to drink it .

aromas are of citrus , lemon , oranges , limes , and mixed spices .  app- the foam looks terrible . either the glass is very dirty , or there is something wrong .  on the plus side , very smooth .
