the aroma of the apricot hits you first , rather crisply . light in body makes it go down quite easy , and you may want it to because the taste gives off slight metallic flavors at first , then the apricot , and finishes with the wheat .  the head fades quickly but it left a goofy-looking dotted pattern in my glass . some corn is present .  m : very light and crisp , moderate carbonation .

s : pear , sweet apple and a bit of yeasty malt . t : carries over from the smell , more pear and apple , with some peppery spice added by the alcohol .  pours a light golden color.. memories of bud light in a glass come to the forefront.. it has to at least taste better than that .  medium bodied and decent carbonation .

s : coriander and orange rind up front followed by a sweet belgian spice and yeast aroma . t : similar to the smell , there 's coriander and orange rind up front followed by a belgian yeast and spice flavor .  this was a decent beer . it looked okay . it was very much like a light macro with its apperance .  m - this is really one of the most redeaming qualities of this beer . its crisp , dry and thin . quite refreshing , but not what i expect from the style .
smell - very , very weak .  appearance : clear pale yellow body . this is pretty poor looking .  m : big body for the style with low carbonation to give it a nice creamy smoothness .

smell : deep roasted malts ; very oaty and raw ; nice coffee-esque scents .  i ca n't figure out why this one is so popular . a- thin , pale yellow with foamy white head that quickly fades and leaves creamy lace that also disappears quick .  the mouthfeel was surprisingly not too syrupy , but at almost $ 7 a bottle i wo n't go back for seconds .

s : w ... .t ... .f. this does not smell like beer , and nor does it smell like creme brulee exactly , but it does smell amazing . gigantic aromas of vanilla , butterscotch , and candy corn absolutely radiate from the glass , providing the most incredibly sweet and candied smell i 've ever experienced from a liquid , much less a beer . this is insane , and i 'm pretty sure that 's what they were going for . t : it 's still insane , but less in a fun willy wonka way than a terrifying clown sort of way : horrifically sweet , to the point of being heart-stopping .  pours a hazy very pale yellow-orange color with a 1/2 inch white head that fades to a fizzy film on the top of the beer . no lacing whatsoever .  the funky yeast just does n't quite meld with the hops . its very spicy on the finish as well , and it feels like the hops and the natural spiciness are fighting with each other for control of your palate . light and zesty on the palate in a good way .

really quite piquant , and very fresh . otherwise , it 's quaffable and drinkable , and the appearance and nose are good . but it 's certainly lacking .  drinkable beacause it goes down easy , since it has no real taste . from a college standpoint , this is not good since you can get drunk quicker on the same priced key ice or natty ice , which tast better too . better tasteing cheap beer can be had quite easily .  mouthfeel , in nice and smooth for an adjuct lager , not overly dry ( maybe it 's supposed to be ) .

smell : smoked malt is accompanied by sweet dark fruit .  a : a clear , raisin-brown colored liquid . no head to speak of , almost no carbonation to be seen .  medium to full body , quite crisp . hops slightly dominate flavor over malt . finish is long , dry , coffeeish , almost stout like .
it is an ale , after all , not a lager and it is that way . aroma was the best part- quite spicey , malt , hop .  pours a pale gold with a rapidly vanishing head .  m - oily creamy and frothy .

( s ) - lots of ripe orange , lemon , and piney citrus .  appearance- crystal clear pale yellow beer that continually effervences . there is a very white head witth little head retention . no lacing at all.. aroma- there is a very soft sulfur note with some sweetness in there somewhere .  nice , filing carbonation , medium-high drying at the end . very nice .
appearnce - bright golden color smell - faint smell malts and alcohol .  lazy straw yellow color , almost no head .  the body is fairly good .
smells much like over ripe bananas and allspice .  golden amber . small head fades to nothing .  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

the aromas are bold of molasses , roasted malts and caramel .  zywiec beer pours a pale yellow with a white head from a brown twelve ounce bottle with a beer thermometer that says the beer is ready to be drank if you can see the logo .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth . a medium bodied beer with a dry finish .

s : the aromas of sweet vanilla and caramel hit you right when you open the bottle . amazing to say the least . not much of a hoppy aroma . smells like a great dessert beer .  spit thin head on a piss yellow body .  m- medium body with a moderate carbonation .

the nose is very nice . rich dark malt and coffee scents .  this beer pours like lightly straw colored water . lots of head though , which is white and frothy .  mouthfeel is good and the drinkability is below average just because of my personal opinion of the taste .

very little smell . the beer leaves lace down the glass in very nice ways .  the beer pours a light straw color , forming a thin white head , that quickly fades .  the texture in the mouth is quite good , remaining effervescent and enjoyable throughout this tasting .

upon smelling it , it lets off the scents of being a white wine . the peach that is brewed with the ale is very prominant , and makes me curious as to what i can expect to taste .  i 'm not a huge fan of the regular version of this brew but i 'm hoping that this might give it a twist to the good ... pours a dull brown with a very murky muddy appearance and virtually no head at all ... just sorta sits there ... no carbonation that i can tell ... decent aromas of caramel malts with hints of the namesake hazelnut mixed in ... perhaps a touch of the spice present in the aroma as well but that could be my imagination .  m : medium bodied with medium carbonation .

a - deep orange haze that fades out to a milky yellow , almost reminiscent of widmer . s - very strong blend of banana and clove , which was quite sweet .  ) a : pours a 100 % transparent straw color that produces a very fizzly and carbonated head that lasts for about 30 seconds and leaves no lacing along the glass .  the smell is rather odd , but that 's a lambic for you i suppose . taste is quite sour , which i am not used to in my americanized lambic drinking . an interesting approach to the style .
fleur has a pretty color and it smells good . however , it 's all downhill from there .  looks like grape juice .  good carbonation makes for a crisp and clean mouthfeel .
s : nice belgian yeast and spice aroma .  looks a lot like apple juice to me .  m - it was crisp , sharp and smooth . a light bodied ale with a dry finish .

sweet fruity scents , some burnt sugar notes .  still this stuff was $ 5.99 a six pack for a dollar more you could at least move up to the much better busch light or stroh 's light . a- looks like light beer s- not bad almost smells like a beer t- sweetish malts that fade into an ok fimish m- normal for the style d- i wo n't buy this again  the mouthfeel was full and approaching creamy .

a very robust nose . not as complex as the nose indicated but still a very good and very drinkable imperial stout .  hard pour gets almost nothing .  decent mouthfeel , medium-full with the right amount of carbonation ; probably the best aspect of this beer .

nose spills out lots of fruit , grape , cherry , plum , spice , and that typical musty belgian yeast aroma .  pours a very pale straw color with a thin soapy white head that settled into a sparse cap .  m : the mouthfeel is good . it 's creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .
pretty decent .  fairly vigorous pour yielded not much in terms of head . color is a hazed amber gold .  m- feels good in the mouth for the style .

the aroma was very faint but slightly nutty and malty .  similar products , similar comments : another product of ambev , this beer is also a commercial lager style . a pale lager beer , with low bitterness ( around 12 ibu ) , original gravity around 11,5 plato .  mouthfeel is watery with a lackluster carbonation . would n't seek out again as the finish was too medicinaly and the feel was thin and watery .

s - strong , spicy , phenolic aroma with notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove . there is a spicy yeast note in the background that supports the spices nicely . t - lots of malt with toasted notes and a bit of toffee . not surprisingly , the aroma is the strong point ; the yeast and spices compliment each other nicely .  if you like freedom , buy some pbr , probably tastes better than other us macros ( ie bud and coors ) , but unlike those , pbr is actually made in the usa , also it usually is significantly cheaper than its us macro competition . if you want to get some cheap beer , pbr is a solid choice , get some !  mouthfeel - watery and thin .

i was rather impressed with this one ; i did n't expect much from this brew but it is decent american lager that was worth the price i paid for it . the taste is sweet and corn like , but not offensive ... it would be a good and cheaper alternative to budweiser .  a : so pale that it 's almost clear . fizzy white head .  sweet , lacking much body . basically a soda pop with a very low abv .
the smell ... what smell .  a : transparent golden amber color with very small white head that quickly fade down and no lacing left .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

s : nose is pretty aromatic . notes of caramel , toffee , and brown sugar . very sweet and appetizing overall .  i acquired a case of this to use the bottles for homebrew ( 16 oz with flip tops , about the same price as empty brown ones from the homebrew store , but they have beer in them = no brainer ) . overall a lot more enjoyable than most macro beers that make the trip from europe , especially those in green bottles .  felt thin in the mouth and did n't have any of the body i was expecting .

i really cant smell much of anything , just a bit of sweetness , maybee from the honey .  appearance- urine yellow in color ... with the kidney stones in tact ( yeast clumps ) . zero head retention and zero lacing .  m : watery . far too watery , even for this style .

a : pours a very light straw yellow . s : not much going on here . faint bready aromoas .  usual cheap lager yellow colour with next to zero head , some insipid lace .  drinks : warm , the obnoxious funk flavor , paired with the unsettling mouthfeel , makes this beer nigh undrinkable .

the aroma is yeasty and subtly clovey , though there 's some raw , stinky yeast cheese in there i do n't care for -- kind of sulfuric .  into a big ol ' mug , the color and smell were not overly impressive . same straw body with fizzy head and a slightly odd smell . i think i found a new cheap summer beer .  the mouthfeel is light and watery .

it smelled of grain and adjuncts , rice , tasted the same , a little bread , some sweetness .  the two finger crown was its good point , now for the bland . the colour on arrival was a slightly murky mid yellow . the carbonation was slight after full pour . the primary taste seems to be that of the wort and bottom feeding cerial grains .  m - there simply is n't enough texture here for a great dunkel . at first it seems almost medium but the brew quickly becomes far too thin for the style .

pretty bad smelling .  a : watery yellow appearance with a big-bubble head , not an attractive beer .  the body is decidedly watery , or maybe that 's the too-high carbonation producing a spritzy , foamy finish .

really , rancid oil and soggy wet grain that has a bit a a spoiled smell .  pale gold in color with decent fizzy carbonation .  mouthfeel is awful due to the lack of carbonation . absolutely no carbonation whatsoever - none , nada . a very interesting beer but the lack of carbonation easily keeps this one from being world class .

smell is hollow much like an american lager . not much there ... taste is crisp , grainy-sweet with a slight noble hop bite .  poured much paler than i expected . it 's a very pale yellow : little color at all .  m - medium body with a dry finish , yet an odd carbonation that again reminds me of soda .

s- smell is of bread , and a slight bit of hops , but also very metallic . the metallic smell is the most predominant and almost ruins the nose in my opinion . the metallic smell is not nearly as noticeable in the taste ( thankfully ) .  poured into a pounder glass aggressively it barely makes a head to note here . no retention or lacing .  mouthfeel was watery and dry with nothing to stick on the tongue .

this smells like grains and noble hops that were sprayed by a frightened skunk and then peed on by an alsatian before being thrown in some boiling wort and fermented into beer . but the aroma leaves me wanting .  pours sludgy and brown without a single damn bubble .  mouf & gt ; overly carbonated and full . the mouthfeel sucks . '' drinkability & gt ; we finished the bottle because it still tasted good , but it was not as good as the 2008 .

way too much hop aroma , and a definite blast of hop flavor .  2.0 a : dark brown color . less than one finger of tan head that falls super quickly and leaves no lacing .  the head was minimal and the level of carbonation a little too high for my liking . the smell was weak and the mouthfeel was too harsh .

the smell is sweet malt . no hop character noted . not much there .  pours out of the can a very pale yellow colour . very large bubbles of carbonation produce a very thin pure white head that does n't really stick or leave much lace .  this beer was very watery for a porter .

aroma is both sweet and smoky . caramel , maple , vanilla ... the peat smoked barley gives it a slight scotch ale kind of vibe . and of course it ends up being a boozy mess .  on tap at tbonz near broadway at the beach . pale lemon color . almost sickly , actually . one of the lightest in recent memory .  mouthfeel is very thin , which i suppose is an asset in tropical countries .

smell of citrus , grass , and sort of a pilsner smell with clvoe but no real bannana .  i poured the beer slowly , and the foam was frothing all the way to the top of the stein ! i had to wait 20 minutes before the foam to subside . it did n't look that appetizing , because i figured it is a sign of extreme over-carbonation ... . i felt like i was drinking a soda that happens to have beer characteristics .  really thin .

not much for flavor , but very clean and refreshing on an overly hot day . does n't leave an aftertaste . a good summer , budget beer .  trys to pour a white head but it does n't so there is no lace . hazy light amber/orange color , looks like yeast is settling in glass .  body is thin and woefully under-carbonated , but in it 's defense , roswell alien amber does n't have any detectable off-notes .

i was unable to detect much of anything aroma wise , so i guess it 's up to the taste buds .  appearance- pee yellow pour with a 1/4 head that shrivels to nothing in seconds .  mouthfeel was a bit flat and watery , and the carbonation made this beer seem harsh and scratchy .

smell is very bland . faint musty hops and a bit of sulfur with a backdrop of sweet caramel malt .  not much to smell here , faint caramel notes , faint lace head on pour . another dark lager that prides itself in not tasting dark . for this beer , the problem is not the colour , or any tastes associated with colour ; the problem with this beer , is that it tastes washed out .  mouthfeel is where it really lets me down again . lots of bitter taste , lots of carbonation , but other than that it 's pretty watery and does n't do much for me on the way down .

a pale yellow color with a thin , white , bubbly head , that recedes rapidly has a very light malt grain or alfalfa aroma . but it 's very refreshing and it does n't seem to carry that metallic aftertaste that you find in a lot of american macros .  very pale pour with a thin , fizzy head .  overall , a good beer that would be better if the carbonation levels were dialed down .

mild grainy aroma , difficult to detect any hops .  12 oz bottle pours a hazed and sedimentated dark brown color . absolutely no foam here and darker than most bws i have had .  it was overly carbonated and thin to my disapointment .

sweet aroma , slightly raspberry with mocha tones .  the beer is a dark gold to light amber , clear with meager head and even worse head retention .  had the banana and clove aroma and taste but the body is just way too think and the lack of carbonation makes it tough to drink .

clear straw color with crisp malty taste was really all i expected from this beer , so i guess i was n't dissapointed . certainly not heavy , but able to compliment spicey food  the appearance is like most other light beers with a light yellow color but it had a decent head .  the mouthfeel is very lively , very slippery/oily and buttery . too carbonated , which is strange for a stout . drinkability is ok given the high abv , but the bitterness , aftertaste and carbonation cancel that out somewhat .

s : nose is of pale malts , faint caramel , and maybe a hint of hops - though indecipherable what kind .  pours with a white head that fades completely . darker gold than most adjunct lagers . in two words : `` clean corn '' ( could be a slogan for ethanol fuel ) .  carbonation is out of control and really distracts from truly enjoying this ale .

the smell is rather weak , there is a hint of rye grain .  appearance : pours a very light yellow color with a 1 '' head that breaks down immediately .  the taste is allright ( besdies the odd must ) , some roastiness in here but the thing that bothered me was the mouthfeel .
no aroma from small taster sample .  pours a yellow color , with a greasy haze ( like pickle brine ) . head is pretty insubstantial .  mouthfeel : wow -- so very watery .

smells great but i feel a little let down by the taste .  a : it is a very pale yellow color , lighter than the color of straw . the beer is opaque , and eventually leaves no head or lacing at all . it looks like fruit juice in the glass .  the body is really watery for the style and unsatisfying despite the flavor being pretty good .

the smell is that of a watered down sa boston lager , but little is left to really capture .  i poured a normal 12oz bottle into a euro beer glass ( 25 cl ) and it came out ... yellow . just pale yellow like a budweiser or something on that level . it had a nice white head that disapated completely in about 30 seconds . no lacing , lumping , anything at all for that matter . no head retention of any kind .  thin bodied overall , and mild maltiness .

nose is somewhat light for an ipa . nothing too impressive here . as with the nose , this is a rather unimpressive ipa .  a- pours out a dark yellow with no head and no lacing .  mouthfeel : watery texture , medium body and low carbonation .

nothing good coming from a deep smell off this beer . smells like 'beer ' , and not in a good way . thankfully , tastes much better than it smells . t- good .  i received my beer with no head and was barely able to generate anything . it had aa clear yellow color . this beer was served too cold , but as it warmed up it became a decent lawnmower beer . i would reach for one of these to quench my thirst in the summertime .  m - thin . very thin .

bad beer .  on tap at the old station house in chiswick , uk . appearance is pale straw with no head at all , and very little carbonation apparent .  its corona , does it really need a review ? tastes like lime juice and pulp . head n/a as much as i would avoid buying a corona to drink with a nice steak dinner , theres always a certain appeal to buying it as ambience at a cookout .

nothing worth noting .  appearance : pours a clear copper color . has an almost non-existent amber-white head that is gone in seconds , and there are no carbonation bubbles visible anywhere- somewhat troublesome .  mouthfeel - seemingly flat , or very undercarbonated .

the nose is full of big citrus hops , with tones of floral and grass . this is very boozy , in my opinion .  pours a flat , reddish apple juice with no head an no pop from the cork .  mouthfeel is equally uninspired , with body on the lifeless , watery side .

soy sauce aroma some maltiness i guess but the soy sauce is pretty overpowering some coffee a little chocolate , i do n't know what was up with the smell but i tastes much better than it smells , coffee , chocolate and some roasted malt is pretty pleasant . a little hot for my tastes really light in body for an imperial , feels watery overall not bad but it all feels a little forced , maybe with some time it 'll turn into a damn fine beer but right now it 's not something i 'll have again  dammit , i was so excited about this beer , right up until i poured it . looked weird , pale and milky and raw like the bruery 's mischief on tap . like something that 's been souring under a leaky washing machine over the summer months .  taste is very mild , with almost nil carbonation . no hops , only water , malt and honey as noted on the label .

no lacing s : this stuff smells simply wonderful , like some fantastic dessert . almost worth the $ 3 bottle just for that ! t : sadly , disappointingly , does not live up to its nose . it is however pretty darn tasty , if syrupy sweet . m : if my sense of smell went bad i 'd swear i was drinking thick and creamy dark a & w root beer .  as far as rice beers go this one was not to bad its better than bud crap and its better the color is weak the taset is smooth and crisp its clean and you could do a lot worse than this beer there is not an over power smell of rice to adjuncts .  sweet maltiness in the front , but very thin . watery and plain .

the smell featured very light sweet corn .  i poured it in a glass and it looks unimpressive . straw color with a small white head that quickly disapears .  mouthfeel : very clean but the body is way to light even for the style . feels like water really .

it has a great smell . it has a decent flavor with a lot of malts .  it pours reddish-brown , with next to no head , no lace and no collar .  there is medium carbonation , but the body really falls off at the end . the thin feeling is not pleasant .

heavy skunk aroma ... when will some of these breweries learn to quit bottling in clear bottles ? after some of the skunk faded , i could smell a mild malt aroma and some grassy hops . t & m - the taste followed the aroma ... mostly sweet malt with a tiny bit of a hop bite on the back end . they are n't all that sexy and any beer connoisseur usually steers clear because they know the effects light can have on beer .  the liquid is a bit cloudy ; the colour is pale amber . the off white foam forms an uninspired finger thick uneven head . in fact , the whole beer looks a bit tired .  mouthfeel : i 'm disappointed . it is very watery and the carbonation is almost non-existent . it tastes/feels almost flat ( and this is the second one i 've tried tonight ) .

color : sits a crystal clear dark copper smell : slightly malty with a toasty/nutty quality . no hops . what variety did they use ? again , not sure what hop variety they used but this beer does not showcase hops at all .  its a cheap macro beer but it has its purpose .  mouthfeel seems remarkably thin here , even for style .

dark reddish/brown pour into a shaker ... actually a really nice pour with a very nice 1 finger head and a very slight malt and hop aroma , nit much but noticable . mostly malt flavor and macro corn , but , slight hops .  pours a straw colour with little head or lacing .  extremely watery .

the smell was typical for an imperial stout .  yellow and fizzy with a large head that quickly went bye-bye , but did leave some lace behind .  this beer is way too carbonated to the point where it almost hurts to drink . much more carbonation than a soda .

s - skunky straw and grains aroma . the skunk is covering it up .  a strong pour yields a 1/2-finger tan-colored head that completely vanishes in less than a minute . the body is a cloudy deep copper amber that looks just like apple cider . almost no lacing can be seen at any point during consumption .  since it is so thin compared to other stouts , i do have to rate it accordingly . sorry but it could be thicker .

the smell is faint grain combined with alcohol , basically the same aroma you get from other macros that are n't skunked .  this one poured a golden color with minimal head .  tastes very watery . low ratings on taste and mouth feel reflect the lack of flavor rather than bad flavor .

leaves behind a off white cap . s - wow ... . smells like finger polish with a slight raspberry sweet smell . really funky and alcoholic .  a- bright golden yellow with bubbles floating to the top .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

s : great tropical fruit nose , almost like a mini sculpin . grapefruit , pineapple , very enjoyable . lots of hop character for 4.5 % . overall the hop profile is enjoyable , but the carbonic acid makes a play which is hardly ever good .  this beer was completely flat and was very murky , looked like prune juice .  thin and watery mouthfeel with more carbonation then desired for the style . carbonation comeing through strong and man , i just cant get past this watery thin , frail mouthfeel .

aroma is faint , almost nonexistent . pale malt ?  pours a pale straw hue , light and fizzy with a light head that disappears amazingly quickly .  woody creek white , flying dog 's 'new ' summer seasonal , pours as near white as one might imagine possible for a beer , which makes for an impressive look that is countered ( and unfortunately not enhanced ) by a fizzy , quick-to-dissipate head . across the tongue , this really just disappears , and the initial spice and malt flavors turn watery . this is not my favorite colorado wit nor my favorite flying dog brew .

it 's got a sweet , malty smell . unfortunately , the smell also has a bit of distracting ethanol , harshness , and misplaced fruitiness ( is n't this supposed to be a lager ?  served on-tap at hot tomato 's in new haven , conn. a : poured a very clear , golden straw yellow color with a very thin head of fizzy foam which left almost no lacing and retained pretty poorly .  light-medium carbonation and light bodied . grapefruit hop nose and flavor is same - grapefruit hops with hints of caramel , watery . $ 1.85 for a 12oz bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .

smell : i smell a lot of alcohol .  pours a light yellow color with a faint head .  extreme level of carbonation here . it seems like this is more carbonated than a soda would be even . i am not sure if it is meant to be this carbonated , but i do not care for this . overall , this a good beer but the carbonation is not what i expected from this style .

at first smell , it smells like ham . wierd smell to get from a beer .  this was a pretty unpleasant drink . no sound when the cap came off , and the underside of the cap was a greyish tint , splotchy and resembled zombie flesh .  the mouthfeel is off , it is way to thin .

smell is just hoppy dingy sunky , whatever kind of nastyish cask ale - certain cask ales just smell like an old sponge , is this what the brits are talking about when they say some pubs dont keep their ales well ?  this is a very cheap beer . but out of all the cheap beers this is n't a horrible choice , especially when you compare it to the bud 's or miller 's , it is actually better .  appearance = 20 % red , nice color , cloudy , low carbonation , litle to no head smell = 20 % citrus smell , slightly sour taste = 40 % cirus flavor , slightly hoppy and bitter mouthfeel : very light , not impressed .

i do n't know if i got a bad bottle or what , but the aroma was terrible . i smelled like blush red box wine , cloyingly sweet .  we had it in copper harbor michigan along with planked fish . it is easy to drink and you can have a few or more without getting too filled up .  mouthfeel- very thin and watery with a brisk , small , tingly carbonation . drinkability- this beer is very different .

smell is somewhat off , with a cider-like aroma and some caramel malt . almost like oxidization of a wine .  because it poured out pretty flat with no head .  it was like a melted milkshake , but really watery . if they made `` dessert beers '' this would qualify . very sweet , very chocolately , almost like a milkshake .

aroma by itself is weak .  a - very light yellow with a quickly disipating white head that leaves no lace .  a text book pilsener-which is a positive note but the bready quality is not full . finish is clean but it has the after-taste of the gaterade power water . drinks ok , and i would enjoy this on a hot summer day-just a bit pricey for a miller lite clone in a nicer bottle .

s - extremely mild . nothing worth note .  the pour is shocking only because your expectation of what comes from the bottle is completely shattered by what appears to be a pink soda complete with the requisite head .  the body is light with a super watery feel .

s : smell is dominated by grassy hops , not very strong and not the greatest hop aroma , some unpleasant stale malt with a hint of alcohol . smells more like a hop forward pale ale than an ipa . t : tastes a bit better than it smells but not the hop dominant taste you expect from an ipa .  appearance : a lighter orange/rust color which is kind of murky with the amount of sediment dancing around . not really an attractive color to me .  it 's body , unfortunately , is fatally flawed : this beer feels more watery than water . an interesting beer that starts off at a sprinter 's pace for excellence and quickly slides downhill .

the aroma is sharp alcohol ( nail polish remover and fuel ) and fruits ( figs and pineapple ) with some very sweet caramel .  i considered this one of the better beers i drank over in korea , but this also motivated me to homebrew more , enough said : 675 ml bottle pours an effervescent gold with a 1/2 '' of pearl white head . minimal head retention 7 zero lacing s : sweet malt , some metallic & citric hops t : much sweetness up front , a bit of lemon & metallic hops also .  mouthfeel - thin , a little oily from the hops , with very strong carbonation that hits you in the palate towards the finish the drinkability of this beer is very high , it is smooth , and makes a much better impression on people than budweiser , a good transition beer , but not too much to write home about .

bone white head ontop of a watered-down coffee pour . aroma of coffee , toasted , buttery bread and grilled cheese . ( i know , fuckin weird , but i ca n't deny it . ) light cocoa powder , nutella smeared toast , and ovaltine powder .  i like esb 's , dopplebock and most belgians ; this is none of those . i do n't drink much light lager ; and have rarely had an na ( but probably should have on some nights ) light yellow and clear with thin white head . i would probably pick it over bud light it those were only two choices .  mouthfeel is slightly flat .
smell is pretty faint .  light red appearance , no head , lace , retention .  it 's almost watery .

aroma was quite weak . the scent that was there had an unappealing plastic presence that overpowered the light grains and grass aromas .  i & lt ; 3 deesko served in a tulip at three floyds on june 23 , 2011.my ratings are based on tasting the beer without any syrup . a : pours hazy pale gold with a head that disappears by the time i 'm typing this description . poor appearance is understandable but unacceptable . a light wheat tang shows up , though . a low-grade funk seems to play at edge of smell .  much too much carbonation .

no smell ... weird , but nothing discernible at all .  well , it pours a pale straw , malt liquor looking beer , with a giant lose bubbled head that thins to a lace . has the look of diet apple juice .  overly attenuated , skimpy and lean in overall body , with a mouthfeel that lacks any firm viscosity .

super hoppy aromoa . smells a little like weed mixed with an asian grocery store ... .and a pigs head . a little too funky .  pours slightly better than a macro , barely darker than straw with a white head that goes away real fast . no lacing .  fairly light and crisp on the palate , the hops snap an edge to it , but then it goes watery on the finish . not an epic beer , but a decent cold mug type brew .

a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher  labatt blue pours a typical macro yellow with a white head from a brown eleven and a half ounce bottle .  mouthfeel is very strange . then an odd meatiness and tannin-laden tongue coating descends upon the palate , rendering all flavors void and unable to be enjoyed .

the aroma is a somewhat weak blend of earthy malt , some nut notes , a bit of chocolate and hints of roasted malt as well . the flavour captures all of these things and does it a touch better than the aroma , but it 's still fairly average overall . the aroma is very weak and fades in and out , the taste has some promise but is bland overall and it 's just not something that i 'd go back to .  anyways ... pours a very pale straw colour with a head that quickly fades away , leaving a small film of foam on top .  too thin and the carbonation is too high given the taste . overall : the taste and smell of this beer are amazing , but the mouthfeel really took away from the beer .

the aroma has that same funk vegetal smell that their belgian white has , which i find rather unpleasant .  pale yellow body and little white head .  a very enjoyable coffee tastes swirls on the tongue ... hmmm ... ... then it breaks my heart , and completely fades away into a watery , thin , no hops finish..not even an aftertaste . if they wanted smooth , they got it by neutering this beer on the tongue and letting it fade into a bad memory . too bad .

dark redish copper color to it s : sweet smelling malts . almost a fruity smell .  it poured a cloudy golden color and it produced a thin white head with poor head retention .  the body was very thin .

s - barely any . smells a bit like beer , nothing prominent . however as really cheap light beers go , this is great . one of the best of the really cheap beers .  appearance - yellow straw pour , a thin watery layer of white bubbles .  i had a really weird reaction to this beer - it caused me my mouth to water . the mouthfeel clings , even as my mouth is fighting back with spit . did i mention it makes my mouth water ?

i can not smell the hops . it smells like corn sort of . considering how popular mexican beers are in the us , i 'm amazed more people do n't drink this beer .  pours a short , shirt lived white fizzy head . beer is an orange golden color . low head retention , no lacing .  the feel of the beer is very dry - too dry for me but others may like it .

delicious ! raisins and coffee ... apparently i poured this waay too cold ... first sip is a slap of roasted bitterness and nothing else , almost astringently ... just ... never mind . much better as she warms . yeah , as it warms some chocolate notes start showing up in the nose , and the flavor mellows out and gets a bit of a mocha hint to it ... but it 's not big enough , the bitterness is still sharp , not as smooth or well-rounded as i would like .  12 oz , clear longneck bottle , capped , bbe date stamped on the bottle this was a difficult one to review because frankly it tasted like gingerale , not beer . this shandy poured a clear , caramel-amber , with thin foam that settled immediately to leave a flat beverage . this was a tasty beverage and was very refreshing , but it was more like a soda than a beer .  m- thin , watery with crisp prickly carbonation throughout .

s- crackerlike malt , metal and some faint herbal hops comprise the nose . smells ok , but nothing impressive .  a : pours a light , clear amber body with no head to note and no lacing either . nothing overly impressive .  far too over-carbonated , and watery mouthfeel .

cloudy , with a yellow gold color and a soft white head , it had almost no aroma on the initial greeting .  the appearance makes me sad . straw yellow , no head , no lacing smell : n/a taste : dry mouthfeel : not bad , very smooth , thin , light body drinkable : very if there was a score for making the beer bland and taste like nothing : 5/5  this is a cheap-o beer that i drink when i want a beer but want to save money . its not a great teasting , smelling , looking , or feeling beer , but once you get a to your 3rd one you can drink about 50 . this is the perfect cheap get hammered , tailgaiting beer .

s : smells faintly of grains ... that 's about all however . clean and crisp .  multiple reviews report similar carbonation problems , so this is not the exception . dark red , little to no head , quickly vanishing whatever is there ; very little lacing . aroma is candy sweetness , but the figs and raisins quickly surface , and never let go . flat body , which feels thin , and the overly sweet taste is just barely balanced by an also excessive spiciness and raisiny flavors that are not well integrated .  m : awful dry , tannic bitterness d : not so average

smells thick and dusty , solid cakes of manure and straw . weird , just weird . tastes crisp and full-on grassy with wheat jumbled about .  one of the easiest beers to drink ... ever . it goes down like nothing , because it kinda is nothing . unfortunately this leads to not much taste , although what is there is average , not awful . i guess if you are health conscious you would n't drink all that much .  m - dry finish , kind of tough , alcohol harshness , medium bodied .

smelled of light malt , nothing too complex here- maybe a bit of honey-like sweetness .  the bottle and the beer itself seems a bit pale like some of the cheaper beers we have back in us . it went down smooth and felt very clean on the tongue .  the flavor is only surpassed , or should i say , harshened due to the over carbonated mess of a mouthfeel - i 'm left with a harsh boozy almost acidic/sour flavor in my mouth .

in a nutshell , this beer is typical of the american light marco-lager piss beer but a step above others in the catagory ( bud light , coors light , etc. ) . or any other time you need to buy alot of cheap beer to appease the masses . its drinkability and wateryness makes it pretty refreshing when mowing the lawn on a 90 degree day .  note : there was a lot of soild yucky looking sediments in the bottom of the glass .  m : quite watery , with vague carbonation and a slight stickiness to the finish .

the smell is quite sweet , very tart with a smell of , you guessed it , peaches . a great smelling fruit beer .  appearance : very pale and yellow like straw , with a thin white lace that barley holds on . mouth-feel : very smooth without much for a mouth-feel drink-ability : very cheap good beer to drink if you just want to get buzzed .  throw on a rather watery mouthfeel , and i am not much impressed .

from tap to maredsous glass pours an opaque apricot-orange , thick sudsy , sea-foam head with lots of lacing s : strong nose , big bouquet carried by ample alcohol volatiles . floral , sweet , citrusy . flavors are big and bold but disjointed . very sweet , almost cloying . d : loses some points here ... interesting brew , lots of flavors and layers , but they 're all over the place . but it 's far from boring .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  mouthfeel - very light , watery .

this one starts with a skunky nose that passes after about 15 minutes of airing out .  a- almost looks like a macro sitting in my glass . not much head , just some spotting on the surface .  mouthfeel is disappointingly watery .

s : a very weak grainy smell . not much going for it .  appearance : pours a lot like a citrus soda , very fizzy . absolutely no head after about fifteen seconds ; not even any residual foam clinging to the edge of the glass .  extremely thick headed but dissipates rather quickly . it has a nice balance of bitter and malt to it . the biggest problem though is the after taste . it is terrible . really ruins the whole thing . easy going , but after the initial taste , it loses it 's luster .

this brew is a very clear amber with a nice white head that leaves a fairly thick lace . it smells of sweet maltyness , some candy like scents , perhaps a little maple syrup . however , the scents are not very powerful .  had an actual pepper floating in the bottle , a big one too , 3 inches long . poured a very yellow color and overly fizzy - reminded me of mountain dew . as a result it gets higher marks , because it is supposed to be hot and spicy .  an intense taste , but at the same time , somewhat light and delicate . flat body .

the aroma is is pretty subdued - some wheaty malts with a touch of cinnamon .  this beer pour a cloudy pale straw colour , with a bony-thin finger of crackling 'head ' , which disappears rapidly , leaving no evidence of its existence anywhere near the glass .  unfortunately the lack of carbonation turns this into an overly sweet and cloying mess .

smells great , but that 's it , a fruit beer not worth drinking .  the doppelbock is a lot lighter than others i have had . the beer poured with a very small white head and disappeared quickly leaving no lacing . from the looks of it , i am not overly compelled to take a drink .  m - light bodied , harsh carbonation level , odd , gritty texture .

nice straw pour . up front the aroma is pretty standard saison with some dusty yeast and very nice lemon touch . rosemary and thyme follow through pretty quickly , mingling with the citrus for a very nice combination .  poored a dark brown/black unable to hold glass to light and see through .  very thin in the feel though .

very , very enticing . the taste is grapefruit rind , bready , biscuit malt , some pithy tropical fruit , and a bit of pine .  it produced a white , one-finger head , with minimal retention and zero lacing . very pale straw yellow , not much to talk about . overall , it is what it is : a shitty `` pilsner '' that fills the belly of many an ignorant or indifferent american .  palate is watery , but drinkable . as i commented to the purveyor , for a pale lager in a can from wisconsin , its not bad .

juicy and nice . taste : what the heck ?  a-nice looking brew , dark brown with a finger and a half of cappacino coloured foam .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , with little-to-no carbonation .

[ edit -- as the beer warms up towards room temperature i do pick up a slight chocolate/coffee aroma , but still very faint . ] mouthfeel is thin as expected , lots of roasted coffee notes but that 's about it . nice for what it is , but not a complex flavor at all .  high & mighty- beer of the gods a- hazy light yellow with the biggest chunkiest head .  appearance black with just a brief , tan film of a head smell only the slightest aroma detectable ; getting mostly cocoa notes taste & mouthfeel surprisingly thin body and low carbonation -- big letdown ; fairly tame from beginning to end ; good flavors of cocoa and roast in the mid-palate ; pretty small overall for a ris .

'' a classic .

a wierd vegetable smell , a little like eggs . a good bitterness , though vegetable notes .  this spring-bok-beer looks good . orange-golden , clear , with an initial nice head , nice bubbles too .  m - thin .

it 's actually an amazing nose ... difficult to place , but it is delicious and entices good feelings of things to come .  looks really good , dark brown with creamy lighter brown head .  mouthfeel : flat . flat .
