maybe my nose is off tonight but i do n't smell anything . it is however very flavorful . tangerine , spices , honey ... i like it , but there is nothing belgian about it , hence the low scores .  pours golden amber with a large suddy head leaving lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is unremarkable , almost like water .

i poured this beer into my tumbler at 45 degrees . i did not like the smell . it was sour like and i do not like that . the taste however was not . it was more of a sweet taste that left an odd burn on my tongue .  the beer poured a deep amber , forming a 1/2 inch head , that quickly faded , leaving medium lacing on the glass .  in the appearance , is a coppery color , with a poor head of foam , the bottle and the logo are retro ; lot of caramel and sugar in the smell ; some essences of caramel and roasted malts in the taste ; the drinkability is good ; the mouthfeel is watery and fizzy , with a low bitterness .

s - the smell reminded me a bit of raw meat .  pours nice enough , dark , almost black with a decent brownish head .  the mouthfeel is very gaseous . i 've had 3 of their beers now and they have all felt shitty in the mouth .

its decent but lets get realistic fellas ... .a very light but clear copper , very good retention , even better lacing ... the aroma is super nice and balanced , malty caramel on the front with an awesome slightly grass and floral and strong hops , the hops really make this aroma nice . light lemon citrus on the back ... the taste is a big let down from the aroma . get rid of the malt and this might really be good . worth a shot , especially if you like esbs .  light red body , good clarity , nice carbonation , topped by a fairly level half-inch of oatmeal colored foam . i was expecting a fireplace sipper , but this is just too laid back in every respect .  mouthfeel is super thin and watery .

whatever it is , its not all that pleasing . would have been much more enjoyable if not for the funky smell . these beers need a best before date or something .  old speckled hen a- hazy reddish brown with a thick creamy head . good lacing .  almost no head and very thin mouthful . this reminds me of cider .

almost perfect nose of coffee , buttery caramel , and sweet chocolate .  a : fairly clear orange like color with a nice fluffy head . good lacing as head dissipates . good looking beer .  the palate is thin .

i am loving this . strong , and unique . t : almost a reverse of the smell .  brew poured a nice hazy copper orange with 1 '' of pure white head that rescinded to a tiny ring with almost no lacing .  mouthfeel is watery , medium carbonation levels .

i must admit i have somewhat of a soft a spot for this beer- i drank it often my senior year of hs , liking its toasty malt flavor while most of my friends stuck to the flavorless bmc varieties- i guess this is technically a coors offering . lets see how it holds up now : a- color is a beautiful red color , with pillowy , quick-developing head that fades rather quickly , leaves very minimal lacing s- tinge of fruit , mustiness , at slight bit of toasted nuts- nothing really stands out or is impressive- rather bland aroma t- stale bitterness up front , which fades into a skunky maltiness , finishes with a creamy , somewhat pleasant taste with minimal hop presence m- carbonation is somewhat heavy up front , leaves a very watery mouthfeel d- the light flavor of this beer makes it somewhat easy to drink , but the skunkiness of it prevents me from wanting to- perhaps i had an older bottle .  pours with an off-white , two-fingered head , fades soon and leaves a good lace .  m- thin and carbonated . probably the worst dimension to this so-so beer .

smell is pretty good , a great balance of the malt and hops .  super fresh best before june 2011 , pours a slightly hazed copper golden hue with a bright white head billowing above the edge of my imperial pint , fine speckled lacing left behind .  flavor is malty with a thinnish mouthfeel . high carbonation , too much alcohol , not very drinkable , however it does n't have a bunch of absurd off-flavors like most organic beers .

the beer has almost no aroma , but the flavor is strong , malty , almost rye-like , with a woody edge and a slight bitterness .  this is a good looking beer that does n't follow with good taste ( to me ) . dark amber on the pour with a very slight reddish cast . good head with nice lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and fizzy , not at all what i want in a chocolate bock .

coors light 's twin . the color is yellow and clear with good carbonation that results in a white foam head that dissapates quickly . smell and taste are primarily grain with attempted balnace of hops , etc .  pours a lively head . colour is quite striking , a vibrant rusty orange - looks good .  m - did n't care for this , too thin with too much carbonation .

s : this beer smells overwhelmingly of cat piss , no two ways about it .  poured a clear golden straw colored body with a good sized white head that quickly disappeared . lots of carbonation rising up , with pretty good lacing .  astringent and unbalanced . the mouth feel is a mixture of sandpaper carbonation and water texture .

a : not purple : ( virtually no head after about 10 seconds ( the one finger head dissipates quickly ) s : what smell ? a scent that is so faint that it is difficult to know what one is smelling .  deep brown hue , changing to mahogany toward the bottom .  mouth feels a lot thinner than it looks , almost watery overall not a bad beer , but almost to overpowering with the nutt flavor and not enough else going on .
smell : unappealing , ultra thin aroma of caramelized sugar and little more .  good looking dark brown pour with a thin , fast-disappearing brown head .  very thin .

smells pretty bad , tastes mostly corn based with some skunkyness .  appearance : extremely pale yellow colour , as clear as water . active carbonation is shown from the large amount of bubbles rising to the top , a big white foamy head forms and leaves a one fingered white lace for most of the time the beer is around before it is consumed .  the mouthfeel was thin , soda like with little real substance .

aroma- very fresh smelling with a nice mellange of different malt sweetnesses , mild hops , bisquits , etc .  nice dark brown yet translucent color . i remember thinking it looked very appetizing .  flavor was shallow , sweetness was hardly there at all , and mouthfeel was really thin .

smells pretty unspectacular to me . very green , very vegetal with slight herbal/skunky aspects . actually it really reminds me of dfh shelter pale .  clear amber pour and well carbonated . very nice color .  this otherwise very nice beer fails in the mouthfeel and carbonation for me .

smell is very strong with the saaz hops .  looks good in the glass , nice orange color with a good head and nice lacing .  first impressions , which you only get one of , is that this beer is anorexic , not enough body to carry this off ; not even sure if this would reach porter territory . and it 's not just that , i do n't care it 's not to style , it 's actively watery . decent enough , but one of the thinnest mouthfeels i 've ever experienced in a dark beer .

s : skunky , more so than regular becks . some trace of hops , and the skunk smell never goes away until it 's all gone .  purchased as part of `` build-your-own-six-pack '' at local grocer . poured small head on a dark amber body .  very light carbonation and very light bodied . starts malty , some hops , way too watery , finish is clean , not a typical lager .

smells of lightly skunked spiced malted grains and a touch of hops . not real great in the smell category .  the first thing i noticed was the nice orange color and the tight foam head .  mouthfeel : on thin side .

definitely too fragrant , there are too many pleasant odors smashed together , not much is decernable .  appearance : pale gold color with a nice white head , nice lacing .  pretty much flat with not much of a mouthfeel .

it has a sharp , metallic aroma that 's a touch cheesy .  pale straw colored in the glass , this malt liquor had a slight chill haze . a nice sized head sat on top , with good staying power . pretty good lacing too . not bad to look at .  there 's no bite , no kick , to the mouthfeel , and it 's not creamy or dense either . that said , there 's nothing to prevent you from having many , because it goes down like water .

s : very weird smell , it actually smelled like a wet dog . i could n't get more scents out it since the wet dog smell over powered .  from a 12 oz bottle , bottled on 2/11/10 into a dfh snifter a- a nice orange copper color with a big head that fades quickly . s- first impression is of a wheat beer .  m - low carbonation , slick , flat finish .

smell : the aroma was great on this one .  a : a deep orange/amber color with a nice foamy white head and good lace .  it was thin and very carbonated , with a bitter aftertaste . the body was poor , although it was bland enough to still be reasonably easy to drink .

amber with a faint white head . the nose is slightly sweet , perhaps a bit cherryish , but otherwise not really distinctive .  the appearance is good . it looks like an ipa , it 's a darker shade of orange with a finger of tawny head that hangs in there and leaves decent lacing .  thin taste of belgian white beer . most other beers i 've tried from unibroue has been fairly strong , maybe that 's why i thought this one lacked body ? still , it 's not as good as hoegaarden if comparing to another belgian wit .

strong and sweet aroma of treacle / caramel , roasted malts , molasses , bakery and chocolate . nice !  v.07 nice yellow pour , with a nice cloud that screams excitement .  mouthfeel is generally flat , sticky , and unappealing .

s- huh , a lot going on . very cidery with some alcohol coming through and american hops . a little like someone mixed a hard cider with an ipa , not very enjoyable but the belgian yeast notes of pear and apricot bring it a little bit back , still kind of weird . t- similar to the smell but without the alcohol being noticeable and the fruity yeast character going more in the direction of pear than apple .  reddish sherry colored . creamy short topping . imagine mulled wine steeped in a thousand tea bags .  thin , spritzy body .

smell : very little smell , slight yeastiness , no hops aroma .  it looks good . a dark ruby color when poured is preceded by a cascade of carbonation signature to the guinness line .  a thin beer , it 's a bit watery with a heavy orange and clove taste . the smell and flavor of this beer is great , but the mouthfeel really takes away from it .

it 's like drinking a liquid christmas tree . not impressed at all .  it pours a turbid yellow-golden hue and is capped with a frothy white head ; it has a good and sturdy appearance .  rather thin for the style ; almost like soda rather than a stout .

aroma is quite stale .  but for now ... appearance : black , light tan head dissipates to a cap that sticks . decent lacings hangs out .  t/m : the mouthfeel is thin and quite watery ; the taste is equally limp . mouthfeel and a general weakness of character ruins any chance at more than a passable brew .

s : lagery yeasts , some resident spiciness . somewhat unimpressive as it reminds me of most macro-lager smells .  appearance : cloudy hazy gold , tightly carbonated with nice white head that dissipates quickly . good for style .  mouthfeel is thin , typical saranac . why do all their brews lack body ?

nose smells fairly light and creamy for the style . not impressed with the nose .  a - diesel head ~5 fingers high with ridiculous lacing .  mouthfeel : smooth but horribly dry , especially on the finish , which is reminiscent of a stale cracker .

did n't have as strong a smell as expected since 8 % - actually seemed a little weak . the taste however did have a bit . good for getting a quick buzz but wo n't be searching it out .  that being said , the head was immediate and gargantuan atop a hazy amber . retention was equally as impressive , leaving a lumpy cone on the way down .  the watery , loose texture certainly did not help things .

s- bright , citrusy , floral hop aroma with lemons of course , orange , pineapple , apple and mango followed by some alcohol fumes . very pleasant . t- whoa .  dark - yes head - no taste - at first not much , then a sour milk aftertaste the smell was ok , not bad but did not even hint to the bland then after swallow assault ahead .  not much compexity and feel was very thin .

the aroma is almost non-existant and the color is a slightly cloudy golden . the mouth is at or below average for a pale ale and the finish is also a bit weak , with a bit of dry hoppiness .  a foamy , frothy tan head builds aggressively on top of this beer . looks like a coffee milkshake sitting atop the black beer . lots of sticky lace . a much better looking beer vs. the flavor .  taste/mouthfeel- watery feel to the beer , some grain and alcohol , hops and malt are present but do n't really make much of an impression . drinkability-refreshing on a hot summer day , other than that the thin feel dissapoints .

smell is excellent on this imperial ipa .  poured a beautiful silky black with rather modest head . has an oily look and dissipates within a minute to a thin film . not as dense as the color and pour suggested .  it 's cheap , surprisingly light-tasting ( for a 40 ) and packs a mighty whallop in terms of buzz . as a long fan of steel reserve 211 and st. ides , i admit that they do n't stand up to double malt in terms of taste and mouthfeel .

the smell is faint , not good at all , musty almost , very grainy ... it may be a blessing that it is a faint smell .  the beer arrived at the table a nice amber colour , with a small off-white head .  diluted watered down light to medium feel that washes back with a diluted overall feel , however lending to some drinkability , but lacking in carbonation . tacky cloying aftertaste .

aroma is not really present to any great degree other than some vague maltiness .  it looks fine with a dark body and a creamy head but looks are deceiving as i knew from the smell that this was anyhting but a smoked porter .  the beer is very thin bodied , so much so that it almost seems to develop a tartness .

though this beer maybe bad its not that bad . it 's very cheap to buy in the store and it gose down nicely . it is a personal favorite though better than bud or miller .  appearance : pours up a clear , brown body with a frothed , ivory-hued head .  it watery and thin and does n't taste completely crappy therefore i say it 's pretty drinkable .

s : very neutral . it 's difficult to pick much up on the nose . very faint aromas of toasted malt , cocoa , cream , and toffee eventually make their presence known . underwhelming .  a : the beer has a nice orange/yellow color that is very cloudy . a good white foamy head forms with a bit of lace down the glass .  lots of carbonation and quite watery .

georgeous copper colored beer with a massive , lasting lightly tanned colored head . subtle aromas of caramel , biscuit , herbal and just a touch of grass .  the three finger head is off-white and compact . quite good retention . it leaves some lacing on the glass .  body is way too thin for the style and way too filtered imo .

errrr ... not sure what 's going on with the aroma here . is it my sniffer or does this smell like wet dog ? there is a very faint ginger smell getting through , like that of a lesser ginger ale soda . it reminds of a car-crash between the kind of hops/malt balance found in good barley wines and the fragrant spiciness of a pumpkin ale . there 's a medicinal quality to this too , but not in the negative way i would usually use that term to describe beer . fruit-like , candy-like , allkindsa-like , this is one intriguing concoction . a pleasure to sip and ponder , as each sip offers something a little different than the one before .  pours a clear golden color with a pretty good white head and some spotty lacing .  this was a strange one for me - i was only able to try this one bottle and i have thought it might have been infected pours muddy dark amber brown with a huge huge head ( my first thought of infection ) that left lacing all down the glass smells of some apples ( # 2 ) but could be raisins - get some brown sugar and oatmeal taste - has lots of roasted malt and chocolate which surprised me - cinnamon and other flavors that reminded me of xmas - those same raisins/apples that seem a bit off mouthfeel - was lacking - the body thin and was flat ?

the nose seems full of noble hops and sweet belgian ale aromas : sugar , fruits .  new beer in illinois i 've never seen ... poured into a rinsed stange glass this generated a foamy head , lasting momentarily before the first sip , then deflating in a cascade of lacing . thick ring of foam that flecks randomly inside the glass . deep gold , almost red in indirect light .  mouthfeel suffers for the overenthusiastic carbonation job .

the nose contains some slight malt with some slight skunk and alcohol , along with some citrus/spicy hop presence . skunk is present but not overpowering . the skunk did n't totally kill it and it was definitely thirst-quenching .  the beer pours a nearly peach coloration . good retention is noted .  awful thin too .

smell is very funky - lots of earthiness and grassiness . loved the aroma . taste is good , but not alot of flavor to it - spiciness with minimal fruit flavors .  pours as a clear yellow honey color with massive carbonation and a nice full white head that 's about 2 inches tall .  a weak attempt at a flemish sour . the beer has good light redish color and the lactic sourness is present but it is thin and watery . no hop aroma or other funky lambic type aromas , just a lactic beer .

the thing that stands out most is the great taste , and the thing that i dislike the most is there is no smell and the color is similar to water . overall a very good beer and i recommend this beer on a hot day while watching a baseball game .  tulip glass , it 's a glowing pastel orange yellow , with a billowing head of white foam .  the addition of the yeast helps , but not much . d - good beer that will be much better if i leave it sitting for awhile so the carbonation will disperse . addition of the yeast make a huge difference in all aspects and is highly recommended , but overall drinkability is negatively affected by the mouthfeel .

poured into a pint glass from the bottle the appearance was almost an amber color maybe a shade darker.picked the pint glass up to smell and about halfway was overwhelmed with spices mostly cinnamon.could n't wait to taste.took a big slurp and it was n't bad just not what i expected.it felt alright going down but was n't as good as it smelled.i would drink again on a holiday maybe but not on a regular occasion .  pours a nice golden color with thick head the thins to a lace .  talking of flat ... here 's the signature low level of carbonation . fortunately the body is a bit fuller , so it partially overcomes this .

my first japanese rice lager , let 's see if it 's much differnt from the american macro ricer . smell is right on though . almost nothing happening here , just a faint sweetness .  nice foamy head that stays around and leaves a sticky lacing on the glass . not straw colored as the bottle says , but a very light orange-brown . nice .  feels flat for how much fizzing is going on .

aroma - plain grain , no hops , not much going on .  from 22oz bomber to jackie 's o 's tulip on 7/14/11 *from notes a : lovely presentation . unfiltered pinkish-red radish in color , with a touch of warm amber at the edges . solid 2.75 finger head on a good pour . the head dies quite quickly , leaving just a bit of lacing . t : the taste is a touch better then the nose , but it sure is n't gon na win rogue any awards .  this beer was pretty damn flat . no getting around it , the lack of carbonation is definitely gon na bring the score down , and i 'm honestly not sure i 'd buy it again unless i knew it did n't have this issue . there are certain styles where a lack of carbonation does n't matter much , an iipa is not one of them .

brown malt aroma with a big dose of metallic character . thankfully the flavor has none of the metal , but it does n't have a lot of anything really .  looks pretty good .  i really love the taste but the complete lack of carbonation is disappointing . i like this but even with some mild carbonation i would love this !

good lord ... the aroma is skunky and gym sock-like . the smell is unfortunately not doing the flavor any favors .  this beer pours a slear rusty brown color , with a thick , fluffy tan head . the head fades slowly , leaving a decent lacing .  first of all the palate was very thin , with hints of chocolate and a slightly smoke flavour .

grapefruit is very present in the nose - it 's a pretty classic ipa aroma .  22 oz bottle dark brown into a snifter with a short lived half inch tan head equal blend of milk and dark chocolates , coffee , and plastic .  unfortunately , the mouthfeel really takes away from the flavor ... far too much carbonation rips through the flavor profile and prevents it from getting through cleanly .

swirling the beer brings our a smell of ... well , since this is a family site , i wo n't say , but it 's rather foul .  into a pint glass , pours an odd dark yellow , with a massive head thats just sticks around for a long time , lacing sticking to the glass .  m : extremely thin body ; low carbonation ; watery texture .

smells like nothing . i got zero smell from it taste- first flavor is water .  starts good with a very nice head and a nice ambercolour beer .  mouthfeel : very light , watery body with not much to recommend it .

colour is a very light copper and the only smell was a faint dry hop off of the initial pour which disappeared quickly but returns at the bottom of the glass . i would recommend this to somebody who is just breaking into trying new things and are used to the typical american lager , namely my father in law .  served in a tulip at the flying saucer , looks fine , brown with a hint of red , tough to tell in the low lighting .  ) and a thin , almost watery mouthfeel .

quite impressive . t : starts tart and fruity , but instantly dies into a nothing sweetness .  this beer has an amber colour and a 1-finger head that sticks around due to the good carbonation .  a slight tartness was overcome by a sticky mouthfeel . the mouthfeel was heavy and coating , and a slight acid burn on the throat .

not getting much of anything on the nose but lager yeast and a super subtle nuttiness with a touch of sweetness .  a - one finger of white foam on top of a crystal clear , amber body .  mouthfeel is where this brew suffers : it 's really just pretty thin .

a bit of a soapy aroma was the first thing to hit the nose , followed by pine and citrus hops , some caramel malts , and a dry hop .  served in a tulip . pours a clear dark orange color with a moderate off-white head that is fairly fizzy but sticks around for awhile , leaving behind some spotty lacing .  m - very thin ... too thin for me .

the off-note is wrapped up with the yeast aroma but its a negative , slightly-foul element ( wet cardboard ? ) , a sort of spoiled smell . otherwise , the nose is full of yeast , roasted malt , oatmeal , smoke , chocolate , and coffee .  poured a very pleasant ruby red , very clear , with no head at all . but i did like the way it looked , sort of like red wine .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

this beer is a good and cheap version of this style . la playa would be great with a lime and some salt and it is half the price of corona . that being said , while i thought that this was an accurate representation of this style , there was a little too much sweet corn adjunct flavor . in fact , overall , the beer was very balanced and refreshing ; however , i would want to cut come of that sweetness with a lime next time .  pours clear copper with off-white head . active carbonation and nice lacing developing .  carbonation fails to hide the watery feel of this beer .

not much aroma at all - just a little maltiness and some grainy character . the flavor is an amped up version of the aroma but a little citrusy tartness is added to the mix .  my first impression of this after tasting it was not good but it is growing on me a little as i dig deeper into bottle # 2 . the first impression is thinnish , acidic , fizzy , dumbed down ... but as it settles i get more of the following : -medium brown color ... .nice creamy tan head ... -light aroma of caramel -taste offers the caramel and a nice dusting of chocolate ... -still feels too thin even for this style but overall this has a little flavor and is drinkable .  goes down kindof harsh with carbonation and alcohol .

smell is mildly cidery and vague ; you really have to search for it .  it came in a large , ceramic type bottle with the pop top . the color was a deep reddish-brown , with a slight head .  thin bodied with a watery finish , this could still be a passable summer brew for when you have little else in the fridge .

surprisingly mild aroma ; subtle dark malts blended with a noticeable alcohol warmth .  thanks to markgugs for this one best beofre 3/21/07 a : pours a slightly hazy golden with a big frothy head . good sustain and lacing .  mouthfeel was very light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

a little green-bottle skunk in the aroma . moderate body and hops .  12oz bottle served in duvel tulip glass . a : very dark & opaque.aggressive pour leads to a 3 finger head . this literally tasted like the vile cough syrup i used to take as a kid .  m : this is where the beer loses me ... it feels thin and watery where i was expecting a richer , creamier texture . it 's just too bad it 's so thin ... if they boosted the maltiness a bit this would be a killer beer .

the smell weak , but if you sniff closely you can pick up some caramel and musty alcohol smells . it is quite smooth , i will say , with no bitterness or abbrasiveness , but other than a faint caramel sweetness there 's nothing to taste here .  nice lightbrown head and a dark beercollor . nose is lots of yeast autolysation giving it a kind of soapy nose next to the good caramel and banana aromes .  the taste is disappointing , just a german macro really . too thin , not much taste.barely average , but sub-par for the price .

smells of grainy corn , with a whisper of generic hops . rather weak .  pours a nice thick white foamy head that dies into a ring of lace .  very thin with little carbonation with a slight oily feel and a buttery aftertaste that lingers .

ok , so there 's more to say than that , but it 's pretty underwhelming . again , underwhelming .  looked interesting . a- pours light brown becoming darker as the glass fills up .  m : the lack of malts hurt the mouthfeel and the endurance of flavor . i realize that apwas are meant to be light , refreshing quaffs but gumballhead , in my opinion , would benefit from a slightly beefier body and thicker texture . the amount of carbonation is average or below and leaves a little to be desired as well . d : despite the low mouthfeel score , gumballhead is still an excellent brew and i would purchase cases of it during the summer months if only fff would distribute to pa , the greedy sobs .

smell was weak with some mild lemon like notes and futile malts .  appearance : cloudy , honey yellow color with 2 fingers of head that faded slowly with a nice curtain of lace .  the mouthfeel is hot as hell . let a mouthful of this rest on your palate for 10-15 seconds , and it feels like the insides of your mouth are being dissolved . it 's very astringent and has a monster bite.the aftertaste is just ... boozy .

an attractive copper/amber color . aroma presence lacking .  the beer pours a very nice golden straw color with a small but lingering white head .  t/m : very thin ... highly carbonated ... gives more of a champagne quality than a sour yeast ... lacks body . just fizzy . lacks body .

pours a clean amber to orange-ish color with an off white head . in the aroma , a small maltiness .  this beer poured a medium amber with a small amount of lasting head .  the mouthfeel leaves a lot to be desired . thin , and too much carbonation .

the only part that falls short is the nose . it 's not too strong at all , although it 's a nice blend of leafy and citrus hops and a bit of malt behind it .  looks like a normal stout , but smells and tastes very tart and very sour .  the mouthfeel is thin and watery with little carbonation .

smells like beer and a faint hint of corn , not much else .  a pinkish orange body with a fizzy whitish head and respectable retention and lacing .  however it 's not very complex and is lacking body . thin and somewhat lost to where it should be .

smelled like pretty much nothing , and the taste is similar to that of seltzer water .  pours a cheap white head - giving way to its true lack of malt body . which happens to look nice , the white tendrils of lace clinging to the sides of the glass , framing the pale straw body of the beer .  2.5/5 m : thin and carbonated . unimpressive .

fantastic . sweet and slightly acid on the tip of the tongue . very drinkable , an extremely nice offering .  best before 12-1-08 pours a decent 1 finger head with good retention and a nice amber color .  let down in the mouthfeel however..very sticky and cloying .
s - slight banana notes ... .but a generally awkward smelling beer . not impressed .  typical dark appearance with good head retention .  felt very thin in the mouth .

s : wow ... the smell was amazing , i could taste it without even drinking it .  appearance : dark orange . nice , off-white head .  next to no beer flavour of any sort , may as well be soda water with a lime wedge .

difficulty detecting nose : somewhat nothingness in both flavor and taste unfortunately . bland forefront character bleeds into slight suggestion of ripe fruit for but a split second as flavor melds into annoying , grainy bitterness found in many similar examples .  without much effort a huge three-finger head is formed , rocky like meringue and audibly crackly while it slowly settles . body is very ipa looking -- reddish orange/copper with excellent clarity and lots of bubbles . a few splotches of thin vertical lace strings .  nutty as well , flavored almost like a typical dark lager very flat feel . watery as much as it is heavy . decent brew but leaves me wondering if they could n't kick up the carbonation at all .

'' i 'm not really sure what the rice contributes to the beer besides a kind of bready ( bready mind you ; i do n't mean yeasty ) taste . a good halfway into the bottle ( which i poured into a tulip glass ) i realized how grassy ( given how subtle the nose is ) it smelled , and then afterwards , tasted .  poured into a perfect pint at ~4c a : light copper . white tea that laces .  m - thin with too much carbonation .

the aroma is rather nondescript . i read the ingredients and thought i was getting a pilsner , but this smells like a domestic macro-brew like bud/miller/coors . no hop nose worth mentioning with that kinda sweet corn smell of a macro .  solid , big bubbled head sits atop a nice copper coloured ale , but that 's about where it ends .  mouthfeel medium-thin , but with low carbonation . not sure if the cork was improperly fit , but this was almost flat .

aroma is ... lacking , to say the least . a whiff of hops and grains , but mostly a weird metallic scent . none too appealing .  it pours a cloudy pale apricot with a fluffy head that leaves lacing down the glass .  however water overrides any other flavor m - very thin .

the smell is weak but the m is better then i tought .  the beer appears transparent and light in orange in color . the head is approximately a half inch thick and leaves some decent lacing in its wake .  the mouthfeel is the beer 's downfall . it is very poppy ... rather , it seems almost too effervescent , which leaves a sort of stinging sensation on the tongue . there is some decent flavor , but the body is weak and not well-rounded .

smells more like grass than grain . something about this smell actually bothers me , almost like there 's a hint of vomit or something , do n't know how else to put it . i 'm a big vienna lager fan , but this is not one of my favorites .  this beer looked very nice after the pour .  mouthfeel is a weak point with this beer being thin & watery , just nothing to hold on to .

it smells a bit skunky but i think thats how all these euro pale lagers smell.it has a crisp smell to it also almost like a pilsner.i cant smell any hops in it .  a : light yellow brew with a nice 1 '' of rocky white foam . good retention and huge lacing .  * mouthfeel is thin and watery , with a plethora of fine carbonation .

s- i honesty ca n't pick much smell here minus a very very small hint of sweetness . quite disappointing for an unplugged beer .  the body has a reddish color .  the middle is thin and sweetens some . when cold , the finish is slightly metallic with some obvious alcohol . this is n't bad compared to american macros and some other strong export lagers , but that 's about it .

s : light smells of roasted malts , some treacle , but light .  it pours a very dark amber , with hints of red occasionally reflecting . decent lacing transitions the froth into a modest crown that lingers for the remainder of the drink .  the taste was descent enough mostly bitter coffee with a bit of fruit but there was little , to almost no , carbonation that really made the beer fall flat for me ( no pun intended ) .

one dimensional but wonderful . taste : not much up front , all flavor is delayed .  pours light cranberry red with a 1+ finger redish head that fades to a film smell - not very strong - cherries and brett taste - brett right of the bat next cherries sour tart lemon mouthfeel - no zip no bite wheres the carbonation ?  scarce body , quite watery .

s : odd metallic smell ... maybe alcohol scents that overpower about anything else . almost like an artificial banana scent with marshmallow overtones .  12oz bottle poured into a pint a : good clear red color . looks like a quality brew .  overwhelming carbonation , especially for the style . it is refreshing though , once you get past the overwhelming carbonation .

aroma is mostly malt , light hops and touch of citrus but is overall meager . overall a nice fairy aggressive pilsner .  v.07 clear dark copper , actively carbonated , but without any accumulation . bitter and thick .  come to think of it , drinking peeber is like drinking water . very thin .
this beer barely had a smell but their was a hint of smokey malt .  nice clear straw with white head , a little r & l .  very watery in the mouth , virtually no carbonation .

i really like the nose on this .  a : pours a clear ruby red/brown color . a two finger beige head forms . the wispy foam has good retention , and some lace is left behind .  smell-fairly clean , i do detect some malt but not much else , no hoppiness , alcohol , or otherwise . taste-fairly tasteless , some malt does come through again but for the most part this tastes like water . drinkability-somewhat malty and low abv , you could pound these that 's for sure . overall-yawn , sorry for the not so detailed review but this is another not so detailed light beer , even from an ok brewery like pocono .

s - rice lager odor and then a caramel sweetness with a bit of dates in the mix .  a : pours a very dark , but clear amber . sorry , not brown . a creamy , dense yet huge head erupts during pour and leaves very nice brussels lacing .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .

not much on the aroma side , but the taste is classic bock ; all malt without any real hops influence , but not sweet .  steam beer you say , actually i like this one very much since i 've gone back more of it . i guess you can say the caramel tint is hidden in the flavor .  mouthfeel this was the porters weak point , imo . the light carbonation was cheap and fizzy , and the body was so thin i wouldnt even call it medium .

probably canada 's finest macro lager ! the taste is sweet , grainy , and slightly hopped . now that moosehead invested in a us headquarters in colorado , they have no more excuse for not bringing it to the usa . it would kick the shit out of all the other canadian imported brands hands down . ( and i am admittedly a molson guy myself )  nice golden color , proper head and lacing .  t/m-weak , watery body with only the bare minimum carbonation required to hold the beer together . the dominant flavor is slick , estery yeast , and even that is muted by the overall watery mouthfeel .

good whiff of raspberries on pouring , much more subtle after that . smells quite promising . past that , however , i 'm afraid it did n't work for me .  anyway , it looks quite nice . lots of sediment in the bottle after the pour .  t - the biting hop profile completely overwhelms the malt to the point of it being thin . there is a touch of what tastes like a sour infection but it plays out more in the mouthfeel . m - thin , light-bodied , and under-carbonated , there is a dry bitterness from the hops but it 's more of a dry , almost lactobacillus-like sourness that seems to be taking a hold of the brew .
pretty nice , but not very complex .  a - bright yellow opaque color . fair lacing .  m- carbonation is too harsh for a hefeweizen .

ok , here 's the one thing that turns me off about this beer : it smells terrible . the odor is of wet flour or some god awful white bread dough .  appearance : the ale pours with a healthy two finger head . it has a nice dark black color with hints of red throughout . i ca n't tell if there is any sediment in here .  except for the very poor mouthfeel , a great beer , one that i would recommend from the bottle .

no hop bitterness , not much flavor or smell to speak of .  appearance : pours a clear dark red/amber color with a layer of off white head .  poured chilled in flared glass a : dark caramel , clear ; very thick head ; good carb beads ; great lacing s : a bit univiting ; thin , malty ( sweet ) aroma ; but i do n't smell a bock here t : one-dimensional bock ; little double about it m : watery , thin , dead it looks fantastic , but 'tai n't .

almost no aroma to speak of . odd collection of tastes .  a-pours a nice clear yellow-gold with persistent white head , nice lacing .  flavor is one dimensional : black coffee . just tastes bitter and thin , like someone aged seltzer water in a used-coffee-filter-lined barrel .

this has a really malty scent , almost sickly sweet smell to it .  pouring a light amber/copper with a dense , white head with decent retention and lacing , this looks solid .  m : whoa , way too carbonated , reminiscent of the swill called bud light i used to drink as one of the ignorant unwashed .

a classic from the southeastern of my country , made originally for in memoriam of the founder of its city merida yucatan , don francisco de montejo , with 45 years of rich history , this brand is one of the czech pilsner beers sold in my city , perfect for mexican and american food , serve in a pilsner glass .  interesting scent , wheat , some banana . first taste , instantly thought bananas the fruit , not the candy . tastes like a wheat beer , not too original . far from being my favorite witbier , but not too bad for a molson-coors product .  mouthfeel - pretty thin .

like a goblet full of fresh goose blood , it has vibrant color and pungent aroma . tremendous malt complexity , slight oxidation adds brilliantly to the bouquet .  decent dark brown color , thin tan head .  the palate is thin .

initially smelled skunk , so i let it sit for a bit . still smelled a little skunky , damned clear bottles .  pours a mud brown with hues of mahogany and dirty white foam that forms about a half-inch head on the first pour and lasts for quite a while .  the puffy body apes airiness up front , but soon gels into a coalgulated syrup , yet still maintaining a thin indistictness of structure . everything here seems to compete against itself . the result is atonal and abrasive .

there is practically no aroma that comes of this beer , which is a big disappointment .  holiday porter pours deep dark amber into the glass and turns black . pours an ok head that leaves lacing and leaves rather quickly . another technically perfect sam adams beer but leaves me rather underwhelmed .  it has an ok flavor , but it 's very thin .

it poured a very pale golden yellow with a thin white head that retained for a short amount of time . although it 's classified as a macro lager , it definitely had more taste than bud or anything like that .  a : translucent dark orange colored beer . egg shell white head that leaves a decent lacing on the glass .  thin and filmy .

smell-rice , malt , a little bit of alc , a slight skunky smell .  a deep dark sludge of a brew , totally opaque , more like a imp stout than a bel dark .  my biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel with no lasting carbonation or creaminess .
s - quite disappointing scent . very bland .  pours a medium black with a quickly dissipating tan head .  slight caramel flavors present mouthfeel : thin and highly carbonated .

s : grainy semi-sweet malt and some bitter hops in the back . kind of buttery and skunky . again the skunky buttery tone is present .  a - a deep red beer with a fairly large foamy head . the slightly pink head lingers for a few minutes and leaves thin sheats of lacing down the sides . looks good for a cherry lambic .  mouthfeel is really quite thin , with the flavour kind of releasing itself more from an emanating aroma than any substantial body .
while the aroma is delicious , it 's rather weak .  it looks and pours great .  poor amount of carbonation .

s : grainy wheat with some orange zest . minimal hops .  appearance : super high score except for the head , the appearnace is of a great apple cider just made in front of you ( of course due to non filtered/non pastuerized ) , the lace isnt much to comment about , so no 5 here . verdict : got this is the dark brown bottle with the tissue wrap , the cork was very dry ( almost broke off into the beer when opening ) , very unimpressive , looks like a beautiful unfiltered gem , but doesnt back it up in the taste .  mouthfeel : thin body , watery texture , moderate-lively carbonation drinkability : well , not bad for the style .

smells like wheat , but there is , i hate to say , a wierd somewhat bologna smell . something is just not right in this department . you could drink a lot of these if you can get past the smell .  the only thing to say about this beer is that its really the only hair of the dog beer i 've ever not liked . rose cassis comes close , but still has some enjoyable elements . so tart , battery acid makeup , could n't help but think that the beer was eating holes through the lining of my mouth .  m : pretty dry and heavily carbonated with an unpleasant metallic aftertaste . body is pretty thin and in line with other macro lagers .

virtually no nose .  pours a one-fingered white head that fades quickly but leaves a good lace .  it is thin bodied despite the nitro , with a masked , watery aroma . the beer may perhaps be too traditional to appreciate as it shows more modesty than american craft beers usually do . shannon 's core values are a dry grain and chaff taste with some show of dark lace . but the lack of body and flavor are obstacles to appreciation .

clear amber colored light bodied , starts malty/hoppy , finishes hoppy . nose is indistinguishable no floral hops , no malt nada .  apperance : cinnamon . actually , more of reddish copper , and very clear . when i try to get `` past '' the cinnamon , there 's perhaps an evergreen smell . this is one of their four repeating seasonal beers .  mouthfeel : sharp at first , but the carbonation quickly fades away to a watery limpness .

upon pouring the beer , i am shocked that the aroma is quite muted . some of the distinct malt aromas from the mikkeller series but not a huge fresh hop nose . very fruity as expected .  g : grolsh pint glass a : clear amber body with two fingers of white head . good retention and decent retention .  m - the one flaw . too wet and smooth .

hoppy aroma but rather subdued .  poured from a 12oz bottle , expiration date of june 2008.. dark amber in color , very little head , slight lacing . the nice color was the last good thing about it .  taste : i thought it had a burnt tar like flavor with some coffee and chocolate tones mouthfeel : it was very thin and watery for a stout .
sweet hoppy aroma with malt accents .  '' this one pours a solid straw yellow in color with a one finger bright white lacing around the glass .  mouthfeel watery + light .

smell : rootbeer and yeast with a slight chicory note .  pouring dark brown with a dense tan head that recedes to a disk , this beer leaves some patchy lace on the side of the glass . quite attractive .  this is too loose on the mouthfeel ; no structure at all .

s : light grassy hops and a bit of indistinguishable sweet malts . not a big fan of this smell ; it 's weak , but more importantly , it 's not particularly enjoyable . t : taste packs a large punch both for the style and considering the weak smell ; a dominant flavor of freshly cut grass , which is far more intense than i expected . '' sweet malts also show up once again ; they 're so light and sweet that they taste almost like corn , although i know this is n't the case .  appearance- nice hazy orange with rather large , creamy head .  weak body and watery mouthfeel .

this is your typical lawnmower , i want something cheap and light beer.as far as light beers go this is my # 1 choice , the app , smell , and taste are not that impressive , but if taken in context of the brew , they 're not bad .  arrived a pretty nice looking dark amber color . certainly looks the part . looks good !  feel is flat , untextured , un-nuanced .
surprised smells like mild grains and a touch of malt tastes like the smell .  90 ibus . tan head with decent retention and decent to good stick .  relatively poor mouthfeel .

s - caramel , malt , and like a previous reviewer mentioned , kind of a mushroom aroma . odd . t - malty , somewhat sweet , bready , a light touch of hops .  popped the top and it pours a cloudy/fizzy amber color with a very active head , cool i think .  with better carbonation , i think this beer has the elements to be phenomenal .

smells like stale piss/aluminum taste is light , crisp , and nothingness .  i do n't believe the hops in this beer come forth on their true bitter shovinism . when i reach for an ipa , i reach for true , crisp , bitter aftertaste that leaves all the feelings of a nice buzz at the end of a long day . this beer just falls a little short of a genuine ipa taste and feel . for a relatively novice beer drinker , this ipa definitely has promise , yet not entirely justifiable for this bitter-beer loving fool .  a thinner mouthfeel too . feels like carbonated soda on the finish .

smells like your typical adjunct lager , corny and grainy with a hint of alcohol .  great light golden color .  mouthfeel was loose and watery ( though the taste did not seem to reflect the watery nature of the beer 's feel ) .

s : citric and a little cindery t : this is a different taste ; there is fruitiness and some spiciness .  i knew this would be a pretty bad beer , but i had to review it for myself ... a : a large fluffy 2.5 finger head rises up and slowly fades over the very dark brownish-black color .  the consistency of this beer was watery , and the mouth feel was rather weak .

armoa is very mild , a little roasty , very true to the style . a little roasty and malty upfront , with nice residual sweetness , coats the mouth and leaves your mouth looking for more .  label is colored a reddish /auburn hue . there is a woman who is being held by the devil no doubt with orange flames comming from underneath . the lacing in nice to look at all over the glass .  the mouthfeel is very thin and kind of disappointing for a high-ish gravity beer .
smells ... like nothing just a hint of toasted malt ... .  a : the pour is just about black in color with minimal brown head .  mouthfeel is very thin , almost watery .

smells of alcohol , some malt and an unpleasant ground corn . on a side note , this beer is best consumed out of the bottle ( and with some chips and salsa of course ) because of the aroma ( smells like a cheap macro to me ) is not appealing .  it falls to a ring and looks pretty nice .  it 's heavy and a little cloying . the mouthfeel is thick and unpleasant .

it looked great as it poured and settled . the taste is similar to belhaven 's scottish ale but much more creamy . this beer is oh so smooth and one i can see myself returning to .  nice enough looking brew .  m - again thin and watery .

s mildly soapy aroma .  brown ale/old ale nutty , brown appearance . no hops , high alcohol on the palate ( way higher than the abv would suggest ) , nutty , not thick viscosity wise . brown mead without the sweetness . same w/ port 's anniversary beer .  mouthfeel : pretty thin and watery for any beer , but especially so for a stout .

aroma is of vanilla , vanilla and more vanilla with some burnt coffee there too . i 'd have to say the aroma was the best part of this beer . very sweet and you would be hard pressed to drink more than one of these .  dark red with orange glowing around the edges .  however , i was very distracted from the taste of this beer with a watery and flat-feeling mouthfeel . this is a good tasting beer , but the mouthfeel issue led me to be slightly disappointed with it .

aroma is surprisingly good , with some ripe fruit notes and that quintessential banana character .  dark brown/black in color with a decent head and lacing .  super fizzy carbonation works for this beer but i still wish it was n't so fizzy .

laced pretty well but the retention was lacking . aromas were almost non-existent , sweet malt ?  maybe it has n't aged long enough for the alcohol to mellow and blend in with the malt ... very raw alcohol and malt flavor . my advice , if you want a readily available , and very good , triple ipa , go with dfh 120 minute .  thin may be a good description , but it was certainly not in line with what i would expect from an imperial stouts of this style .

the aroma is very faint : a bit of burnt coffee , flowers , and a touch of cloves . oddly reminiscent of car exhaust . very much to style .  decent foamy head that leaves a decent lace .  a little too grassy , and excess carbonation , not nearly enough hop bite . thin body .
the aroma is very hoppy .  nice looking ale , a dark brown with a fully formed creamy white head .  mouthfeel is way thin , and drinkability is just not that great for me .

although when i play that foul , foul game known as beer pong , a tecate beer looks like a pretty little lady down at the bottom of my solo cup . the smell is usually reminiscent of a fart a little bit .  a : pours a black with a thin tan head . decent lacing on the glass s : chocolate aroma with a hint of hops .  mouthful is thin and reminds me of rice .
smells mildy grainy with a hint of hops .  the appearance is right , it 's dark brown with a large tan head .  m : thin . very dissapointing .

s : not really much of anything other that a very mild , sweet malt . t : mild , not exciting at all . d : very drinkable , goes down very easy .  appearance : surpisingly good . thick ( 2 finger width ) white head that diminished , but at least some head stayed on the beer the entire time .  mouthfeel : way too thin for this type of beer .

color is a bubbly very very clear brass yellow s - pale weak straw and hay . no yeast .  i never understood why ozzies label some of their bottom-fermented lagers as `` bitter '' which is clearly reserved for topfermented brews ... but anyway ... vb has a lovely golden colour , a less pleasant nose and a herb character ... all in all a good blue collar lager ... . better than foster 's lager ( brewed in the same group ) , but then again that would n't be to difficult , would it ?  too carbonated for my taste and has a dry character on the tail as it warms that i do n't care for .

smell- light roasted coffee beans , very light .  a-clear , light orange ... 1/8 inch white head on top s-the dominant aroma is a butterscotch/vanilla note that is common in some of the beers here .  m - no body to speak of and a bit of unpleasant starchyness .

poured a misty yellow with a creamy head , but the strong , strong smell of skunk hit immediately .  drank in a tulip from 12oz twist top bottle . appearance - amber brown with a sparse cream colored head .  again , almost no carbonation at all , and it just feels watery and heavy at the same time . flavorful i guess , but i did n't care for what there was , and the lack of carbonation really makes this unpleasant .

s : caramel malt a sweet ( but not malty sweet ) odor i coiuld n't identify .  to reiterate - i dont get this beer or the brewery. & lt ; br & gt ; & lt ; br & gt ; dark chocolate brown with very small creamy heads that fades quickly .  nothing at all in the middle except an annoying hard carbonation , watery . finish - a bit nutty , astringent and very mild fruit esters overall - this beer is not bad , but very average in taste . i liked most aspects about this mild except for the taste which i felt could have had more roundness and a bit more plump , just too watery .

golden in color , straw-like with a thick white beautiful head that laces the aroma is very lite malty with some earthy hops but hard to get .  this beer pours out very dark amber with a two inch white head . retention and lacing is good .  too watery though - a beer this thin ought to have more carbonation to stay interesting .

this is a hop bomb , so bitter , it 's a bit unbalanced but very hardcore . this detracts from the drinkability . awesome brew .  as the name and location suggest , the thing to try is the porter ... they produce one called xxxx and it is outstanding . 5.5 % great flavor etc ... i have n't completed my 20 reviews yet or else i would add it to the list and give it 4/4/4.5/4.5/4.5 the food at the brewery is also excellent !  mouthfeel was a bit thin and slippery .

the nose is mostly grainy rice with just a hint of spices .  pours a sturdy brown-black and is capped with a big umber head ; lace is deposited in small spots .  mouthfeel is lacking as this beer just feels watered down in all aspects .
the aroma is a bit sour ( i think it has a metallic smell ) .  pours a opaque brown with a thick creamy tan head .  some light but lasting carbonation . leaves mouth feeling bubbly and sudsy .

poured a light copper/amber with no head to speak of looked flat to me , the aromas on the other hand have plenty of life very juicy and fruity with orange really sticking out with some `` wet '' grain underneath.flat feeling in the mouth just not impressed in any way there , quite sweet the flat feel just makes it unineresting to even finish there is a little fruitiness to it but nothing can save it for me , i 'll stay away from this in the future .  pours a solid amber color with a sticky , white head that stays for a good long while .  it is watery and just doesnt taste as strong as i think a porter should . you taste what you smell , but the mouthfeel always leaves me thinking , `` why did i buy this again '' ? if you like the taste of porters but do not like the thickness and wish it felt more like a light beer , this is for you !

all very pleasant here . a mouthfull of this beer gives first a fair amount of cloves , then the fruits fill out the rest of the mouth .  a beautiful label does not make a great beer . pours a rich , dark , deep ruby red , almost brown but not quite . good head and good lace .  m : extremely thin , almost water like thickness .

smell is malty , with a hint of cabbage , straw .  appears a pale hazed golden hue much like other wits out there , the white head has tight bubbles which dwindle quickly leaving a nice collar of lacing sticking to the edges of my glass .  the taste can only be described as `` extremely watery '' . as far as mouthfeel goes , once again the key words are `` extremely watery '' . flat and dull .

resembled a weak wheat beer . well , honestly i could n't find much of a smell . i tried agitating this brew ... nothing .  poured bronze , with a nice sized tan head .  a - appealing , very red color , but less than a half-finger of head and no lacing whatsover s - mostly malt scent , slight roasted , with a hint of coffee t - nice , roasted malt flavor , stronger than the smell but not too strong m - highly carbonated , to the detriment of the flavor d - a good red , but too carbonated in that it masks the flavor .

it dissipated slower than other japanese beers , although there was no lacing to speak of . s : not much of one ... a tiny bit of nondescript fruitiness if you really breathed hard . t : there 's more flavor in the finish than the beer itself , but the finish is the same flowery , peachy hop flavor found in the `` frozen hop '' used to make kirin 's sparkling hop , my favorite dai-san .  reviewed 1/17/2006 ( on tap @ bww , clear lake , houston , tx ) : pours an amber-red color body , with a medium white head and some good lacing .  ok mouthfeel is pretty bad . thin and watery .

aroma and flavor are extremely light . grain and honey notes are barely perceptible . outstanding carbonation streams . very bland but completely non-repulsive .  it pours the color of a lemon drop candy with a nice sized frothy white head .  ) version of carlsberg 's elephant bock . this is one of my standard `` crap beers , '' the ones that you 're ashamed to admit you enjoy ( hey , we ca n't drink belgians all the time ) . it 's cheap , easy to stomach , tastes decent and has a cool elephant head on the label .

the smell is pretty awesome . just a thick rich , perfect scent for the baltic porter . it is a nice beer , the flavor could be better , but overall it is enjoyable  poured in to a pint glass a : this beer pours a solid copper color , minor sediment is visible in the class . a 1/2 inch of white colored head sits on top that recedes relatively quickly but leaves ample spotted sheets of lacing .  nutty with bready malts some hints of caramel and a bit of smokeiness malty taste with some cherry flavors and hints of wet tabacco thin body , little carbonation , very watery , i was incredibly unimpressed with the body of this beer a very sessionable abv which is appreciated , but i found the mouthfeel of this beer so offputting that i have no desire to try it again anytime soon

s = cough syrup , wet hay which is starting to rot , quite unpleasant .  one finger white head with nice retention and some lacing .  light roast lingers in the finish , not much bitterness , but again a very thin body detracts majorly from this beer and keeps it from being recommendable .

no head whatsoever and not much of a floral scent . lot of sediment floating around in it to .  reviewed 3/3/2006 ( 25.9oz bottle ) : pours a very dark brown/black color body , with a brown head , good sized , but quickly diminishing .  finally , the finish of this thin bodied beer was short and watery .

this smells alot like soy sauce , probably as a result of the roasted barley .  this beer left nice lacing though , and it left traces at the sides of the glass like rock layers at the niagara escarpment .  the beers got a big body , almost too big for its style . its not terrible , the body is really killing this one for me .
in the aroma , small malt and a hint of earth .  the color was excellent however a nice amber red , bright yet opaque .  mouthfeel : pretty thin and watery .

great fresh hoppyness in the taste , great green grass smell , pine , together with some apricots , i would say , and some milky chocolate malts .  i have to say that this beer does make for a good presentation in my lager glass . it 's straw in color , but not as pale as i had feared it would be . the head is impressive , billowing out to a good 2.5 inches and rising above the glass rim . it 's slightly off-white and has the look of marshmallow ... not right from the package but from when you scorch the crap out of it over a campfire and then pull off the burnt part . at least it was nice enough to leave behind a bit of lacing .  f - pretty limp , even more than i remember . like stout-flavored water .

the nose was initially non-existent until , after repeated attempts , i discovered a faintly sour aroma akin to rotting or moldy grain . no floral or citric aromas were detected .  out of the brown stubby bottle it pours a deep , hazy orange tone . this is followed by acrid sterile gauze , and a general mustiness and briny smell afterward .  m : 2.0 a very watery beer , while the flavors are constantly present there are no real stand out characteristics in the feel . d : 3.0 goes down easy thanks to its thin consistency .
pretty sad smelling .  it poured a deep mahogany brown color with a thin , frothy tan head barely covering the top of the beer .  m - watery and very light .

s = maybe a slight malty bread smell , but not very strong . very bready .  stella artois ( poured from a 12 oz . bottle ) has a thick , white head and a very clear yellow-golden appearance . carbonation is high and lacing is fairly pronounced and even .  finish is flat and lackluster . as a bartender , i 've tried to steer newc fans toward better micro versions of brown ale , like goose island or moose drool , and they order corona instead .
